name: ╪vre Gefionelv
description: River in north Scoresby Land on the NW side of SchΘele Bjerg, joining Nedre Gefionelv just before reaching Store Blydal. Named by prospecting teams associated with Lauge Koch's 1948-49 expeditions. See also Nedre Gefionelv. (╓vre Gefionelv.)

name: ╪vre Gefionpas
description: Pass between Skeldal and ╪vre Gefionelv. The name was suggested by N.P. Lasca following work in the area in 1966-67. (Gefion Pass.)

name: ╪vre Mysteries°
description: Higher of two lakes in Mysteriedalen. The 1933 Louise A. Boyd Arctic expedition distinguished J.M. Wordie's Mystery Lakes observed in1929 as Upper Mystery Lake and Lower Mystery Lake.

name: ╪vre Randgletscher
description: Upper and eastern of two glaciers south of Aldebaran Gletscher, on the north flank of Randspids. Named during Lauge Koch's 1953-54 expeditions by Peter Bearth and Eduard Wenk.

name: ╪vre Rypegletscher
description: Upper, NE-trending branch of Rypegletscher, north Goodenough Land, named by J.M. Wordie's 1929 expedition as Upper Ptarmigan Glacier.

name: ╪vre Studer Gletscher
description: Glacier in the north Werner Bjerge. Named during Lauge Koch's 1953-54 expeditions by Peter Bearth and Eduard Wenk. See Nedre Studer Gletscher.

name: ╪vres°
description: Small lake in Brogetdal, Strindberg Land, above Holmes° and Lakses°. Named during Lauge Koch's 1948-49 expeditions by H.R. Katz.

name: ╪yedalen
description: Broad valley in north Scoresby Land south of Antarctic Havn, the present Henrik M°ller Dal. The name was used by Norwegian hunters, and arose because the meandering river had left a series of æislands' (= °yar). (╪yadalen.)

name: ╓yneset
description: Peninsula on the south side of Carlshavn, eastern Hold with Hope, equivalent to the present Knudshoved. So named on an NSIU map (1932a), and possibly derived from a place name in the Aust-Agdar district of Norway.

name: Aage Bertelsen Gletscher
description: Glacier on the north side of Hekla Sund (Fig. 24). Named by John Haller following explorations during Lauge Koch's 1956-58 expeditions after Aage Bertelsen [1873-1945] - See also Kap Aage Bertelsen.

name: Aage de Lemos Dal
description: Valley on NW Ymer ╪. The name was suggested by Ove Simonsen in 1983, and given for Aage de Lemos. A long-serving member of Lauge Koch's geological expeditions, he was telegraphist from 1931 to 1942, station leader on Ella ╪ 1933-42 and equipment chief 19

name: Aage Nielsen Fjµld
description: Name used by Rosenkrantz (1934, 1942) for one of the summits of Gulfjelde in south Liverpool Land. See also Aage Nielsen Gletscher. (Mt. Aage Nielsen.)

name: Aage Nielsen Gletscher
description: Glacier in SE Liverpool Land. So named by Laurits Bruhn during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen after Aage Nielsen [1902-26], a young astronomer who overwintered at Scoresbysund during the expedition to found the colony in 1924-25, and died soon after ret

name: Aagenµsfjellet
description: Mountain on north Clavering ╪, equivalent to the present Koralbjerg. The name is used on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937), and was given for Sigurd Aagenµs [1905-33], a Norwegian pilot who took part in the NSIU expedition in 1932.

name: ┼kerblom ╪
description: Island at the mouth of SegelsΣllskapet Fjord, named by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst ias ┼kerbloms ╓ after Filip ┼kerblom [1869-1942]. He was a geophysicist, subsequently professor of meteorology at the University of Upp

name: ┼lborg Fjord
description: Fjord or large bay in east Canning Land, named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Arne Noe-Nygaard as Aalborg Fjord after the town in Jylland, Denmark.

name: ┼lborghus
description: Danish hunting station at Gefion Havn on the south side of Godfred Hansen ╪. Built in August 1938 by Nanok with funds raised by the Danish newspaper æAalborg Stiftstidende', and named originally in the form Aalborghus. It replaced a hut on the same site

name: ┼ndehullet
description: Hut built by staff of Danmarkshavn weather station on the south side of Weasel°, as a replacement for Weaselhytten.

name: Aanstadpasset
description: Pass on western Geographical Society ╪, so named on NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937) after the Norwegian botanist Sigurd Aanstad [b. 1906], who took part in the 1932 NSIU expedition to East Greenland.

name: ┼rhus Bugt
description: Bay or fjord in north Canning Land (Fig. 90), named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Arne Noe-Nygaard as Aarhus Bugt after the town in Jylland, Denmark. Noe-Nygaard was a student at Aarhus Kathedralskole.

name: Aarsethsundet
description: Sound between Silja ╪ and south Geographical Society ╪, in Vega Sund (Fig. 14). Used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937), the name was given for Elling Aarseth [b. 1897], a Norwegian ship-owner who supplied ships used by NSIU expeditions.

name: ┼sen
description: Hill in southern Hochstetter Forland. The name originated from the wintering party at Kulhus during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen. (┼sen = the ridge).

name: Aases°en
description: Lake in south Ole R°mer Land, named by Sigurd Skaun and Harald Welde in 1932 as ┼sevannet. Girl's name. (Aasesee.)

name: River a, d, e, f, g, j
description: Reference names used by Maync (1942, fig. 18; 1949) and Dunbar (1955, fig. 7) for a series of streams east of Margrethadal, Gauss Halv°.

name: River Zero
description: The name does not appear on recent official lists of approved names, and is assumed to have unofficial status.

name: Rivieradal
description: E-W-trending valley with several lakes in south Kronprins Christian Land, draining into the south end of Hekla Sund (Fig. 24. So named during Lauge Koch's 1952-53 expeditions by Erdhardt FrΣnkl, because it is a pleasant valley with relatively rich vegeta

name: Robertselv
description: Stream on east Clavering ╪ flowing south into Lervig. The name appears on a sketch map in Gustav Thostrup's 1921 logbook.

name: Robertson ╪
description: Island at the mouth of Sofia Sund, which the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst named as Robertsons ╓ after Captain Tom Robertson of the Scottish whaler BALAENA, which they met several times during the expedition. Tom Robertson w

name: Skrukkryggen
description: Ridge in the south Giesecke Bjerge, equivalent to Saxo Bjerg. So named on an NSIU map (1932a) for the wrinkled or puckered appearance of the ridge slopes due to the numerous minor drainage channels.

name: Skrµllingedalen
description: Valley on south Clavering ╪ reaching the coast at D°demandsbugten. There are three large Inuit settlements east of the mouth of the river. The name was used first on the NSIU (1932a) map in the form Skrµlingedalen, and derives from the old Norwegian word

name: Skrµllingelven
description: Name used by Glob (1946) for the river in Skrµllingedalen, south Clavering ╪.

name: Skrµntdal
description: Valley west of the head of R÷hss Fjord, so named by Ove Simonsen during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen because of its steep sides.

name: Skrµnterne
description: Range of cliffs set back from Volquaart Boon Kyst, so named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Laurits Bruhn (skrµnterne = the cliffs).

name: Skrµnthytten
description: Name used for the Norwegian hunting hut 3 km NW of Kap Ehrenberg in Tyrolerfjord, built for Finn Devold's expedition in September 1928. It has also been known as Tyrolerheimen.

name: Skrσbrµ
description: Glacier between Hobbs Land and Arnold Escher Land, named by the 1931 H°ygaard & Mehren expedition as Skrσbreen because it descends steeply down to join Adolf Hoel Gletscher (skrσ = sloping, oblique).

name: Skuvfjellet
description: Mountain on Gauss Halv°, corresponding to part of H°jsletten. So named on the 1932a NSIU map, the name in Norwegian dialect implying something uplifted or prominent.

name: Skygge Fjord
description: Narrow fjord in north Ad. S. Jensen Land, the present Syttendemajfjord. One of the names on the 1932 edition of the Geodµtisk Institut 1:1 million scale map, it derives from Lauge Koch's aerial observations during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen (skygge

name: Skyggedal
description: Valley in Lyell Land south of Kap Alfred. The name was given by the Place Name Committee in 1935, and records that the valley is often in shadow (= skygge), being open only to the NE.

name: Skygges°
description: Lake west of the head of Bessel Fjord. The name was suggested by the Place Name Committee in 1935, and records that the lake is often in shadow.

name: Skylstad
description: Norwegian hunting hut built in August 1932 for John Giµver's expedition on the south side of the mouth of Kildedalen. Giµver named it for his friend Jakob Skylstad [b. 1888], editor of the Trondheim newspaper æNasjonbladet'.

name: Skylstaddalen
description: Valley on central Geographical Society ╪ west of Rudbeck Bjerg, draining north into Sofia Sund. So named on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937) after Jacob Skylstad - See Skylstad.

name: Skµrene
description: Group of small islands off the front of Nioghalvfjerdsfjorden also known as Bloch Nunatakker. The name was used by the 1996 Mylius-Erichsen's Mindeekspedition.

name: Skµrfjorden
description: Broad irregular fjord north of Germania Land with many islands and skerries, so named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen. Baie d'Orleans has also been used. (Reef Fjord, Skµr Fiord, Skjµrfjorden.)

name: Skµvdal
description: Name proposed by Alfred Rosenkrantz for a small valley on the west side of Hurry Inlet (skµv = crooked).

name: Skrubbtind
description: Mountain in the south Giesecke Bjerge corresponding to the present Svanning Bjerg. So named on the 1932a NSIU map, and derived probably from the Norwegian word for a wolf.

name: Skrukkedalen
description: Valley south of Skrukkryggen in the south Giesecke Bjerge, corresponding to the present Vilddalen. So named on the 1932a NSIU map. See also Skrukkryggen.

name: Skµvelv
description: River flowing in Skµvdal on the west side of Hurry Inlet. The name was suggested by Alfred Rosenkrantz.

name: Skσldal
description: Valley in south Liverpool Land draining NW into Gubbedal. So named by Laurits Bruhn during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen for its shape (skσl = bowl).

name: Skσldalen
description: Valley on west Geographical Society ╪ draining north into Sofia Sund. Used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937), and so named because it drains a bowl-shaped corrie.

name: Skσlen
description: Bowl-shaped glacier, an upper lobe of Schuchert Gletscher. The name was adapted from the Grosses Becken of Styger (1951), a name used on maps of a climbing excursion to the region during Lauge Koch's 1950 expedition. (Skaalen.)

name: Skσrene
description: Mountain on south Clavering ╪. Adapted from the Skorfjellet of Norwegian maps used for a nearby mountain ridge (see Skorfjellet). (Skaarene.)

name: Skσrkammen
description: Mountain ridge on the south side of Fingerb°llet at the head of Aldebaren Gletscher, Werner Bjerge. Named during Lauge Koch's 1953-54 expeditions by Peter Bearth and Eduard Wenk.

name: Skσrungane
description: Small island in east Vega Sund, north of Nordenski÷ld ╪. The name was used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937; Fig. 14), and was given for the young gulls.

name: Slambugten
description: Bay east of Hvalrosodden on the south coast of Germania Land. So named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition, for its muddy water.

name: Slamodden
description: Peninsula east of Slambugten. The name was reported as in general use by the staff at Danmarkshavn weather station in the period 1969-71.

name: Slams°
description: Lake in Kildedalen, C.H. Ostenfeld Land. The name refers to the muddy waters of the lake, and is first found on the 1932 edition of the Lauge Koch's 1:1 million scale map published by the Geodµtisk Institut.

name: Slams°en
description: Name occasionally seen used for Britannia S° in northern Dronning Louise Land, and arising from the muddy waters.

name: Slanstinde
description: Peak 2350 m high in the north Stauning Alper, on the south side of Vikingebrµ, climbed by Claude Rey's 1970 expedition. Exact position uncertain according to Bennet (1972).

name: Sydkap
description: Prominent south-facing peninsula between the mouth of Nordvestfjord and Nord°stbugt. Named by the 1891-92 Den ╪stgr°nlandske expedition as Syd Cap. Hunters from Scoresbysund spent long periods here from about 1934, with great success, and the ruins of th

name: Sydkap
description: South cape of Schnauder ╪, J°kelbugten, named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition.

name: Sydkronen
description: Mountain 1140 m high in the south part of the Bjergkronerne massif, north of ╪rsted Dal. Named by Katharina Perch-Nielsen during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions.

name: Sydkµrene
description: Locality south of Zackenberg Forskningsstation. The name is used as a reference locality in reports by visiting scientists.

name: Sydlige Fligelyhytten
description: Danish hunting hut north of the mouth of Lindeman Fjord, about 10 km south of Blσbµrdal, built by Nanok in August 1931. It is also known as Lindemannhytten.

name: Sydlige Gneisnµs
description: Southern of two gneiss ridges bounding areas of sediments on the east side of Store Koldewey. Named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen as south Gneiss Naze. (Sⁿdliche Gneisnaes.)

name: Sydlige Jµgersundhytte
description: Danish hunting hut built by Nanok in September 1938 on the south point of Nanok ╪ in the southern part of Jµgersund. It is officially known as Hasserishytten. (Jµgersundhytten.)

name: Sydney Tinde
description: Mountain on the east side of Prinsessegletscher at the head of Castor Gletscher. Named and first climbed by the 1967 Berchtesgaden expedition. (Sidney Tinde.)

name: Sydvejen
description: Branch valley on the south side of eastern Rivieradal. Named during Lauge Koch's 1952-53 expeditions by Erdhart FrΣnkl. On new topographic maps the valley is entirely south of latitude 80░N.

name: Sydvestgletscher
description: Glacier on the SW side of Schaffhauserdalen. Named by John Haller following explorations during Lauge Koch's 1954 expedition.

name: Sydvestpynten
description: Cape on west Gauss Halv°, facing SW. The name was suggested by the Place Name Committee in 1935, and has been variously placed on the rounded coastline. It is said to correspond to the original Cap Gauss of the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt

name: Sylbugten
description: Bay on the east side of Godfred Hansen ╪, north of the mountain Sylen. Named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition.

name: Sylen
description: Mountain on SE Godfred Hansen ╪. So named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen, because its prominent pointed summit resembled an awl (= sylen). Staff at Danmarkshavn weather station in the 1950s referred to the mountain as Jennovs Nµse (= Jennov's nose)

name: Sylfjeldene
description: Mountain ridge between Horsens Fjord and Vejle Fjord on the east coast of south Liverpool Land. So named by Laurits Bruhn during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen for its pointed summits (syl = awl).

name: Syltekrukken
description: Landing strip and hut north of Danmarkshavn weather station. Knud æSylte' Nielsen and his younger brother Bendt æLille Sylte' Nielsen prepared a 300 m long airstrip and built a small hut in 1961, both being improved in 1964. The present hut was built in

name: Syltoppene
description: Range of spiked mountains in the NE Stauning Alper (Fig. 78), named by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst as Syltopparne because of their needle-like summits. Five of the summits including Ochsenberg were climbed by the 1964

name: Sylva Maria Tinde
description: Mountain in south Suess Land, named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by EugΦne Wegmann in the form Sylva-Maria Massif. Sylva-Maria is a common girl's name in Switzerland.

name: Synna
description: River in east Hudson Land, a minor tributary to Storelv, which flows south from Nordhoek Bjerg and Synshovd. So named on an NSIU map (1932a), possibly for a river of the same name in the Oppland region of Norway.

name: Synshovd
description: Mountain 1317 m high south of Nordhoek Bjerg, on the west side of Loch Fyne. So named on the NSIU (1932a) map, probably for its situation at the head of the river Synna.

name: Syttendemajfjorden
description: Narrow fjord in northern Ad. S. Jensen Land. The name was first used by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen in the form Syttendemaj Fjord. 17 May is the Norwegian National Day, and two members of the expedition were Norwegian. Skyggefjord has been used for

name: Syttenkilometernµshytten
description: Danish hunting hut north of the peninsula Syttenkilometernµsset on the east coast of Germania Land. Built by Nanok in 1935, it is now a ruin. It was replaced by a hut built by Danmarkshavn weather station personnel in March 1979, known as Syttenkilometer

name: Syttenkilometernµsset
description: Peninsula NE of Danmarkshavn. So named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen in this form because of its approximate sledging distance from their base at Danmark Havn. There is an Inuit settlement with 16 houses here. (17-Kilometernµsset, Seventeen-kilome

name: Ujuattuttalerajiip Kangerterajiva
description: Bay on the east side of Rosenvinge Bugt, south Liverpool Land. Recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, the name translates as æthe little fjord with the large stones'. It is regarded as an unsuitable harbour because of the numerous roc

name: Ukaleqarteq
description: Peninsula on the east coast of south Liverpool Land. Recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, the name means æthere are hares'.

name: Ukaleqarteq
description: Small valley or slope between Kap Lister and Kap Hodgson. Recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, the name translates as æthere are hares'.

name: Ukaleqartip Oqqummut Nuaa
description: Cape on the east coast of south Liverpool Land, west of Rathbone ╪. One of the names recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, the name means æthe cape in the lea of Ukaleqarteq'. (Ukaleqartip orgungmut n√a.)

name: Ulddal
description: Valley in Graben Land west of Eielson Gletscher. So named by Peter Homewood during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions GGU because of the abundant muskox wool (= uld). Muskox are present in large numbers on the nunatak of Graben Land.

name: Ulka
description: Small island in east Vega Sund, east of Nordenski÷ld ╪. Used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937), and named after the ulke, a small fish.

name: Ulla ╪
description: Island in the mouth of Grandjean Fjord (Fig. 86), named after the wife of Commander, later Captain, Asger Emil Valdemar Grandjean [1889-1948]; she was Hedwig Alvine Augusta (Ulla) Haak [1898-1986]. The name first appears on the 1932 edition of the Geodµt

name: Ullahytten
description: Danish hunting hut west of Ulla ╪, north of the mouth of Grandjean Fjord, built by Nanok in September 1934. (Ullestuen.)

name: Ulmer Spids
description: Mountain about 2400 m high on the north side of uppermost Duart Gletscher, central Stauning Alper. First climbed by the 1966 Deutsche Gr÷nland-Expedition in die Staunings-Alpen led by Karl M. Herligkoffer on 17 August, and named after Ulm in south German

name: Ulstein
description: Small dark island 3 km SE of Kap Mackenzie. The name is used in Den Gr°nlandske Lods (1968), and is probably of Norwegian derivation. See also Ulsteinpynten.

name: Ulsteinpynten
description: West cape of Jackson ╪. The name appears on an NSIU map (1932a), and evidently derives from the village of Ulstein, near ┼lesund in Norway, the home town of Peder Sulebak who hunted in this region as a member of the Hird expedition from 1929 to 1930.

name: Ulva
description: Tributary of Dyraelv in south Hold with Hope, so named on an NSIU map (1932a; Fig. 87), for the wolf.

name: Ulvebjerg
description: Mountain in southern Kronprins Christian Land, SE of Centrums° (Fig. 24). So named during Lauge Koch's 1952-53 expeditions by Erdhardt FrΣnkl because fresh wolf (= ulve) tracks were found near the summit in August 1952.

name: Ulvebugthytten
description: Name sometimes used for the Danish hut built in September 1934 in central Grandjean Fjord which is officially known as Grandjeanhytten.

name: Ulvedal
description: Valley on Gauss Halv° at the west flank of Giesecke Bjerge. So named by Th. Johansen during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen because wolf tracks were repeatedly seen here (Fig. 87).

name: Ulvedalen
description: Name occasionally used on Norwegian maps (Ingstad 1935; Akre 1957) for a valley in Jameson Land corresponding to the valley containing the present Depotelv; it is the locality where Helge Ingstad observed tracks of two wolves (= ulve) in 1932. (Wolf Vall

name: Ulvedalen

name: Ulveelv
description: River west of the head of Hurry Inlet draing into Ugleelv. It was named by Alfred Rosenkrantz during Lauge Koch's 1926-27 expeditions in the form Wolf River for a sighting of a wolf (= ulv) or wolf tracks. See also Ulvedalen above.

name: Ulveh°j

name: Ulveh°jen
description: Small hill, sometimes described as having two summits, near the Nanok hunting station in southern Hochstetter Forland. The name was used by Danish hunters in the 1930s (e.g. Nyholm-Poulsen 1985). Their foxtrap on the summit was reported to have caught pr

name: Ulvekam
description: Mountain ridge about 2200 m high west of Petermann Bjerg, in the nunataks of west Frµnkel Land. So named during Lauge Koch's 1951 expedition by John Haller and Eduard Wenk because they encountered fresh wolf (= ulve) tracks here (Fig. 87). (Ulvebakken, W

name: ╪stre Skanse

description: Eastern of twin glaciers south of the head of Rhedin Fjord (Fig. 88). Named by John Haller following explorations during Lauge Koch's 1952-53 expeditions.

name: ╪stre Vibeke Gletscher

name: ╪stre Vikingeborg
description: Mountain on the east side of Borggletscher, on the south side of Kejser Franz Joseph Fjord. So named during Lauge Koch's 1952-53 expeditions by John Haller, for the castle-like appearance.

description: Small plateau west of Knuden and east of Margrethedal on SE Gauss Halv°, named by Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions in the form Eastern Plateau.

name: ╪sttinden
description: Mountain peak on south Clavering ╪. The name was first used, together with Vesttinden, in a report by Gelting (1934) on work during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen.

name: ╪sttungerne
description: Glacier in NE Germania Land on the east side of Fladebugt. Named by David Malmquist during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen as ╓sttungerne.

description: Camp site on Bersµrkerbrµ in the north Stauning Alper, just below its junction with Dunottar Gletscher. The site was first used by the 1958 Scottish East Greenland expedition led by Malcolm Slesser. According to Bennet (1972) it has become one of the mos

name: Sunderland Gletscher
description: Glacier in NW Dronning Louise Land. The name was given by the 1952-54 British North Greenland expedition for the Sunderland flying boats of the RAF which flew the expedition and equipment to Britannia S° from Zackenberg Bugt.

description: Norwegian hunting station 2 km SE of Kap PetersΘns built by the M°re expedition in 1930, and named after the Sunm°re area in Norway from which the expedition came. The station was also called Vardevakt, but is more commonly known for its location as Kapp

name: Sunnm°resterrenget

name: Tvillingodden
description: Peninsula with two similar narrow projections on the north side of east Geographical Society ╪. So named on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937) (tvilling = twin).

name: Tvµrdal

name: Tvµrdal
description: Valley on NE Clavering ╪, named by Arne Noe-Nygaard and Gunnar SΣve-S÷derbergh during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen in the form Quertal (= transverse valley).

description: River that forms the west boundary of Home Forland. Derived from the Tverσdalen of the 1932a NSIU map, and so named because it cuts deeply into the plateau to form the lowest pass on the north side of Tobias Dal (tvµr = cross).

name: Tyskit Nunaat
description: Part of west Jameson Land south of Gurreholm. Recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, the name means æland of the Germans'. The eastern station of Alfred Wegener's 1930-31 expedition was situated here, established with the assistance o

name: Zurchergletscher

name: Zwergspids

name: Zackenbergdalen

name: Sjussen

name: Sjµllandselv

name: Skardvatnet

name: Skartind

name: Suselv

name: Svampebugt

name: Svanning Bjerg
description: Mountain in the central Giesecke Bjerge. The name was proposed by the Place Name Committee in 1939 to replace suggestions by Wolf Maync and Andreas Vischer, and commemorates the Danish historian, Hans Swaning [1500-84]. It corresponds to Skrubbtind and S

name: Svartetua

name: Svarthammerhytta
description: Norwegian hunting hut on the south side of Bessel Fjord, built in September 1932 by John Giµver's expedition. It has also been known as Fredhaug.

name: Svarthamrane
description: Mountain ridge on central Geographical Society ╪ corresponding to the present Julekagen. Used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937), the name was given for the black cliffs.

name: Svarva
description: Stream on south Clavering ╪ adjacent to Sveiva. So named on NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937) for the turbulence (= svarva) of the stream.

name: Svedenborg
description: Norwegian hunting hut at the cape NW of Svedenborg Bjerg on west Geographical Society ╪. Built by Arktisk Nµringsdrift in September 1930, it has also been known as Joplassen, Valborghytten and R°vballehytten.

name: Tyssa

name: Tyvholmen

name: Tµnderne

name: TΣrnholmen
description: Small island or skerry in the inner part of Mackenzie Bugt, So named by Kolthoff (1901) for the several hundred nesting terns he saw there in 1900. NSIU expeditions in 1932 used a similar name, Tennholm, for the same reasons. The name also appears on som

name: Tµrskeldal
description: Level, high valley between Violingletscher and Forsblad Fjord. So named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Ove Simonsen because the valley occurs at the watershed (tµrskel = threshold).

name: Tµrskels°
description: Lake in Tµrskeldal, Nathorst Land. Named during Lauge Koch's 1954 expedition by John Haller.

name: T÷dibjerg
description: Mountain south of Violingletscher, east of Hj°rnes°, Nathorst Land. Named during Lauge Koch's 1954-55 expeditions by Hans Zweifel after the mountain T÷di, the highest peak in the Glarner Alpen, Switzerland.

name: T°flerne
description: Two small skerries SE of the Trip-Trap-Trµsko. Discovered and so named during the 1932 Gefion expedition, the name (= a pair of slippers) deriving from their proximity to the Trip-Trap-Trµsko (trµsko = clogs).

name: T÷lzer Spids
description: Mountain on the south side of the head of Roslin Gletscher. Climbed by the 1966 Deutsche Gr÷nland-Expedition in die Staunings-Alpen led by Karl M. Herligkoffer on 15 August, and probably named after Bad T÷lz, a small town in the Bavarian Alps, the home t

name: T°mmerbugt

name: T°rvestakken

name: T°rvekµret

name: Tσgedal

name: Tσgefjeld

name: Tσrnet
description: Mountain on Wegener Halv°. Named by Katherina Perch-Nielsen during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions for its tower-like shape. Eastern Mountain has also been used.

name: Tσrnet
description: Peak about 2310 m high on the spiky ridge south of Dansketinden, Stauning Alper. Climbed and so named by the 1996 Norwegian Stauning Alper expedition. The peak was climbed later the same summer by the 1996 Scottish Mountaineering Club expedition who name

name: ╞sken

name: ╪fjord
description: Long fjord between Renland and Milne Land. Discovered and named by the 1891-92 Den ╪stgr°nlandske expedition led byCarl Ryder during the exploration of the Bj°rne°er in September 1891 (Fig. 7). There are no islands within the main stretch of the fjord, a

name: ╓ienfjellet

name: ╪iens hus

name: ╪ksebladet

name: ╪ksnevad

name: ╪resund
description: Sound between Lille Koldewey and Kap Bismarck. The name was used by Trolle (1913) in his hydrographical reports of the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen, and was probably given for the sound of the same name between Sweden and Denmark. See also Lille Bµlt an

name: ╪rkenbjergene
description: Hills south of the head of Fleming Inlet, named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Arne Noe-Nygaard as Desert Mts, because of their appearance. (Desert Bjergene).

name: Skillebugt

name: Skilledal
description: Valley on north Clavering ╪, which with Skillegletscher divides Clavering ╪ into two equal parts. The name is attributed to Richard Foster Flint and arises from work during the 1937 Louise A. Boyd Arctic expedition. Nivlheimdalen has also been used. (Ski

name: Skillegletscher
description: Glacier on north Clavering ╪, which with Skilledal divides Clavering ╪ into two parts. The name is attributed to work by Richard Foster Flint during the 1937 Louise A. Boyd Arctic expedition. Vintergata has also been used. (Skille Glacier.)

name: Skotsketinde

name: Skrubbfjellet

name: Sveiva

name: Svejstrup Bjerg
description: Mountain on the south side of the mouth of Svejstrup Dal. Named by the 1948 Leeds University expedition led by W.R.B. Battle. (Svejstrups Bjerg, Svejstrups Mountain.)

name: Svejstrupdalshytten

name: Svenskenµs

name: Sydh°jen

name: Tσrnfjeld

name: Ugleelv

name: Ugleh°jene

name: Uglespids

name: Wegener Halv°

name: Weisskopf

name: Snekuppelkl°ft

name: Snemarken
description: Ice cap on central Clavering ╪. The name (= snow field) was suggested by the Place Name Committee in 1951 as a replacement for the Lars Christensenfonna of NSIU maps, rejected on the grounds that Lars Christensen was then still alive.

name: Smedal Valley
description: Name occasionally used for the present Margrethedal west of Kap Franklin, where the Norwegian hunting hut Smedal is situated.

name: Snenµs
description: Peninsula on Winge Kyst in south Germania Land, so named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen because it was usually snow-covered. This point has also been called Store Snenµs to distinguish it from Lille Snenµs. (Snow Naze, Sne Point.)

name: Snenµshytten
description: Danish hunting hut at Snenµs on the south coast of Germania Land, built by Nanok in August 1933. It has more usually been known as Store Snenµshytten to distinguish it from Lille Snenµshytten. A newer hut nearby is known as Ny Store Snenµs Hytte.

name: Snerta
description: Small river on the north coast of Home Forland, so named on an NSIU map (1932a). Derived from a Norwegian dialect word. (Snerta River.)

name: Sneryggen

name: Snespurvefjeld

name: S°nderelv
description: River in east N°rlund Land, south of the mouth of Bessel Fjord. The name first appeared on a map in Jennov (1939). A Nanok hut on the north side of the river sometimes known as S°nderelv-huset is officially known as Hundehushytten. (S°ndre Elv.)

name: S°nderelv
description: Norwegian hut built in November 1933 on the south side of S°nderelv for John Giµver's expedition. It was replaced in 1949 by Astralhytten.

name: S°ndergletscher

name: S°nderland
description: Southernmost part of Hertugen af OrlΘans Land. Named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition.

name: Victor Madsen Gletscher

name: Vidarbreen

name: Vifteelv
description: Name used by Rosenkrantz (1942) for the small, fan-shaped river in south Liverpool Land draining Gulfjelde (vifte = fan).

name: Vifteelv
description: River flowing into Skeldal on the east side of the Stauning Alper. The name was suggested by N.P. Lasca following field work in 1966-67, and records the numerous, large, depositional fans.

name: R÷hss Fjord
description: E-W-trending fjord which divides Gletscherland almost into two parts (Fig. 52). Named R÷hss' Fjord by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst after Johan Anders August R÷hss [1836-1904], who contributed 5000 Swedish kronor to the

name: R÷hss Fjord Hytten
description: Norwegian hunting hut built for Arktisk Nµringsdrift in July 1934 on the east side of Str°mnµs, R÷hss Fjord (Fig. 82). It was originally known as Festningen, and is often called Str°mnµshytten.

name: R÷hssfjordbotnen
description: This name has been used in NSIU botanical reports as a reference locality for the innermost section of R÷hss Fjord (Vaage 1932).

name: R÷hssfjordsundet
description: Name used as a reference locality in NSIU botanical reports (Vaage 1932) for the narrow part of R÷hss Fjord at Str°mnµs known as Sarpaq.

name: R°iskattlia
description: Norwegian hunting hut built in August 1932 for Arktisk Nµringsdrift on the north side of Moskusoksefjord, commonly known as Petrahytten. The area was plagued by hermelin (= r°yskatt), which often broke into the hunters' fox traps. The hut has also been k

name: R°iskattlia
description: Norwegian hunting hut built by Arktisk Nµringsdrift in July 1947 on the north side of Suess Land, and commonly known as Polarheimen. The name records the presence of hermelin (= r°yskatt).

name: R°ievatnet
description: Small lake on the west side of outermost Loch Fyne. The name was used by NSIU in the 1930s for a lake where they fished for salmon (arctic char = r°ie). It has been used as a reference locality in botanical and zoological reports. (R°yevand, R÷yevatnet,

name: R°mer Fjord
description: Fjord SW of Turner ╪ on the north Blosseville Kyst. Named by the 1898-1900 Carlsbergfondets Expedition as R°mers Fjord, after Ole R°mer [1644-1710], a Danish physicist and astronomer noted especially for the first measurement of the speed of light.

name: R°sel°bet
description: Narrow sound between the two islands of Lille Koldewey. So named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen because it is only a sound at spring tides (Thostrup 2007). (R÷sel÷bet, R÷se L÷bet.)

name: R°snes
description: Name occasionally used by Norwegian hunters for Kap Hamburg, southern Kuhn ╪. The name has also been used for the Norwegian hunting hut 3 km west of the cape commonly known as Furnes.

name: R°stholmane
description: Small skerries off the coast of SE Geographical Society ╪. Used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937), the name was given for the island R°st in the Lofoten region of Norway. (R÷stholmane.)

name: R°vballehytten
description: Name often used for the Norwegian hunting hut built for Arktisk Nµringsdrift in September 1930 in inner Sofia Sund, which is also known as Svedenborg, Bakkehytta, Joplassen and Valborghytta. The name stems from the position of the hut on a steep slope, w

name: R°verreden
description: Mountain on the north side of Bredegletscher, a fantasy name (= den of thieves) given by Laurits Bruhn during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen.

name: Rσum°yane
description: Two islands in Vega Sund, part of the Scott Keltie ╪er group. So named on NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937), after Knut Rσum [b. 1909], a Norwegian hunter who wintered in East Greenland in 1933-35 and 1936-37.

name: S. Paolo
description: One of the pinnacles of Satans Galleri in the Stauning Alper, NNE of Korsspids. Climbed on 29 July 1984 by Sandro Pucci's expedition, and named after two of the climbers (Paolo Piconi and Paolo D'Ugo).

name: S. Thomsen Pynt
description: South cape of Joh. G. Guildal ╪. Named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen as S. Thomsens Pynt, possibly after Sigismund Gotthelf Thomsen [1831-1903] who was Thomas Thomsen's father. See also Thomas Thomsen Nµs.

name: Saakattaakajik
description: Point east of Sydkap on the west side of Nord°stbugt. Recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, the name means æthe rather flat'. (SΓkßtΓkajik.)

name: Sabine ╪
description: Island NE of Wollaston Forland, one of the Pendulum ╪er. Named by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt as Sabine Insel (Fig. 6), after Edward Sabine [1788-1883], British general and physicist who carried out pendulum experiments on the island i

name: Silberspitzen
description: Name used by the 1964 AAC Zⁿrich expedition for the peaks about 2400 m high on the ridge west of Spµrregletscher (silber = silver). The second ascent was made by the 1966 Deutsche Gr÷nland-Expedition in die Staunings-Alpen led by Karl M. Herligkoffer. Th

name: Silja ╪
description: Small island in Vega Sund. The name was proposed by S°kortarkivet in 1956-57 following surveying of the channel through Vega Sund as an alternative approach for ships en route to Mestersvig. It was given for the SILJA DAN, a 4250 ton ice-strengthened pol

name: Silldal
description: Valley draining north into the upper part of ╪rsted Dal. So named by Katharina Perch-Nielsen during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions because of the numerous dolerite sills.

name: Sillerendal
description: Valley in NW Wollaston Forland, so named by Wolf Maync during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition, for the fossils.

name: Silvio Bjerg
description: Mountain 2280 m high SE of Nordenski÷ld Gletscher, named by J.M. Wordie's 1929 Cambridge expedition as Monte Silvio. Origin of name unknown.

name: Simonsen Skµr
description: Skerries on the east side of Lille Koldewey, named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen as Simonsens Skµr. Possibly named after the popular opera singer Niels Juel Simonsen [1846-1906], as the expedition had a gramophone with them (Jan L°ve, personal com

name: Simpson Dal
description: Valley on SE Traill ╪, so named during Lauge Koch's 1956-58 expeditions by H.P. Heres. See also Kap Simpson.

name: Simpson-Stranda
description: Name given to an intended Norwegian hunting hut at Kap Simpson, SE Traill ╪. Material for the hut was deposited here by Arktisk Nµringsdrift in 1929. A hut built here for Sirius in 1955-56 is usually known under the name Kap Simpson Hytten.

name: Sindalen
description: Valley in the southern Giesecke Bjerge, draining eastwards. The name was proposed by the Place Name Committee in 1939 to replace suggestions by Wolf Maync and Andreas Vischer. It was probably given for the town of Sindal in north Jylland. Stubbdalen has

name: Sinus Gletscher
description: Minor glacier on the south side of Gully Gletscher, north Stauning Alper. Named by Sandro Pucci's 1984 expedition.

name: Sirius Bjerg
description: Mountain 1632 m high in the Werner Bjerge north of Sirius Gletscher. Named during Lauge Koch's 1953-54 expeditions by Peter Bearth and Eduard Wenk. Sirius, the dog-star, is the brightest star in the northern night sky.

name: Shirley's Peak
description: Peak in the Stauning Alper on the ridge south of Major Passet. Climbed by the 1996 Scottish Mountaineering Club expedition.

name: Shrivenham
description: Peak on the south side of Schuchert Gletscher about 1951 m high. It was climbed by the 1990 Exercise Green Ice expedition. (Mt. Shrivenham).

name: Sirius Dal
description: Valley on SW Hovgaard ╪, providing a route from the front of Nioghalvfjerdsfjorden to inner Dijmphna Sund. The name was approved in 1958, and was given for the Sirius sledge patrol.

name: Sirius Gletscher
description: Glacier in the Werner Bjerge, draining west to join Schuchert Gletscher. The name first appeared on the maps of Styger (1951), in his description of a climbing excursion during Lauge Koch's 1950 expedition, and was given for the star Sirius.

name: Sista Nσlbrevet
description: Name used by Helge G. Backlund during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen for the SE pinnacle of one of the Bj°rne°er (island IX - see also Bj°rne°er), which was climbed in 1933 and used as a surveying point.

name: Siste-Huset
description: Norwegian hunting hut built by Helge Instad's expedition in August 1932 at the head of Nathorst Fjord. It has also been known as Bunn-Huset.

name: Sivbreen
description: Small glacier on central Clavering ╪. So named on NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937) after Sif, wife of Tor in old Nordic mythology.

name: St°vfanget
description: Sheltered area on the SW side of Paul Stern Land between the glacier and the cliff, where large quantities of mica-dust collect (st°v = dust). Named by W.E. Adrian Phillips during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions.

name: Sⁿdprofil
description: Geological reference locality on SE Kuhn ╪, used by Maync (1947) in his description of work during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition.

name: Suess Land
description: Land area bounded by Kejser Franz Joseph Fjord to the north and Kempe Fjord and Dickson Fjord to the south. Named by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition lede by A.G. Nathorst after Eduard Suess [1831-1914], an influential Austrian geologist who wa

name: Sugar Basin
description: Name given in reports of James Clarkson's 1961 expedition to the upper broad basin of Spµrregletscher. It is an area without crevasses which was named for the snow conditions.

name: Suhm Bjerg
description: Mountain in the central Giesecke Bjerge. The name was proposed by the Place Name Committee in 1939 to replace a suggestion by Wolf Maync and Andreas Vischer. It commemorates Peter Frederik Suhm [1728-98], a Danish historian who produced a 14 volume æHist

name: Orienteringsspids
description: Mountain 1342 m high on the north side of Tyrolerfjord, SE of Zackenberg. Named by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt as Orienterungs Spitze, probably because it was a prominent peak used as a surveying point. (Orienteringstoppen, Mt Orienter

name: Orienterings°erne
description: Island group in Dove Bugt, one of which was named Orienterungs Insel by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt, probably because the view from the summit was useful in determining the route of the expedition. The term East Island is used in the E

name: Orion Gletscher
description: Glacier in the south Stauning Alper, flowing SE to join Jupiter Gletscher. Named Orion Glacier by John Hunt's 1960 expedition, after the major constellation.

name: Orion-Borgbjerg Col
description: Col between the head of Orion Gletscher and Borgbjerg Gletscher. The name is used by Bennet (1972). The 1996 Norwegian Stauning Alper expedition crossed the col during their south to north ski traverse, and called it An Dorus Mor (The Great Gate).

name: Orleans Island
description: Name occasionally used for the present Gamma ╪ in OrlΘans Sund in reports on the 1909-12 Alabama-ekspeditionen (E. Mikkelsen 1922). See also OrlΘans Sund.

name: OrlΘans Sund
description: Sound between Gamma ╪ and Stormlandet. Named by the 1905 ExpΘdition Arctique du Duc d'OrlΘans as Fiord d'OrlΘans. See Hertugen af OrlΘans Land.

name: Ortlerspids
description: Mountain 1513 m high on north Clavering ╪, named during the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt as Ortler Spitze by Julius Payer, because of its resemblance to mountains he had explored in the Ortler Alps of the Austrian Tyrol. According to Seiden

name: Orvaelv
description: River in Home Forland draining south into Tobias Dal. Named on an NSIU map (1932a) as Orva, possibly after a river of the same name in the Hedmark district of Norway.

name: Orvin Fjµld
description: Name used by Eigil Nielsen (1935) in a report on work carried out on the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, for part of the mountain west of Blσelv, north Hold with Hope.

name: Orvinhytta
description: Norwegian hunting hut on the north side of Sofia Sund, SW of Celcius Bjerg. Built in September 1929 by Arktisk Nµringsdrift, and named after Anders Kristian Orvin [1889-1980], a geologist who worked for NSIU in Spitsbergen and East Greenland, and was dir

name: Oscar Wisting Bjerg
description: Mountain 2512 m high on the NE side of Gerard de Geer Gletscher, named by the 1931 H°ygaard & Mehren expedition as Oscar Wistings Fjell. The name appears to have been applied originally to a mountainous region 20 km NE of the present position. Oscar Adol

name: Ostreaelv
description: River in SE Jameson Land west of Kap Stewart, named by Alfred Rosenkrantz during Lauge Koch's 1926-27 expeditions in the form Ostrea Elv after the fossil oysters. It has also been called Slate River.

name: Oststation
description: Locality in west Jameson Land, the site of Alfred Wegener's 1930-31 eastern scientific station, originally a wooden house. Fuchs (1984) mistakingly identified Lauge Koch's Gurreholm station as this building. The German station was originally put up with

name: Oswald Heer Klinter
description: Low cliffs on the east side of Schuchert Dal. Named during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition by Hans Stauber after Oswald Heer. See also Kap Oswald Heer.

name: Otocerasdal
description: Minor valley on the north slope of Stensi÷ Plateau, NW Hold with Hope, draining into Blσelv. So named by Eigil Nielsen during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen for the finds of fossil æOtoceras'.

name: Liavaag
description: Norwegian hunting station built in 1929 for Arktisk Nµringsdrift beside the 1928 Gσsneshuset, about 1 km north of Kap Wynn. Named after Severin Gaasnes Liavaag, see also Gσsneshuset. The two huts have also been known for their location as Kap Wynn hytter

name: Licht ╪
description: Island in SW Dove Bugt, so named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen. Possibly given for Mathias Kjeldsen de Fine Licht [1859-1917], a lieutenant in the Danish navy and chief pilot (J. L°ve, personal communication 2009). (Lichts ÷, Lichts Island, Lichts

name: Lidskjalv
description: Mountain about 1300 m high in Th. Thomsen Land, east of Odin Dal. The name originated from the wintering party at Kulhus during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, and was given for Odin's throne in Nordic mythology.

name: Lilienthalflya
description: Lower slopes of northern Geographical Society ╪, WSW of Tveholmen (flya = plain). The name is used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937), and commemorates Otto Lilienthal [1848-96], a German pioneer of gliding. His death in a gliding accident was reported to

name: S°ndermarken
description: Triangular area of land south of Nordmarken, between Annekss°en and Valdemarsmuren. The name was apparently a modification of a suggestion by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition.

name: S°nderstrand
description: Flat coastal stretch of south Godfred Hansen ╪. Named during the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition, perhaps by Paul Gelting who visited it in April 1939.

name: S°ndersund
description: Sound south of Godfred Hansen ╪, SW Dove Bugt. Named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition.

name: S°nderσs
description: Ridge in south Canning Land. The name was first used by SΣve-S÷derbergh (1937) in the form Southern Ridge and derives from work during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition.

name: S°ndre Basisdal
description: Valley in SE Canning Land draining south to Carlsberg Fjord. The name appears to have first been used by SΣve-S÷derbergh (1937) in the form S. Basis Valley, and derives from surveying work during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition.

name: S°ndre Biot
description: Norwegian hunting hut on the NW side of Fleming Fjord about 10 km SW of Kap Biot. It was built in September 1954 for Hermann Andresen's expedition, and has also been known as Sur°je, Lapstun Hytten, Fleming Fjord Hytten and Fladestrand.

name: S°ndre Mellemland
description: Southernmost but one part of Hertugen af OrlΘans Land, so named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition.

name: S°ndre Muschelberg
description: South-western of the two low mountains making up Muschelberg, Hochstetter Forland. So named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Hans Frebold. (S°ndre Muslingebjerg.)

name: S°ndre Nµs
description: Name used occasionally in reports of the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen for one of the peninsulas of Danmark Havn, probably ╪stre Havnenµs.

name: S°ndre Orienterings°
description: Southernmost island of the Orienterings°er in Dove Bugt. So named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen.

name: S°plateauet
description: Plateau between Morµnedal and Geologfjord, named by Erdhart FrΣnkl during Lauge Koch's 1948-50 expeditions for the many small lakes. (S°plateau.)

name: S°rensenflya
description: Hillside on Geographical Society ╪, sloping down to Vega Sund NE of Gσse°en (flya = plain). Used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937), the name was given for Sverre S°rensen [b. 1899], a Norwegian hunter who wintered in East Greenland in 1929-31 and 1932-33.

name: S°rkjosen
description: Bay on SE Geographical Society ╪, west of Kap McClintock. Used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937; Fig. 14), and named for its position relative to Nordkjosen a bay to the NW.(S÷rkjosen.)

name: S°ryggen
description: Ridge between two large lakes, Vibeke S° and Krumme Langs°. Named by Heinrich Bⁿtler during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition, originally in the form Seerⁿcken.

name: S°nderelv
description: River SW of Kap Leslie, east Milne Land, draining south. Named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Hermann Aldinger as Sⁿdfluss.

name: S°spidsen
description: Mountain 333 m high on east Sabine ╪. Named by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt as Seespitze, apparently because the summit cliffs descend steeply to the sea below.

name: S°sters°er
description: Two very similar, adjacent lakes in north Dronning Louise Land, named by the 1909-12 Alabama-ekspeditionen (s°ster = sister). (S°sters°erne, S÷sters÷erne.)

name: S°stjernen
description: Island in theeastern part of the Broch ╪er group with a cross-like shape, originally named on the NSIU (1932a) map as Korstrollet. Both Danish and Norwegian names translate as æstarfish'.

name: S°strene
description: Three similar mountain peaks about 1070 m high on a ridge on northern Savoia Halv°. So named by Laurits Bruhn during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen (s°strene = sisters).

name: S°vngµngerbjerg
description: Mountain 1790 m high north of Rolige Brµ. So named by Laurent Jemelin during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions, apparently because the party reached the summit at the end of a long and exhausting day, almost like sleep-walkers.

name: T-S°
description: Large lake shaped like the letter æT' on the north side of inner Nordvestfjord. The name came into use during the 1950s when the lake was used as a landing site for Catalina aeroplanes attached to Lauge Koch's expeditions.

name: Tafelbjerg
description: Mountain 428 m high on NE Sabine ╪. Named by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt as Tafelberg, for its flat top, and possibly also for a mountain of similar name in Austria. (Mt Tafelberg.)

name: Tagbjergene
description: Range of mountains on the south side of Promenadedal, north Hudson Land. Named by Heinrich Bⁿtler during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition (tag = roof).

name: Taget
description: Mountain in the central Werner Bjerge, on the north side of Sirius Gletscher. Named during Lauge Koch's 1953-54 expeditions by Peter Bearth and Eduard Wenk, and climbed by Bearth in 1953 (taget = the roof).

name: Uunarterajik
description: Hot spring close to Kap Tobin, south Liverpool Land. The name was recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, and translates as æthe not particularly hot spring'. The local population are reported to have used the variation Uunardaajik. (█

name: Uunartertaqarteq
description: SE part of Henry Land, north Blosseville Kyst. The name was recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, and translates as æthe place with the hot spring'. (█nartertaqarteq.)

name: Saddle Lake
description: Lake on a col south of Klµgbugt, Nordmarken. Named by the 1987 Irish expedition to northern East Greenland.

name: R°gelen
description: Mountain 552 m high on the east side of Loch Fyne. Named on an NSIU map (1932a) in the form Rugelen, possibly because of the ominous manner in which clouds developed. The approved Danish form suggests æsmoking'.

name: Sadelbjerg
description: Mountain 1181 m high with twin summits in Wollaston Forland. Named by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt as Sattelberg, for its saddle-like shape. The first ascent was made by Julius Payer and Ralph Copeland in September 1869. (Sattelberges,

name: Sadelen
description: Col or pass between Morµnedal and Geologfjord. Named during Lauge Koch's 1948-50 expeditions by Erdhart FrΣnkl. It is said to be the easiest place to reach for a good view of inner Geologfjord (sadelen = the saddle). (Sadlen.)

name: Sadlen
description: Mountain on the south side of M°rkefjord, west of Danmarksmonumentet. The name is found on Charles Poulsen's (1991) map (J. L°ve, personal communication 2009).

name: Spath Plateau
description: Plateau up to 1510 m high in north Hold with Hope. So named by Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions in honour of Leonard Frank Spath [1882-1957], an English palaeontologist and stratigrapher at the British Museum (Natural History), who identified many of Koc

name: Spejderhatten
description: Mountain in AndrΘe Land with the charactersistic shape of a scout's (= spejder) hat. Named by John Haller following explorations during Lauge Koch's 1949-51 expeditions.

name: Spenna
description: Island in the east part of Vega Sund east of Nordenski÷ld ╪. Used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937), and named after an island of the same name in the Troms district of Norway.

name: Sphinx
description: Peak 1920 m high on the south side of Korridoren, Milne Land. Climbed by the 2004 West Lancashire Scouts expedition.

name: Sphinx Gletscher
description: Glacier draining northwards from the mountain Sfinksen in southern AndrΘe Land. The name is found on a sketch drawn by John Haller in 1949, and published in Schwarzenbach (1993).

name: Spiralkl°ft

name: Spiret
description: Mountain on Volquaart Boon Kyst west of Solgletscher, so named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Laurits Bruhn for its appearance (spiret = the spire).

name: Splinten
description: Prominent rock ridge west of Prins Axel Nunatak, Dronning Louise Land (Fig. 21). Named by the 1909-12 Alabama-ekspeditionen for the shape (splinten = the splinter). The ridge was traversed by members of the 1952-54 British North Greenland expedition.

name: Splinten Col
