name: Sporfjeld
description: Mountain north of the mouth of ╪rsted Dal. So named by Hans Stauber during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition, because he had found geological evidence here for a theory previously doubted (spor = track, clue).

name: Sporfjeld Hytte
description: Hut at the entrance of Fleming Fjord below Sporfjeld. See also Lapstun-Hytten.

name: Sporvognen
description: Hut at the mouth of Karupelv, NE of the Haslum ╪er. It was moved to this site from Mestersvig airfield in 1976, and was intended as a holiday hut for airfield personnel. Reported in good condition in 1990.

name: Spuedalen
description: Name used by the 1908-09 FLOREN expedition, probably for one of the valleys west of Kap Borlase Warren. Exact position uncertain. Derived probably from the Norwegian dialect word for a bird of the curlew family.

name: Spurvebugt
description: Small bay on SW Milne Land SW of Mudderbugt. Named during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions by Svend Funder for the numerous snow buntings.

name: Spydodden
description: Elongate peninsula south of the mouth of Hellefjord, so named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen because it resembles in shape the point of a spear. A Nanok hut a few kilometres to the south at the mouth of Port Arthur is sometimes known by the name Sp

name: Spyd°en
description: Small island north of the north point of Spydodden, off east Daniel Bruun Land. Named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition. (Spyd°.)

name: Wendel Pynt
description: Peninsula west of Danmark Havn, south of Harefjeldet. Named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen as Wendels Pynt, possibly after Andreas C.D. Wendel of the Royal dockyard (J. L°ve, personal communication 2009).

name: Scoresby Land
description: Land area bounded to the north by Kong Oscar Fjord and Alpefjord, and to the south by Scoresby Sund and Nordvestfjord. The west boundary runs from Borgbjerg Gletscher via Prinsessegletscher to Alpefjord. The official usage defined in 1961 includes the St

name: Scoresby Sund
description: Major fjord up to 40 km wide leading west and NW to an extensive fjord system. Named by William Scoresby Jr. in 1822 as Scoresby's Sound after his father, who he describes as the original discoverer, and the first navigator to enter it. William Scoresby

name: Scoresbysund
description: Town in south Liverpool Land in the NE part of Rosenvinge Bugt, north of the mouth of Scoresby Sund. The first houses were built by the expedition that founded Scoresbysund in 1924-25, and settled by a group of about 70 Greenlanders from Ammassalik in 1

name: Scoresbysundvarden
description: Cairn at the mouth of Vardedalen on the north side of Ingolf Fjord. The name was given by Elmar Drastrup's 1938-39 expedition for the Scoresbysund Committee, which had given support to his expedition. The cairn was not observed by a geological party that

name: Scorpio
description: Mountain about 2302 m high west of the head of Jupiter Gletscher, southern Stauning Alper. Named and first climbed by the 1975 Scottish Scoresby Land expedition led by E.A.M. Walker for the constellation of the zodiac.

name: Scorpio Glacier
description: Glacier in the Stauning Alper flowing west to join Duart Gletscher at its confluence with Spµrregletscher. Named by James Clarkson's 1961 expedition for Scorpius, a constellation of the zodiac.

name: Scotstounhill
description: Large nunatak 1254 m high in Wordie Gletscher NW of Jordanhill. Named by J.M. Wordie's 1926 Cambridge expedition for the Scottish locality, which is spelt æScotston Hill' on modern maps.

name: Scott Bjerg
description: Mountain massif 1723 m high on Ymer ╪, south of DusΘn Fjord. Named by Peter Friend during his 1968-70 expeditions after Scott Polar Research Institute, Cambridge, at which he was based. The institute was founded in 1920 with the balance of proceeds of th

name: Scott Keltie ╪er
description: Island group in Vega Sund (Fig. 12). Named by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst as Scott Kelties ╓ar after John Scott Keltie [1840-1927]. Keltie was secretary of the Royal Geographical Society 1892-1915, and its increasing p

name: Scott's Inlet
description: This was the name used by William Scoresby Jr. in 1822 for Gael Hamke Bugt, and it featured for a short period (1872-75) on British Admiralty charts. It was named in honour of Sir Walter Scott [1771-1832], Scottish historical novelist and poet, perhaps m

name: Scout Centenary
description: Summit 2016 m high on the north side of Edward Bailey Gletscher, Renland. Climbed and named by the 2007 West Lancashire Mountaineering Group Expedition.

name: Seanearbheinn
description: Peak 2350 m high in the upper reaches of Sefstr÷m Gletscher, Stauning Alper. Climbed by the 1998 Scottish Mountaineering Club expedition.

name: Lille Blydal
description: Valley in northern Scoresby Land draining northwards into Noret. It is separated from Store Blydal by a low pass. Named by prospecting teams associated with Lauge Koch's 1948-49 expeditions.

name: Lille Bµlt
description: Sound between Lille Koldewey and Store Koldewey. Named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen, and first used in the hydrographical report by Trolle (1913). Named after the sound of the same name in Denmark between the island of Fyn and Jylland. See also S

name: Lille Cervin
description: Mountain about 1600 m high in northern Frµnkel Land on the south side of Jµttegletscher (Fig. 58). The name apparently arose independently from two sources, Laurits Bruhn of the Geodµtisk Institut and Noel E. Odell. Both remarked on its resemblance to th

name: Lille Cirkusbjerg
description: Mountain on south Wegener Halv°, named during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition by Gunnar SΣve-S÷derbergh (1937) as Little Circus Mountain.

name: Lille Finsch ╪
description: Next largest of the Finsch ╪er. Distinguished first on maps of Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions as Little Finsch Island, and on Norwegian charts as Vesle Finsch; the name was briefly in use as an approved name, but later discontinued.

name: Lille Kl°ft
description: Small ravine on the west side of Hurry Inlet, north of Moskusoksekl°ft. The name was used in a report by Heinrich Aldinger (1935) on work during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen.

name: Lille Koldewey
description: Two islands separated by a narrow sound, R°sel°bet, situated NE of Store Koldewey. So named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen. North Koldewey Island was used by Amdrup (1913) for the same feature. A depot left on the east coast of the northern island

name: Lille Myteklippe
description: Cliff on the south coast of Kaskades°, western Gσseland. So named during Lauge Koch's 1958 expedition by Eduard Wenk, because it and the adjacent cliff (Store Myteklippe) were in their shape and tectonic relationships similar to the Grossen Mythen and Kl

name: Lille Noa S°
description: Name occasionally used by Eha (1953) for a small lake east of Noa S° in Ymer ╪, but first used by Andersen (1937) in the form Kleine Noa See.

name: Lille Oksedal
description: Valley draining from Oksehorn into the north side of Kolledal. So named during Lauge Koch's 1953-54 expeditions by Peter Bearth and Eduard Wenk, because of the numerous muskox calves seen here. Officially it is considered to be identical to R°dedal, alth

name: Lille Pendulum
description: Island NE of Sabine ╪, part of the Pendulum ╪er group. Named by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt as Kleine Pendulum Insel (Fig. 6), possibly an unfortunate choice of name as the original pendulum experiments were carried out on the present

name: Lille Petermann
description: Pronounced peak 2700 m high on the west side of Nordenski÷ld Gletscher, SW of Petermann Bjerg (Figs 65, 69). Named by J.M. Wordie's 1929 Cambridge expedition as Little Petermann, and approved in the 1950s at the suggestion of John Haller.

name: Lille Ravnefjeld
description: Mountain 3 km SW of Ravnefjeld, Wegener Halv°. Named during the Lauge Koch expeditions in the 1950s by Rudolf Trⁿmpy.

name: Lille Skibss°
description: Small lake at Danmarkshavn, immediately SW of Skibss°. The name was suggested by Hans Meltofte in 1972, who also noted that the lake was often referred to by the staff at Danmarkshavn weather station in 1969-71 as Lille Vands°. Fischer (1983) notes it wa

name: Lille Snenµs
description: Peninsula east of Lumskebugten on the south coast of Germania Land. So named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen, because it was often confused with nearby Snenµs (Thostrup 2007). It is now a noted haul-out locality for walrus. Up to 48 walruses have be

name: Lille Snenµshytten
description: Danish hunting hut at Lille Snenµs on the south coast of Germania Land. Built by Nanok in October 1939.

name: Lille Stu
description: Small Norwegian hunting hut at the head of Isfjord, on the east side of Gerard de Geer Gletscher, built in March 1940 for Arktisk Nµringsdrift (lille stu = small room). It has also been known as Isfjordhytten.

name: Mountain 1
description: Informal name used by Eha (1953) for a mountain in east Suess Land, in his report on work during Lauge Koch's 1947-49 expedition.

name: Mountain 2
description: Informal name used by Eha (1953) for a mountain in east Suess Land, in his report on work during Lauge Koch's 1947-49 expedition.

name: Mountnorris Fjord
description: Fjord on SE Traill ╪. Named by William Scoresby Jr. in 1822 as Mountnorris Inlet in honour of Lord Mountnorris (Fig. 12). This was possibly Lord George Annesley, Earl of Moutnorris [1769-1844], noted for his voyages to India and Ceylon. (Mountnorris Einb

name: Uunartertaqartikajiip Oqqummut Kangertiva
description: Fjord south of Henry Land, north Blosseville Kyst. One of the names recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, it translates roughly as æthe sheltered little fjord south of the place with the hot spring'. (█nartertaqartikajεp orqunqmut ka

name: Uunartip Nuaa
description: Southernmost cape of Liverpool Land. Recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, the name translates as æthe cape at the hot springs'. (█nartip n√a.)

name: 1V, 2V, 3V, 4V, 5V, 6V, 7V, 8V
description: Designations used on 1:15 000 maps of the Mesters Vig region printed in 1951 for eight rivers west of Expeditionshus flowing SE into Mesters Vig. On some maps (e.g. Bondam 1955) they appear as 1 Vest - 7 Vest. Of these, river 2V was subsequently approved

name: V. Clausen Fjord
description: Small fjord branch in the inner part of Skµrfjord, named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen after Viggo Clausen [1875-1920], an officer in the Danish navy (J. L°ve, personal communication 2009). (V. Clausens Fjord).

name: Vadrettal
description: Valley in Gletscherland on the west side of Rhedin Fjord with a glacier at the head. So named by EugΘne Wegmann during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen after a Swiss locality of the same name. æVadret' is a local Italian/Romansch name for a glacier.

name: Vagtpasset
description: Col between Vedetten and Knoen, Goodenough Land. Named by J.M. Wordie's 1929 Cambridge expedition as Sentinel Col because of its proximity to the mountain Sentinel, now Vedetten.

name: VΣhfreude
description: Mountain west of Findelen S°, Goodenough Land. So named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by EugΦne Wegmann after æDie KΣserei in der Vehfreude', a noted novel of the 19th century by Jeremias Gotthelf. Vehfreude was a place very far away where the a

name: Valborghytta
description: Norwegian hunting hut in NW Geographical Society ╪, built in September 1930 by Arktisk Nµringsdrift. It is reported to have been named after one of the hunters' homes in Norway. It is also known as R°vballehytten, Svedenborg and Joplassen. (Valborghytten

name: Valdemarsmuren
description: Eastern edge of the highland area of S°ndermarken, forming the west border of Slµdelandet. Named by the 1938-39 M°rkeford expedition, the name derives from the Valdemarsmuren, the main rampart of the Dannevirke, Sydslesvig, Germany. The Dannevirke earth

name: Valdemarshaab
description: Danish hunting station built by ╪stgr°nlandske Fangstkompagni at Kap Borlase Warren in 1922, and taken down in 1923. It was replaced by a new hut built at Sandodden, Ny Valdemarshaab, now known as Sandodden. Both stations were named after Arner Ludvig Va

name: Valhal
description: Ice plateau south of inner Grandjean Fjord. The name originated from the wintering party at Kulhus during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen and was given for the ævalhalla' of Nordic mythology, the home of the gods.

name: Valhallbreen
description: Name given to a northern branch of Roslin Gletscher by the 1996 Norwegian Stauning Alper expedition. See Valhal.

name: Valmuehytten
description: Hut built by Sirius in 1955 or 1956 on eastern Geographical Society ╪, 3 km west of Kap MacClintock (valmue = poppy). It is also known as Kap Mac Clintock Hytten.

name: Van Hauens Fjeld
description: Name occasionally used by Danish hunters in the 1930s for Nordre Muschelbjerg, Hochstetter Forland. James van Hauen was a hunter with Nanok from 1929 to 1931.

name: Vandfaldsklippe
description: Cliff on the east side of Graben Land, where a large river falls over the cliff edge to Eielson Gletscher. Named by Peter Homewood during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions.

name: Vandhulkl°ft
description: Ravine on the north side of the front of Bj°rnbo Gletscher. So named by Enrico Kempter during Lauge Koch's 1956-58 expeditions, because the river has eroded a hole through the Permian arkoses to expose an inlier of crystalline rocks.

name: Vandreblok
description: Ice-transported boulder on the low ridge between ╪stelv and ╪sthavn, east of Eskimonµs station, south Clavering ╪. The name originated from the wintering party at Eskimonµs during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen (vandre = wander, travel).

name: Vandreblokken
description: Large, ice-transported boulder 15 ╫ 10 ╫ 5 m in size on the SW coast of Jameson Land. Named by the 1898-1900 Carlsbergfondets Expedition as Vandreblok.

name: Vandredalen
description: Extensive N-S valley west of the alpine mountains of Kronprins Christian Land, extending from Marmorvigen to the head of Ingolf Fjord and northwards to Romer S°. Named by Elmar Drastrup's 1938-39 expedition who traversed the valley in 1939 and considered

name: Vandrepasset
description: Pass in N°rlund Land between inner Bessel Fjord and Knµks°. The name originated from the wintering party at Kulhus during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen (vandre = wander, travel).

name: Vandskels°
description: Ice-dammed lake in Frederiksdal, Nathorst Land. Named during Lauge Koch's 1954-55 expeditions by Hans Zweifel. The lake lies on the watershed (= vandskel), and when full can overflow southwards; when the glacier dam is broken it drains to the north.

name: Spµrrebugt
description: Bay on the south side of Lillefjord, on the coast of SE Liverpool Land. Named by Helge G. Backlund who explored this region during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen (spµrre = obstruct, block). (Spoerrebugt.)

name: Spµrregletscher
description: Large glacier which forms a complete barrier (= spµrre) across the east end of Fures°. Named by Ove Simonsen during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen.

name: St. Andrews Klippe
description: Large cliff on the north side of Budolfi Isstr°m, Dronning Louise Land (Fig. 21). Named by the 1952-54 British North Greenland expedition after the University of St Andrews, Scotland's oldest university founded in 1410 as St. Mary's College. One of the e

name: St. Bartholomews Tσrn
description: Rock peak with twin summits about 2440 m high SW of Crescent Pas, Stauning Alper. Named by the 1963 Cambridge University expedition who climbed it on 23 August. (St. Bartholomew's Tower, Torre di S. Bartolomeo.)

name: St. Johns Tinde
description: Peak 2200 m high on the NE side of Cavendish Gletscher, Stauning Alper. Climbed by the 1963 Cambridge expedition on 20 August, and named after St John's College, Cambridge, founded in 1511 on the site of the Hospital of St. John. Official name lists omit

name: Stabbene
description: Name used by the 1908-09 FLOREN expedition for basalt columns in the vicinity of Kap Borlase Warren. The Norwegian word translates as something short or stubby. Exact position uncertain.

name: Stakkarsdalen
description: This name was apparently used by the 1908-09 Floren expedition for Dronning Augustadalen in Wollaston Forland (Brandal 1930).

name: Theodolite Hills
description: Minor range of hills in south Jameson Land west of the mouth of Raukelv. So named by Herman Aldingerer (1935) during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, probably because the hills were used during surveying.

name: Theodolitplateau
description: NW plateau area of Clavering ╪ rising to about 700 m. Named by Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions in the form Theodolit Plateau because Oskar Kulling began a series of theodolite measurements here. (Theodolith÷gda.)

name: Theodolitskµr
description: Small, rocky island south of Joinville ╪ in Skµrfjorden. So named by David Malmquist during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, presumably because theodolite measurements were made here. (Theodolitskµrene.)

name: Theresabjerg
description: Mountain in north Scoresby Land, on the west side of Majdal. Named by Hans Kapp during the 1957-58 Lauge Koch expeditions. Girl's name.

name: Third River
description: Name used by University of Dundee expeditions between 1968 and 1974 for a minor stream draining into Holm Bugt, SW Traill ╪.

name: Thomas Bjerg
description: Summit on the ridge between Aldebaren Gletscher and Breithorn Gletscher, south Werner Bjerge. Named during Lauge Koch's 1953-54 expeditions by Peter Bearth and Eduard Wenk, probably for a friend, although officially it was said to be for the æThomas proc

name: Thomas Thomsen Nµs
description: Peninsula on the NE coast of Germania Land with large Inuit ruins. So named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen after Thomas Marius Thomsen [1870-1941], a Danish archaeologist who had assisted in the preparation of a report on the expedition's finds (Th

name: Thomson Klippe
description: Cliff on the north side of Admiralty Gletscher, NW Dronning Louise Land (Fig. 21). One of the names given by the 1952-54 British North Greenland expedition for notable scientists, it commemorates the British physicist Sir Joseph John Thomson [1856-1940],

name: Thora ╪
description: Small island in Vega Sund. Name proposed by S°kortarkivet in 1956-57 following surveying of the channel through Vega Sund as an alternative approach for ships en route to Nyhavn. It was given for the THORA DAN, a 5050-ton polar ship built in 1956 for the

name: Thorolf Vogts Bugt
description: Name occasionally used by Norwegian hunters for a small bay on Geographical Society ╪ where the Richter-hytta was built in September 1929.

name: Thorshanes°
description: Small lake on SW Milne Land. Named during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions by Max Fumasoli for the numerous grey phalarope (= thorshane) observed here.

name: Thorshanes°
description: Small lake on Winge Kyst in south Germania Land. So named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen for the grey phalarope, observed to be breeding in this and other small lakes in 1907 and 1908.

name: Thorsten ╪
description: Small island off NE Lambert Land, the present Panorama°. The name was used by the 1996 Mylius-Erichsen's Mindeekspedition, who misplaced their Panorama° northwards to the present Gamle Jim ╪er.

name: Thorstensenvika
description: Innermost part of Cambridge Bugt in east Geographical Society ╪. So named on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937) for John Thorstensen [b. 1907], a Norwegian telegraphist who manned the Myggbukta radio station in 1932-33.

name: Sechsspitze
description: Name used by Danish hunters for Kronebjerg on west Sabine ╪, because of the many pinnacles which make up the summit (sechs = six). Sevenspits has also been recorded.

name: Store S°dal
description: Valley containing two large lakes, situated north of and parallel to Tyrolerfjord. The name first appeared in a botanical report by Gelting (1934) on work during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen as Great Lake Valley. (Store S÷dal.)

name: Store Vinter÷ya
description: Larger of the two Vinter°er at the mouth of DusΘn Fjord. So named on the 1932a NSIU map for its relative size.

name: Storedal
description: Term employed by Pessl (1962) for the present Deltadal, which drains into Mesters Vig.

name: Storeelv
description: River on NW Ella ╪, draining into Solitµrbugt. It was so named by the Ella ╪ wintering party during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, because it is the largest river on the island.

name: Storefjord
description: Major E-W-trending fjord which cuts through the mountain range of Liverpool Land. The name first appeared on a map compiled by Janus S°rensen in 1928, although the mouth of the fjord had been seen by William Scoresby Jr. in 1822 (his Masclet Bay). The fj

name: Storelv
description: River draining Stordal, east Hudson Land. Named by Heinrich Bⁿtler during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition, and first used in the form Stortalfluss.

name: Storelvhytten
description: Danish hunting hut built in May 1947 for Nanok on the north side of Storelv. It is also known as Arvehytten and Vuachehytten.

name: Storgletscher
description: Large glacier in the Stauning Alper draining east to Schuchert Dal. Bjorn Jorsalfarers Gletscher and Langgletscher have been used for the same feature (both as officially approved names), but in 1971 Storgletscher became the only recognised name.

name: Storgaard Elv
description: Small river in SE Jameson Land NW of Kap Stewart. Named by Alfred Rosenkrantz during Lauge Koch's 1926-27 expeditions after Einar Storgaard [1890-1981]. An eminent Danish geographer, Storgaard travelled widely in Asia and Africa and had particular intere

name: Storhamrene
description: Steep cliffs of SW Renland, on the north side of ╪fjord. Named during the 1963 Geodµtisk Institut expedition after the cliffs of the same name in Bornholm.

name: Storholts Hus
description: Norwegian hunting hut built in August 1954 by Sverre Storholt for Arktisk Nµringsdrift. It is situated about 5 km SE of Kap ╪tker, and replaced an older hut known as Nesodden. It is also known as Kap ╪tker Hytten.

name: Storlandet
description: Name given by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition for the highland area west of Valdemarsmuren, covering the areas of both present S°ndermarken and Okselandet.

name: Storm P. Elv
description: River formed by the confluence of Peter Elv and Ping Elv, SW of Mesters Vig. Named by prospecting teams associated with Lauge Koch's 1948-49 expeditions. Robert Storm Petersen [1882-1949], a Danish artist and writer always known as æStorm P.', was especi

name: Stormbu
description: Norwegian hunting hut built by Oscar Bang and Eiliv Herdal for Arktisk Nµringsdrift in October 1938, on Vestersletten near Fl°elv. So named because it survived a severe storm on the night it was built. Bang (1944) reports that two earlier huts on the sam

name: Stormbugt
description: Bay north of the Koldewey ╪er, NW of Kap Bismarck. Named Sturmbai by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt, because the sledge party was delayed by a three-day storm here in April 1870. (Stormbugten, Storm Bay, Stormvik.)

name: Stormbugthytten
description: Danish hunting hut east of the mouth of Stormelv, in Stormbugt on the south coast of Germania Land. Built in September 1939 for Nanok, it has also been known as Stormelvshytten and Stormely-hytten.

name: Stormdal
description: Minor valley on east Traill ╪ on the north side of Mountnorris Fjord. Named by Hans P. Schaub during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition, presumably for a storm experienced while working here.

name: Stormdalen
description: Valley in south Hold with Hope, so named on an NSIU map (1932a; Fig. 1932NSIU). Possibly named after Erik Storm [1904-36], a Norwegian pilot. See also Stormfjellet.

name: Stormdalen
description: Valley in south Germania Land, in which Stormelv flows. Named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition.

name: Stormelv
description: River in south Germania Land draining into Stormbugt. So named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen for its proximity to Stormbugt. (Stormkapelv, Storm River, Stormelven, Stormß.)

name: Stormfjellet
description: Mountain 1100 m high on north Clavering ╪. Used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937), the name was given for Erik Storm [1904-36], a Norwegian pilot who led and organised the 1932 NSIU aerial photography.

name: Stormgletscher
description: Glacier west of the head of Bredefjord. The name originated from the wintering party at Kulhus during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen.

name: Stormheimen
description: Norwegian hunting hut built in March 1953 about 12 km south of Kap Pansch, on the east coast of Shannon. Just after they had built the hut, the three hunters involved experienced a violent snow-storm.

name: Mozart Dal
description: Long valley in Dronning Louise Land running from Farimagsdal to L. Bistrup Brµ (Fig. 21). One of the names given by the 1952-54 British North Greenland Expedition for composers, it commemorates Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart [1756-91], regarded as one of the gr

name: Mudderbugt
description: Bay on the SE coast of Milne Land. So named by the 1891-92 Den ╪stgr°nlandske expedition led by Carl Ryder because it was very shallow and so full of clay and sand it was impossible to land in their boat.

name: Mⁿhldorfer Spids
description: Mountain on the south side of the col between Spµrregletscher and upper Bj°rnbo Gletscher. Climbed by the 1966 Deutsche Gr÷nland-Expedition in die Staunings-Alpen led by Karl M. Herligkoffer on 19 August, and named after the Bavarian town of Mⁿhldorf, ho

name: Munatius Plancus Tinde
description: Peak 1067 m high on the south side of Kaskades°, west Gσseland. It was climbed, and so named, by Eduard Wenk during Lauge Koch's 1958 expedition to honour the founder of the city of Basel on its 2000 years anniversary. Lucius Munatius Plancus founded the

name: Mⁿnchner Tinde
description: Mountain about 2500 m high on the east side of the upper basin of Spµrregletscher, Stauning Alper. Climbed by the 1966 Deutsche Gr÷nland-Expedition in die Staunings-Alpen led by Karl M. Herligkoffer, and named after Mⁿnchen (Munich), the capital city of

name: Mundingshytten
description: Danish hunting hut on the south side of the mouth (= munding) of Bessel Fjord, built by Nanok in September 1932. This hut and a Norwegian hut nearby (Perka Hytta) are sometimes referred to as Mundingshytter i Besselfjorden. Now a ruin. (Mundinghytten.)

name: Munin
description: Mountain on the west side of Odin Dal, Th. Thomsen Land. The name originated from the wintering party at Kulhus during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen. See also Munin S°.

name: Munin S°
description: Lake in Jameson Land south of Fegin Elv. Named during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions by Svend Funder, in style with nearby Fegin Elv and Lodin Elv. Munin and Hugin were Odin's two ravens in old Nordic mythology, which every morning left his sh

name: Munkekutten
description: Mountain 1555 m high north of Rolige Brµ. So named by Laurent Jemelin during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions because the summit ice cap was reminiscent of a monk's cowl.

name: Munotbjerg
description: Mountain about 1150 m high on SW Ymer ╪, east of Margerie Dal. Named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by EugΦne Wegmann as Munot Mountain, after the castle in Schaffhausen, Switzerland.

name: Murbjerg
description: Mountain 853 m high on the north side of Dronning Augustadalen in Wollaston Forland. Named by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt as Mauer Berg, possibly because of the steep wall-like appearance of its north side. Frebold (1932) used the vari

name: Murchison Bjerge
description: Group of mountains in the NW Stauning Alper. Named by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst as Murchisons Berg after Sir Roderick Impey Murchison [1792-1871], a British geologist most noted for æThe Silurian System' published in

name: Murgangsdalen
description: Valley in south Suess Land. Named by EugΘne Wegmann for the mud slide (= murgang) of 1932, caused by the sudden emptying of a glacier-dammed lake (Murgangss°) in inner Suess Land. The slide filled the entire valley with water several metres deep, and was
