description: Nunatak on the north side of Vestfjord Gletscher. So named during Lauge Koch's 1958 expedition by Eduard Wenk, because of the strong winds experienced here.

name: Vindsel°en
description: Island in NW Dove Bugt, so named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen for its shape (vindsel = reel). (Vindsel÷en, Vindsel Island, Vindselseyra.)

name: Vindsel°hytten
description: Danish hunting hut on the east coast of Vindsel°en, NW Dove Bugt, built by Nanok in November 1938. A very small hut, it has now disappeared. (Vindsel° hytten.)

name: Vindslugten
description: Outflow gap at the SW corner of Geikie Plateau, on the divide between Magga Brµ and Bartholin Brµ. It was named so by the 1969 Watkins Bjerge expedition, because they were held up here by a prolonged blizzard. (Windy Gap.)

name: Vindue Gletscher
description: Glacier running along the west and north side of Graben Land. So named by Peter Homewood during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions because several geological æwindows' exposing older rocks occur beside the glacier.

name: Vindue Nunatak
description: Nunatak west of Vindue Gletscher where older, geological formations are exposed by erosion through a thrust, a so-called æwindow'. Named by Peter Homewood during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions.

name: Vindueskarmen
description: Mountain on the east side of the Werner Bjerge, south of Blomsterdal. Named by Peter Bearth and Eduard Wenk during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition, originally as Sill-Ryggen for the numerous basalt sills, subsequently corrupted to Vindueskarmen (= window

name: SΣve S÷derbergh Bjerg
description: Mountain on eastern Gauss Halv°, south of Agassiz Bjerg. The name is attributed to Heinrich Bⁿtler, and arose during his work with Lauge Koch in the 1950s. It commemorates Gunnar SΣve-S÷derbergh [1910-48], a Swedish palaeontologist who participated in La

name: SalΦvebjerg
description: Mountain in SE Hudson Land, so named by Heinrich Bⁿtler during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition after Mont SalΦve, a mountain SE of Geneva, Switzerland. (SalΦveberg.)

name: Salix Dal
description: Minor valley in SW Jameson Land draining into Sjµllandselv. Named during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions by Tove Birkelund, for the unusually rich willow vegetation.

name: Sandbach Halv°
description: Prominent peninsula between Vejle Fjord and Kolding Fjord in Liverpool Land. Named Sandbach Island by William Scoresby Jr. in 1822 after a much respected friend. The æisland' was later found to be a peninsula (= halv°). (Sandbach ╓.)

name: Sanddal
description: Valley in Hertugen af OrlΘans Land. So named during Lauge Koch's 1956-58 expeditions by John Haller, because the valley was full of sandy alluvium.

name: Sanddalen
description: Valley on the north side of Geographical Society ╪, so named by NSIU in 1930 because of the deposits of sand at its mouth. Norwegian and Danish botanists have used the name as a reference locality. (Sanddal.)

name: Sanderling River
description: Name used by University of Dundee expeditions between 1968 and 1974 for a minor stream west of Karupelv draining into Holm Bugt, SW Traill ╪. It was named after the common wading bird (Calidris alba).

name: Sandertoppene
description: Mountain summits in north Lyell Land south of Kap Alfred. Named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by EugΦne Wegmann as Sander Peaks, after Bruno Hermann Max Sander [1884-1979], a noted Austrian mineralogist and petrologist.

name: Sandgletscher
description: Glacier on the west side of Schaffhauserdalen, with extensive sand and gravel moraines at its front. So named by John Haller following explorations during Lauge Koch's 1954 expedition, because he was stranded here with Fritz Schwarzenbach for three days

name: Sandodden
description: Pronounced sandy peninsula on the SE coast of Milne Land. Named by the 1891-92 Den ╪stgr°nlandske expedition as Sandodde.

name: Trolddal
description: Valley west of Turner ╪ on the Blosseville Kyst, used by Malcolm Slesser's party in 1969 on their route to Skottepasset and Steno Gletscher. Slesser describes it as a beautiful valley with an eerie cirque at its head, a suitable abode for trolls (trold =

name: Troldedal
description: Valley in N°rlund Land draining into the head of Agnete S°. The name originated from the wintering party at Kulhus during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, and was approved for many years in the form Troldedalen.

name: Troldehaven
description: Complex of islands south of Stor°en. Named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition led by Ebbe Munck and Eigil Knuth, and described on a spring sledge journey as resembling a fairy tale town of castles and houses of different styles and ages which would mer

name: Wenkhorn
description: Mountain in southern AndrΘe Land. The name appears on a panorama drawn by John Haller in 1949, reproduced in Schwarzenbach (1993). It was intended as a tribute to John Haller's professor at the University of Basel, Eduard Wenk [1907-2001].

name: Werenskioldflya
description: Land area on SE Geographical Society ╪, immediately NW of Kap McClintock. So named on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937) after the brothers Werner and Dagfin Werenskiold. See Dagfinvika and Wernernatnet.

name: Werner Bjerge
description: High mountain range in Scoresby Land east of the Stauning Alper. William Scoresby Jr. noted these as the most elevated mountains he had seen upon the East Greenland coast in 1822, and gave them the name Werner Mountains, in respect to the memory of the c

name: Wernervatnet
description: Lake on SE Geographical Society ╪, WNW of Kap McClintock. Used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937), the name was given for Werner Werenskiold [1883-1961], a Norwegian geologist, geographer and glaciologist, and professor at Oslo University, who participated

name: West Gletscher
description: Name used on 1957 AMS maps for the present Daugaard-Jensen Gletscher at the head of Nordvestfjord.

name: West Pond
description: Name used by Dundee University expeditions between 1968 and 1974 for a small pool near Langdyssen at the NE end of Mestersvig airfield.

name: Westbrooks Varde
description: Cairn on the 760 m high summit south of the mouth of Berg Fjord, built in 1941 and with the NW side originally painted yellow. The name is used in Den Gr°nlandske Lods (1968), and the cairn may have been built by the crew of the NORTHLAND. The cairn was

name: Westendspids
description: Mountain 1404 m high at the west end of Blσbµrdalen. Named by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt as Westend Spitze, possibly because it was one of the westernmost points surveyed in the terrain mapped by the expedition. It was climbed by Juli

name: Western Circus Valley
description: Name used by Gunnar SΣve-S÷derbergh during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, together with Eastern Circus Valley, for cirque valleys on the north slopes of Celcius Bjerg, Ymer ╪.

name: Western Upper Terrace
description: Kochi-Ridge, Double Ravine, Eastern Upper Terrace, Large Debris Cone, East Plateau, Kulisserna/Coulisse and Western Upper Terrace are a series of reference localities on the north and south slope of Celcius Bjerg, Ymer ╪. They were used during the 1931-3

name: Western°ya
description: Island off the coast of SE Geographical Society ╪, north of Kap McClintock. Used on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937), the name was given for Bj°rn Western [b. 1913], Norwegian telegraphist on a 1932-34 hunting expedition to East Greenland, and in 1935-36

name: Westfal-Larsen Nunatak
description: Nunatak west of J.L. Mowinckel Land, named by the 1931 H°ygaard & Mehren expedition after the noted Norwegian company founded by Hans Westfal-Larsen in 1905. (Westfal-Larsens Nunatak.)

name: Westliche Schwarze Hⁿgel
description: Name used by Vischer (1943) for the mountains on the west side of Storsletten, Wollaston Forland. The name derives from work by Wolf Maync and Andreas Vischer during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition.

name: Westminster
description: Mountain 2500 m high between Bersµrkerbrµ and Schuchert Gletscher, Stauning Alper, which Bennet (1972) considered identical with Royal Peak climbed by the 1961 Bangor JMC expedition. However, some climbers consider Westminster to be a subsidiary summit a

name: Weydmannsburg
description: Mountain about 2700 m high on the NE side of Sefstr÷m Gletscher, so named and climbed by the 1964 AAC Zⁿrich expedition. It is close to and may be the same as Korsspids or Weisse Wand (Bennet 1972).

name: White
description: Mountain about 2000 m high at the head of Gannochy Gletscher, central Stauning Alper. Named for the colour by the 1968 University of Dundee expedition who made the first ascent.

name: Otto Johnsenvika
description: Broad, open bay on the north coast of Geographical Society ╪, SE of Robertson ╪. Used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937), and named after Otto Johnsen [b. 1901], a Norwegian hunter who wintered in East Greenland from 1929 to 1931 and 1932 to 1934.

name: Ottostrand
description: Norwegian hunting station south of Haystack on the east coast of Hochstetter Forland, one of John Giµver's main stations built in 1932. It was manned in the periods 1932-34, 1938-39 and 1948-53. The name commemorates the Norwegian hunter Otto Johnsen. Th

name: Overgangsdal
description: Valley on the north side of the front of Bj°rnbo Gletscher, close to the boundary between crystalline and sedimentary rocks (overgang = transition). Named by Enrico Kempter during Lauge Koch's 1956-58 expeditions.

name: Overk°rslen
description: Name sometimes used for the low col between inner Nathorst Fjord and Carlsberg Fjord, an easy sledge route.

name: Overk°rslen
description: Low col east of Danmarkshavn, so named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen. This was the pass used by sledge parties proceeding northwards from Danmark Havn to lay out depots. (Overk÷rslen.)

name: Oxford Gletscher
description: Glacier in the south Stauning Alper, draining south into the east end of Nordvestfjord. Named by the 1962 Oxford University expedition, which undertook survey work on the glacier. Oxford University is one of the world's oldest and most prestigious univer

name: P.K. Larsen Pynt
description: South cape of Renskµret, south of Danmark Havn. Named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen as P.K. Larsens Pynt. Origin unknown.

name: Pad Lochan
description: Name used by Dundee University expeditions between 1968 and 1974 for a temporary water pool between Mestersvig airfield and Langdyssen.

name: Pain de Sucre
description: Isolated nunatak in Charcot Gletscher, east Milne Land. The name was used in the report by Parat & Drach (1934), and presumably derives from its colour and shape (pain de sucre = sugar loaf).

name: Palasip Qammavaajua
description: Cape on the west side of Ittoqqortoormiit [Scoresbysund], close to Ferslew Pynt. Recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, the name means æthe priest's hunting place', and was the locality where the settlement's first priest, Sejr Abelse

name: Palatinus
description: Mountain 2600 m high in the north Stauning Alper, NW of Korsspids at the head of Cavendish Gletscher. Climbed on 26 July by Sandro Pucci's 1984 expedition.

name: Paletten
description: Group of nunataks in SW Dronning Louise Land (Fig. 21). The name was given by the 1952-54 British North Greenland expedition because the different coloured rocks forming the nunataks seemed to bare some resemblance to an artist's palette.

name: Palisaderne
description: Peninsula on the north side of Holm Bugt, SW Traill ╪. The name was proposed by S°kortarkivet in 1956-57 following surveying of the channel through Vega Sund as an alternative approach for ships en route to Nyhavn (palisaderne = the palisades).

name: Palisaderne
description: Range of mountains on the west side of S°dalen. Named by Eigil Nielsen during the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition for its appearance.

name: Palldal
description: Valley in NW Jameson Land draining in Schuchert Dal, the present Major Paars Dal. So named during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition by Hans Stauber (Stauber 1940), because it was the winter pony route to ╪rsteddal used by Pall Pallson of Reykjavik, who loo

name: Palnatoke Bjerg
description: Mountain 1056 m high in NW Wollaston Forland. The name was proposed by the Place Name Committee in 1939 to replace a suggestion by Wolf Maync and Andreas Vischer, and commemorates the Danish saga hero, Palnatoke (Toke Palness°n), founder of Jomsborg, and

name: Palnatokeelv
description: River draining the slopes of Palnatoke Bjerg, north of Zackenberg Forskningsstation. The name is used as a reference locality by visiting scientists.

name: Pannekaka
description: Small skerry off the coast of east Ymer ╪, so named on the 1932a NSIU map for its pancake-like shape.

name: Panorama Lake
description: Lake on Store Koldewey where sampling was undertaken for phytoplankton studies (Cremer et al. 2005).

name: Panoramafjeld
description: Mountain in east AndrΘe Land, west of the mouth of Grejsdalen. It was named by Erdhardt FrΣnkl during Lauge Koch's 1948-50 expeditions for the view.

name: Panorama°
description: Small island near NE Lambert Land. Named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition, possibly by Svend S°lver who took a series of photographs here.

name: Panoramic Peak
description: Peak 1700 m high on the east side of Bersµrkerbrµ, north Stauning Alper, climbed by the 1967 Toni Gobbi expedition.

name: Parachute Ponds
description: Series of small ponds on the west side of the river draining Holger Danske Briller. So named during the 1962 Oxford University expedition (Hall 1963, 1966) because six parachute loads of food and equipment were dropped here by DC3 on 19 July 1962.

name: Solitaryplateau
description: Small plateau on SE Clavering ╪, so named during Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions because it is isolated by a fault from adjacent parts of the plateau.

name: Solitµrbugt
description: Bay on north Ella ╪, on the west shore of which Lauge Koch's scientific station and the Sirius depot houses are situated (Fig. 40). The name is said to have originated from Aage de Lemos, telegraphist on Ella ╪ during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen and

name: Solstrand
description: South-facing beach on the coast of south Strindberg Land. Named for its sheltered setting, delightfully warm on sunny days. The name was first used as a botanical reference locality in reports of the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen (Gelting 1934).

name: Solkµret
description: Reference locality west of Zackenberg Forskningsstation, used in reports by visiting scientists.

name: Taggletscher
description: Ice cap on south Clavering ╪, due north of Eskimonµs station. The name was first used during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Gelting (1934), and was given for the roof-like appearance.

name: Tagstenstop
description: Mountain 1360 m high on a nunatak on the SE side of Vestfjord Gletscher. So named by W.E. Adrian Phillips during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions because the rocks weather into cleaved slabs suitable for roofing slates (= tagsten).

name: Tait Bjerg
description: Mountain 710 m high on the west side of Carlsberg Fjord. Named as Cape Tait by William Scoresby Jr. in 1822, probably after William Tait [1793-1864], bookseller and publisher, and a well known figure in the social life of Edinburgh. Scoresby's cape was f

name: Takkerne
description: Mountain or cape on east Traill ╪, north of Kap Parry. So named by Hans P. Schaub during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition led by Lauge Koch because of its serrated summits.

name: Takkerne
description: Mountain range in NE Hudson Land, on the north side of Stordal. Adapted from a suggestion by Heinrich Bⁿtler arising from his work during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition.

name: Tancredia River
description: Name used by Harris (1931) for the river flowing in Tancrediakl°ft.

name: Tancrediakl°ft
description: Conspicuous ravine in Neill Klinter on the west side of Hurry Inlet. Named by Alfred Rosenkrantz during Lauge Koch's 1926-27 expeditions as Tancredia Kl°ft for the occurrence of fossil lamellibranchs. (Tancrediakl÷ft.)

name: Tanden
description: Mountain on the south side of inner M°rkefjord. So named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition led by Ebbe Munck and Eigil Knuth, for the shape (tand = tooth).

name: Tandlaegetinde
description: Summit 2350 m high in the upper reaches of Sefstr÷m Gletscher, Stauning Alper. Climbed by the 2001 Scottish Mountaineering Club expedition. The leader of the expedition, Colwyn Jones, is a dental surgeon (= tandlµge).

name: Tangebugt
description: Bay on the east coast of Liverpool Land, on the north side of Kap Greg (tang = seaweed).

name: Tangen
description: Large delta on the west side of Clavering ╪ almost blocking the fjord apart from the channel Revet. Named by Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions. Muskos÷yra is used on Lacmann's (1937) maps.

name: Tangodden
description: Headland west of M°rkefjord Station, west of Gamma Havn. Named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition led by Ebbe Munck and Eigil Knuth, probably for the occurrence of seaweed.

name: Tantallon Gletscher
description: Narrow glacier with Tantallon Spids at its head, on the NE side of Sefstr÷m Gletscher, north Stauning Alper. Named Tantallon Glacier by the 1958 Scottish East Greenland expedition led by Malcolm Slesser.

name: Tantallon Spids
description: Rock peak 2480 m high with many spires on the NE side of Sefstr÷m Gletscher, north Stauning Alper. First climbed by the 1958 Scottish East Greenland expedition led by Malcolm Slesser, and named after Tantallon Castle, East Lothian, a Douglas stronghold d

name: Tantalus
description: Mountain 2477 m high on the NE side of Orion Gletscher, south Stauning Alper. First climbed by James Clarkson's 1961 expedition, and named after the Tantalus of Greek mythology.

name: Tappedal
description: Valley draining Tappes° in SW Renland. So named by J.D. Friderichsen during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions because the ice-dammed lake Tappes° drains (= tappe) through the valley.

name: Tappes°
description: Lake in SW Renland, NE of Rypefjord, at the margin of Eielson Gletscher. So named by J.D. Friderichsen during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions because the lake drains (= tappe) through Tappedal.

name: Taraxacumfjeld
description: Summit 1261 m high SW of Pothorst Bjerge, north Jameson Land. The name was proposed by Russel Marris following his journeys in the region in 1968, and given for one of the 25 Greenland species of dandelion.

name: Tartaajik
description: Island off the east coast of Liverpool Land. Recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, the name means æit looks like a seal's kidney'. (TartΓjik.)

name: Taseq
description: Name used occasionally for one of the lakes of Holger Danske Briller north of Sydkap (taseq = the lake).

name: Sandodden
description: Danish hunting station on the SW coast of Wollaston Forland on the north side of Young Sund. It was named after the sandy peninsula 4-5 km to the south, Kap Berghaus, which is known to Norwegian hunters as Heklas Hvalrossnµs. The station (originally know

name: Sandstensdal
description: Valley in west Wollaston Forland, named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Hans Frebold. (Sandstendal.)

name: Sandstensfjeldene
description: Range of hills on east Milne Land, NW of Kap Leslie, extending from Kronen to Hartz Fjeld and southwards to Slottet and Glaukonitbjerg. Named Sandstens Fjµlde by the 1891-92 Den ╪stgr°nlandske expedition, because of the abundant, light-coloured sandstone

name: Sandstensodden
description: Name used in the 1891-92 diaries of Helge Vedel (Gull°v 1991) for the Kap Leslie area of east Milne Land. See also Sandstensfjeldene.

name: Sandtorg
description: Cape on east Geographical Society ╪ on the north side of Cambridge Bugt. Used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937), the name was given for the locality of the same name in the Troms district of Norway.

name: Sandvik
description: Norwegian hunting hut west of the mouth of Granatdal, south Clavering ╪. It was built by the Foldvik expedition in August 1926, and moved to this site in July 1927. The name appears on the NSIU (1932c) map and translates as æsandy bay'. The hut has also

name: Sand°en
description: Small island in Young Sund, named by Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions as Sand Island, because it comprises exclusively sand and gravel. Eiders and terns were reported to nest here in their thousands (Pedersen 1960), and the locality was a bird sanctuary

name: Sand°yra
description: Flat, sandy delta on NE Geographical Society ╪, so named on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937).

name: Sanikkivaajaq
description: Coastal strip near to the town of Scoresbysund. Recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, the name translates as æthe poor side'. (SanφkivΓjaq.)

name: Sankt Vitus Bjerg
description: Mountain on the south side of Borgj°kel, Dronning Louise Land (Fig. 21). Named by the 1912-13 Den danske Ekspedition til Dronning Louises Land in various forms (St. Vitus Bjµrg, St. Vitus-Berg, St. Vitus-Spitze, St. Vitus Fjall.) Sankt Vitus is a Catholi

name: Santes Fair
description: Mountain about 2100 m high on the west side of lower Storgletscher, Stauning Alper. Named by the 1961 Bangor Mountaineering Club expedition.

name: Stakken
description: Small island east of Godfred Hansen ╪. Named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition for its appearance (stak = haystack).

name: Startdal
description: Valley on SE Traill ╪ east of the head of Dr°mmebugten. So named by Hans P. Schaub during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition, probably because he started his geological work here.

name: Station-mountain
description: The name was used only by B÷ggild (1905), for the 1300 m high summit of Kap Dalton. See also Stationsbugt.

name: Stationsbugt
description: Small bay north of Kap Dalton. The ANTARCTIC anchored here in July 1900 during the 1898-1900 Carlsbergfondets Expedition while a depot house (Amdrup Hytte), and possible wintering station, was built on land. This name is only used by Jacobsen (1900).

name: Stations°
description: Small island SW of Kap Beurmann at the mouth of Bessel Fjord. It was used by Thostrup (1911) as a reference locality in his archaeological report of the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen.

name: Statuebjerg
description: Mountain on the west side of the head of Hurry Inlet, named by Alfred Rosenkrantz during Lauge Koch's 1926-27 expeditions as Statue Mt for its appearance.

name: Stauning Alper
description: Alpine mountain range bounded to the north by Kong Oscar Fjord and SegelsΣllskapets Fjord, to the east by Skeldal, Schuchert Flod and Holger Danske Briller, to the west by Alpefjord and Borgbjerg Gletscher, and to the south by part of Nordvestfjord (Figs

name: Steensby Bjerg
description: Mountain in north Hold with Hope, named by Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions in the form Mt Steensby for Hans Peder Steensby [1875-1920]. Steensby was a Danish geographer and professor at the University of Copenhagen, with interests in North Africa and th

name: Whitefront Pond
description: Name used in an ornithology report of the 1963 British East Greenland expedition (Hall & Waddingham 1966) for a lake on the north side of ╪rsted Dal. A single Greenland white-fronted goose was seen here on 18 July 1963.

name: Whittard Bjerg
description: Mountain in east Hudson Land, named by Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions as Whittard Mtns after the chief geologist of James Wordie's 1929 Cambridge expedition. The original usage was for a wider region including the present Aravis and Saussure Massiv (Se

name: Wildspitze
description: Mountain 1599 m high in the southern Barth Bjerge. Named during the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt, probably by Julius Payer, after the highest mountain in the Otztal Alps, Austria. Wildspitze was climbed in 1952 by members of the 1952-54 Bri

name: Sederholm Bjerg
description: Mountain on Gauss Halv°. Named by Helge G. Backlund during Lauge Koch's 1929 expedition in the form Mt. Sederholm to commemorate the authority on Fennoscandian structures, Jakob Johannes Sederholm [1863-1934]. A Finnish petrologist and structural geologi

name: Sedgwick Gletscher
description: Glacier in the north Stauning Alper, dividing the Murchison Bjerge. Named during Lauge Koch's 1950-51 expeditions by Erdhart FrΣnkl, after the noted British geologist Adam Sedgwick [1785-1873] who first applied the name Cambrian to the geological period.

name: Sedimentkl°ft
description: Small ravine at the NW end of Annekss°en, east of Kofoed-Hansen Brµ. So named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen, because of an outcrop of sedimentary rocks. (Sedimentkl÷ft.)

name: Seebach Bjerg
description: Mountain 677 m high NW of Roseneathbugt. Named by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt as Cap Seebach, after Karl Albert Ludvig von Seebach [1839-1880], a German geologist and palaeontologist who was professor at G÷ttingen. Seebach had worked o

name: Seejoch
description: Lake in Adam af Breemen Dal, east Geographical Society ╪, which drains into Cambridge Bugt. The name was used on a map by Stauber (1938) describing work during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition.

name: Seenplatte
description: Name used by Eduard Wenk for the plateau area north of central Nordvestfjord, which has many lakes. One of the largest lakes is known as T-s°.

name: Seerakajik
description: Cove or lagoon in southern Jameson Land, dry at low water. Recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, the name means æthe little sandy beach'. (SΩrakajik.)

name: Seerakajik
description: River delta on the NW side of Hvalrosbugt, south Liverpool Land. Recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, the name means æthe little sandy beach'. (SΩrakajik.)

name: Sefstr÷m Gletscher
description: Glacier draining west from the Stauning Alper into Alpefjord, where it merges with Gully Gletscher and almost blocks the fjord except for a narrow passage on the west side. Named by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst probably

name: Sefstr÷m Tinde
description: Mountain about 2800 m high on the NE side of Sefstr÷m Gletscher (Fig. 77). The name seems to have been used first by Hans Gsellman's 1957 expedition (which made the first ascent), and was approved in 1955 at the suggestion of John Haller. The second asce

name: Sefstr÷msgipfel
description: Mountain 2622 m high at the head of the SE branch of Sefstr÷m Gletscher. The name was used by Hans Gsellman's 1957 expedition, which made the first ascent. (Sefstromsgipfel).

name: Sefstroms-Lang Col
description: Col at the head of Sefstr÷m Gletscher leading to a tributary of Storgletscher (formerly Langgletscher). The name is used by Bennet (1972).

name: SegelsΣllskapet Fjord
description: Fjord between Lyell Land and the northern Stauning Alper, named by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst after the Kongelige Svenska SegelsΣllskapet. (SegelsΣlskapets Fjord, Royal Yacht Club Fjord, Yacht Club Fjord.)

name: Segldal
description: Valley between Mesters Vig and Antarctic Havn, north Scoresby Land. Named by Hans Kapp during Lauge Koch's 1957-58 expeditions. A Norwegian hunting hut near Pictet Bjerg sometimes goes under the name Segldalen (see Jostein).

name: Seglpas
description: Pass between the head of Segldal and Majdal, north Scoresby Land. Named by Hans Kapp during Lauge Koch's 1957-58 expeditions.

name: Seismisk Station
description: Official designation for the seismic station at Scoresbysund, erected by Janus S°rensen in 1927-28. It was later moved to Kap Tobin.

name: Paradigma Pass
description: Name used by Trⁿmpy (1969) for the col north of Paradigmabjerg, Wegener Halv°, and used in his desciption of ammonites collected during Lauge Koch's 1958 expedition.

name: Paradigmabjerg
description: Mountain on Wegener Halv°. So named by Arne Noe-Nygaard during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen as Mt. Paradigma because it produced a continuous geological sequence.

name: Lille Vands°
description: Hut built by Daneborg weather station at a small fresh-water lake in Lille S°dal, Wollaston Forland.

name: Lillebittes°dal
description: Name used by Daneborg weather station personnel for a side valley to Lille S°dal, Wollaston Forland (bitte = diminutive; lillebitte = very small; lillebittes°dal = very small lake valley).

name: Lilledal
description: Minor tributary valley to Slugtdal, west of Antarctic Havn. The name was used by Hans Kapp during Lauge Koch's 1957-58 expeditions.

name: Lilleelv
description: Small river on NE Traill ╪ draining into Vega Sund. Named by Desmond T. Donovan during Lauge Koch's 1949-50 expedition.

name: Lillefjord
description: Fjord on the east coast of southern Liverpool Land. The name first appears as Lille Fjord on a map compiled by Janus S°rensen (S°rensen 1928).

name: Lillegletscher
description: Name occasionally used for a minor glacier between Toscano Gletscher and Sydgletscher, on the south side of northern Frederiksdal, Nathorst Land (Zweifel 1958).

name: Lille S°dal
description: Valley in south Wollaston Forland where there are many small lakes. The name originated from the wintering parties at Kulhus and Eskimonµs during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen.

name: Lille Teufelcap
description: Name used by Henning Bistrup in October 1907 for Ravnefjeldet in Rechnitzer Land. Probably named for a similarity to Teufelkap. (Jan L°ve, personal communication May 2012).

name: Lille Vands°
description: Name reported by Hans Meltofte as in use by the staff at Danmarkshavn weather station in 1969-71 for Lille Skibss°.

name: Lillegletscher
description: Glacier west of the head of Bessel Fjord. The name appears to have been suggested by the Place Name Committee in 1935, probably as a replacement for a proposed name they considered unsuitable.

name: Limfjordsbakkerne
description: Eastern slopes of Harefjeldet, near Danmark Havn. The name was used by Friis (1909) in his popular account of the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen, because the slopes resembled the locality of the same name in Denmark after a heath fire.

name: Lindauer H÷rnli
description: Mountain about 2000 m high on the SW side of Roslin Gletscher. Climbed by the 1966 Deutsche Gr÷nland-Expedition in die Staunings-Alpen led by Karl M. Herligkoffer on 21 August, and named after Lindau, a town at the east end of Bodensee, of which the old

name: Lindbergh Fjelde
description: Nunatak area west of Christian IV Gletscher, northern Christian IX Land. Mapped by Lauge Koch during flights in 1933 on the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, and named Lindbergh Land after Colonel Charles Lindbergh and his wife, whom Koch met on Ella ╪ in Aug

name: Lindbergh Gletscher
description: Glacier in northern Kong Christian IX Land, named by Lawrence Wager's 1935-36 expedition as Lindberghs Glacier after nearby Lindbergh Fjelde.

name: Lindeman Fjord
description: Fjord SW of Kuhn ╪. Named by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt as Lindeman Bai (Fig. 6), after Moritz Karl Adolf Lindeman [1823-1908]. He was secretary of the Bremen geographical society, the æVerein fⁿr die deutsche Nordpolarfahrt', and edi

name: Lindeman Fjord hytten
description: Danish hunting hut on the south side of Lindeman Fjord, built by Nanok in 1931, and rebuilt in 1938. It was burnt down in December 1978. It was also known as Fjordhytten. A Norwegian hut nearby is known as Svendsby.

name: Lindemannelv
description: River in Lindemansdalen, north of Zackenberg Forskningsstation. The name is used as a reference locality by visiting scientists.

name: Lindemannhytten
description: Danish hunting hut on the west side of Fligely Fjord, north of the mouth of Lindeman Fjord, built by Nanok in 1931. It is also known as Sydlige Fligelyhytten. (Lindeman hytten.)

name: Lindemans Bugt
description: Koldewey's original Lindeman Bai between Kuhn ╪ and Wollaston Forland was renamed Lindeman Fjord when the extent of the æbay' became clear during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen. However, Vischer (1943) and Maync (1947) both used Lindemans Bugt on their

name: Lindemansdalen
description: Valley running from Lindeman Fjord southwards to Young Sund. The name first appears in a geological report by Frebold (1932). (Lindemann Dal, Lindemanndal.)

name: Lindemanspashytten
description: Danish hunting hut built by Nanok in May 1951 on the west side of the pass at the southern end of Lindemansdalen.

name: Taseq Qutteq
description: Lake NE of Scoresbysund town. One of the names recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, it translates as æthe uppermost lake'. (Taseq q·teq.)

name: Taskedalen
description: Name used by the 1908-09 FLOREN expedition for one of the valleys west of Kap Borlase Warren. Position uncertain.

name: Tassiusark
description: Name used during the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen for the eastern bay of Danmark Havn (Poulsen 1991).

name: Tattaalakajia
description: Moraine ridge on Roma Gletscher, Volquaart Boon Kyst. Recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, the name translates as æthe little stone ridge'. (TavtΓlakajia.)

name: Taurobjerg
description: Mountain 1860 m high at the head of Leo Gletscher, south Stauning Alper. So named by the 1970 University of Dundee expedition, because two of the climbers who made the first ascent were born under the zodiac sign Taurus, and the name fitted with others i

name: Taurus Glacier
description: Tributary to Orion Gletscher, south Stauning Alper, so named by James Clarkson's 1961 expedition for the constellation of the zodiac.

name: Tavlen
description: Nunatak in northern Hobbs Land, originally named Tafelbjerg for the flat-lying basalts by Hans R. Katz during Lauge Koch's 1951 expedition; the name was changed to Tavlen (= the board) by the Place Name Committee. The highest point at 2400 m was climbed

name: Vandyke Klipper
description: The SE part of Traill ╪ was described by William Scoresby Jr. in 1822 as a stupendous cliff of singular beauty, with a prevailing colour of slate blue, intersected by zig-zag strata of bright yellow and red. He named it Vandyke Cliffs, probably because t

name: Varde Elv
description: Name used by Rosenkrantz (1934) for the river in Vardekl°ft, on the west side of Hurry Inlet.

name: Varde Nunatak
description: Nunatak on the west side of Vindue Gletscher. So named by Peter Homewood during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions because of a cairn (= varde) on the summit.

name: Vardedalen
description: Valley on the north side of Ingolf Fjord, NE of Brede Spµrregletscher. So named by Elmar Drastrup's 1938-39 expedition because they erected a cairn, Scoresbysundvarden, at the mouth of the valley.

name: Vardefjeld
description: Mountain in the north Stauning Alper on the east side of Skjoldungebrµ. It was first climbed by a Norwegian party in 1951. The name was adopted by John Haller following explorations during Lauge Koch's 1954 expedition (varde = cairn).

name: Vardefjeld
description: Mountain 790 m high in SE Hold with Hope. It appears on an NSIU map (1932a) in the form Vardefjell, and was presumably named for a cairn.

name: Vardekl°ft
description: Ravine in Neill Klinter on the west side of Hurry Inlet. So named by the 1898-1900 Carlsbergfondets Expedition because the remains of a cairn (varde) built by Carl Ryder in 1891 were found on the cliff top above the ravine. (Vardekl÷ft, Vardekloeft, Vard

name: Vardenµs
description: Peninsula on the south side of Sabine ╪, east of Germania Havn. Named by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt as Cairn-Spitze, because they built a cairn here with a report on the work of the expedition. (Cairnspitze, Cairn Point.)

name: Varderyggen
description: Ridge in south Germania Land, NW of Danmark Havn. So named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen, because a cairn was built here. (Cairn Ridge, Varde-Ridge.)

name: Vardevakt
description: Norwegian hunting station 2 km SE of Kap PetersΘns built by the M°re expedition in 1930 (Rogne 1981). It is better known under the names Sunnm°resheimen or Kapp Petersens.

name: Vargbukta
description: Bay on the west coast of Ymer ╪, the present Blomsterbugten. So named by NSIU in 1929, because the crew of the VESLEKARI were surrounded by a pack of five wolves while capturing a muskox calf here. The name appeared on several NSIU maps of the 1930s. (Va

name: Varghytta
description: Norwegian hunting hut in Blomsterbugten, west Ymer ╪, built by Arktisk Nµringsdrift in March 1930. While building the hut Olav Kjelbotn and Hallvard Devold were surrounded by a pack of eight wolves, who subsequently followed them throughout their winter

name: Vaskedalen
description: Valley west of Vindue Gletscher, where a large river flows from the glacier eastwards into an ice-dammed lake (vaske = wash). Named by Peter Homewood during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions.

name: Vassdalen
description: Valley west of Ankerbjerg on the north side of Moskusoksefjord, the present Prospekt Dal. It was used as a botanical reference locality in the report on NSIU investigations by Vaage (1932).

name: Vassvika
description: Bay on the north side of east Geographical Society ╪, NW of Kap Mackenzie. The name is used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937), and was given for the boggy nature of the ground bordering the bay (vass = water).

name: Steenstrup Bjerg
description: Mountain 1294 m high on SE Traill ╪. Named Steenstrups Berg by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst after Johannes Japetus Smith Steenstrup [1813-1897], with whom Nathorst cooperated on studies of glacial flora as a student. Ja

name: Steenstrup Dal
description: Valley in extreme SE Traill ╪, south of Steenstrup Bjerg. Named by Hans P. Schaub during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition. See also Steenstrup Bjerg.

name: Steffensens Hytte
description: Norwegian hunting hut at the mouth of DusΘn Fjord, built by Arktisk Nµringsdrift in 1929. It has been more commonly known by the names Kikut and Dusens Fjordhytten. (Steffensen.)

name: Stegocephalryg
description: Minor ridge north of Frebold Bjerg, adjacent to River 7, NW Hold with Hope. So named by Eigil Nielsen during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, for the find of a particularly fine example of the fossil fish æStegalocephalus'.

name: Steinbjerg
description: Mountain about 1950 m high on the SW side of Roslin Gletscher. Climbed by the 1966 Deutsche Gr÷nland-Expedition in die Staunings-Alpen led by Karl M. Herligkoffer on 21 August 1966.

name: Steinenbjerg
description: Name used by Buess (1953 p. 216) for a mountain in the Martin Knudsen Nunatakker. It was named during explorations on Lauge Koch's 1951 expedition after the street Steinenberg in the old town centre of Basel, Switzerland.

name: Steinmannspids
description: Mountain 1332 m high on Clavering ╪. Named Steinmann Spitze by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt, because of the cairn-like basalt pillars which crown the summit. (Steinmannen, Mt. Steinmann, Steinmann Peak.)

name: Stakkel°bet
description: Sound between Godfred Hansen ╪ and Stakken in the SW part of Dove Bugt. Named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition (stakke = haystack).

name: Stakken
description: Name used by 1927-29 Hird expedition for a feature in the vicinity of the hunting station at Kap Mary, east Clavering ╪ (Rogne 1981).

name: Steinr÷ysa
description: Small island east of the Vinter°er, at the mouth of DusΘn Fjord. So named on an NSIU map (1932a). The name implies a stony desert or plain.

name: Steinr°isdal
description: Valley south of Antarctic Havn in Scoresby Land, the present Flexurdal. The name has been often used by Norwegian hunters (Ingstad 1937), and appears on Norsk S°kort 511 (1937). Moskusdal has been used for the same valley.

name: Steinsund
description: Narrow sound between Strip÷ya and Vesle Finsch÷ya in the Finsch ╪er group. So named on an NSIU map (1932a).

name: Stejlfjeld
description: Steep cliff on Volquaart Boon Kyst west of Solgletscher. So named by Laurits Bruhn during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen for its appearance (stejl = steep). Engelsborg has also been used.

name: Stejlgletscher
description: Small glacier in NW Suess Land. So named by Ove Simonsen during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen because it descends steeply to Kejser Franz Joseph Fjord (stejl = steep).

name: Stejlgletscher
description: Glacier in west A.P. Olsen Land on the NE side of Tyrolerdal. So named by the 1948 Leeds University expedition because it was one of the steepest on which they worked. (Steep Glacier.)

name: Tiedemannfjellet
description: Mountain on north Clavering ╪. Used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937), and named after J.L. Tiedemanns Tobaksfabric, Oslo, which financed the 1932 NSIU aerial photography in East Greenland.

name: Tillit Nunatak
description: Nunatak in west Charcot Land, with small outcrops of the rock type tillite. Named during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions.

name: Tillitekl°ft
description: Ravine in east AndrΘe Land, draining into Geologfjord. Named by Christian Poulsen during Lauge Koch's 1929 expedition as Tillite Canyon, because of the occurrence of late Precambrian glacial deposits (tillites). This locality is placed incorrectly on the

name: Tillyrie
description: Peak about 2415 m high in the upper reaches of Sefstr÷m Gletscher, Stauning Alper. Climbed by the 1998 Scottish Mountaineering Club expedition, the name means nipple.

name: Timeglasset
description: Hill with two summits in north Dronning Louise Land. The name was given by the 1952-54 British North Greenland expedition, possibly because the hill in plan has an hour-glass-like shape (timeglasset = the hour-glass).

name: Tinderne
description: Range of mountain peaks on the north side of Forsblad Fjord. Named Tinnarne by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst for the spiky summits. (The Pinnacles, Tindane.)

name: Tindernes Dal
description: Name used in a report by Christian Vibe in Larsen (1960) and by Andersen (1960), for a valley in Renland, the present Catalinadal. It was named for the high mountain peaks on both sides of the valley (tinderne = pinnacles).

name: Selwyn Fjeld
description: Peak 2140 m high on the north side of Gully Gletscher. It was climbed by a Cambridge University expedition on 22 August 1963, and named after Selwyn College, Cambridge, incorporated into the university in 1882. (Selwyn.)

name: Sem-Gletscher
description: Southern of three small glaciers between Vestre Gletscher and Mellem Gletscher in the north Werner Bjerge. The name was used by Styger (1951) in his report on a climbing excursion during Lauge Koch's 1950 expedition, and was named after Shem (Sem), the o

name: Semspitze
description: Name used by Styger (1951) for a mountain in the north Werner Bjerge at the head of Sem-Gletscher, between Vestre Gletscher and Mellem Gletscher. It was climbed by Gerold Styger with Peter Bearth during Lauge Koch's 1950 expedition. See also Sem-Gletsche

name: Sendlinger Spids
description: Mountain about 2300 m high between the upper part of Duart Gletscher and the upper basin of Spµrregletscher. Climbed by the 1966 Deutsche Gr÷nland-Expedition in die Staunings-Alpen led by Karl M. Herligkoffer on 20 August 1966, and named apparently for S

name: Sendlinger Kalotte
description: Mountain about 2250 m high on the ridge between Duart Gletscher and the upper basin of Spµrregletscher. Climbed by the 1966 Deutsche Gr÷nland-Expedition in die Staunings-Alpen led by Karl M. Herligkoffer on 22 August 1966.

name: Stormpynt
description: Small peninsula on the north side of outer Nordvestfjord. Named in this form by the 1891-92 Den ╪stgr°nlandske expedition, because the expedition sheltered here in a storm during their return from the first exploration of Nordvestfjord.

name: Stormryggen
description: Low-lying dolomite ridge in north Scoresby Land on the north side of Kolledalen. It was near one of Hans Kapp's camp sites during Lauge Koch's 1957-58 expeditions (Kapp 1960), and presumably named for stormy weather.

name: Storskµrene
description: Group of large skerries in Skµrfjorden, so named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by David Malmquist.

name: Storsletten
description: Extensive plain in north Wollaston Forland, SW of Albrecht Bugt. Named by Wolf Maync and Andreas Vischer during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition.

name: Storstr°mmen
description: River on NE Clavering ╪ draining into Young Sund. The name first appears on a sketch map in Gustav Thostrup's 1921 logbook in the form Storstr°m, and was reported as used by Danish hunters. It may originally have been applied to the river occupying Gr°nn

name: Storstr°mmen
description: Large glacier flowing south between Dronning Louise Land and Daniel Bruun Land (Fig. 21), that merges with L. Bistrup Brµ to form Bredebrµ. Named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen for its size (= the great stream). (Storstr÷mmen, Storstrommen, St≤rist

name: Stortoppen
description: One of the original names used by the Norwegian climbers who made the first ascent of Norsketinden in 1954, the second highest mountain in the Stauning Alper (Hoff 1955). See also Eirik Raudes Tinde.

name: Stor°
description: Largest of the islands on the east side of R°defjord. Discovered and so named by the 1891-92 Den ╪stgr°nlandske expedition led by Carl Ryder during their first winter sledge journey.

name: Stor°en
description: Large island in the Danske ╪er group in the south part of Jokelbugten. So named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition because of its size. (Stor÷en.)

name: Straight River
description: Minor, straight river in south Jameson Land, so named by Hermann Aldinger during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen.

name: Stranda-huset
description: Norwegian hunting hut on the NW side of Fleming Inlet below Sporfjeld, built by the M°re expedition in August 1931. It is also known as Flatstranda. The hut was swept away by a wave during a storm in 1953.

name: Stranddal
description: Valley in north Dronning Louise Land containing Strandelv, which drains Britannia S°. Named by the 1952-54 British North Greenland expedition.

name: Strandelv
description: River draining Britannia S° in north Dronning Louise Land (Fig. 21). It follows the west margin of Storstr°mmen and at its north end flows over sandy beaches and terraces from which the name derives. The name was given by the 1952-54 British North Greenl

name: Strathclyde Pynt
description: Cape where the west end of Turner Sund meets R°mer Fjord. Named by Malcolm Slesser's 1969 expedition for the University of Strathclyde, to which the leader Malcolm Slesser was affiliated. Strathclyde was the name given in the 9th and 10th centuries to a

name: Stratumbjerget
description: Mountain 679 m high in west Wollaston Forland, made up of alternating layers of sandstone and shale. So named by Wolf Maync and Andreas Vischer during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition for the geological relationships. (Stratumbjµrget.)

name: Straumneset
description: Elongate sand spit on south Geographical Society ╪, NE of Silja ╪ (Fig. 14). So named on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937) because it borders a sound with strong currents (= straum).

name: Lindemanss°
description: Lake system in the SW part of Lindemansdalen north of Zackenbergelv. The name was introduced by Hans Meltoft and Thomas Bj°rneboe Berg, and is used as a reference locality in ornithological reports by visiting scientists to Zackenberg Forskningsstation.

name: Lindhard ╪
description: Island south of Borgfjord. Named by the 1912-13 Den danske Ekspedition til Dronning Louises Land as Lindhards ╪, after Jens Peter Johannes Lindhard [1870-1947], doctor on the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen. (Lindhards Ey.)

name: Lindqvist-Hytta
description: Norwegian hunting hut on the north side of Vega Sund, SE of Svedenborg Bjerg (NSIU 1932c), built by Arktisk Nµringsdrift in 1929. The name was given for Gustav Lindqvist, a Norwegian hunter who in addition to hunting in East Greenland had spent 17 years

name: Muschelbjerg
description: Range of hills in south Hochstetter Forland, with two main peaks, Nordre and S°ndre Muschelbjerg. Named by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt as Muschelberg for the finds of fossil shells. The name was preserved by the Place Name Committee in

name: Musk Ox Tower
description: Minor summit about 1450 m high on the north side of Korridoren, Milne Land. Climbed by the 2004 West Lancashire Scouts expedition.

name: Muskox Plateau
description: Name used by Hermann Aldinger (1935) during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen for a plateau area between Ostreaelv and Lakseelv in south Jameson Land, and given for the muskox.

name: Muskox Pond
description: Lake on Store Koldewey where sampling was undertaken for phytoplankton studies (Cremer et al. 2005).

name: Muskox River
description: Minor river in south Jameson Land draining into Ostreaelv near its mouth. So named by Hermann Aldinger (1935) during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, after the muskox. (Upper Muskox River.)

name: Muslingebjerg
description: Translation into Danish used by Surlyk (1977) for Muschelbjerg in Wollaston Forland, who also used Nordre Muslingebjerg and S°ndre Muslingebjerg for the two peaks officially known as Nordre and S°ndre Muschelbjerg. See also Muschelbjerg.

name: Muslingebjerget
description: Name occasionally used for Aucellabjerget on southern Store Koldewey during the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen (J. L°ve, personal communication 2009).

name: Muslingeelv
description: River in southern Jameson Land. Named by Hermann Aldinger during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen as Mussel River, for the rich finds of fossil lamellibranchs. It was given the name Hesteelv by mistake on the 1965 Geodµtisk Institut maps. There appears to

name: Muslingeelv
description: Small river draining south into Nordostbugt, near Sydkap. So named by the 1962 Oxford University expedition for finds of shells on terraces at the mouth of the river.

name: Muslingefjeld
description: Mountain in Okselandet, north of the west end of Sµls°en. Named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition, presumably for finds of shells (musling = mussel). It was first visited by Paul Gelting and Alwin Pedersen in May 1939. (Muslingefjµld.)

name: Muslingehj°rnet
description: Ridge adjacent to Bopladsdalen, Kap Brewster. Name used in a report by Hassan (1953) describing work on material collected during Lauge Koch's 1951 expedition, and given for the numerous fossil shells.

name: Myalinadal
description: Valley on SW Wegener Halv°. Named by Katherina Perch-Nielsen during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions after the fossil mussel æMyalina', common in the valley.

name: Myggbukta
description: Norwegian radio and weather station on the north side of Mackenzie Bugt (Fig. 13), an appropriate name as the area is one of the worst for mosquitoes (= mygg) in this part of East Greenland. The original station was erected and so named by Johan A. Olsen

name: Myggbukta
description: Norwegian hunters name for Mackenzie Bugt, in use from about 1922 to 1930. See also Myggbukta. (Midge Bay, Mosquito Bay.)

name: Myggedal
description: Valley south of Grejsdalen in AndrΘe Land. Named during Lauge Koch's 1948-50 expeditions by Erdhardt FrΣnkl, but shown only on his cross-section (FrΣnkl 1953).

name: Myggedammen
description: Pond south of ╪sterport in the vicinity of Zackenberg Forskningsstation. The name was introduced by Claus Nordstr°m. Information from Lars Holst Hansen, 2011.

name: Mygges°
description: Small lake at Hestepas, west of the mouth of Mesters Vig. Named by prospecting teams associated with Lauge Koch's 1948-49 expedition.

name: Myggvatna
description: Swampy area with many small lakes west of Myggbukta; so named on an NSIU map (1932a) because it is the breeding ground of mosquitoes.

name: Vastidal
description: Western of two exactly parallel valleys on central Gauss Halv° draining north to Moskusoksefjord. Named by Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions as Vasti Valley, or VΣstidal, the name having been inspired by that of nearby GΣstisdal. The name means æwestern v

name: Vauxhall
description: Mountain 2140 m high between Harlech Gletscher and Dunottar Gletscher, north Stauning Alper. First climbed by the 1963 Imperial College expedition, and named after the London village, now swallowed up by Lambeth, whose name is preserved in Vauxhall Bridg

name: Vands°
description: Name used by staff at Danmarkshavn for Skibss°, which is the source of their drinking water. In spring and early winter aeroplanes bringing supplies and post sometimes landed on this lake.

name: Vedel S°
description: Lake between Pony Gletscher and Ejnar Gletscher, Dronning Louise Land (Fig. 21). Named by the 1952-54 British North Greenland expedition after the Danish Vice-Admiral Aage Helgersen Vedel [1894-1981], head of the S°vµrnet from 1950 to 1958 with special i

name: Vedet Hytten
description: Danish hunting hut about 2 km south of Kap Negri in Fligely Fjord, at the foot of the mountain Vedetten. It was built by Nanok in August 1951. It has sometimes been known as Kap Negri Hytten.

name: Vedetten
description: Mountain 2200 m high in Goodenough Land, named by J.M. Wordie's 1929 Cambridge expedition as Sentinel for its appearance.

name: Vedetten
description: Mountain behind Kap Negri in NE Th. Thomsen Land. The name originated from the wintering party at Kulhus during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen.

name: Vega Sund
description: Sound between Geographical Society ╪ and Traill ╪. Named by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst as Vegas Sund, after the steamer VEGA, which carried the successful Swedish expedition to Spitsbergen in 1868, and through the NE

name: Rypedalene
description: Small valleys or ravines in the Rypefjeldene on Danmark ╪. The reference is only found in the report by Hartz (1895) on work during the wintering of the 1891-92 Den ╪stgr°nlandske expedition in Hekla Havn.

name: Rypefjeldene
description: Low hills on the north side of Elvdalen on Danmark ╪. Named by the 1891-92 Den ╪stgr°nlandske expedition as Rypefjµldene. They were notably free of snow in the winter and the haunt of ptarmigan (= rype).

name: Rypefjeldet
description: Hill on the west side of M°rkefjord Station, south of Sµls°en. So named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen because ptarmigan were shot here in 1906 (Fig. 75 ; Thostrup 2007). (Ptarmigan Hill, Rype Mt., Rj·pnafell.)

name: Rypefjord
description: Fjord between SW Renland and C. Hofmann Halv°. Named by the 1891-92 Den ╪stgr°nlandske expedition led by Carl Ryder, which discovered the fjord during a sledge journey in April 1892. Ptarmigan (Lagopus mutus) are common in the region (Fig. 75). The Green

name: Rypegletscher
description: Glacier in north Goodenough Land, flowing NW to join Nordenski÷ld Gletscher. Named by J.M. Wordie's 1929 Cambridge expedition as Ptarmigan Glacier, because occasional ptarmigan were seen here. The glacier was divided into three parts, Upper, Middle and L

name: Rypenµs
description: Peninsula on the west side of Rypefjord. The name was approved in 1961 at the suggestion of Ulrik R°en. Recent 1:100 000 topographic maps show the location to be just south of latitude 71░N.

name: Rypesletta
description: The name has been used by Norwegian hunters for the plain west of the hunting station at Kap Wynn, where there always seemed to be ptarmigan.

name: Rypesvinget
description: Pronounced bend in the river north of Zackenberg Forskningsstation. The name is used by visiting scientists.

name: Rypes°
description: Small lake west of Noret, north Scoresby Land. Named by prospecting teams associated with Lauge Koch's 1948-49 expeditions.

name: Rytterknµgten
description: Cape in NE Lyell Land on the SW side of Narhvalsund. The name was given by the Place Name Committee in 1935, as a replacement for an unsuitable proposed name, probably after the highest point on the Danish Island of Bornholm.

name: Rµvebrµ
description: Small glacier on the south side of Gσsefjord. So named during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions by E.A. Hailwood because of the many foxes (= rµve) seen in the vicinity (Fig. 76).

name: Rµvedal

name: Rµveelv

name: Rµveelv

name: Rµvehalen

name: Rµveh°jene

name: Tintagel Fjeld
description: Mountain about 1800 m high at the head of Bersµrkerbrµ, north Stauning Alper. First climbed by John Hunt's 1960 expedition, and named Tintagel for Tintagel Castle in Cornwall. The castle, dating from 1150 and built on the site of a Celtic monastry, was a

name: Tioram Gletscher
description: Glacier in the north Stauning Alper, SW of Sefstr÷m Gletscher, named by John Haller and Malcolm Slesser after nearby Tioram Spids.

name: Tioram Spids
description: Mountain 1800 m high on the SW side of Sefstr÷m Gletscher, north Stauning Alper. First climbed by the 1958 Scottish East Greenland expedition led by Malcolm Slesser that named it for a Nordic castle in west Invernesshire. (Tioram.)

name: Titlingen

name: Tjµldebjerget

name: Tobias Dal
description: Major valley in Hold with Hope. In April 1927 Lauge Koch sent his Greenlandic assistant, Tobias Gabrielsen, to investigate the valley to find a route from the outer coast to Loch Fyne. Tobias Otto Mikael Gabrielsen [1878-1945] was a West Greenlander who

name: Tobias ╪
description: Island about 2 km long and 1500 m across with an ice cap about 35 m high, situated in the Greenland Sea about 80 km from the coast of NE Greenland. A number of associated small islets led to it originally receiving the name Tobias ╪er. The new land was d

name: Tobiashytten
description: Danish hunting hut in the upper part of Tobias Dal, Hold with Hope, built by Nanok in August 1938.

name: Tommelen
description: Tongue of ice from Rolige Brµ extending southwards. Named by Laurent Jemelin during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions for its association with Djµvlehσnden and Langemanden (tommelen = thumb).

name: Tommelen
description: Prominent south cape of Tvillingerne, an island north of Ad. S. Jensen Land. So named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen because it is thumb-shaped.

name: Tomsborg
description: Danish hunting hut on the west coast of Shannon, about 4 km north of Kap Tramnitz. Built by Nanok in September 1948, and named after Hans Thomsen who helped build it. It is also known as Kap Tramnitz Hytten.

name: Toni Kurz Spids
description: Mountain on the west side of Spµrregletscher, between Castor Glacier and Pollux Glacier. First climbed by the 1967 Berchtesgaden expedition, who named it after the Bavarian guide Toni Kurz [1913-1936] from Berchtesgaden, who died on the north face of the

name: Vinkeldal
description: Broad valley on south Milne Land with several marked, right-angled bends. Named by Stuart Watt during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions (vinkel = angle).

name: Vinkelklippe
description: Cliff on the north side of Admiralty Gletscher, Dronning Louise Land (Fig. 21), where the glacier makes a sharp turn to the NE. Named by the 1952-54 British North Greenland expedition as Vinkel Klippe.

name: Vinkels°
description: Ice-dammed lake in the upper reaches of Violingletscher, SW of Cecilia Nunatak. So named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Ove Simonsen because of the right-angled shape of the lake (vinkel = angle).

name: Vintergata
description: Large glacier on central Clavering ╪, the present Skillegletscher. So named on NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937) because when snow covered in the winter it can be used as a route to the interior of the island.

name: Vinter°er
description: Islands off the mouth of DusΘn Fjord. Named Vinter÷arne by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst because they seemed a suitable place to overwinter, a good harbour and sheltered site for a hut being available. These islands were

name: Straumpollen
description: West-facing bay on south Geographical Society ╪, SE of the Scott Keltie ╪er. Used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937; Fig. 14), the name was given for the strong currents (= straum).

name: Strawberry Peak
description: Name used in a climbing report by Odell (1943) for the 2268 m mountain north of Lystergletscher, Frµnkel Land. It was climbed by N.E. Odell during the the 1933 Louise A. Boyd Arctic expedition. The mountain, sometimes referred to as Mount Gore, has a sum

name: Stress-hytten
description: Hut on the east side of Fleming Fjord, about 4 km from the head of the fjord. It was built by Nordisk Mineselskab in 1976 with material supplied by æStress Tagelementer' of Fσrevejle, Sjµlland.

name: Stribebjerg
description: Mountain 2565 m high in west Frµnkel Land. Named during Lauge Koch's 1951 expedition by John Haller and Eduard Wenk for its striped appearance, due to alternating granite and gneiss bands.

name: Stribedal
description: Minor valley on the north slope of Stensi÷ Plateau, NW Hold with Hope, draining west into Blσelv. So named by Eigil Nielsen during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen because repetition of beds by faults produces a striped appearance.

name: Strindberg Land
description: Land area bounded by Geologfjord to the west and Waltershausen Gletscher and Nordfjord to the east. Named by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst as Strindbergs Half÷ after Nils Strindberg [1872-1897], a Swedish physicist who w

name: Strindberg Valley
description: Name occasionally found used in Norwegian reports for Brogetdal in Strindberg Land, although the more common Norwegian usage is Giµverdalen or Stordalen. (Strindbergdalen.)

name: Troldmarkerne
description: Basalt plateau between Dolomitdal and Djµvlekl°ften, NE Clavering ╪. So named by Wolf Maync and Andreas Vischer during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition led by Lauge Koch because of the peculiar weathering.

name: Trolds°en
description: Lake in SE Hold with Hope, named on an NSIU map (1932a) in the form Trollvatnet, probably for its mysterious or enchanted setting. There are numerous similar place names in Norway. (Lake Trolds°en.)

name: Trolds°en
description: Name used for a supposed lake in S°dalen, west of Ingolf Fjord. Named by Eigil Nielsen during the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition led by Ebbe Munck and Eigil Knuth for the ôlarge lake occupying S°dalen or, if there are several lakes, the northeasternmost o

name: Trompeteren Bastion

description: Norwegian hunters name for the south end of Paralleldal on Gauss Halv°, named by John Giµver in 1930 for its resemblance to the area around Troms°. A hunting hut built at the mouth of the valley (73░30.4'N 23░40.2'W) was also known as Tromsdalen, althoug

name: Tromsdalstinden
description: Norwegian hunters name for a mountain in Paralleldal on Gauss Halv°, probably the west end of Sederholm Bjerg. Named by John Giµver in 1930 for its resemblance to the area around Troms°.

name: Tromsyra
description: Peninsula about 5 km south of Str°mtangen. The name is used on Lacmann's (1937) maps.

name: Troms°tind
description: Peak about 2250 m high on the spiky ridge south of Dansketinden, Stauning Alper. So named by the 1996 Norwegian Stauning Alper expedition because the first ascent was made by two climbers from Troms°.

name: Trondfjellet
description: Mountain on southern Gauss Halv°, part of H°jsletten. So named on the 1932a NSIU map, possibly for the mountain of the same name in the Troms district of Norway.

name: Trumpington Pas
description: Pass on the NW side of upper Storgletscher, connecting with Schuchert Gletscher. Named by the 1963 Cambridge University expedition for Trumpington Street, Cambridge, site of part of the university. (Trumpington Col.)

name: Trums ╪
description: Island at the mouth of Bessel Fjord. So named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen, probably after the locality of the same name in Norway. (Trums ╓, Trums Island.)

name: Trumsdalen
description: Valley north of Trums ╪, where the Bessel Fjord hunting station (sometimes called Trumsdalen or Trums°dalen) was established in 1932. The name was given by Danish hunters who built a hut here in 1931. (Troms Dal.)

name: Mysteriedalen

name: Rekdalsundet
description: Sound between SE Geographical Society ╪ and Nordenski÷ld ╪. Used on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937; Fig. 14), the name commemorates the Norwegian skipper Hans Rekdal [b. 1899], commander of the VESLEKARI on the 1929 NSIU expedition.

name: Rekstadfjellet

name: Renbjerg

description: Pronounced bay on the north side of Isfjord. Named by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst as Renbukten, because a flock of 12 reindeer was seen here. This was the largest flock seen during the expedition, and the last living r

name: Rencontre Dal

name: Rencontre S°

name: Rendalen

name: Rendalshytta

name: Rµvekl°ft

name: R÷beckstua

name: R°de Mur
description: Mountain ridge in the Werner Bjerge on the NE side of Langefirn. Named during Lauge Koch's 1953-54 expeditions by Peter Bearth and Eduard Wenk for its colour (= red wall). Quartz-fluorite veins in the east part of the wall contain abundant pyrite, the ru

name: Solstrand

name: Solstrand

name: Solstrand

name: Volquaart Boon Kyst
description: Stretch of mountainous coast along the south side of Scoresby Sund between Kap Stevenson and Kap Brewster. The name was suggested by the Geodetic Institute in 1938 to commemorate the original discovery of Scoresby Sund by Volquaart Boon, a Danish whaler

name: Vulkanhytten

name: Vµdderen
description: High peninsula between Hellefjord and M°rkefjord. Named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen. It was climbed by Paul Gelting on 25 July 1939 during the 1938-39 M°rkeford expedition. The authorised spelling was changed from Vµderen to Vµdderen in 1973 to

name: Vµdderhornet

description: Danish hunting hut on the east coast of Vµdderen, north of the mouth of Hellefjord. Built by Nanok in 1933, and rebuilt after an avalanche in 1938. The name was approved as Vµderhytten up to 1973 and from 1984 to 1994.

name: Sarpaq

name: Satans Galleri
description: Mountain ridge with a series of formidable pinnacles running NNE of Korsspids, south of Gully Gletscher. Named by the 1963 Cambridge University expedition

name: Trµelv
description: River on the south coast of Hold with Hope, named on an NSIU map (1932a; Fig. 13) as Treelva. Fossilised wood was found in the delta of the river by Norwegian hunters in 1929 (trµ = tre = wood). Wood Valley has been used for the valley in which the river

name: Trµsko S°

name: Tsulitsuuligai

name: Tuborgfondet Land
description: Nunatak in the Garde Nunatakker group west of N°rre Mellemland. Named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition after the committee of the Tuborgfondet, which had made substantial donations to the expedition. (Tuborgfondets Land.)

name: William Smith Dal
description: E-W-trending valley on Geographical Society ╪ between Cambridge Bugt and Vega Sund. So named by Desmond T. Donovan during Lauge Koch's 1949-50 expeditions after William Smith, the pioneer of stratigraphy known as the father of English geology, who was th

name: Wiman Bjerg
description: Mountain on the south coast of Gauss Halv°. Named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Gunnar SΣve-S÷derbergh as Mt. Wiman, after Carl Wiman [1867-1944], a Swedish palaeontologist and stratigrapher. A professor at the University of Uppsala, he was c

name: Windy Corner
description: Northern end of Prins Axel Nunatak, where a party of the 1952-54 British North Greenland expedition was storm-bound for two days. It was known as a particularly windy area. The name was occasionally used informally in expedition accounts (Simpson 1957).

name: Ursus Major Gletscher

name: Ursus Minor Gletscher

name: Sonnenkopf

name: Teebjerg

name: Savoia Halv°

name: Schaffhauserdalen

description: Mountain 1617 m high in central Hudson Land. Named by Heinrich Bⁿtler during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition after Ferdinand Schalch [1848-1918], a German geologist noted for his work on the geology of Baden and Schaffhausen. (Schalchs Bjerg.)

name: Schiwiese

name: Tellplatte

description: Valley connecting Svejstrup Dal and Tyrolerdal, the present Mellemdal. The name was used by Mittelholzer (1941) in his report on work during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition (verbindung = connection).

name: Verena Horn
description: Mountain in south Goodenough Land about 2320 m high. The name was used by EugΘne Wegmann during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, and commemorates a locality in Switzerland of similar name. It was climbed by John Haller on 13 August 1953. (Verena Hornes.)

name: Stenen
description: Northern peak of Moltke Nunatak. The name was given by the Place Name Committee in 1940 to replace a suggestion by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition. An association with Milepµlen immediately to the south was intended (stenen = the stone).

name: Stenknolden
description: Marked feature on the coast of east Germania Land south of Syttenkilometernµs; exact position uncertain. The name was used by Thostrup (2007) in his account of the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen (J. L°ve, personal communication 2009).

name: Stenl°sgletscher
description: Glacier on the south side of Knµkdalen, notable for the absence of moraine or dirt bands. Named by the 1933 Louise A. Boyd Arctic expedition as Moraineless Glacier.

name: Stenmanden
description: Mountain at the west end of Grejsdal, where it divides into Gnejsdal and Djµvlekl°ften. Named by John Haller following explorations during Lauge Koch's 1949-51 expeditions, for the presence of a large band of migmatitic gneiss in the shape of a man.

name: Steno Brµ
description: Glacier west of Manby Halv° on the north Blosseville Kyst. Named by the 1898-1900 Carlsbergfondets Expedition after the pioneer Danish geologist Niels Steensen. Nicolaus Stenonis (Niels Steensen) [1638-86], a Danish cleric, physician and geologist, was n

name: Steno Land
description: Land area between Vibeke Gletscher and Wordie Gletscher, so named by Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions. In its original usage the name covered the area extending west to Waltershausen Gletscher and thus included the present Ole R°mer Land. The limits were

name: Stenpikkerelv
description: River on the west side of Rypefjord. Named during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions by Svend Funder for the numerous wheatear (= stenpikker, i.e. Oenanthe oenanthe).

name: Stensi÷ Bjerg
description: Mountain on the SW coast of Gauss Halv°. Named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Gunnar SΣve-S÷derbergh as Mt. Stensi÷, for Erik A:son Stensi÷ [1891-1984]. An eminent palaeozoologist, he became professor at the Swedish Museum of Natural History a

name: Stensi÷ Plateau
description: Plateau in north Hold with Hope between Gulelv and Blσelv, named during Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions after Erik A:son Stensi÷ who described the fossil fishes collected from the region by Koch's expeditions. (Stensi° Plateau, Stensi÷fjellet, Stensi÷be

name: Stensund
description: Fjord in east Liverpool Land NW of Kap Topham. So named by Helge G. Backlund during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, who thought it to be a sound.

name: Stens°
description: Small lake in Morµnebakkerne, north of Zackenberg Forskningsstation. It was named in 1998 by Kirsten S. Christoffersen because it has a stony bottom.

name: Sten°rken
