name: Steward ╪
description: Small island SW of Kap Brewster. Named by William Scoresby Jr. in 1822 as Steward Island, after Charles Steward of Yarmouth, a companion on one of his earlier voyages to the whale fishery. The name appeared on the maps of the 1879 Ingolf expedition (Mour

name: Stigb°jlen
description: Large island in J°kelbugten. Named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition, together with the adjacent islands Hammeren and Ambolten, for a supposed resemblance in shape to bones in the ear (stigb°jlen = stirrup).

name: Stigdalen
description: Valley on west Geographical Society ╪, draining south into Vega Sund. So named on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937) because the valley is steep (= stig).

name: Stejlgletscher
description: Glacier west of the head of Smallefjord (Fig. 81). The name originated from the wintering party at Kulhus during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen.

name: Stille ╪
description: Southern island of the Finsch ╪er group. Named by Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions in the form Stille Island for the German petrographer and structural geologist Hans Stille [1876-1966], noted for his studies of mountain building processes. Norwegian map

name: Stirling Fjeld
description: Mountain 1640 m high on the south side of Bersµrkerbrµ, north Stauning Alper. First climbed by John Hunt's 1960 expedition, and at the request of the boys of the expedition named Stirling for Stirling Castle, an outstanding example of renaissance achitec

name: Torbern Bergman Bjerg
description: Mountain 1515 m high in Moskusokselandet, north of the mouth of Moskusoksefjord. Named by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst after Torbern Olof Bergman [1735-1784], a Swedish scientist noted for his contributions to qualitati

name: Sfinxgletscher
description: Glacier east of Sfinxen on Volquaart Boon Kyst, so named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Laurits Bruhn.

name: Shackleton Bjerg
description: Prominent peak about 2900 m high in SW Goodenough Land. The name was given by J.M. Wordie's 1926 Cambridge expedition, to commemorate Sir Ernest Henry Shackleton [1874-1923], a noted British Antarctic explorer. Shackleton was a member of Scott's 1901-04

name: Shale Peak
description: Mountain north of Ardencaple Fjord, N°rlund Land, climbed by Michael Banks and Richard Brooke in 1952 during the 1952-54 British North Greenland expedition. It was named for the shales forming the summit (Banks 1955).

name: Shangri-la
description: Sheltered corner of Thomson Klippe or Newton Klippe, west Dronning Louise Land. The locality was used as a camp site by the 1952-54 British North Greenland expedition, and so named informally because it provided a haven from the piercing wind. Shangri-La

name: Shannon
description: Large island east of Hochstetter Forland. Named Shannon Island by Douglas Clavering in 1823 after the Royal Navy frigate SHANNON, a 38-gun frigate on which he served as midshipman under Sir Philip Broke. See also Kap Philip Broke. Ejnar Mikkelsen occasio

name: Shannon Sund
description: Broad sound between Shannon and Hochstetter Forland. The name was said to have been used by Danish hunters from about 1929, and first appears on the maps of the 1932 Gefion expedition (Jennov 1935). (Shannonsund.)

name: Shannonfjorden
description: Name occasionally used by Norwegian hunters and sealers for the fjord complex west of Shannon, comprising the present Shannon Sund, Peters Bugt and Ardencaple Fjord (Isachsen & Isachsen 1932).

name: Sharks Fin
description: Culmination of a narrow ridge on the south side of Korridoren, Milne Land. Climbed, apart from the final 70 m, by the 2004 West Lancashire Scouts expedition.

name: Shell Iskappe
description: Small ice cap in central Dronning Louise Land, SW of Army Iskappe. Named by the 1952-54 British North Greenland expedition after the Shell Petroleum Company, one of the two financial supporters of the expedition, which provided fuel, advice, facilities,

name: Strindberghuset
description: Norwegian summer station built in June 1935 at the mouth of Brogetdal, Strindberg Land, for salmon fishing. Attempts at tinning salmon (arctic char) were made here in 1938. The station was renovated in 1954. It has also been known as Laksehytta. (Strindb

name: Strindberghytta
description: Norwegian hunting hut in Strindberg Land at the mouth of Brogetdal, built by Arktisk Nµringsdrift in 1930. In 1935 it was demolished, and the material used to build Strindberghuset. (Strindberghytten.)

name: Striped Cliff
description: Cliff at the bend of Knµkdalen where the stream from Lystergletscher meets Knµkelven. So named by the 1933 Louise A. Boyd Arctic expedition because of the alternating dark and light layers of the banded gneisses.

name: Strip÷ya
description: Island in the Finsch ╪er group, so named on an NSIU map (1932a) for its long, narrow form.

name: Strittberg
description: Peak about 1840 m high on the west side of Spµrregletscher. It was climbed, and so named, by the 1964 AAC Zⁿrich expedition.

name: Str°mbugt
description: Large bay on SW Milne Land, opposite the mouth of Vestfjord. Named during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions by Svend Funder for the marked tidal current along the coast of the bay.

name: Str°mhytta
description: Norwegian hunting hut on the north coast of Geographical Society ╪, SE of Robertson ╪. Built by Arktisk Nµringsdrift in August 1929, and named after Ingwald Str°m, one of the three hunters who built it. It was moved to Sofia Sund in August 1932 where it

name: Str°mhytta
description: Norwegian hunting hut on the north side of DusΘn Fjord, SW of Barrieren. Built by Arktisk Nµringsdrift in September 1930, 2 km east of the narrow part of the fjord which is subject to strong currents (= str°m). The hut has also been called Dyrfaret (NSIU

name: Str°mmen
description: Narrow part of northern Loch Fyne marked by strong tidal currents, named by Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions. (Str÷mmen, Straumen.)

name: Str°mmenhytten
description: Danish hunting hut on the west coast of Loch Fyne, east Hudson Land, immediately south of Str°mmen (Fig. 82). It was built by Nanok in September 1950, and has also been known as Danske Villa. The Norwegian hut on the east side of Loch Fyne has also gone

name: Str°mnµs
description: Peninsula half way along R÷hss Fjord, at the narrowest part where there is a strong tidal current. The name was used by EugΦne Wegmann during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen. A ruined hut lies on the east side of the peninsula (see Str°mnµshytten).

name: Roscoe Bjerge
description: Mountain chain in south Liverpool Land, thickly crested and serrated with pinnacles, whose north limit is taken as a line through S°dal and Aage Nielsen Gletscher. The mountains were named by William Scoresby Jr. in 1822 as the Roscoe Mountains in compli

name: Roseneathbugt
description: Pronounced bay on the north part of the east coast of Hochstetter Forland, south of Haystack. Named by Douglas Clavering in 1823 in the form Roseneath Inlet after the locality opposite Ardencaple Castle, Dumbarton, Scotland (Rosneath on modern maps). It

name: Rosenheimer Spids
description: Mountain 1950 m high on the ridge between Duart Gletscher and the upper basin of Spµrregletscher. Climbed by the 1966 Deutsche Gr÷nland-Expedition in die Staunings-Alpen led by Karl M. Herligkoffer, and named after the small town of Rosenheim at the foot

name: Rosenjoch
description: Highest point in the camp area of the 1943-44 Operation Bassgeiger at Kap Sussi, Shannon. The name is reported by Olsen (1965).

name: Rosenvinge
description: Name occasionally used in error for the town of Scoresbysund in reports by French scientists of J.-B. Charcot's expeditions (e.g. Faure 1933). Scoresbysund lies on the north side of Rosenvinge Bugt.

name: Rosenvinge Bugt
description: Large bay in south Liverpool Land. Named by the 1898-1900 Carlsbergfondets Expedition led by G.C. Amdrup, after Janus Andreas Kolderup-Rosenvinge [1858-1939], a Danish botanist and professor at the University of Copenhagen. (Rosenvinge Bay, Bai de Rosenv

name: Rosinante
description: Mountain 758 m high on NW Ymer ╪ (Fig. 74. Named during Lauge Koch's 1947-49 expeditions by Silvio Eha, possibly for a supposed resemblance to Don Quixote's horse. It has also been called Little Chocolate Mountain.

name: Sletta
description: Norwegian hunting hut on the east side of Albrecht Bugt, Wollaston Forland built by the Hird expedition in 1928. Named after the wide plain (= sletta) where it is situated. It has also been known as Grµstorvshytten. (Sletten, Slettehuset, Slette Huset.)

name: Slettedalen
description: Broad flat valley between Lindeman Fjord and Store S°dal. The name is attributed to the wintering party at Kulhus in 1935.

name: Slettefloden
description: River draining Storsletten in north Wollaston Forland. Named by Wolf Maync and Andreas Vischer during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition.

name: Slettehytten
description: Danish hunting hut built for Nanok in May 1947 on the west side of Storsletten, Wollaston Forland.

name: Slettens°
description: Shallow lake on the plain south of Vesterport and Morµnebakkerne, north of Zackenberg Forskningsstation. It was named in 1998 by Kirsten S. Christoffersen. Information from Lars Holst Hansen, 2011. (Dammen I Vestkµret).

name: Slien
description: Fjord in east Liverpool Land NE of Kap James. Named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Laurits Bruhn.

name: Slippen
description: Valley on the north side of Gunnar Andersson Land, Ymer ╪, draining NE. Named by Th. Johansen during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen. It is a long narrow ravine with a moderate gradient (slippen = the slipway).

name: Slippenhytten
description: Norwegian hunting hut built in August 1938 for Ole Klokset's expedition at the mouth of the valley Slippen, Gunner Andersson Land. It has also been known as Kloksethytten and Kap Martha Hytten.

name: Slottet
description: Minor summit on a ridge NW of Kap Leslie, east Milne Land. Named by Hermann Aldinger during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen in the form Schloss (= castle = slot). (Castle Hill).

name: Slottet
description: Imposing nunatak of white quartzite at the east end of Langeryg, Arnold Escher Land (Fig. 79). Named during Lauge Koch's 1951 expedition by Hans R. Katz for its supposed resemblance to a castle.

name: Slottneset
description: Cape on east Geographical Society ╪, corresponding to the south flank of Kap Mackenzie. So named on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937) because it resembles a castle (= slot) in shape.

name: Slugtdal
description: Valley west of Antarctic Havn, north Scoresby Land. So named by Hans Kapp during the 1957-58 Lauge Koch expeditions, because of the marked ravine in the valley. (Slugtdalen.)

name: Slugtdalen
description: Valley in north Hudson Land draining north to Wordie Gletscher. Named by Heinrich Bⁿtler during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition. Mehrendalen is used on Lacmann's (1937) maps.

name: Slate River
description: Name used by Hermann Aldinger during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen for the present Ostreaelv, a river in south Jameson Land where there are slaty rocks (Aldinger 1935).

name: Slyngelv
description: Minor tributary to Lakseelven NE of M°rkefjord Station. So named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition for its strongly meandering course (slynge = swing).

name: Vergys
description: Mountain in Hudson Land south of Dybendal, so named by Heinrich Bⁿtler during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition after the mountain chain of the same name in the Savoy Alps.

name: Verlorenes Tal
description: Name used by Stauber (1938) for a valley on east Traill ╪, following work during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition. It takes its name from a wild valley south of Thusis, Switzerland. In a slightly modified sense it was approved in the form ╪dedal, a name a

name: Vermessungsbjerg
description: Name used by Helge G. Backlund for the present Rungstedbjerg, south of Wordie Bugt in north Hudson Land.

name: Vertebrae
description: Small glacier on the north side of Gully Gletscher. Probably named by the 1963 Cambridge University expedition, which climbed many peaks in this region.

name: Vesle Finsch
description: Next largest of the Finsch ╪er, so named on an NSIU map (1932a) for its size relative to Store Finsch. (Lille Finsch ╪, Vesle Finsch°ya).

name: Vesle Vinter÷ya
description: Smaller of the two Vinter°er at the mouth of DusΘn Fjord, so named on an NSIU map (1932a) for its relative size.

name: Vestdammen i Gadekµret
description: Western of two ponds in Gadekµret, immediately east of Zackenberg Forskningsstation. It was named by Hans Meltofte. Information from Lars Holst Hansen, 2011. (Gadekµret Vest.)

name: Vestelv
description: River west of Kap Leslie, east Milne Land, named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Hermann Aldinger as Westfluss.

name: Vestelven
description: Reference locality used by visitors to Zackenberg Forskningsstation.

name: Vesterdalen
description: Valley west of Danmarkshavn on the NW side of Harefjeldet. So named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen. (West Valley.)

name: Vesterelv
description: Small river near Eskimonµs station, south Clavering ╪, draining into Vesthavn. The name originated from the wintering party at Eskimonµs during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen. Flipa has also been used.

name: Vesterelven

name: Vesternµsset
description: Peninsula about 7 km west of Kap Beurman on the north side of Bessel Fjord. It was used as a reference locality in the archaeological report of the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen (Thostrup 1911). (West Naze.)

name: Vesterport
description: Mountain between Femdalen and Kildedalen in C.H. Ostenfeld Land. The name is attributed to the wintering party at Kulhus in 1935. The mountain marks the gateway (= port) to the inner western part of the fjord, and the name apparently first appeared on a

name: Vesterport
description: Area north of Zackenberg Forskningsstation, west of the major river flowing through Zackenbergdalen into Zackenberg Bugt.

name: Vesterport S°
description: Small lake in the area known as Vesterport, north of Zackenberg Forskningsstation. The name was introduced by Hans Meltofte. Information from Lars Holst Hansen, 2011.

name: Vestersletten
description: Broad plain west of Mackenzie Bugt, named on an NSIU map (1932a) as Vestflya. The 1932 NSIU expedition used the area as the main base for its flying operations, and established their Balσs flyveplass here.

name: Vestfjeldet
description: Mountain on the west side of S°dalen, west of Profilfjeldet. Named by Eigil Nielsen during the 1938-39 M°rkeford expedition as Vestfjµldet.

name: Vestfjord
description: Fjord extending westwards from the southern part of R°defjord. So named by the 1891-92 Den ╪stgr°nlandske expedition led by Carl Ryder for its direction. (West Fjord, VΣstfjorden.)

name: R°de Roseelv
description: River in east Hudson Land draining east into Loch Fyne. The name was used by Gunnar SΣve-S÷derbergh during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, originally in the form Red Rose Valley.

name: R°de St°vhorn
description: Mountain on the north side of Dickson Fjord. Named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by EugΘne Wegmann originally as Red Staubhorn, after a professor Staub of Zⁿrich, an ironic tribute to a colleague who as a consequence of excessive drinking often

name: R°debjerg
description: Mountain ridge SW of Mesters Vig. Named by prospecting teams associated with Lauge Koch's 1948-49 expeditions for the colour.

name: R°debjerg
description: Mountain 1683 m high on south Ymer ╪. Named as R÷da Berget by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst because it was made up of red Devonian sandstone. (Red Mountain, R°da Mountain, R°da Berget.)

name: R°debjerghytten
description: Norwegian hunting hut built for Arktisk Nµringsdrift in October 1929 on the north side of Sofia Sund, about 7 km east of R°debjerg. It has also been known as Arentzhytta and Snehytten.

name: Toretind

name: Torkjellfjellet

name: Torn°eh°gda
description: Mountain on south Geographical Society ╪. So named on NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937) after Johannes Kristoffer Torn°e [b. 1892], a Norwegian who took part in NSIU expeditions to Svalbard and Greenland. He was also secretary of NSIU.

name: Torn°estua
description: Norwegian hunting hut built in August 1933 by John Giµver's expedition on the north side of Smallefjord. Named after J. K. Torn°e, see above. It is also known as Smallefjordhytten. (Thorn°e-hytten.)

name: Torteerniarfik
description: Hillside west of Kap Brewster on Volquaart Boon Kyst. Recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, the name translates as æwhere one collects rhododendrons'. (TortΩrniarfik.)

name: Torv Brµ

name: Torvet
description: Small glacier east of Gavlen on Volquaart Boon Kyst, surrounded on three sides by high mountain ridges. So named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Laurits Bruhn for its appearance (torv = market place, square).

name: Torvgletscher
description: Large flat glacier or small ice cap on Volquaart Boon Kyst forming the plateau above Torvet. Named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Laurits Bruhn. See also Torv Brµ.

name: Toscano Gletscher
description: Glacier on the SE side of Frederiksdal near Fures°, Nathorst Land. So named during Lauge Koch's 1954-55 expeditions by Hans Zweifel, because Eduard Wenk smoked his last æToscano' cigar of the summer here.

name: Tour CarrΘe
description: Peak 2250 m high in the north Stauning Alper at the head of Frihedsgletscher. Named and climbed by Claude Rey's 1970 expedition.

name: Tour Chartreuse

name: Tour Vercors

name: Tour de Pavot

name: Tovika
description: Bay on south Geographical Society ╪, divided into two parts by a flat sandy peninsula. Used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937; Fig. 14), and so named because it has two parts (to = two).

name: Trafsa
description: Stream on south Clavering ╪, the present ╪sterelv. Only used on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937).

name: Traill Hytten
description: Norwegian hunting hut built in August 1929 by Arktisk Nµringsdrift in northern Traill ╪, on the south side of Vega Sund. It is also known as ╪sthytten and Sn°heim.

name: Traill ╪
description: Large island bounded by Vega Sund and Kong Oscar Fjord (Fig. 29). Named Traill Island by William Scoresby Jr. in 1822 in compliment to a highly esteemed friend, Thomas Stewart Traill [1781-1862], who became professor of medical jurisprudence at Edinburgh

name: Traill-iup Immikkeertivi
description: Island group off SW Traill ╪ on the south side of Holm Bugt. The Greenlandic name was recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, and translates as æTraill's islands'. (Traill-iup ingmikΩrtive.)

name: Trammen
description: Small island in central Vega Sund adjacent to Gσse°en. Used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937) and so named because the island is small with a step-like shape (trammen = small step).

name: Trangen
description: Name occasionally used for the Norwegian hut built in September 1930 for Arktisk Nµringsdrift at the narrow part of the head of DusΘn Fjord (trang = narrow, tight). It is more usually known as Dyrfaret or Str°mhytten.

name: Trangfjorden
description: Name used by Norwegian hunters in the 1930s for the relatively narrow stretch of Tyrolerfjord on the north side of Clavering ╪, bounded to the north by the steep cliffs of Zackenberg and to the south by those of the Eiger. It was also used by Danish hunt

name: Vµgtertσrnet
description: Mountain 1340 m high between Rolige Brµ and Vestfjord. Named by Laurent Jemelin during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions for a resemblance to a watch-tower.

name: Str°mnµsdal
description: Valley in Gletscherland draining into R÷hss Fjord at Str°mnµs. So named by EugΦne Wegmann during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen.

name: Str°mnµshorn
description: Mountain in Gletscherland between Str°mnµsdal and R÷hss Fjord, so named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by EugΦne Wegmann.

name: Str°mnµshytten
description: Norwegian hunting hut on the south side of R÷hss Fjord at Str°mnµs (Fig. 82), built in July 1934 for Arktisk Nµringsdrift. It was originally known as Festningen. Now a ruin. An old dog-sledge and a heavy wooden boat lie beside the hut, the latter abandon

name: Str°msbukta
description: Norwegian hunting hut built in August 1933 by John Giµver's expedition 2-3 km west of Kap Peschel, Ad. S. Jensen Land.

name: Str°msund
description: Narrow sound of the coast of SE Daniel Bruun Land. So named by the 1912-13 Den danske Ekspedition til Dronning Louises Land because they encountered a 4-5 knot strong current while negotiating the sound with their boat. (Straumsund.)

name: Str°mtangen
description: Low peninsula on the west side of the mouth of Loch Fyne. Named on an NSIU map (1932a) as Straumtangen, because it was built up by strong currents.

name: Stubba
description: River draining the southern Giesecke Bjerge, flowing in the present Sindalen. So named on the 1932a NSIU map. The name in translation implies something short or stubby.

name: Stubbdalen
description: Valley in the south Giesecke Bjerge, corresponding to Sindalen, and carrying the river Stubba. So named on the 1932a NSIU map.

name: Stuegulvet
description: Low (1780 m) and easy summit on the north side of Roslin Gletscher. Ascended on ski by the 1996 Norwegian Stauning Alper expedition, it was situated north of one of their depots. The name translates as æground floor'.

name: Stugunosa
description: Hill 252 m high north of Myggbukta. So named on an NSIU map (1932a; Fig. 13), for its proximity to Myggbukta station (stugu = house).

name: Stuttgarter Spids
description: Mountain on the south side of the head of Roslin Gletscher. Climbed by the 1966 Deutsche Gr÷nland-Expedition in die Staunings-Alpen led by Karl M. Herligkoffer on 21 August 1966, and named after the south German city of Stuttgart, capital of Baden-Wⁿrtem

name: Styggbreen
description: Lobe of Wordie Gletscher between Scotstounhill and Manley Bjerg. Used on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937), the name was given for its grim and dangerous appearance (stygg = nasty).

name: St°vdal
description: Valley between the snouts of Admiralty Gletscher and Britannia Gletscher, filled by moraine, fluvial and aeolian deposits (Fig. 21). So named by the 1952-54 British North Greenland expedition because of the frequent dust spirals seen here during the summ

name: Tunnel Pools
description: Name used by University of Dundee expeditions between 1968 and 1974 for seven temporary lakes east of the lower end of Tunnelelv gorge, west of Mestersvig airfield.

name: Tunnelelv
description: River draining Store Blydal, north Scoresby Land. So named by prospecting teams associated with Lauge Koch's 1948-49 expedition, because it runs in a deep canyon at the mouth of the valley. Falcons and geese regularly nest on the canyon walls.

name: Tupikajik
description: Small hill on the valley floor near the south end of Klitdal. One of the names recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, the name refers to its shape, meaning æthe little tent'.

name: Tupilaq

name: Sorteskµr

name: Sorthorn

name: South Cirque Glacier

name: South Lochan

name: Spalenbjerg

description: Branch of the floating E-W-trending glacier filling Nioghalvfjerdsfjorden which extends north into Dijmphna Sund. Named by Elmar Drastrup's 1938-39 expedition for the numerous wide crevasses. Gustav Thostrup and Alfred Wegener were delayed by the crevass

name: Terrasohytten

name: Schuchert/╓rsteds Pass
description: Name used by Hall (1964) for the pass between ╪rsted Dal and Schuchert Dal.

name: Schultzhytten
description: Danish hunting hut built for Nanok in the spring of 1938 east of Trekronen, Germania Land, by Carl Henrik Schultz. It has also been known as Trekronerhytten, Pashytten, Hvalsletten and Slettehytten.

name: Schwaben Gletscher
description: Glacier in the NE part of the Borgbjerg Gletscher region, southern Stauning Alper, NW of Schwabentinde. Probably named by the 1977 SchwΣbische Stauning Alper expedition.

name: Schwarck-Tal

name: Schwarze Wand

name: Schwarzer Zwilling

name: Scioraspids

name: Stjernefjeldene
description: Range of hills in Daniel Bruun Land south of M°rkefjord, named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen as Stjerne fjeldene. When all the watches at the meteorological station manned by Peter Freuchen at Pustersvig became unreliable, Alfred Wegener and J.P.

name: Stjernes°en

name: Stopklodsen
description: Small island in Dijmphna Sund at the front of Spaltegletscher. The name is attributed to David Malmquist following his work with Lauge's Koch geological expeditions, and arose because the glacier front then rested on the island (stopklodsen = door stop).

name: Zachers Grav
description: Grave of Gerhard Zacher at Kap Sussi (Fig. 16). He was a member of the German 1943-44 Bassgeiger meteorological expedition, shot during a raid by the sledge patrol on 22 April 1944. The grave was intact in 1988, and the inscription on the broken cross st

name: Zackenberg

name: ╪stersletten

name: ╪stkµret

name: ╪stre Havnenµs

name: Rosinante Pas

name: Rosio
description: Small island on the south side of Skµrfjorden. Named by the 1905 ExpΘdition Arctique du Duc d'OrlΘans as Ilot del Rosio. æRosio' is French for Walrus. The name was misplaced by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen, the original Rosio being the present Rekve

name: Roslin Borg
description: Mountain 2560 m high at the head of Roslin Gletscher, south Stauning Alper. It was first climbed by the 1958 Scottish East Greenland expedition led by Malcolm Slesser, and named after Roslin Castle, near Edinburgh, part of which dates from the 14th centu

name: Roslin Gletscher
description: Glacier more than 20 km long in the south Stauning Alper, flowing SE to Schuchert Dal. It was first traversed by the 1958 Scottish East Greenland expedition led by Malcolm Slesser and named Roslin Glacier, officially approved in danicised form in 1959. D

name: Rosmule
description: Peninsula on the south side of Borgj°kel, Dronning Louise Land, named by the 1912-13 Den danske Ekspedition til Dronning Louises Land. Possibly given for the shape (rosmule = horse muzzle), or an incident with the ponies used on the expedition. (Rosmulen

description: Mountain 426 m high on Lille Pendulum. Named by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt as Stufenberg, probably for the step-like profile of successive basalt lava flows. The SW flank of the mountain projecting into the sea has been called Kap Stu

name: Teufelkap

name: Tevla

name: Th. S°rensen Land
description: Land area between Flyverfjord and Edvard Bay Dal (Fig. 41). Named by Geoffrey Halliday following botanical work during the 1971 Northern Universities expedition, for Thorvald Julius S°rensen [1902-73], a Danish botanist who had published the botanical wo

description: Land area bordered by Grandjean Fjord, Svejstrup Dal, Tvegegletscher and Fligely Fjord (Fig. 15). Mapped by Lauge Koch during flights in 1932 on the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen expedition, it was named after Thomas Thomsen [1870-1941], Danish ethnographe

name: The Great Claw

name: The Rock Finger
description: Prominent minor peak on the south side of Harlech Gletscher, north of Poplar, north Stauning Alper. First climbed by the 1963 Imperial College expedition, it was named for its appearance. (The Finger.)

name: Stor-Dalen
description: Name sometimes used for the Norwegian hunting hut east of the mouth of Barnabas Dal, south Ymer ╪, and also used by Norwegians for the valley itself. The hut was moved to this site from the opposite side of the fjord in October 1930, where it was known a

name: Storborgen
description: Peninsula between Smallefjord and Bredefjord (Fig. 51). The name is attributed to the wintering party at Kulhus in 1935, and derives from its resemblance to a large castle (borg = castle).

name: Store Koldewey

name: Store Myteklippe
description: Cliff on the south coast of Kaskades°, west Gσseland. So named during Lauge Koch's 1958 expedition by Eduard Wenk, because it and the adjacent cliff (Lille Myteklippe) were similar in their form and tectonic relationships to the Grossen Mythen and Kleine

name: Store Norske

name: Store Raset

name: Store S°
description: Original name for the present Sµls°en, which was discovered during the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen. This version of the name is mentioned by Trolle (1909), and also appears on a sketch map by C.S. Poulsen published in Lundbye (1984). Lakses° has also b

name: Store S°
description: Name used by scientists at Zackenberg Forskningsstation for the largest and easternmost of the two large lakes in Store S°dal. Information from Lars Holst Hansen, 2011.

name: Trangfjordhuset
description: Norwegian hunting hut on the north side of central Tyrolerfjord, which they usually called Trangfjorden. The hut was built in September 1927 by the Foldvik expedition, and also goes under the names Meyer-hus and Zackenberghuset.

name: Trangsund
description: Narrow sound between Stille ╪ (Kil÷ya) and Strip÷ya in the Finsch ╪er group. So named on the 1932a NSIU map.

name: Trangsund
description: Narrow sound between the island Tvillingerne and the mainland to the south. So named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition led by Ebbe Munck and Eigil Knuth (trang = narrow). Zielers Sund has also been used.

name: Moskusoksefjord
description: Fjord between Moskusokselandet and Gauss Halv°, named by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst as Myskoxefjorden because he saw 67 muskox on the fjord sides on his first exploration of the fjord. (Muskoxen Fjord, Muskox Fiord, M

name: Moskusoksehytte
description: Name for a hut in SE Hold with Hope built in August 1927 by the Foldvik expedition, which was partly covered by muskox skins. The hut has also been known under the names Bukta, Tvivlsom and Skandalen. (Moskushytte.)

name: Moskusoksekl°ft
description: Ravine on the west side of Hurry Inlet, named by Alfred Rosenkrantz during Lauge Koch's 1926-27 expeditions in the form Moskusokse Kl°ft, after the numerous muskoxen. (Musk-ox Kl°ft.)

name: Moskusokselandet
description: SW part of Hudson Land, between Moskusoksefjord to the south, and Ankerbjergselv, Visp and Johan Davidsen Dal to the north. Named by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst as Myskoxelandet after the abundant muskoxen seen on the

name: Moskusokses°
description: Lake in south Strindberg Land, west of Moskusoksefjeld. Named during Lauge Koch's 1948-49 expeditions by Hans R. Katz after the muskox (Fig. 60).

name: Moskus°yra
description: Large delta on west Clavering ╪, the present Tangen. Used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937), and named after the numerous muskoxen seen here.

name: Mosquito Ridge
description: Ridge on the west side of M°ns Elv, southern Jameson Land. Named by Herman Aldinger during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen after the abundant mosquitoes.

name: Mount Brassica
description: Point 2065 m high on the ice cap north of Edward Bailey Gletscher, Renland. Climbed and named by the 2007 West Lancashire Mountaineering Group expedition.

name: Mount Fatigue
description: Summit on the south side of Korridoren, Milne Land. Climbed by the 2004 West Lancashire Scouts expedition.

name: Mount Marcel Bertrand
description: Mountain in SE Suess Land, NE of Lumskebugten, the present Gravh°jen. The name was used by EugΘne Wegmann during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen (Wegmann 1935), and given for Marcel Alexandre Bertrand [1847-1907], a French stratigrapher and structural ge

name: Mount of Gods Mercie
description: Mountain probably corresponding to the Blσserk of the Icelandic sagas and the present Rigny Bjerg on the Blosseville Kyst (Ryder 1892; Torn° 1935). It was seen and named during the 1607 Henry Hudson voyage, where it was described as a ôvery high mount, l

name: Mount Mistake
description: Minor peak north of Ardencaple Fjord climbed in error by Mike Banks and Richard Brookes in 1952 during the 1952-54 British North Greenland Expedition; they had to descend it again to regain their route to Matterhorn (Banks 1955).

name: Mount Petersberg
description: Highest part of the cliff on the south side of Trµkpasset, Store Koldewey, named by Louise Boyd who climbed it on 15 August 1938 during the 1938 Louise A. Boyd Arctic expedition. It features in Den Gr°nlandske Lods (1968) as St. Petersburg Bjerg.

name: Ran ╪er
description: Small islands or skerries on the SW side of Kong Oscar Fjord. Named by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst as Rans SkΣr, according to Nathorst's expedition narrative after æden falska Ran'; this features in the Swedish master

name: Randbjerg
description: Ridge between Endel°s and Spaltegletscher, AndrΘe Land. Named during Lauge Koch's 1948-50 expeditions by Erdhardt FrΣnkl (rand = edge).

name: Randb°ldalen
description: Valley in the south Giescke Bjerge, draining eastwards. The name was proposed by the Place Name Committee in 1939 after the area of Randb°l in mid-Jylland where there are more than 300 burial mounds. Bj÷rndalen and Franklindalen have also been used.

name: Randelven
description: Name used by the 1912-13 Den danske Ekspedition til Dronning Louises Land for a large river at the margin of the Inland Ice in west Daniel Bruun Land, flowing into Borgfjorden (rand = margin).

name: Randen
description: High plateau in Ole R°mer Land west of Vibeke S°. Named by Heinrich Bⁿtler during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition, probably for the locality of the same name near Schaffhausen.

name: Randenµs
description: Peninsula on the north side of Forsblads Fjord. So named by EugΘne Wegmann during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, probably because the peninsula marks an important geological boundary.

name: Randers Fjord
description: Fjord on the east coast of central Liverpool Land, named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Laurits Bruhn after the fjord of the same name on the east coast of Jylland, Denmark.

name: Randspids
description: Mountain at the SW margin of the Werner Bjerge (rand = margin). Named by Peter Bearth and Eduard Wenk during Lauge Koch's 1953-54 expeditions and climbed by Bearth in 1954.

name: Rossily Bjerg
description: Mountain 770 m high in east Scoresby Land, originally named Cape Rossily by William Scoresby Jr. in compliment to a French philosopher, probably Francois Etienne Rosily-Mesros. Scoresby used the form Cape Rossilly in the appendix of his English (1823) na

name: Rostrum Avis
description: Name used for the feature Fuglenµbsfjeldet on the Christmas card sent to Peter Freuchen at Pustervig in 1907. It is reproduced in Koch (1916 p. 398). (Fuglenµb = bird's beak = rostrum avis).

name: RothΘ Island
description: Name proposed for the present Janus ╪ off the coast of south Liverpool Land by Helge G. Backlund during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen. Jean RothΘ was a French geophysicist, one of the party manning the French International Polar Year station at Scoresb

name: Round Pond
description: Name used by the 1968-74 Dundee University expeditions for a small pool near Langdyssen at the NE end of Mestersvig airfield, possibly identical with Gσses°.

name: Rovmσges°
description: Lake east of Scoresbysund town in south Liverpool Land. Named during the 1924-25 colonisation expedition for the numerous Arctic gulls (Pedersen 1926). (Rovmaages°, Arctic Gull Lake.)

name: Royal Peak
description: Mountain 2500 m high between the head of Bersµrkerbrµ and Schuchert Gletscher, Stauning Alper. It was first climbed by the 1961 Bangor expedition. The second ascent has been stated to be by the 1963 Imperial College expedition (Bennet 1972), which called

name: Royston Nunatakker
description: Nunatak group south of Daugaard-Jensen Gletscher. Mapped by Lauge Koch during flights in 1932 on the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, and apparently named after the small town of Royston north of London where Arthur Hinks had a summer cottage (See also Hinks

name: Rubjerg Knude
description: Mountain on north Traill ╪. Named by Ove Simonsen during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen after the Danish locality of the same name on the coast SW of Hirtshals, Jylland.

name: Rud.-Johansen Valley
description: Valley in SE Suess Land, the present ╪rkendal. The name was used by EugΘne Wegmann during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen (Wegmann 1935), and was in general use by expedition members in 1931-32. It was said to be named after the master-tailor Rud.-Johans

name: Rudbeck Bjerg
description: Mountain 1322 m high on north Geographical Society ╪. Named by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst as Rudbecks Berg, possibly after Olaf (Olaus) Rudbeck [1660-1740], a noted Swedish scientist, whose best-known work was his fiv

name: Rudi Bugt
description: Small fjord on the NW side of Clavering ╪, named by Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions in the form Rudi Bay for the Norwegian hunter Henry Rudi who hunted from Moskusheimen (also known as Revet) at the head of the bay for many years. Henry Rudi was one of

name: Ruin ╪
description: Name used by Glob (1946) for the islands SE of Sydkap also known as Immikkeertivaqqat, where a large Inuit settlement with 10 house ruins was found by Helge Larsen in 1937.

name: Ruinerne
description: Mountain 1314 m high in the Werner Bjerge north of the head of Sirius Gletscher, named by Peter Bearth and Eduard Wenk during Lauge Koch's 1953-54 expeditions (ruinerne = the ruins). It was climbed by Bearth in 1953.

name: Smith Woodward Bjerg
description: Mountain on the SW coast of Gauss Halv°, named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Gunnar SΣve-S÷derbergh as Mt. Smith Woodward. Sir Arthur Smith Woodward [1864-1944] was a British vertebrate palaeontologist noted for his work at the British Museum

name: Smith's Island
description: Supposedly an island adjacent to Canning Land, but probably the mountain behind the present Kap Tyrell (Fig. 3). It was named by William Scoresby Jr. in 1822 for Sir James Edward Smith [1759-1828], a botanist notable for his purchase of the entire librar

name: Sm°gen
description: Valley on the south side of Langs°, N°rlund Land. The name originated from the wintering party at Kulhus during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen (sm°ge = narrow passage, alley).

name: Smσskµrene
description: Group of small skerries SE of Joinville ╪ in Skµrfjorden, so named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by David Malmquist.

name: Snaddheimen
description: Norwegian hunting hut on the coast of east Frµnkel Land, south of Niggli Dal. Built by Bjarne and Oddvar Akre for Arktisk Nµringsdrift in August 1938, and named for the ringed seal (= snadd), which is very common in the fjords. Reported as a ruin in 1976

name: Vestfjord Gletscher
description: Large glacier at the head of Vestfjord. Named during Lauge Koch's 1958 expedition by Eduard Wenk.

name: Vesthavn
description: Small harbour east of Eskimonµs station, south Clavering ╪. The name originated from the wintering party at Eskimonµs during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen. (West Harbour.)

name: Vestkronen
description: Mountain 1140 m high on the NW side of the Bjergkronerne massif, north of ╪rsted Dal. Named by Katherina Perch-Nielsen during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions.

name: Vestkµret
description: Reference locality used by visitors to Zackenberg Forskningsstation.

name: Vestlandet
description: Name used for the present Gσseland in Ragnvald Knudsen's diaries of the 1891-92 Den ╪stgr°nlandske expedition to the Scoresby Sund region.

name: Vestmar Bjerg
description: Mountain on SW Clavering ╪. The name was first used by Gelting (1934) in the form Mt. Westmar, and was given for N.C. Vestmar, captain of the GUSTAV HOLM during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen. (Vestmars Bjerg.)

name: Vestplateau
description: Minor plateau on the north slope of Frebold Bjerg, west of River 6, north Hold with Hope. So named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Eigil Nielsen.

name: Vestporten
description: Mountain forming the west side of Edvard Bay Dal as seen from Rypefjord. Named by J.D. Friderichsen during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions (port = gateway).

name: Vestre Borggletscher
description: Glacier on Volquaart Boon Kyst west of Borgen, so named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Laurits Bruhn.

name: Vestre Brudelv
description: Name used by Alfred Rosenkrantz for a west branch of Brudelv, south Liverpool Land.

name: Vestre Eskimovig
description: Bay west of Eskimovig in south Clavering ╪. The name is used in the form West Eskimo Bay in the archaeology report of J.M. Wordie's 1926 Cambridge expedition (Johnson 1933).

name: Vestre Gletscher
description: Western of three glaciers draining into the head of Deltadal, north Werner Bjerge. The name first appeared on the maps of Styger (1951) in the form Vestregletscher, and stems from a climbing excursion during Lauge Koch's 1950 expedition.

name: Vestre Havnenµs
description: Peninsula on the west side of the mouth of Danmark Havn. So named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen. (Vr. Havnenµs, West Harbour Pt.)

name: Vestre Skanse
description: Plateau area west of Pemmikanelv, south Germania Land. ╪stre Skanse occurs east of the river. Named by the 1938-39 M°rkeford expedition.

name: Vestre Spµrregletscher
description: Western of two glaciers in Suess Land which merge to dam Murgangss°. Adopted from a suggestion by EugΘne Wegmann who explored the region in 1933 during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen.

name: Vestre Tvillingegletscher
description: Western of twin glaciers south of the head of Rhedin Fjord (Fig. 88). Named by John Haller following explorations during Lauge Koch's 1952-53 expeditions.

name: Vestre Vibeke Gletscher
description: Western branch of Vibeke Gletscher, at the east side of Batholin Land. Named by John Haller following explorations during Lauge Koch's 1956-58 expeditions.

name: Vestre Vikingeborg
description: Mountain on the west side of Borggletscher, on the south side of Kejser Franz Joseph Fjord. Named by John Haller following explorations during Lauge Koch's 1952-53 expeditions.

name: Vestreplateau
description: Small plateau 1000 m high west of Margrethedal on Gauss Halv°. Named by Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions as Western Plateau.

name: Vesttinden
description: Mountain peak on the NW side of Taggletscher on SW Clavering ╪. The name was first used by Gelting (1934) during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, together with ╪sttinden.

name: Vibeke Dal
description: Informal name used by S°nderholm et al. (1989) for the valley in Hudson Land containing Vibeke S° and Vibeke Elv.

name: Vibeke Elv
description: River draining Vibeke S°, flowing eastwards through Promenadedal to Wordie Gletscher. Named by Heinrich Bⁿtler during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition, originally in the form Vibeckefluss. See also Vibeke Gletscher. (Vibekes Elv.)

name: Vibeke Gletscher
description: Glacier between Steno Land and Ole R°mer Land, dividing northwards into ╪stre and Vestre Vibeke Gletscher. Mapped and named by Lauge Koch during flights in 1932 on the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen.

name: Vibeke Nunatak
description: Nunatak between Vestre Vibeke Gletscher and ╪stre Vibeke Gletscher, east of Bartholin Land. Named during Lauge Koch's 1956-58 expeditions by John Haller.

name: Vibeke S°
description: Large lake at the front of Vibeke Gletscher. Named by Heinrich Bⁿtler during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition, and used first in the form Vibekesee. (Vibekes S°.)

name: Vibekefjµld
description: Mountain on east Clavering ╪, part of Magnetikerbjerg. The name appears on a sketch map in Gustav Thostrup's 1921 logbook. Girl's name.

name: Victor Madsen Bjerg
description: Mountain on Gauss Halv° named during Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions as Mt. Victor Madsen. See also Victor Madsen Gletscher.

name: Trap S°
description: Small lake in the area known as Morµnebakkerne, north of Zackenberg Forskningsstation. The name was introduced by Kirsten S. Christoffersen in 1998. It is middle-sized of a group of three lakes, and takes its name from the Danish phrase æTrip Trap Trµsko

name: Trappebjerg
description: Mountain 2500 m high on the west side of Gregory Gletscher, west Frµnkel Land. So named by John Haller and Eduard Wenk following explorations during Lauge Koch's 1951 expedition, because the ascent over stratified rocks resembled climbing a staircase (=

name: Trappedal
description: Valley on the north side of Rolige Brµ with a profile resembling a staircase (= trappe). Named by Laurent Jemelin during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions.

name: Trappes°er
description: Name used for a locality on the east side of Wegener Halv° in some geological reports, where shallow drill cores were taken from Upper Permian rocks.

name: Traunsteiner Spids
description: Mountain 1950 m high on the ridge between Duart Gletscher and the upper basin of Spµrregletscher. It was climbed by the 1966 Deutsche Gr÷nland-Expedition in die Staunings-Alpen led by Karl M. Herligkoffer, and named after the small town of Traunstein at

name: Tre S°stre
description: Three closely similar adjacent peaks in western Gσseland, on the north side of Vindblµsedal. Named during Lauge Koch's 1958 expedition by Eduard Wenk.

name: Tredie Hvide
description: Part of a mountain range on NE Clavering ╪, named by Arne Noe-Nygaard and Gunnar SΣve-S÷derbergh during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen. Originally three peaks were given the names Erste Weisse, Zweite Weisse and Dritte Weisse, for their colour. The name

name: Trefjord Bjerg
description: Mountain in east Jameson Land west of inner Carlsberg Fjord. So named by John H. Callomon during Lauge Koch's 1958 expedition, because rivers draining its flanks flow into three different fjords, Carlsberg Fjord, Hurry Inlet and Scoresby Sund.

name: Trefoden
description: Mountain in south Liverpool Land, the culmination of three converging ridges (trefod = tripod). So named by Laurits Bruhn during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen.

name: Trefork Gletscher
description: Glacier in Dronning Louise Land draining into Trefork S°. Named by the 1952-54 British North Greenland expedition.

name: Trefork S°
description: Large lake in central Dronning Louise Land between Admiralty Gletscher and Borg Gletscher. The name was given by the 1952-54 British North Greenland expedition for its shape, the three arms of the lake resembling an inverted æT'.

name: Tregletscherdal
description: Valley in north Scoresby Land, NW of Antarctic Havn, where three glaciers merge. Named by Hans Kapp during Lauge Koch's 1957-58 expedition.

name: Trekant
description: Mountain 2250 m high at the head of Trekantgletscher, west of Alpefjord. Climbed and so named by Wolfgang Weinzierl's 1970 expedition.

name: Trekanten
description: Island on the east coast of Liverpool Land. So named by Laurits Bruhn during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen for its triangular (= trekant) shape. Hildegard Island has also been used.

name: Trekanten
description: Mountain in the Tagbjergene, north Hudson Land. Used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937), and named for the pyramidal form (trekant = triangle).

name: Trekanten
description: Small nunatak in west Dronning Louise Land, on the south side of Borg Gletscher (Fig. 21). The name was given by the 1952-54 British North Greenland expedition for its triangular shape viewed from the north.

name: Trekanten
description: North point of N°rre Orienterings° with a triangular shape, a useful landmark during sledge journeys by staff at Danmarkshavn weather station. The name was said to be in use by Danish hunters, and is noted in Jennov (1963) as the site of a barnacle goose

name: Trekantgletscher
description: Glacier on the west side of inner Alpefjord. Named during Lauge Koch's 1954 expedition by John Haller.

name: Trekroner
description: Steep and barren mountain 360 m high, east of the south end of Sµls°en, noted for its colony of barnacle geese. The name was used as a reference locality in several of the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen reports, and is described as having three summits wi

name: Trekronerhytten
description: Danish hunting hut east of Trekroner, Germania Land. It was built by Nanok in the spring of 1938. Officially known as Pashytten, it has also been known as Schulzhytten, Hvalsletten and Slettehytten. It has now disappeared (P.S. Mikkelsen 2008).

name: Tresteinane
description: Small skerries off SE Geographical Society ╪ near Kap McClintock. So named on NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937) because there are three rocks (= tresteinane).

name: Bσdskµret
description: Small island or skerry off Wendel Pynt, west of Danmark Havn. Named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen as Baadskµret, apparently because of Inuit stone ruins found here interpreted as supports for kayaks (bσd = boat). According to Friis (1909) the sker

name: Flyverfjord
description: Fjord branching off the south side of Nordvestfjord between Hinks Land and Th. S°rensen Land (Fig. 41). Mapped by Lauge Koch during flights in 1932 on the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen. Koch noted it as a tribute to his pilot, N.V. Petersen (see also Kap J

name: Flyvers°
description: Lake in Nordmarken. So named by John Haller following explorations during Lauge Koch's 1955 expedition, because it was possible to land on the lake with a Heinkel sea plane in August 1955. The name is a tribute to the pilot (flyver = airman, flyer).

name: Fl°degletscher
description: Glacier in the north Stauning Alper, draining east into Skeldal. Named by Erdhart FrΣnkl during Lauge Koch's 1950-51 expeditions for the milky colour (fl°de = cream). (Fl÷de-Gletscher, Flode Gletscher.)

name: Fl°elv
description: River draining Jakob Dal flowing across Vestersletten, eastern Hudson Land. The name was proposed by the Place Name Committee (fl° is an old Danish expression for a reversed tidal flow in the mouth of a river).

name: Fog River
description: Minor river in south Jameson Land flowing into Hesteelv. The name was used during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Aldinger (1935), and is assumed to record the common coastal fog in the vicinity while working here.

name: Foksa
description: River on the west side of Loch Fyne, draining the east slope of Nordhoek Bjerg. So named on an NSIU map (1932a), the name may derive from the Norwegian dialect word for drifts of snow.

name: Foldaelv
description: River draining the southern Giesecke Bjerge. Named on an NSIU map (1932a) as Folda, probably because it flows in the valley the Norwegians called Folddalen, and reaches the coast close to the Norwegian hunting hut known as Foldvik. æFolda' is a common pl

name: Folddalen
description: Valley in the southern Giesecke Bjerge. So named on an NSIU map (1932a), possibly after the Norwegian hunting hut Foldvik built at its mouth. It carries the river known as Foldaelv.

name: Foldebjerg
description: Mountain about 1400 m high in SW Gletscherland. So named by EugΦne Wegmann during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen because of the pronounced folds in the rocks.

name: Foldegletscher
description: Glacier on Volquaart Boon Kyst draining north to Terrassevig. Named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Laurits Bruhn, probably for the presence of folded dirt bands in the ice.

name: Foldvik
description: Norwegian hunting hut on the south side of Kap Bennet, built by the Foldvik expedition in August 1927. This name appears on the NSIU (1932a) map, and commemorates Nils Foldvik [b. 1892], assistant at the Geophysical Institute in Troms°, and leader of the

name: Foldvik Kl°ft
description: Ravine about 6 km east of Kap Stosch, named by Lauge Koch's 1926-27 expeditions as Foldvik Creek after Nils Foldvik, leader of the 1926-28 Foldvik expedition. See also Foldvik. This is an important geological type locality for the Foldvik Creek Formation

name: Foldvikfjellet
description: Mountain 1120 m high on western Geographical Society ╪. So named on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937) after Nils Foldvik (see also Foldvik).

name: Folly
description: Surveying station in eastern Dronning Louise Land used by the 1952-54 British North Greenland expedition. The name appears on the maps of Hamilton et al. (1956).

name: Forbindelsesdal
description: Valley on the north side of Moskusoksefjord providing a route through to Ankerbjergsdal. The name is attributed to Heinrich Bⁿtler, and arose from his work with Lauge Koch's expeditions in the 1950s (forbindelse = connection).

name: Forchhammer Bjerg
description: Mountain about 1350 m high on SE Traill ╪. Named by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst as Forchhammers Berg after Johan Georg Forchhammer [1794-1865], a Danish geologist and chemist, and professor of mineralogy and geology at

name: Forchhammerdal
description: Valley in extreme SE Traill ╪, east of Forchhammer Bjerg. The name was given by Hans P. Schaub during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition led by Lauge Koch.

name: Forellenseepingo
description: Large pingo beside Forels°, south of Karupelv, Traill ╪. The pingo is 29 m high, 515 m in circumference, and was so named by Fritz Mⁿller during Lauge Koch's 1954-55 expeditions after the adjacent lake Forels°.

name: Forels°
description: Large lake south of Karupelv, Traill ╪, in the vicinity of five large pingos. The name was given by Fritz Mⁿller during his work on the pingos in 1954-55, for the numerous trout (= forel).

name: Forhindringsgletscher
description: Glacier in north AndrΘe Land, partially blocking Eremitdal. So named during Lauge Koch's 1948-50 expeditions by Erdhart FrΣnkl because it hindered progress along the valley. (Forhindrings Gletscher.)

name: Glacier le Mouchoir
description: Minor glacier on the east side of Prinsessegletscher, western Stauning Alper, named and traversed by the 1968 ExpΘdition Franτaise au Groenland Nord-Est led by Claude Rey on their ascent of Pic Ludovica. The name may recall its small size (mouchoir = han

name: Glacier Watkins
description: Name used on an inaccurate 1933 map drawn by M. Parat during J.B. Charcot's 1933 expedition for a small glacier on the west side of Lillefjord, southern Liverpool Land. See also Baie Watkins.

name: Glamis Borg
description: Mountain 2200 m high between Bersµrkerbrµ and Kishmul Gletscher, northern Stauning Alper. First climbed by the 1958 Scottish East Greenland expedition led by Malcolm Slesser, and named after Glamis Castle, Angus, the imposing and historic 17th century ho

name: Glamis Gletscher
description: Minor glacier on the SE side of Bersµrkerbrµ, SW of Glamis Borg, north Stauning Alper. Named Glamis Glacier by the 1958 Scottish East Greenland expedition led by Malcolm Slesser.

name: Glamis Pas
description: Col between Glamis Gletscher and the head of Kishmul Gletscher, north Stauning Alper. The approved position of the pass is SE of Glamis Borg, the name having originated from the 1958 Scottish East Greenland expedition led by Malcolm Slesser who climbed t

name: Glasgow ╪
description: Small island off the coast of Liverpool Land, named by William Scoresby Jr. in 1822 as Glasgow Island after the Scottish city. (╬le Glasgow, Glasgow ╓.)

name: Glatze
description: Snow mountain on the east side of Prinsessegletscher, western Stauning Alper, at the head of Castor Glacier and Pollux Glacier. Named and first climbed by the 1967 Berchtesgaden expedition.

name: Glaukonitbjerg
description: Minor summit about 180 m high NW of Kap Leslie, east Milne Land. Named by Hermann Aldinger during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen as Glaukonitberg or Glaukonit Berg, for the presence of the mineral glauconite in the sandstones.

name: Gleditschfjellet
description: Mountain about 1200 m high on Geographical Society ╪. The name was used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937), and commemorates Kristen Gran Gleditsch [1867-1946], a Norwegian colonel who was head of Norges Geografiske Opmσling (Norwegian Geographical Survey)

name: Glemmedalen
description: Valley on the NE side of Werner Bjerge, draining into the head of Oksedal. So named by Peter Bearth and Eduard Wenk during Lauge Koch's 1953-54 expeditions because the valley is hidden from sight until one is abreast of its mouth (glemme = forget).

name: Glesdalen
description: Valley in southern Wollaston Forland, west of Herschell Bjerg, corresponding to the present Blµsedalen. The name appears on an NSIU map (1932a), and may derive from a glistening appearance.

name: Gletscherbugt

name: Gletscherdal
description: Small valley on Gauss Halv° draining NW to join Paralleldal. Named by Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions. The original usage was Dobbeltglacier Valley (Seidenfaden 1931), a mixture of Danish and English, and a reference to the glaciers occupying the valley

description: Land area bounded by Dickson Fjord and Wahlenberg Gletscher, and divided almost into two parts by R÷hss Fjord. The name was adapted from a suggestion by Ove Simonsen during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, and was given for the many ice caps and glaciers

description: Small skerries off the coast of east Hovgaard ╪, south of a glacier lobe draining the ice cap which just reaches the coast. Named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition.

name: Gletschers°

name: Glipa
description: River in the Giesecke Bjerge draining the present Gustav Dal. The name appears only on the NSIU (1932a) map, and may derive from the Norwegian word for a long, small opening.

name: Hermann von Barth Tinde
description: Mountain 2681 m high on the west side of Spµrregletscher in the western Stauning Alper, at the head of Pollux Glacier. Named after the noted German mountaineer Hermann von Barth [1845-1876], born in Berchtesgaden. First climbed by the 1967 Berchtesgadene

name: Hvidbj°rn Nunatakker
description: Extensive nunatak group between Evers Gletscher and Hamberg Gletscher. This nunatak region was first partly explored by the 1931 H°ygaard & Mehren expedition, and was mapped and named by Lauge Koch during flights in 1932 on the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditione

name: Hvidefirn
description: Glacier in the southern Werner Bjerge draining NW along the west flank of Mσgeborg. Named during Lauge Koch's 1953-54 expeditions by Peter Bearth and Eduard Wenk.

name: Hvidefjeld
description: Ice cap 730 m high in south Liverpool Land, NE of the town of Scoresbysund. The name came into use during the 1924-25 colonisation expedition (E. Mikkelsen 1927). French expeditions used the name D⌠me Charcot. (White Fjeld.)

name: Hvidefjeld
description: Mountain over 2000 m high in east-central Strindberg Land, on the north side of Rµvedal. Named during Lauge Koch's 1948-49 expeditions by Hans R. Katz.

name: Hvidevµggen

name: Hvidhoved
description: Mountain about 2100 m high in western AndrΘe Land, north of Kalvedal. Named by John Haller following explorations during Lauge Koch's 1949-51 expeditions, for its large, rounded summit ice cap.

name: Hyolithuskl°ft
description: Small ravine in eastern AndrΘe Land, NW of Kap Weber, draining into Geologfjord. Named by Christian Poulsen during Lauge Koch's 1929 expedition as Hyolithus Creek for the finds of numerous fossil hyolithids. The position of the ravine is incorrectly plac

name: Hyttebugt
description: Bay on the SW side of Kap Greg, Liverpool Land, close to a hunting hut established by Scoresbysund municipality. The name was introduced by Helge G. Backlund in 1935.

name: Hyµnen
description: Name used in a climbing report by Buess (1953) for a summit north of Petermann Bjerg and SW of Kalifbjerg, western Frµnkel Land (hyµnen = the hyena).

name: HΣsi Bjerge

description: Southernmost low cape of Store Koldewey, south of Kap Arendts (it has also been called Kap Arendts Nµs). The name was given by the 1932 Gefion expedition after Alf Trolle [1879-1949], captain of the expedition ship during the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditione

name: Kap Alfred
description: Northern cape of Lyell Land at the mouth of Kempe Fjord (Fig. 29), named by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst. The name was probably given for a member of Nathorst's family, as were many other capes in the vicinity. (Cape Al

name: Kap Alfred Beauvais
description: Cape on the east side of Lille Koldewey. So named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen for the supplier of provisions to the expedition. Alfred Beauvais was a director of the meat-packing company Danica which supplied this and many other Danish expeditio

name: Kap Allen
description: Cape on Canning Land named by William Scoresby Jr. in 1822 as Cape Allan for an Edinburgh friend. This was probably Thomas Allan [1777-1833], a mineralogist who had purchased GieseckΘ's Greenland mineral collection, which among other items included a new

name: Kap AmΘlie
description: Cape north of the mouth of Penthievre Fjord. Named by the 1905 ExpΘdition Arctique du Duc d'OrlΘans as Cap AmΘlie, possibly for Marie AmΘlie des Deux Siciles [1782-1866], wife of Louis-Philippe 1, King of France. (Cap Amelie.)

name: Kap AmΘlie Hytten
description: Hut built on 15 March 1941 about 3 km NE of Kap AmΘlie by Ib Poulsen and other meteorologists of Eigil Knuth's 1938-39 expedition. The outbreak of war in Europe had disrupted normal contacts with Denmark, but meteorological observations were continued at

name: Kap Amundsen
description: South cape of the southernmost island in the Norske ╪er. Named by John Haller following explorations during Lauge Koch's 1956-58 expeditions after Roald Amundsen [1872-1928]. A noted Norwegian Polar explorer, Amundsen's first major exploit was the traver

description: Valley in Home Forland. The name appears to have been adopted from the Great Fault Valley of Koch (1931), a name used for the valley in which Blσelv flows. Officially it is said to be a side valley draining into Blσelv, but this may be an error.

description: Valley on eastern Ymer ╪, west of Celsius Bjerg, so named on an NSIU map (1932a) because the valley is eroded along a fault, a geologically weak zone (forkastning = fault).

name: Doumer H°j
description: Point on the east side of Scoresbysund where a memorial to Paul Doumer was erected by the French International Polar Year Station 1932-33. Paul Doumer [1857-1932], a mathematician, journalist and politician, was president of France when assassinated in 1

name: Dove Bugt
description: Extensive bay west of Store Koldewey, bounded to the north by Germania Land and to the south by Ad. S. Jensen Land. So named Dove Bai by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt, after the German physicist and meteorologist Heinrich Wilhelm Dove [1

name: Downing Fjeld
description: Snow mountain about 2500 m high south of Granta Brµ, Stauning Alper. Climbed by the 1963 University of Cambridge expedition, and named after Downing College, Cambridge, founded in 1800 with the proceeds of the estates of Sir George Downing. (Downingfjeld

name: Draba Sibirica Elv
description: River in Jameson Land draining west to Hall Bredning. So named by Geoffrey Halliday following botanical work during the 1961-1962 Leicester University East Greenland expeditions, after a species of whitlow-grass.

name: Drach Kl°ft
description: Ravine SE of Charcot Havn, east Milne Land, named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Hermann Aldinger as Drach-Schlucht. Pierre Drach, a scientist at the University of Paris, was a member of J.B. Charcot's 1933 expedition that visited this region.

name: Dragneset
description: Peninsular in eastern Geographical Society ╪. The name was used on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937), and derives from the Norwegian word æsj°drag' (= swell of the sea).

name: Drag°yane
description: Small islands in Cambridge Bugt, off eastern Geographical Society ╪. So named on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937), the name derives from the Norwegian (see Dragneset.)

name: Draugen
description: Skerry off Kap Kraus in Home Forland, northern Hold with Hope. Used on an NSIU map (1932a), the name is a Norwegian dialect word for a ghost, often a headless evil spirit which appears as a warning of death.

name: Dreiecks Plateau
description: Triangular plateau about 508 m high in Th. Thomsen Land, on the west side of Fligely Fjord. The name was used by Vischer (1943) in a report on work during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition led by Lauge Koch (dreieck = triangle).

name: Dreieselbjerg
description: Mountain 1442 m high in the north Werner Bjerge, named by Peter Bearth and Eduard Wenk during Lauge Koch's 1953-54 expeditions. It was climbed by a party of three in 1953, a not particularly nice climb of an unimpressive peak. The climbers were æthe thre

name: Dreikant
description: Mountain about 2400 m high on the NE side of Sefstr÷m Gletscher, Stauning Alper. Named for the shape of the mountain, a three-sided pyramid, and first climbed by Hans Gsellman's 1957 expedition.

name: Dreikonigsgrat
description: Ridge with three peaks between the heads of Borgbjerg Gletscher and Orion Gletscher. Probably first climbed and named by the 1977 SchwΣbische Stauning Alper expedition.

name: Dreispitz

name: Dreverspids
description: Mountain 2210 m high between Dalmore Glacier and Gannochy Glacier, central Stauning Alper. First climbed by the 1968 University of Dundee expedition and named after Harold Irving Drever [1912-75], professor at the University of St. Andrews. Drever had vi

name: Driftwood Valley
description: Small valley on the NE coast of Suess Land, east of Scheele Bjerg. The name is used only in the archaeological report of McI.Johnson (1933) describing his work during J.M. Wordie's 1929 Cambridge expedition.

description: Small lake near Danmark Havn, SE Geremania Land. The name was used during the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen (Lundager 1912), as the lake was the source of the expedition's drinking water. Trolle (1909) referred to the same lake as Den Lille S°. It may be

name: Drillinge
description: Mountain 2560 m high between Hecate Glacier and the upper part of Spµrregletscher, Stauning Alper, with three conspicuous granite pinnacles (drillinge = three barrelled rifle). It was climbed by the 1966 Deutsche Gr÷nland-Expedition in die Staunings-Alpe

name: Cardiocerasdal
description: Small valley in western Wollaston Forland draining SW from Cardiocerasbjerg into Young Sund. Named by Lauge Koch's 1926-27 expeditions as Cardioceras Valley for the common occurrence of the fossil ammonite.

name: Cardioceraselv
description: Name used by Rosenkrantz (1932) during Lauge Koch's 1929 expedition, for the river flowing in Cardiocerasdal, western Wollaston Forland.

name: Cardioceraskl°ft

name: Carl Heger ╪

description: Fjord between Canning Land and Liverpool Land, first observed by William Scoresby Jr. in 1822, who thought it connected with Hurry Inlet. It was mapped by the 1898-1900 Carlsbergfondets Expedition, which had the official name æCarlsbergfondets Expedition

name: Carlshavn

name: Carlshavn

name: Carrick Spids
description: Twin rock spires 1970 m high SW of Dunottar Gletscher in the northern Stauning Alper. Named by the 1958 Scottish East Greenland expedition led by Malcolm Slesser, which made the first ascent, after Carrick Castle on Loch Goil, Argyllshire, Scotland. (Car

name: Fuglevarden
description: Highest point of the peninsula Hovedet, east of the mouth of Noret, north Scoresby Land, marked by a mound built up from generations of bird droppings (fuglevarden = the bird cairn). Named by prospecting teams associated with Lauge Koch's 1948-49 expedit

name: Fugle°

name: Fugle°
description: Small island in NW Dove Bugt, east of Vµdderen. Named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition for the numerous birds.

name: Fugle°ya
description: Island in Vega Sund, the present Gσse°en. This name appears on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937), and derives from the abundant traces of geese and ducks seen here. (Fugle÷ya.)

name: Fulach Gletscher
description: Glacier on the north side of Dickson Fjord, Suess Land. So named by EugΦne Wegmann during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, after Fulach near Schaffhausen, Switzerland. He visited the glacier in 1932.

name: Fundal Glacier
description: Term used by Pessl (1962) for the glacier formerly occupying the valley he calls Fundal (Nedre Funddal), near Mestersvig.

name: Cardiocerasbjerg

description: Cape in Rechnitzer Land at the front of Soranerbrµen. Named by Henning Bistrup during the by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen after his colleage at the marine cadet school, Hans Christian Ullidtz [1878-1950]. Henning Bistrup and H.C. Ullidtz were promot

description: Cape in eastern Liverpool land west of Trekanten. So named by Helge G. Backlund during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, after his oldest son, Vidar, who was his assistant in 1934. To avoid the recently introduced prohibition of naming features after livi

name: Kap Weber
description: Eastern cape of AndrΘe Land. Named Cap Weber by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt, possibly for Wilhelm Eduard Weber [1804-1891], a German scientist who had worked with Gauss. From 1849 he was head of G÷ttingen Observatory (J. L°ve, personal

name: Kap Weinschenck
description: Low hill on the east side of Dronning Louise Land, west of Strandelv, named by the 1912-13 Den danske Ekspedition til Dronning Louises Land after Ivar Kjerulff Weinschenck [1882-1963]. Weinschenck was first engineer on the DANMARK during the 1906-08 Danm

name: Kap Wijkander
description: Easternmost cape of Ymer ╪. Named by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst as Wijkanders ╓, probably after Erik Anders Gustaf August Wijkander [1849-1913], a Swedish physicist and politician who had participated in the 1872-73 e

name: Kap Wynn
description: Cape in eastern Wollaston Forland, named Cape Wynn by Douglas Clavering in 1823. Several hunting huts were built about 1 km NW of the cape (see Kopperneshuset, Liavaag, Gσsneshuset). (Cap Wynn, Cape Wyen, Kap Wyen.)

name: Kap Young
description: Headland on SE Traill ╪, named Cape Young by William Scoresby Jr. in 1822 after George Young [1777-1848]. He became pastor of a presbyterian congregation at Whitby in 1806, and stayed there 42 years.

name: Kap Zachariae
description: Peninsula on the south side of Lambert Land, north of Zachariae Isstr°m. Named by John Haller following explorations during Lauge Koch's 1956-58 expeditions.

name: Kap Aage Bertelsen
description: Minor feature in eastern Dronning Louise Land forming a small cape-like feature at the confluence of Storstr°mmen and L. Bistrup Brµ. Named by the 1912-13 Den danske Ekspedition til Dronning Louises Land after Aage Bertelsen [1873-1945], artist on the 19

name: Kapelle

name: Kapelleturm

name: Kaphytten

description: Norwegian hunting hut on the east coast of Wollaston Forland about 4 km south of Haredalen. Built in July 1930 by the M°re expedition, and named after the Norwegian hunter Herman Andresen, who helped build it. See Herman Andresenfjellet. It was originall

name: Hermelintop
description: Summit 1172 m high on SW Milne Land. So named during the 1963 Geodµtisk Institut expedition because ermine (= hermelin) were observed here during surveying (Fig. 46).

name: Hermes
description: Mountain about 2100 m high on the south side of Mercurius Gletscher, south Stauning Alper. First climbed by James Clarkson's 1961 expedition, and named after the Greek god, son of Zeus and Maia.

name: Hermitage
description: Mountain about 2200 m high at the head of Mars Gletscher, south Stauning Alper. First climbed by James Clarkson's 1961 expedition, and probably named after Hermitage Castle, a remote 13th castle on the Scottish Borders.

name: Hermodbreen
description: Glacier on central Clavering ╪, draining east into Skillegletscher. So named on NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937), after Hermod, son of Odin in old Nordic mythology.

name: Heron Hump

name: Herschell Bjerg
description: Mountain 682 m high in south Wollaston Forland. It was named Cape Herschel by William Scoresby Jr. in 1822 after John Frederick William Herschel [1792-1871], baronet, physicist and astronomer, noted for his survey of the skies in the southern hemisphere.

name: Herschellhus

name: Herthabjerg

name: Herthadal

name: Hertugen
description: High, dark peak in NW Dronning Louise Land, NE of Prinsessen (Fig. 21). Named by the 1952-54 British North Greenland expedition after Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh [b. 1921], husband of the expedition patron Queen Elizabeth II. Prinsessen and Hertugen

name: Hertugen af OrlΘans Land

name: Hesleyside

name: Hessbreen

name: Hesselbergfjellet

name: Hesteelv
description: River in south Jameson Land, named by Hermann Aldinger during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen as Horse River. It commemorates the use of Icelandic ponies (heste = horse) during the geological exploration of Jameson Land.

description: The curved horse-shoe shaped northern part of Djµvle°en, Dove Bugt, so named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen. The devil (= djµvle) is alleged to have had hooved feet (= hestefod).

description: Extensive land area bounded by Hall Bredning, Scoresby Sund, Hurry Inlet and Carlsberg Fjord, with its northern boundary fixed in 1966 following Major Paar Dal, Coloradodal, Olympen and Passagen at about latitude 71░35'N. Named by William Scoresby Jr. in

name: Dritten Lagergipfels

name: Dromedaren

name: Basiskµret

name: Bass Rock
description: Small island NE of Lille Pendulum. Named by Douglas Clavering in 1823 for its resemblance to Bass Rock on the south side of the Firth of Forth, Scotland, an impressive, steep-sided island which was the site of a castle, later a prison and fortress destro

name: Bass Rock-husene
description: Two eight-sided depot huts were built on the south side of Bass Rock for the Baldwin-Ziegler expedition in 1901. They were subsequently visited and used by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen, the 1909-12 Alabama-ekspeditionen, 1919-24 A/S ╪stgr°nlandske F

name: Bastian Bugt
description: Pronounced bay on eastern Kuhn ╪. Named by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt as Bastians Bai for Adolf Bastian [1826-1905], a German explorer and ethnologist who had formed a committee for raising funds for the expedition. A Norwegian huntin

name: Bastians Dal
description: Name occasionally used for the E-W valley on Kuhn ╪ draining into the head of Bastian Bugt (e.g. Vischer in: Koch 1955).

name: Bastille
description: Peak 1870 m high south of Concordia, on the SW side of Bj°rnbo Gletscher, southern Stauning Alper. First climbed by James Clarkson's 1961 expedition, and named after the medieval fortress on the east side of Paris, a notorious French state prison in the

name: Bastionbugt

name: Drumglas Beag
description: Peak 2060 m high on the west side of upper Storgletscher, central Stauning Alper. Climbed and named by the 2007 SMC East Greenland Expedition.

name: Dryasdal
description: Valley in north Dronning Louise Land. Named by the British North Greenland expedition 1952-54 for the occurrence of the plant æDryas octopetala' in what is described as a pleasant, green and flower-filled valley.

name: Dr°mmebjerg
description: Mountain NE of Centrums° (Fig. 24), Kronprins Christian Land. Named during Lauge Koch's 1952-53 expeditions by Erdhart FrΣnkl, who had planned to visit the area because of its promising geological relationships, but was forced to return to base; his plan

name: Dr°mmebugten

name: Dr°mmetinde
description: Nunatak summit about 2500 m high on the west side of Nordenski÷ld Gletscher. Named during Lauge Koch's 1953 expedition by John Haller. After a long and difficult traverse across several large glaciers, the party was prevented by bad weather from completi

name: Drσbegletscher
description: Hanging glacier on the east side of innermost Ingolf Fjord. So named Draabegletscher by Eigil Nielsen during the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition because it resembled a round, clear glass drop (= drσbe), which had hardened halfway down the mountain (Nielsen

name: Havna
description: Norwegian hunting station east of Noret on the south side of Kong Oscar Fjord, built by S°ren Richter's expedition in 1939. Named after a small bay below the station known as Havna or Hamna (= harbour). An earlier hut near the site known as Solstrand was

name: Havnevig
description: Bay on the south side of Constable Pynt [Nerlerit Inaat], where ships anchor to discharge cargo for the Constable Pynt airfield. The name is used in the æGr°nlands Havnelods' (KMS 1990).

name: Hawkins Vandfald
description: Waterfall 15-20 m high on the north side of Bessel Fjord, NW of Trums ╪, where ships can readily take on water. The name is used in Den Gr°nlandske Lods (1968).

name: Hawley Skµr
description: Skerry west of Hawley ╪ in Holm Bugt, SW Traill ╪.

name: Hawley ╪
description: Island in Holm Bugt, SW Traill ╪. The name was proposed by S°kortarkivet following their 1956-57 surveying of the channel through Vega Sund as an alternative approach for ships en route to Mestersvig airfield.

name: Haystack
description: Prominent peninsula 305 m high on the east coast of Dronning Margrethe II Land, north of Roseneathbugt, with a conical profile viewed from north and south. Named by Douglas Clavering in 1823 as Haystack or The Haystack, because of its characteristic shap

name: Haystack-Tangen
description: Norwegian hunting hut on the low neck of the Haystack peninsula, built by John Giµver's expedition in November 1932 (Haystackhytten.)

name: Hecate Glacier
description: Tributary to Spµrregletscher in the Stauning Alper, named by James Clarkson's 1961 expedition after the Greek goddess. Berchtesgadener Gletscher is used for the same glacier in German mountaineering reports.

name: Hecla
description: Peak about 2400 m high at the head of Cantabrµ, Stauning Alper. So named by the 1998 Scottish Mountaineering Club expedition.

name: Heden

name: Heden
description: Area NE of Zackenberg Forskningsstation. The name has been used by visiting scientists.

name: Heens Fjell
description: Mountain about 2530 m high on the north side of Roslin Gletscher, between Ravnas Bre and Baltos Bre. The southern of three summits was climbed by the 1996 Norwegian Stauning Alper expedition, and so named after Arner Randers Heen [1905-1991] of ┼ndalsnes

name: Heeringhus
description: Hut built by Danmarkshavn weather station personnel east of the station in the autumn of 1949, on a small island south of ╪ksebladet. It was named after E. Heering-Hansen, chief mechanic at the station (Thomsen 1966). It is also known as ╪ksebladet.

name: Heidelbeerberge
description: Locality near Eleonore Bugt where the GERMANIA ran aground during the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt. Opportunity was taken to carry out scientific investigations, and the name was used in reports (e.g. Mⁿller 1974) because of finds of edible

name: Heidrunvatnet
description: Lake on Theodolitplateau on west Clavering ╪. So named on NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937), after the goat of old Nordic mythology which stood on the roof of the Valhal, eating the leaves of a tree.

name: Heimdalbreen
description: Glacier on central Clavering ╪ draining east into Skillegletscher. So named on NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937), after Heimdal of old Nordic mythology, who was born of nine maidens.

name: Heimen
description: Norwegian hunting hut on the west coast of Wegener Halv°, in the inner part of Fleming Fjord. It was built in the autumn of 1932 by the 1932-34 Helge Ingstad expedition, and was their main depot and hunting station (heimen = the home). It has also been k

name: Isfjeldsund
description: Sound between Edvard ╪ and Carl Heger ╪, western Dove Bugt, where icebergs from Bredebrµ accumulate. Named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition. (Isfjµldsund.)

name: Isfjord

name: Isfjord
