name: Isfjord
description: Name used for Vestfjord, the fjord extending westwards from R°defjord, in the 1891-92 diaries of Helge Vedal (Gull°v 1991). The name recorded the abundant icebergs calved from Vestfjord Gletscher. (Isfjorden).

name: Kalven
description: Island in the Finsch ╪er group, south of Store Finsch. The name first appears on an NSIU map (1932a), and derives from its small size relative to Store Finsch (kalven = the calf).

name: Kalven
description: Island in M°rkefjordsbugten. So named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen (kalven = the calf). (Kalven°, Kßlfur.)

name: Kaporniagaqarpik

name: Kaporniagaqarteq
description: River on the east side of Hurry Inlet draining S°dal. Recorded during the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, the name translates as æit has trout'.

name: Kapp 17. Mai
description: Cape on western Geographical Society ╪, so named on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937) for Norway's National Day. (Cape 17th of May.)

name: Kapp 7. Juni
description: Cape on west Geographical Society ╪. So named on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937) after the 7DE JUNI, a 14-ton, 40-foot sealer used by the pioneer 1909-10 wintering expedition led by Vebj°rn Landmark.

name: Kapp Agnes
description: Norwegian hunting hut on the south side of Lindemann Fjord, near Kap Schumacher, built by the Hird expedition in September 1928. The Norwegians often referred to Kap Schumacher as Kapp Agnes or Kapp Hynes. Agnes was the youngest daughter of J°rgen Furnes

name: Kapp Astrid
description: Minor cape in southern Payer Land on the north side of the mouth of Grantafjord. This position is shown on the 1:100 000 scale NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937), but on the 1932a NSIU map it appears to be indicated as the cape on the opposite side of the fjord, t

name: Kapp Bj°rvig
description: Cape on the west side of Lerbugt, north Clavering ╪. So named on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937) after Paul Bj°rvig [1857-1932], a Troms° hunter who had participated in expeditions to the Arctic and Antarctic.

name: Kapp Brandal
description: Cape on NW Clavering ╪. Used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937), the name commemorates Peter Severinsen Brandal [1870-1933] of Brandal, the Norwegian ship-owner who instituted Norwegian sealing activities off East Greenland.

name: Kapp Cathrine
description: Cape on the south side of Grantafjord. Used on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937). Girl's name.

name: Kapp Dagny
description: Cape in southernmost Payer Land on the north side of Grantafjord. Used only on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937).

name: Kapp Else
description: Minor cape on the south side of Jordanhill. So named on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937).

name: Kapp Floren
description: Minor cape on the north side of western Geographical Society ╪. So named on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937), after the FLOREN, the sealer used by the 1908-09 FLOREN expedition led by Severin Liavaag. The 37-ton FLOREN was constructed by Hans Gravdal of O

name: Kapp Giµver
description: Minor cape north of Jordanhill. So named on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937) after John Giµver. See also Giµverhytte.

name: Kapp Gj÷a
description: Minor cape on the south side of Geographical Society ╪. The name is used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937), and was given for the GJ╓A, the 47-ton herring boat with which Roald Amundsen made his voyage through the NW Passage in 1903-05. It is now a museum

name: Kapp Gr÷dahl
description: Cape on NE Clavering ╪, corresponding to the delta of Storstr°mmen. Used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937), the name was given for Ole Iversen Gr°dahl [1850-1922], a Norwegian skipper who pioneered summer sealing off East Greenland.

name: Kapp Hedlund hytta
description: Norwegian hunting hut in the bay east of Kap Hedlund, built by Arktisk Nµringsdrift in 1934, and also known as Rimhytten. It was replaced in 1964 by a new hut built by Sirius. The skeleton of an unnamed hut occurs on the west side of Kap Hedlund; strong

name: Kapp Hekla
description: Minor cape on west Geographical Society ╪. So named on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937) after the Norwegian ship HEKLA. See Hekla Havn.

name: Kapp Isachsen
description: Cape on the north side of the mouth of DusΘn Fjord, SW of Kap Graah. Named on an NSIU map (1932a) after Gunnerius Ingvald Isachsen [1868-1939], a Norwegian polar explorer who led several expeditions to Spitsbergen, and the 1930-31 æNorvegia' expedition t

name: Kapp Isbj°rn
description: Minor cape on the south side of Geographical Society ╪. So named on NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937) after the ISBJ╪RN, a 172-ton Norwegian sealer built in 1918, and used by a variety of Norwegian and foreign expeditions for voyages to Franz Josef Land, Svalb

name: Hestehale S°
description: Shallow lake in the SW part of Morµnebakkerne, north of Zackenberg Forskningsstation. The name was first used by Kirsten S. Christoffersen in 1998 and records the common occurrence of mare's tail (Hippuris = hestehale). Information from Lars Holst Hansen

name: Hestepas
description: Low col beside Mygges°, west of the mouth of Mesters Vig. So named by prospecting teams associated with Lauge Koch's 1948-49 expeditions, because it lies on the pony route between the airfield at Mestersvig and Expeditionshus. (Hestepasset.)

name: Hesteskoen

name: Hesteskoen

name: Heywood Bjerge
description: Mountain massif between Kolding Fjord and Lille Fjord on the coast of Liverpool Land. Named originally as Heywood Island by William Scoresby Jr. in 1822 in compliment to a Mr. B.A. Heywood. (Heywood Insel.)

name: Hidden Valley
description: Valley between Chokoladebjerg and Rosinante, west Ymer ╪, the present Rosinante Pas. The name was given by Arthur B. Cleaves and Ernest F. Fox in the course of geological work during John K. Howard's 1933 expedition (Cleaves & Fox 1935), because the vall

name: Highgate
description: Mountain 2450 m high at the head of Kishmul Gletscher, north Stauning Alper, the present Kishmul Borg. First climbed by the 1963 Imperial College expedition, and named after the north London district of Highgate, which originally had a toll gate on top o

name: Hildebrandbreen
description: Glacier on central Clavering ╪, draining to the west. So named on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937) after Hildebrand, who features in the German epic poem from c. 1200, the Nibelungenlied.

name: Hildegard Island
description: Name used occasionally in reports of the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen (e.g. Kranck 1935) for the present island Trekanten, Liverpool Land. The name was given by Helge G. Backlund for his wife Hildegard Dischner, whom he married in 1914. Two nearby capes,

name: Hill End Pond
description: Name used by the 1974 Joint biological expedition for a pool near Langdyssen at the NE end of Mestersvig airfield.

name: Himmelberget
description: Mountain 241 m high on east Clavering ╪, on the west side of Henningelv. The name is used by Lacmann (1937), and may be a reference to Himmelbjerget in Jylland, Denmark. Norwegians traditionally make fun of the diminutive height (175 m) of this Danish æm

name: Himmelbjerg

name: Himmelpas

description: Plateau on the north side of Borgj°kelen, Dronning Louise Land. Named by the 1912-13 Den danske Ekspedition til Dronning Louises Land as Himmerlandshede, after the area of the same name in Denmark where one of the expedition members, Lars Larsen, was bor

name: Hindarfjellet
description: Mountain ridge about 1430 m high on north Clavering ╪, NE of Ortlerspids. The name appears on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937), and was named after a character in the German epic poem from c. 1200, the Nibelungenlied.

name: Hindringsgletscher

name: Hinks Land
description: Land area between Daugaard-Jensen Gletscher and Flyverfjord (Fig. 41). The name first appeared on the 1932 1:1 million scale Geodµtisk Institut map prepared on the basis of 1932 aerial observations by Lauge Koch during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen. Th

name: Hird Star
description: Prominent peak on the south side of Roslin Gletscher, about 2159 m high. So named and climbed by the 1970 University of Cambridge expedition on 15 August 1970, the 3rd ascent. Probably named after T.A. Hird, a member of 1968 Queen Mary College expedition

name: Duck Lake

name: Duck Pond
description: Name used by the 1974 Joint biological expedition for a small lake at the SE end of Mestersvig airfield.

name: Dudhope

name: Dukkegletscher

name: Beaumaris Fjeld
description: Mountain 1900 m high at the head of Bersµrkerbrµ, northern Stauning Alper. First climbed by John Hunt's 1960 expedition, and named after Beaumaris Castle, Anglesey, North Wales. The second ascent was by the 1968 Queen Mary College expedition. The positio

name: Beaumaris Gletscher
description: Glacier on the south side of Bersµrkerbrµ, north of Beaumaris Fjeld, northern Stauning Alper. Named by John Hunt's 1960 expedition.

name: Begtrup Vig

name: Belgica Banke

name: Bellavista
description: Mountain in western Strindberg Land, overlooking Geologfjord, named by Hans R. Katz during Lauge Koch's 1948-49 expeditions for the spectacular view.

name: Bellerephon Glacier
description: Minor tributary glacier to Bj°rnbo Gletscher, southern Stauning Alper. Named by James Clarkson's 1961 expedition for Bellerophon, the hero of the Iliad.

name: Bellevue
description: Mountain in the Werner Bjerge between Langefirn and Bredefirn. The name appears to have been given by the Place Name Committee as a replacement for Styger's (1951) Pyramiden. The mountain was climbed by Hans Stauber in 1948 and Peter Bearth in 1953. æBel

name: Bendaelv
description: River flowing into the south end of Loch Fyne. So named on the NSIU 1932 map (NSIU 1932a), as Benda because of the pronounced curve in the inland course of the river.

name: Benjamin Dal
description: Valley in SE AndrΘe Land, draining into Eleonore Bugt west of Teufelsschloss. Named by Ove Simonsen during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen for Benjamin Samuelsen, a Greenlander who assisted the surveying parties. (Benjamins Dal.)

name: Benjamins Bugt

name: Bennethytta
description: Norwegian hunting hut on the south side of Kap Bennet, eastern Gauss Halv°, built by the Foldvik expedition in August 1927. It has also been known as GieseckΘ, Giskehytta and Foldvik. (Kap Bennet Hytte.)

name: Benneth°gda
description: Name used on the NSIU (1932a) map for the 358 m hill west of Kap Bennet, eastern Gauss Halv°. (Bennet Ridge.)

name: Berchtesgadener Gletscher
description: Name used by the 1967 Berchtesgadener expedition for the glacier on the west side of Spµrregletscher, Stauning Alper, more usually known as Hecate Gletscher. Named with Berchtesgadener Kopf at the head of the glacier for Berchtesgaden, a popular holiday

name: Berchtesgadener Kopf

name: Isikajia

name: Isikajia
description: Small peninsula in NE Liverpool Land. One of the names recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, it means æthe little spire'.

name: Isjomfruen

name: Islantit
description: Small islands east of Kap H°egh, south Liverpool Land. Recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, the islands were so called by the Greenlanders because they were situated æfar off the coast in the direction of Iceland'.

name: Isle de Philippe
description: Name occasionally used by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen for ╬le de France (from 2004 Qeqertaq Prins Henrik), of which the SE cape is Kap Philippe.

name: Islington
description: Mountain 2400 m high at the head of Bersµrkerbrµ, north Stauning Alper, the present Merchiston Tinde. This name was used by the 1963 Imperial College expedition, which made the second ascent, and was given for the London district of Islington. The mounta

name: Independence Fjord
description: Major E-W trending fjord between J.C. Christensen Land to the south and Peary Land to the north, eastern North Greenland. The name was given by the 1891-1892 North Greenland expedition led by Robert E. Peary, who mapped the area around the head of the fj

name: Ismarken
description: Ice sheet covering the plateau between Wahlenberg Gletscher and Violingetscher, western Lyell Land. Named by Ove Simonsen during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen (ismark = ice field).

name: Ismσgen
description: Locality in the NW Watkins Bjerge, where three ivory gulls were seen, and initially located on maps as The Ivory Gulls (Courtauld 1936). Several ivory gull colonies have subsequently been located in this nunatak region.

name: Ispassagen
description: Glacier in NW Suess Land. Named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Ove Simonsen. The original description is of a glacier draining to both north and south, which fits nearby Borggletscher better than the official location. The two names may have b

name: Isdal
description: Valley in west Wollaston Forland, so named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Hans Frebold (isdal = ice valley).

name: Ispynt
description: Small peninsula on the north coast of inner Vestfjord. Named in this form by the 1891-92 Den ╪stgr°nlandske expedition, possibly because an ice-filled ravine adjacent to the point was ascended during their sledge journey in May 1892. (Is Pynt.)

name: Iss°
description: Lake at the north margin of Hisinger Gletscher at the head of Agassiz Dal. Named during Lauge Koch's 1953 expedition by John Haller. Apart from major features with both Greenlandic and Danish names; this is one of the few localities in East Greenland wit

name: Iss°
description: Small lake in Morµnerbakkerne north of Zackenberg Forskningsstation. The name was given by Kirsten S Christoffersen in 1998, because in both 1997 and 1998 there was still ice on the lake in August. Information from Lars Holst Hansen, 2011.

name: Istoppene
description: Mountain in the centre of an ice cap in south AndrΘe Land. Named during Lauge Koch's 1949-51 expeditions by John Haller.

name: Istorvet
description: Large N-S-trending ice cap in central Liverpool Land. So named by Laurits Bruhn during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen (torv = a square or market place). (Istorvet Gletscher.)

name: Italytinde
description: Peak 2710 m high in the Vikingebrµ area of the north Stauning Alper, climbed and named by G. Dionisi's 1982 expedition. Exact location uncertain.

name: Kjerulf Fjord
description: N-S-trending fjord on the south side of innermost Kejser Franz Joseph Fjord (Fig. 65). Named during the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt, although the name is only found on the maps in Payer's (1876) narrative. Probably named after Theodor Kjer

name: Kjerulfsdalen
description: Name used by Boyd (1932) in her report on her 1931 expedition for the present Bocksrietdalen, south of the head of Kjerulf Fjord.

name: Kapp Johan Olsen
description: Cape on west Clavering ╪, the present Kap Oetker. The name is used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937), and was given for Johan Peter Kornelius Olsen [b. 1879] who as skipper of the VESLEKARI made great contributions to the scientific expeditions of NSIU in

name: Kapp Krogness
description: Minor cape close to the Norwegian hunting station Krogness, SW of Kap Stosch. Named by the 1926-28 Foldvik expedition after Ole Andreas Krogness (see also Krogness) who had given them great help and advice, and stimulated them to undertake the expedition

name: Grossglockner
description: Mountain massif 1300 m high NW of inner Tyrolerdal, Thomas Thomsen Land. Named by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt as Gross Glockner. Discovered by Julius Payer in November 1869, it was named after the mountain of the same name in Austria.

name: Grottedal
description: Valley north of Centrums°, Kronprins Christian Land. Named during Operation Groundhog 1960 for the presence of several limestone caves (Davies & Krinsley 1960). These were explored by a French speleological expedition in 1983.

name: Grottenfjeldet
description: Name used by the 1983 French speleological expedition for a limestone cave in Kronprins Christian Land at the corner between Grµselv and Centrums°. (Grotte des Quatre.)

name: Grouchs Snack
description: Southernmost skerry of the Depotskµrene, ENE of Trums ╪. The name is used in Den Gr°nlandske Lods (1968).

name: Gruberfjellet
description: Mountain on central Clavering ╪, west of Skillegletscher. So named on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937) after Otto von Gruber [1884-1942], who made significant contributions to the development of photogrammetry while working with Carl Zeiss, Jena.

name: Grundtvigskirken
description: Mountain massif 1977 m high in Renland, on the NW side of ╪fjord, dominated by a granite tower bearing a remarkable resemblance (as seen from the east) to the tower of Grundtvigskirken in Copenhagen (Fig. 44). A photograph of this peak appears in reports

name: Grunnvσgen
description: Bay on east Geographical Society ╪, north of Cambridge Bugt. So named on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937), because the bay is shallow (= grunn).

name: Gryden
description: Major depression in central Gauss Halv° at the head of Vastidal. Named by Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions (gryden = the bowl).

name: Grydepas

name: Grµnsedalen

name: Grµst°rvshytten
description: Norwegian hunting hut built in August 1928 by the HIRD expedition on the west side of Albrecht Bugt, Wollaston Forland. The walls of the hut were supported by turf (= grµst°rv). The hut was more commonly known as Sletta.

name: Joakimpasset
description: Pass on central Geographical Society ╪, corresponding to part of Tvµrdal. Used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937), and named after Joakim Devold [b. 1908], a Norwegian artist who took part in expeditions to East and SE Greenland in 1931 and 1932.

name: Joffert-Gletscher
description: Northern of three small glaciers between Vestre Gletscher and Mellem Gletscher in the northern Werner Bjerge. The name was used by Styger (1951) in a report on a climbing excursion during Lauge Koch's 1950 expedition, and was named after Japheth, one of

name: Joh. G. Guildal ╪

name: Johan Davidsen Dal

description: Hill NE of Myggbukta station in southern Hold with Hope. The name occurs on the NSIU map (1932a; Fig. 13), and was probably given for Johan A. Olsen whose 1922 expedition built the first Myggbukta radio station. The entire expedition was lost when the AN

name: Johannes Knudsens topper

description: Valley on west Geographical Society ╪ draining north into Sofia Sund. The name is used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937), and was given for Sigurd Halvorsen Johannesen [1881-1964], a Norwegian businessman who was a member of several Norwegian ministries c

name: Camp Col

name: Camp Peninsula

name: Camp Tahoe
description: Name used by Washburn (1965) for the house north of Tunnelelv on a section of road between Nyhavn and Minebyen, the headquarters for his geomorphological studies between 1955 and 1964. It was named after his wife, Tahoe Washburn. It is usually known as W

name: Canis Major Gletscher

name: Kjµrsundet

name: Klinten

name: Klipperne

name: Klippe°

name: Klubben

name: Klubben

name: Klubtinde
description: Mountain about 2550 m high on the NE side of Orion Gletscher. Climbed by the 1996 Norwegian Stauning Alper expedition, and named after the Norsk Tindeklub (a Norwegian mountaineering club).

name: Klumpen

name: Kl°ft 1

name: Holmslethuset

name: Horsedal
description: Valley on the north side of ╪rsted Dal, Scoresby Land. Named by Hans Stauber during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition led by Lauge Koch, following a suggestion by Ib Poulsen, who travelled this route to Antarctic Havn with horses (Icelandic ponies) in the

name: Horsens Fjord
description: Fjord on the east coast of south Liverpool Land. So named by Laurits Bruhn during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen after the fjord of the same name on the east coast of Jylland, Denmark.

name: Horsnµs Fangststation
description: Danish hunting station built by Nanok in the summer of 1945 on the west side of the river draining into Zackenberg Bugt, western Wollaston Forland. This was the proposed original name, as the finances to build the station were offered by the Danish newsp

name: Horva

name: Hovgaard ╪
description: Island north of Nioghalvfjerdsfjorden. Named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen as Hovgaards ╪, after Andreas Peter Hovgaard [1853-1910], a Danish naval officer and polar explorer. Hovgaard took part in the 1881 VEGA expedition through the NE Passage a

name: Huggeblokken
description: Small skerry in the inner NW part of Danmark Havn, southern Germania Land. So named during the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen by Charles Poulsen. In his published diary (Poulsen 1991) he relates that to avoid waking sleeping members of the expedition on t

name: Kap Reinhardt
description: Cape on the SW side of Ardencaple Fjord, north of the mouth of Kildedal. Named by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt as Cap Reinhard or Cap Reinhardt, probably after Johannes Theodor Reinhardt [1816-1882], the director of the Natural History

name: Kap Rink
description: South cape of Hochstetter Forland. Named Cap Rink by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt after Heinrich Johannes Rink [1819-93], a Danish geologist, Greenland explorer and administrator. He had corresponded with the expedition committee. The D

name: Kap Ryder

name: Kap Schumacher
description: Peninsula south of Kuhn ╪ opposite Kap Hamburg. Named Cap Schumacher by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt, after Hermann Albert Schumacher [1839-1890], a jurist and historian, and one of the members of the expedition organising committee (J.

name: Kap Seaforth

name: Kap Simpson

name: Kap Steglich-Petersen
description: Cape-like feature in southern Kronprins Christian Land facing south towards the Inland Ice. The area was mapped by Lauge Koch from the air in 1933 during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, and the feature was named after the high-court lawyer Kristian Steg

description: Major peninsula between Nathorst Fjord and Carlsberg Fjord (Fig. 90). William Scoresby Jr. in 1822 had used the name Canning Island for a tract of bold land that appeared to be insular (Fig. 3). It was named after one of the secretaries of state, George

name: Canongletscher
description: Glacier SW of the head of Smallefjord (Fig. 81), C.H. Ostenfeld Land. The name originated from the wintering party at Kulhus during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen.

name: Cap Albert de Belgique

name: Kangertivatsiaakajik

name: Kangikajiip Kangerterajiva

name: Granta-Kirk Passet
description: Pass between Kirkbrae and Grantabrae, about 2100 m high. So named by the 1996 Norwegian Stauning Alper expedition, which had been aiming for the Grantalang Col but took a slightly too northerly route.

name: Grantabotn
description: Norwegian hunting hut on the north side of inner Grantafjord, southern Payer Land, built by Arktisk Nµringsdrift in September 1931 (NSIU 1932c). (Grantafjordhytten, Grantahytta, Granta-botn.)

name: Grantabrae
description: Tributary glacier on the north side of upper Sefstr÷m Gletscher, so named by the 1963 Cambridge University expedition. See also Grantafjord.

name: Grantafjellene
description: Name occasionally used by Norwegian hunters for the mountains on the north side of Grantafjord in southern Payer Land.

name: Grantafjord
description: Fjord west of Clavering ╪, The name was given by J.M. Wordie for the River Granta (also known as the Cam) which runs through the city of Cambridge, England. (Grant's Fjord.)

name: Grantagletscher
description: Branch of Wordie Gletscher draining into Grantafjord. Named by Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions in the form Granta Gletscher.

name: Grantalang Col
description: Col on the south side of upper Langgletscher (now Storgletscher) leading to the head of Grantabrae and Sefstr÷m Gletscher, Stauning Alper. The name was used by Bennet (1972).

name: Grantapynt

name: Graven

description: Series of mountain summits up to 1800 m high on the NE side of Nordvestfjord opposite the mouth of Flyverfjord. The name originated during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen because the mountain tops resembled a row of gravestones, and was adopted at the su

name: Great Cumbrae
description: Upper branch of Cantabrµ, Stauning Alper. So named by the 1998 Scottish Mountaineering Club expedition.

name: Great Fault River
description: Reference locality used by Dunbar (1955) for one of Lauge Koch's sample sites east of Kap Stosch, Home Forland. This is probably the river flowing in Forkastningsdal (Great Fault Valley), also called River 16, and officially known as Blσelv.

name: Great White
description: Marked summit 1645 m high on the north side of Korridoren, Milne Land. Climbed by the 2004 West Lancashire Scouts expedition via the glacier to the north of the summit, which they named Great White Glacier.

name: Green River
description: Name used by the 1974 Joint biological expedition for a minor stream on SW Traill ╪, west of Karupelv, which drains into Holm Bugt.

name: Gregory Cove

name: Gregory Lake
description: Name occasionally used during the 1933 Louise A. Boyd Arctic expedition for the traces of a former lake in Knµkdalen, western Strindberg Land, their Gregory Valley.

name: Froggies Beaut
description: Peak on the divide between the heads of Gullygletscher and Schuchert Gletscher. The name is used by the 1996 Norwegian Stauning Alper expedition in their report and on their maps, but was not claimed as a first ascent.

name: Frosnebugt
description: Large bay on east Shannon. Named by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt as Gefrorne Bai, because the bay was still ice-covered and impassable when their ship reached here in July 1870 (gefrorne = frosne = frozen). (Gefrorene Bai, Frozen Bay.)

name: Frydendal
description: Valley on the south side of Storefjord, central Liverpool Land. So named by Laurits Bruhn during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen (fryd = delight).

name: Frµnkel Land

description: Mountain ridge up to 1600 m high in eastern Hudson Land, named by Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions in the form Fuchs Ridges or Mt Fuchs after Vivian Ernest Fuchs [1908-1999]. He was one of the geologists of J.M. Wordie's 1929 Cambridge expedition that ma

description: Name used by Severin Liavaag's 1908-09 expedition (Brandal 1930) for a feature in the vicinity of Kap Borlase Warren, SE Wollaston Forland, where the expedition had shot ptarmigan (fugl = bird). Exact position uncertain.

name: Dyrdalen

name: Dyrskolten

name: J.F.B. Mountain

name: Kapp ╪ien
description: Cape on SW Clavering ╪, equivalent to the delta at the mouth of Granatdal. The name is used on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937), and was given for Jens ╪ien [b. 1870], a Norwegian skipper who with the LAURA sailed a number of hunting expeditions to East G

name: Kapp ┼lesund
description: Cape on the east coast of Jordanhill. Used on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937), the name was given after the town of ┼lesund in Norway, home of many of the Norwegian sealers that hunted off East Greenland.

name: Kapspidsen
description: Mountain near Kap Peschel in Ad. S. Jensen Land. The name Kap-Spitze is only mentioned in the geology section of the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt narrative, but was adopted by subsequent visitors to the region and approved in its Danish for

name: Gregory Valley
description: Name originally used by J.M. Wordie's 1929 Cambridge expedition for the valley in western Frµnkel Land containing Gregory Gletscher and continuing northwards to the Mysteries°er. The name was subsequently applied by the 1933 Louise A. Boyd Arctic expedit

name: Hj°rnet
description: Mountain c. 2000 m high in west AndrΘe Land. So named during Lauge Koch's 1950 expedition by John Haller, because it was in an outlying corner (= hj°rne) of the region he mapped.

name: Hochstetter
description: Name commonly used by Danish hunters in the 1930s for the Danish hunting station in southernmost Hochstetter Forland, officially known as Nanok. (Hochstetter Station.)

name: Hochstetter Forland
description: Low-lying land area NE of Ardencaple Fjord, limited to the west by the Barth Bjerge. Named by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt as Hochstetter Vorland, after Ferdinand Ritter von Hochstetter [1829-1884]. An Austrian geologist, he was profess

name: Hochstetterbugten
description: Broad bay between Hochstetter Forland and Shannon to the north, and Wollaston Forland and the Pendulum ╪er to the south. The name is said to have been in use from 1929 by Danish hunters, and first appeared on the maps of the 1932 Gefion expedition. (Hoch

name: Hochwacht
description: Mountain 1605 m high in Hudson Land south of Ritoms°. Named by Heinrich Bⁿtler during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition led by Lauge Koch, after the small prominent hills of Switzerland used as watchtowers (= hochwacht).

name: Hodal
description: Valley in Liverpool Land on the east side of Hurry Inlet. So named by Laurits Bruhn during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, possibly after the small town of Ho near Esbjerg, Denmark.

name: Hodbreen
description: Glacier on Clavering ╪ draining east to the front of Skillegletscher. The name is used on the maps of Lacmann (1937), and derives from old Nordic mythology. H°der, the blind son of Odin, was lured into shooting his brother Balder with an arrow made of mi

name: Hofgaardvatna
description: Lake on SE Geographical Society ╪, the present Basalts°. Used on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937; Fig. 14), the name was given for Knut Hofgaard [b. 1903], a Norwegian hunter who wintered in East Greenland from 1932 to 1933.

name: Hohe Kugel
description: Mountain 1337 m high on the north side of Lindeman Fjord, so named by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt probably after the mountain of the same name in Austria. (Mt Hohe Kugel, Store Kugle.)

name: Hohgant
description: Mountain 658 m high in northern Wollaston Forland. So named by Wolf Maync and Andreas Vischer during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition led by Lauge Koch (Maync 1947), because in shape and geology it resembles the mountain ridge of the same name in the Bern

description: River draining from Holbergpasset eastwards to Mesters Vig. Named by prospecting teams associated with Lauge Koch's 1948-49 expeditions after Ludvig Holberg [1684-1754], a Danish historian and writer, who wrote 25 plays for the theatre. On detailed 1:15

description: Glacier north of Paul Stern Land draining into Vestfjord. So named during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions to Scoresby Sund by Ole Olesen because studies showed it to be stationary (d°d = dead).

name: D°demandsbugten
description: Bay on SE Clavering ╪. The name appears in the form Daudmannsvσgen on an NSIU map (1932a), and like the term Daudmanns°yra for the coastal stretch, may have been in use earlier by Norwegian hunters. At this site there are 43 Inuit winter houses in three

name: D°demandsbugten

description: Coastal stretch of D°demandsbugten, SE Clavering ╪. The name was used by Danish hunters about 1931 because of the numerous Inuit house ruins (tomt = building site). See also Daudmanns°yra.

description: Mountain range on the east side of Gr°nlands Styrelse Gletscher, in the high plateau region south of Scoresby Sund. The name originated from Martin Lindsay's 1934 British Trans-Greenland expedition, and has appeared on maps in the forms Mountains of the

name: D°dis S°
description: Lake in Hochstetter Forland where samples were taken for radiocarbon age determinations (Bj÷rck et al. 1994; Cremer et al. 2008).

name: D°d°rnryggen
description: Name used for the SW ridge of Dansketinden by the 1996 Scottish Mountaineering Club expedition. Part of the ridge was climbed, and it was described as resembling a dead eagle lying on its back.

name: Dσsen
description: Mountain 780 m high on SW Wegener Halv°. Named by Katharina Perch-Nielsen during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions for its shape (dσse = box, can).

name: E. Horse-shoe Mountain
description: Eastern of the two ridges of Hesteskoen on Canning Land. The name is used by SΣve-S÷derbergh (1937).

name: East Cape
description: Eastern cape of Jackson ╪. The name is used only in the English edition of the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt (Koldewey 1874). The expedition anchored here on 1 August 1870.

name: Binucleus
description: Mountain on SE Clavering ╪ with two summits, 1493 m and 1471 m high. Named during Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions in the form Mt. Binucleus. See also Monacleus and Trinucleus. (Binucleusfjellet, Binucleus Bjerg).

name: Biot-Stua
description: Norwegian hunting hut 3 km NW of Kap Biot, eastern Scoresby Land, built by the M°re expedition in August 1930. It also goes by the names Davy Sund Hytten, Villa and Nordre Biot.

name: Birgitnµs
description: Minor cape on SE Clavering ╪, possibly the present Basaltkap. So named on a sketch map in Gustav Thostrup's 1921 logbook (M°ller 1939). Girl's name.

name: Birgitsbjµrg
description: Name given by Erdhart FrΣnkl during Lauge Koch's 1950-51 expeditions to the present Nordsylen, a mountain about 1500 m high in the northern Stauning Alper. The name appears on the profiles in FrΣnkl (1953). Girl's name.

name: Birkedal
description: Valley on the west side of inner Grandjean Fjord. The name originated from the wintering party at Kulhus in 1935, and was given for the occurrence of the dwarf birch. See also Betula Havn.

name: Birkedalshytten
description: Alternative name for Betulahavnhytten, a Danish hunting hut built in 1951 at Betulahavn, inner Grandjean Fjord. It is sited at the mouth of Birkedal.

name: Bischofsmⁿtze
description: Mountain 1360 m high in the Trekantgletscher area, west of Alpefjord. Climbed by Wolfgang Weinzierl's 1970 expedition, and named after the Austrian peak of the same name, the highest mountain in the Dachstein group. (Bishopæs Mitre.)

name: Bishop
description: Name used by Bennet (1972) for a glacier in NE Nathorst Land draining east to Alpefjord.

name: J.L. Mowinckel Land
description: Mountainous region south of Adolf Hoel Gletscher and west of AndrΘe Land. Named by the 1931 H°ygaard & Mehren expedition as J.L. Mowinckels Fjell for the Norwegian prime minister [Johan Ludwig Mowinckel, 1870-1943], who had shown interest in their expedi

name: J.P. Koch Fjeld
description: Hill 909 m high, the highest point in southern Jameson Land. The name was used in the form J.P. Koch Mountain by Alfred Rosenkrantz in L. Koch (1929a), and was given for Johan Peter Koch [1870-1928]. A Danish army officer and explorer, Koch took part in

name: Jaalspids
description: Peak in the Stauning Alper on the SW ridge of Dansketinden. It was climbed by the 1996 Scottish Mountaineering Club expedition.

name: Jacks Hytte
description: Danish hunting hut built by Nanok in August 1950 on the west side of Brorson Halv°, northern Wollaston Forland. The name commemorates an incident in the winter of 1949-50, when the hunter Jack Christensen lost two of his toes to frostbite.

name: Jackson ╪
description: Island NE of Hold with Hope. Named by William Scoresby Jr. in 1822 as Jackson Island after Thomas Jackson of Whitby, who had married Scoresby's third and youngest sister Arabella in 1812. He was also a cousin of Scoresby's. Jackson's son, Robert Edmund S

name: Jacksonstua
description: Norwegian hunting station on SW Jackson ╪, built by the Hird expedition in 1928. The station was manned only in the periods 1928-29 and 1933-34, and was subsequently occasionally used by hunters (P.S. Mikkelsen 2008). It was maintained by Sirius, until a

name: Jacksontoppen
description: Highest point of Jackson ╪, 422 m in altitude. The name appears on the NSIU (1932a) map.

name: Jacob's House
description: Name used by Tuborg & Sandell (1999) for one of four hunters houses in a bay on the NW side of Steward ╪, northern Blosseville Kyst. The houses are used by hunters from Scoresbysund, who regularly overwinter here, and the first house was built in 1971 by

name: Jakhellnsundet
description: Narrow sound between Kista ╪ and Traill ╪ in Vega Sund, corresponding to the present Snµvringen. The name is used on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937), and was given for Anton Jakhelln [1904-1990]. A Norwegian meteorologist and oceanographer, he took part

name: Jakob Dal
description: Valley in the Giesecke Bjerge, draining eastwards. It was named by Wolf Maync and Andreas Vischer during Lauge Koch's 1936-38 expeditions after Jakob Sanimuinak of Scoresbysund, their Greenlandic assistant and sledge-driver in 1937 and 1938. (Jakobsdal.)

name: Jakob Kj°de Bjerg
description: Large nunatak 1850 m high on the north side of Adolf Hoel Gletscher. Named by the 1931 H°ygaard & Mehren expedition as Jakob Kj°des fjell, for one of Norway's largest ship owners [Jakob Kj°de 1880-1946]. (Jacob Kj°des fjell, Jakob Kj°des Bjµrg.)

name: Jakob Severin Bjerg
description: Mountain in central Jameson Land, south of Olympen. The name was one of a group of names given by the Place Name Committee in 1939 to replace proposals by Hans Stauber. It was given for Jakob Severin [1691-1753], a Danish businessman and nobleman who acq

name: Jakobsbo
description: Two huts, built in 1960 by Nordisk Mineselskab in the interior of Deltadal, were known by this name, which commemorates æGamle Jakob', a carpenter from Minebyen, the lead mine near Mestersvig airfield. They were built in connection with bulldozer transpo

name: Jakobsendalen
description: Valley on north Geographical Society ╪. Used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937), it was named after Anton Karl Hagbart Jakobsen [1874-1983], a Norwegian bank director and politician, who was also a ship-owner.

name: Jaksla
description: Mountain 1330 m high on west Geographical Society ╪. Used on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937), and apparently named for its tooth-like shape.

name: Jamesondal
description: Name occasionally used for the valley on Wegener Halv° containing Jameson Elv.

name: Jameson Elv
description: River on Wegener Halv° draining NE into Nathorst Fjord. Named by Arne Noe-Nygaard during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen as Jameson River, because of its proximity to Jameson Land.

name: Kap Mohn
description: Western cape of Ymer ╪. Named during the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt, although the name is only found in the narrative of Payer (1876) in the form Insel Mohn. Henrik Mohn [1835-1916] was a Norwegian meteorologist, founder and director of t

name: Kaptajn Hansens Promenade
description: Name given by Danish hunters to a pathway constructed by Captain F. Hansen on Bass Rock to improve the passage from the beach to the higher parts of the island. After the wreck of the DAGNY commanded by Hansen in 1920, the nine crew and Danish hunters wi

name: Kar Glacier
description: Name used by Andreas Vischer (in: Koch 1955) in a report on his 1937 field work, for a glacier on the slopes of Hⁿhnerbjerg east of point 630 m (kar = large vessel or bathtub).

name: Karabiner Fjeld
description: Mountain 2000 m high south of Leo Gletscher, southern Stauning Alper. First climbed by John Hunt's 1960 expedition, and named Karabiner for the Karabiner Mountaineering Club of which he was Honorary President. The second ascent was by the 1971 University

name: Karbon Elv
description: River flowing through Sandstensdal, west Wollaston Forland. The name was used by Alfred Rosenkrantz (1932) because rocks of Carboniferous (= Karbon) age were found here in 1929. (Karbon River.)

name: Kargletscher
description: Small glacier in the Werner Bjerge, merging to the north with ╪stre Gletscher. Named during Lauge Koch's 1953-54 expeditions by Peter Bearth and Eduard Wenk.

name: Karh°jen
description: Mountain in the Werner Bjerge between Kargletscher and ╪stre Gletscher, named by Peter Bearth and Eduard Wenk during the 1953-54 Lauge Koch expeditions. It was climbed by Bearth in 1953.

name: Karin Dal
description: Valley on Gauss Halv° draining north into Moskusoksefjord, named by Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions in the form Karin Valley. Girl's name, said to be a Swedish girlfriend of one of the expedition members. (Karinsdal, Karin Tal.)

name: Karinas Lyst
description: Name given to the first small house built by the 1924 expedition that founded Scoresbysund; it was a food store. It was named after Karina Bell, a Danish actress who was Aage Nielsen's cousin. See also Aage Nielsen Bjerg.

name: Karl Dal
description: Valley in the northern Giesecke Bjerge draining east into Badland Dal. Named by Wolf Maync and Andreas Vischer during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition, after Karl Andersen, their Greenlandic assistant and sledge-driver in 1937 and 1938.

name: Gule Horn
description: Mountain 975 m high in eastern Jameson Land, west of inner Carlsberg Fjord. Named in geological reports during Lauge Koch's 1958 expedition by John H. Callomon, for the colour of the rocks (gule = yellow).

name: Gulelv
description: River in Home Forland, northern Hold with Hope draining north. Named by Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions in the form Yellow River, probably for the colour of the Triassic rocks. It has also been referred to as River 19 (Koch 1931). (Gula, Gulaelv.)

name: Gulfjelde
description: Mountains of yellow sandstone about 300 m high on the west side of Rosenvinge Bugt, southern Liverpool Land. Named during the 1924-25 colonisation expedition. (Gule Fjµlde, Yellow Fjeld, Montagne Jaune.)

name: Gully-Lang Col
description: Pass in the northern Stauning Alper between the head of Gully Gletscher and Storgletscher (formerly Langgletscher).

name: Gultop Gletscher
description: Small glacier flowing from Ad Astra Iskappe, near Gultop, to the snout of Admiralty Gletscher, north Dronning Louise Land (Fig. 21). Named by the 1952-54 British North Greenland Expedition.

name: Gundahl Knold
description: Isolated hill in eastern Dronning Louise Land at the front of Borgj°kel (Fig. 21). Named by the 1912-13 Den danske Ekspedition til Dronning Louises Land as Gundahls Knold, after Jens Gundahl Knudsen [1876-1948]. He was the carpenter on the 1906-08 Danmar

name: Gunnar Andersson Land
description: North part of Ymer ╪, north of DusΘn Fjord. In 1929 Lauge Koch followed up the reports by his Greenlandic hunters that DusΘn Fjord was longer than it was thought to be, and found that it almost divided Ymer ╪ into two parts. He named the northern part af

name: Gunnar Hornsletta
description: Low-lying area on the NE side of Geographical Society ╪. Used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937), the name commemorates Gunnar Horn [1894-1946], an NSIU geologist who participated in several expeditions to Svalbard and Franz Joseph Land between 1924 and 19

name: Gullygletscher
description: Glacier occupying a deep and spectacular gully in the Stauning Alper. The name originated from J.M. Wordie's 1929 Cambridge expedition, and appears to have been used originally as an alternative name for Sefstr÷m Gletscher, with which the present Gullygl

name: Jubilee Peak
description: Mountain 1048 m high west of Stensund, Liverpool Land, climbed by four members of the 1977 Joint Services Expedition. The name, given to commemorate the 25th jubilee year of Queen Elizabeth II's accession, was reported in several British newspapers.

name: Julekagen
description: Mountain range between Grµsdalen and Lysedal, Geographical Society ╪. The name was derived from a suggestion by Hans Stauber during Lauge Koch's 1936-38 expeditions, who had compared the mountain to a giant Christmas cake (= julekagen).

name: Juliasbjerge
description: Peak 2058 m high on the west side of upper Storgletscher, central Stauning Alper. Climbed and named after a living person by the 2007 SMC East Greenland Expedition.

name: Julles ╪
description: Island in the west part of Dove Bugt, the present Midterholmen. The name was used during a sledge journey in October 1907 by Henning Bistrup. (Jan L°ve, personal communication May 2012).

name: J√lut Dal
description: Valley on south Ymer ╪, draining west to Karl Jakobsen Bugt. Named by Ove Simonsen during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen for J°rgen Petersen, known as J√lut, a Greenlander who acted as assistant and dog-driver throughout the expedition and hunted in thi

name: Junction Peak
description: Peak in the upper reaches of Roslin Gletscher, Stauning Alper. Named by the 1970 Cambridge University expedition which climbed the mountain on 1 August 1970.

name: Junctiondal
description: Valley in southern AndrΘe Land, named by J.M. Wordie's 1929 Cambridge expedition as Junction Valley, because the valley followed fault contacts between different rock units. On some maps a hunting hut is shown at the mouth of the valley, but this was nev

name: Jupiter Gletscher
description: Glacier flowing NE to join Bj°rnbo Gletscher, south Stauning Alper. Named Jupiter Glacier by John Hunt's 1960 expedition, for the planet Jupiter, fifth major planet from the sun.

name: Juradal
description: 71╪ (71░19.6'N 22░38.6'W) Name used on the maps of Callomon (1970) for the valley in NE Jameson Land carrying Liaselv, which flows east into Carlsberg Fjord. The valley was used during Lauge Koch's 1958 expedition as a route to the interior of Jameson La

name: Juraelv
description: River in west Jameson Land draining SW into Lodin Elv. Named by Hans Stauber during Lauge Koch's 1936-38 expeditions after the widespread outcrops of Jurassic rocks.

name: Jurakl÷ft
description: Name used by Maync (1947) for a ravine in north Wollaston Forland, just east of Sillerendal. The name arose during Lauge Koch's 1936-38 expeditions, and was given for the Jurassic rocks.

name: Jyllandselv
description: River in SW Jameson Land flowing SW to enter the sea north of Vandreblokken. Named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Laurits Bruhn for Jylland (= Jutland), Denmark.

name: Jytte Havn
description: Pronounced bay in the SW island of the Bj°rne°er, regularly used as an anchorage by GGU's 9-ton motor cutter JYTTE (Fig. 50) during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions.

name: Jµgerdal
description: Valley in north Scoresby Land, SW of Mesters Vig. Named by Hans Kapp during Lauge Koch's 1957-58 expeditions, and named after the Norwegian hunters (= jµger).

name: Jµgerly
description: Name sometimes used for the Danish hunting hut built in 1923 by ╪stgr°nlands Fangstkompagni about 2 km NE of Kap David Gray, Shannon (see Kap David Grayhytten).

name: Jostein
description: Hunting hut 15 km NW of Kap Syenit, east of the mouth of Mesters Vig. It was built in 1930 by the M°re expedition, and named after Jostein, the youngest son of Odd ┼mbakk, one of the hunters. It has also been called Segldalen, Bj°rnebu and Pictetbjerghyt

name: Jostgletscher
description: Name used by Mittelholzer (1941) for the present Snemarken, central Clavering ╪, in his report on work during Lauge Koch's 1938-39 expeditions. (Josts Gletscher.)

name: Josvakajiip kaporniagaqarpia
description: Name sometimes used for the hut at the mouth of Hj°rnedal, where F°nfjord and R°defjord meet.

name: Jotunheim
description: Ice plateau in western C.H. Ostenfeld Land. The name originated from the wintering party at Kulhus during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, and was given for the region of the same name in south Norway.

name: Jµgersund
description: Sound between Tvillingerne and Nanok ╪, in the SW part of Dove Bugt. The name was suggested by the Place Name Committee as a substitute for a proposal by Eigil Knuth. It commemorates the Danish hunters (= jµger) operating in the region. A Danish hut on t

name: JΣgmΣsteren ╪
description: Island at the mouth of SegelsΣllskapet Fjord. The name JΣgmΣsterens ╓ was originally given by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst to the present Karlenes ╪, and commemorated E. Nilson [b. 1863], the expedition hunter, always r

name: Jµttebringen
description: Eastern part of Ymer Nunatak in north Dronning Louise Land. So named by 1906-08 Danmark expedition probably for its shape, and perhaps also after the feature of the same name at M°ns Klint, Denmark. Koch (1916) translates it as æthe giant's chest'. (Jµtt

name: Biskop Alfs Gletscher
description: Glacier draining the south flank of the Werner Bjerge, the present Breithorn Gletscher. The name was one of a group of names for glaciers given by the Place Name Committee in 1939, which replaced proposals by Hans Stauber. Alf (┴lfr) was bishop to the No

name: Biskop Joseph Fjeld
description: The name is used in Den Gr°nlandske Lods (1968) for a mountain in Liverpool Land, the present Kirken. It was one of the names introduced by Henning Bistrup on his coast profiles drawn in 1923 and 1930.

name: Bison Lake
description: Lake south of Klµgbugt, Nordmarken. Named by the 1987 Irish expedition to NE Greenland.

name: Bispehuen
description: Mountain 1261 m high east of Pothorst Bjerge, northern Jameson Land, with a shape said to resemble a bishop's mitre. The name was suggested by Russel Marris following his explorations in 1968.

name: Bivuakkammen
description: Ridge in the Werner Bjerge. Named by Peter Bearth and Eduard Wenk during Lauge Koch's 1953 expedition for the locality of one of their satellite camps used during geological exploration (kam = ridge).

name: Bjarne Larsenfjellet
description: Mountain 1293 m high on central Clavering ╪. Used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937), the name was given for Bjarne Larsen [b.1904], a Norwegian aeroplane mechanic who took part in the 1932 NSIU expedition.

name: Bjergandes°
description: Lake on Winge Kyst in southern Germania Land. So named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen because a pair of scaups (= bjergµnder) were observed here in June 1907, an uncommon bird in this part of East Greenland.

name: Bjergkronerne
description: Mountain range in Scoresby Land north of ╪rsted Dal, with summits formed by basalt sills giving a crown-like appearance (krone = crown). Named during Lauge Koch's 1936-38 expeditions by Hans Stauber.

name: Bjerring Pedersen Fjµld
description: Name used by Rosenkrantz (1934, 1942) after one of the summits of Gulfjelde in southern Liverpool Land, an area first investigated by Bjerring Pedersen in 1924. See also Bjerring Pedersen Gletscher. (Mt. Bjerring Pedersen.)

name: Bjerring Pedersen Gletscher
description: Glacier in southern Liverpool Land draining east to the head of Vejle Fjord. Named by Laurits Bruhn during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen after Bjerring Pedersen [1898-1925], a Danish geologist who led the party of six scientists and carpenters during t

name: Bj°rktun
description: Norwegian hunting hut built in September 1931 by the M°re expedition, about 10 km from the inner end of Forsblad Fjord. It was destroyed by an avalanche in the spring of 1976. The hut was named after the small birch trees surrounding the hut (Rogne 1981)

name: Bj°rn Jorsalfarers Gletscher
description: Glacier in the Stauning Alper draining east to Schuchert Dal, the present Storgletscher. The name was one of a group of names for glaciers given by the Place Name Committee in 1939, which replaced proposals by Hans Stauber. The name was officially approv

name: Bj°rn Pynt
description: Cape on eastern Lille Koldewey, so named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen, possibly after Poul Harald Bj°rn who at one time worked with Bendix Thostrup at the Danish nautical charts archive (J. L°ve, personal communication 2009). (Bj÷rns Pynt, Bj°rn

name: Cape Ross
description: William Scoresby Jr. in 1822 reported Cape Ross as a bold promontory, but was uncertain whether it formed part of Jameson Land or some other distinct region. Ryder (1895) said that the cape did not exist at the position indicated, while Bay (1896) placed

name: Cape Rossel
description: William Scoresby Jr. gave this name in 1822 to what he thought was a cape, but was probably a mountain on Ymer ╪, perhaps the present Celsius Bjerg. The name, which has not survived, was given out of respect to Elisabeth Paul Edouard de Rossel [1765-1829

name: Cape Stufenberg
description: Name given to the SW cape of Lille Pendulum by J.M. Wordie's 1926 Cambridge expedition, which was named after the mountain above it, Karl Koldewey's Stufenberg, now Terrasseberg.

name: Cape Syntektite
description: Name proposed by Helge G. Backlund for the present Kap Buddicom, Liverpool Land, during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen. The name derives from the geology, but was never approved, and occurs on only very few maps (e.g. Kranck 1935).

name: Capella Plateau
description: Name given by Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions to the plateau area west of Margrethedal, corresponding to the present Vestreplateau.

name: Carbondal
description: Name used by Dunbar (1955) for a valley in western Wollaston Forland where Lauge Koch collected rock samples of Carboniferous age. The exact location is uncertain, but it is probably the present Sandstensdal, in which flows the river Alfred Rosenkrantz h

name: Kap Montpensier
description: Northern cape of ╬le de France (from 2004 Qeqertaq Prins Henrik). Named by 1905 ExpΘdition Arctique du Duc d'OrlΘans as Cap Montpensier, probably after Isabella de Montpensier [d. 1919], the Duc's mother.

name: Kap Moorsom
description: Short promontory on SE Traill ╪, named Cape Moorsom by William Scoresby Jr. in 1822 out of respect to Richard Moorsom Jr. of Whitby.

name: Kap Mosle
description: NW cape of Kuhn ╪. Named by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt as Cap Mosle, after Alexander Georg Mosle [1827-1882]. He was president of the æBremisches ComitΘ fⁿr die zweite Deutsche Nordpolarfahrt', one of the expedition's principal suppor

name: Kap Mµchel
description: Cape between Forsblad Fjord and Alpefjord (Fig. 61), named by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst. The name appears on charts in both Swedish (1900) and English (1901) editions of Nathorst's narrative in the form æMµchel', but

name: Kap Nansen
description: North cape of the largest of the Norske ╪er. Named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition after the Norwegian Arctic explorer Fridtjof Nansen [1861-1930], who was noted especially for his crossing of the Inland Ice of Greenland in 1888, and his drift acros

name: Kap Nax
description: SE cape of C. Silfverberg ╪, so named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen. Origin of name unknown.

name: Kap Negri
description: Cape on the south side of the mouth of Grandjean Fjord. Named Cap Negri by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt, after Baron Christoforo Negri [1809-96]. An Italian geographer, he was founder and first president of the æReale Societα Geografica

name: Kap Neumayer
description: Northern cape of Sabine ╪. Named Cap Neumayer by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt after Georg Balthasar von Neumayer [1826-1909]. A German meteorologist and oceanographer, he was founder of æDeutsche Seewarte Hamburg' (German Naval Observat

name: Kap Niels
description: Cape on the east coast of Rechnitzer Land, so named by Henning Bistrup during the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen. Possibly named after Niels Baron Juel-Brockdorff [1878-1964], a colleague at the marine cadet school in 1898 (J. L°ve, personal communication

name: Kap Niels Hytten
description: Norwegian hunting hut at the peninsula north of Kap Niels, NE Rechnitser Land, built in August 1933 by John Giµver's expedition. Hunters had assumed this more prominent cape was Kap Niels, and as it has no other name the name is still often used.

name: Kap Oetker
description: Cape on SW Clavering ╪. Named Cap Oetker by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt after Friedrich Oetker [1809-81], a German author and lawyer. Huts at and SE of the cape have been known as Kap ╪tker Hytten (see Nes-Odden) and Kapp Oetker. (Cape

name: Kap Oswald
description: Cape on NW Ella ╪. So named by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst, possibly for Oswald Heer [1809-1883] (see also Kap Oswald Heer), or more probably for a member of Nathorst's own family. (Cape Oswald).

name: Kap Oswald Heer
description: Relatively elevated section of the east coast of Hochstetter Forland, with the appearance of a cape in the field, although it is not particulary prominent on a map. Named Cap Oswald Heer by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt after Oswald Heer

name: Kap Oswald Heerhytten
description: Danish hunting hut about 4 km south of Kap Oswald Heer, built by Nanok in May 1931, and rebuilt in 1932 and 1933. (Kap Oswald Heer Hytten, Oswald Heer Hytten.)

name: Kap Ovibos
description: SE cape of Strindberg Land. So named by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst for the muskox (Ovibos muschatus), of which he saw five at the cape. (Cape Ovibos.)

name: Kap Oviboshytten
description: Norwegian hut on the south side of Kap Ovibos, built by Arktisk Nµringsdrift in September 1933. It was originally known as Solheim. (Ovibos.)

name: Glacier J.L. Faure
description: Glacier tongue draining south into Vinkeldal, SE Milne Land. The name was used by Parat & Drach (1934), and named after Jean-Louis Faure, a French surgeon who accompanied J.B. Charcot's 1932 expedition and wrote an account of that voyage (Faure 1933).

name: Glacier Lauge Koch
description: Glacier in south Liverpool Land NE of Scoresbysund, draining north to Lillefjord. The name was used on maps and in accounts of the æCampagne du Pourquoi Pas?' led by J.B. Charcot (e.g. Faure 1933; Parat & Drach 1934). The French expeditions had received

name: Gulmann Sund
description: Sound between Jackson ╪ and Home Forland, NE Hold with Hope. The name was in use by hunters of 1919-24 A/S ╪stgr°nlandske Fangstkompagni from about 1923, and is said to originate with Gustav Thostrup, captain of the TEDDY in 1922. It was named after Chri

name: Gultop
description: Mountain in northern Dronning Louise Land at the NW edge of Ad Astra Iskappe (Fig. 21). So named by the 1952-54 British North Greenland Expedition because of the yellow quartzite forming its summit. (Guletop.)

name: Gunnbj÷rnfjellet
description: Mountain on the south side of Gauss Halv°, corresponding to the west end of the present Hjelmbjergene. So named on an NSIU map (1932a) after Gunnbj÷rn Ulfsson, noted for the discovery of skerries off SE Greenland which bear his name. The name appears as

name: Gunner Andersen S°
description: Lake in Ad. S. Jensen Land. The name was proposed by the Place Name Committee as a substitute for the rejected Nanok name Frieda S°. It commemorates Gunner Andersen, a Nanok telegraphist who died of exhaustion when overtaken by bad weather during a sledg

name: Gunnsteinfjellet
description: Mountain north of Gustav Dal in the Giesecke Bjerge, corresponding to the east summit of Troels-Lund Bjerg. Used only on the NSIU (1932a) map. (Gunnsteinsbjµrg.)

name: Guntherbreen
description: Glacier on central Clavering ╪, draining west. So named on NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937), after Gunther, who married Brunhilde in the German epic poem from c. 1200, the Nibelungenlied.

name: Gunvor Bjerg
description: Mountain 1231 m high in Strindberg Land. Named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen in the form Mt Gunvor, apparently after Paul Gelting's wife. Gelting visited the area in November 1931. (Gunv°rs Bjerg, Gunvors Bjerg.)

name: Gurreholm
description: Danish scientific station in western Jameson Land near Nordostbugt, built in 1937. It was named after a summerhouse of that name belonging to the owner of the Bulldog shopping chain, who had made a large contribution to Lauge Koch's expedition finances.

name: Hvalrosodden
description: Danish hunting station on the north coast of Dove Bugt, SW Germania Land, at the peninsula of the same name. The station was established by 1919-24 A/S ╪stgr°nlandske Fangstkompagni in 1919, and taken over by Nanok in 1929. Improvements and a radio stati

description: Mountain 1255 m high west of Clavering ╪. The name was originally used by Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions in the form Courtauld Land for the area of which the present Courtauld Bjerg is the highest point. The name commemorates Augustine Courtauld [1904-

name: Craig ╪er
description: Islands in Mountnorris Fjord. They were named the Craig Islands by William Scoresby Jr. in 1822 after a much respected episcopalian clergyman of Edinburgh. Scoresby evidently intended the name to apply to eight islands, including those close to the north

name: Crescent Pas
description: Col or pass between the heads of Gully Gletscher and Storgletscher, Stauning Alper, first reached by the 1961 Bangor expedition. It may have been given its name by the 1963 Cambridge University expedition. (Crescent Col).

name: Crescent Tind
description: Summit about 2450 m high on the west side of Crescent Pas, at the head of Gully Gletscher, Stauning Alper. Climbed and so named by the 1996 Norwegian Stauning Alper expedition.

name: Crinoid Bjerg
description: Minor hill in south Jameson Land on the west side of Muslingeelv. It was originally named in the form Crinoid Mt. by Hermann Aldinger (1935) during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen for finds of fossil crinoids, although the name was first approved in 1972

name: Crossopterygian Ravine
description: Ravine on the south side of the west end of Sederholm Bjerg, Gauss Halv°. The name was used by Johansson (1935), and records his finds of vertebrate fossils during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen. (Crossopterygie-ravinen.)

name: Culross
description: Mountain about 2067 m high on the south side of Jupiter Gletscher, southern Stauning Alper. Named by James Clarkson's 1961 expedition after Culross Palace, Fife, Scotland.

name: Curie Klippe
description: Cliff south of Admiralty Gletscher in Dronning Louise Land. One of the names given by the 1952-54 British North Greenland expedition for notable scientists (Fig. 21), it commemorates Pierre and Marie Curie who with Henri Becquerel were jointly awarded th

name: Czoks Topp
description: Mountain about 2490 m high on the north side of Roslin Gletscher, between the two branches of the minor glacier Valhallbreen. It was climbed by the 1996 Norwegian Stauning Alper expedition, and so named after Andrzej Czok [1948-1994] a polish climber and

name: D. Eglin Spire
description: Peak about 2500 m high at the head of Bersµrkerbrµ, between Bersµrker Tinde and Royal Peak, Stauning Alper. It was climbed and so named by the 1985 I.M. Marsh College expedition.

name: Andresensfjell
description: Name used by Norwegian hunters for a mountain on northern Clavering ╪, probably that which appeared on 1932 NSIU maps as Tiedemannfjellet. It may have been named after Herman Andresen, who organised numerous hunting expeditions to the region. See also He

name: Angalasut Nuuat
description: Cape to the west of Scoresbysund [Illoqqortormiut], southern Liverpool Land, probably identical with the original Ferslew Pynt. Recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, the name translates as ætravellers cape'. The colonisation ship unl

name: Findlingsbucht
description: Name used by Bⁿtler (1954) for a small bay at Kap Franklin. On the plates of his publication Bⁿtler uses Erratic Bloc Bay for the same feature. Both names refer to finds of fossils in ice-transported boulders in the bay.

name: Fingerb°llet
description: Mountain in the Werner Bjerge between Sirius Gletscher and Aldebaren Gletscher, named by Peter Bearth and Eduard Wenk during Lauge Koch's 1953-54 expeditions (fingerb°llet = thimble). It was climbed by Bearth's party in 1954, and named for the shape. (Fi

name: Fingerfjeld
description: This name is used in Den Gr°nlandske Lods (1968) for an 800 m high mountain on NE Clavering ╪, the present Langelinie. Possibly named for a finger-like shape.

name: Fingerklippen
description: Cape on NE Clavering ╪ south of Kap Breusing, the present Kap Arnakke. The name is used in Den Gr°nlandske Lods (1968). Possibly named for a finger-like appearance.

name: Finnsb·dir
description: Bay mentioned in the Icelandic sagas (Ivar Baardsson's annaler), which according to Torn°e (1944) might correspond to the present Antarctic Havn on the south side of Kong Oscar Fjord. In support of his speculations Torn°e noted the remains of a wooden ho

name: Finnvatnet
description: Lake on eastern Geographical Society ╪. Used only on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937), the name was given for Finn Devold [1901-77], who led Norwegian hunting expeditions to East and southern East Greenland in 1928-30 and 1931-33. From 1938 until his reti

name: Finsch ╪er
description: Group of five large islands south of Clavering ╪, including Store Finsch, Stille ╪, Kalven and Lille Finsch. The islands were named by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt as Finsch Inseln, after Otto Friedrich Hermann Finsch [1839-1917], a Ger

name: Fireskµret
description: Skerry east of Godfred Hansen ╪ in the SW part of Dove Bugt. Named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition.

name: Firkanten
description: Mountain 970 m high north of Margrethedal in SE Gauss Halv°, so named on an NSIU map (1932a) for its shape (firkant = square).

name: Firkanten
description: Norwegian hunting hut built by Arktisk Nµringsdrift in the summer of 1937 about 5 km west of Kap Franklin. It was also known as Funkis. No trace of it now remains.

name: Depotkulle
description: Mountain about 420 m high on the north side of Sµls°en. Named during the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition by Paul Gelting who had made a depot at the foot of the mountain in June 1939 when exploring Sµls°en.

name: Depotnµsset
description: Easternmost cape of Stormlandet. So named by Eigil Knuth's 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition because both the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen and the M°rkefjord expedition had made depots here. Svend S°lver found a depot here in April 1939 laid out by Gaston M

name: Depotskµret
description: Small island off SE Ad. S. Jensen Land. So named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen, probably for the prominent Inuit cairn built as a marker for a large meat depot (Thostrup 1911). Den Gr°nlandske Lods (1968) uses Depotskµrene for a group of nine isla

name: Depotsten
description: Rock on the east side of Loch Fyne, north of Str°mmen. The rock had been used as a depot marker, and the name occurs as a botanical reference locality in reports of the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen (Gelting 1934).

name: Depot°
description: Island on the south side of Nathorst Fjord, so named by Lauge Koch's 1926-27 expeditions as Depot Island because supplies were cached here during his sledge journeys.

name: Derry
description: Mountain 1480 m high north of the front of Bj°rnbo Gletscher, the present Snekuppel. Climbed during John Hunt's 1960 expedition, and named after Derry Lodge, Aberdeenshire, where young men selected for the expedition were trained.

name: Devaux Plateau
description: Plateau south of Charcot Havn, east Milne Land, so named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Hermann Aldinger after J. Devaux, a member of the 1933 Charcot expedition which visited the area. He was drowned in the wreck of the POURQOUI PAS? in 1936.

name: Devoldhalv°ya
description: Broad peninsula on Geographical Society ╪, north of Cambridge Bugt. So named on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937), after the brothers Finn, Halvard and Joakim Devold. See also Devoldhytta, Hallvardvatnet, Finnvatnet and Joakimpasset.

name: Devoldhytta
description: Norwegian hunting hut on the north side of DusΘn Fjord, Ymer ╪, west of Zoologdalen. It was built in 1929 for Arktisk Nµringsdrift by Olav Kjelbotn and Halvard Devold, and named after Halvard Ophus Devold [1898-1957]. A Norwegian telegraphist, he worked

name: Agnes-Tufta
description: Norwegian hunting hut 3 km west of Kap Schumacher on the west side of Albrecht Bugt, northern Wollaston Forland. It was built in September 1928 by the Hird expedition, and named after the youngest daughter of J°rgen Furnes who had helped build the hut; s

name: Agnesbjerg
description: Mountain in the N°rlund Alper, NE Hudson Land. This name appears to have been suggested by the Place Name Committee in 1963 as a substitute for a proposal by Paul Stern. Girl's name.

name: Bj°rnbo Gletscher
description: Large glacier in the southern Stauning Alper draining SE into Schuchert Dal. The name was one of a group of names for glaciers given by the Place Name Committee in 1939. It commemorates Axel Anthon Bj°rnbo [1874-1911], a noted authority on Greenland and

name: Bj°rnbos Corner
description: Name used by Kempter (1961) for the area NE of the terminus of Bj°rnbo Gletscher where it meets Schuchert Dal; this has become the type locality of his æBj°rnbos Corner Formation'. The name is not approved.

name: Bj°rnbos Elv
description: Name occasionally used in reports of the 1962 Oxford University expedition for the river draining Bj°rnbo Gletscher.

name: Bj°rnebu
description: Norwegian hunting hut built in August 1930 for the M°re expedition east of the mouth of Mesters Vig. It was originally called Jostein, and has also been known as Pictetbjergshytten and Segldalen.

name: Bj°rnebu
description: Norwegian hunting hut on the coast of Wollaston Forland, on the north side of Dronning Augustadalen. Built by the Hird expedition in July 1928, it has also been known as Stordalen and Augustadalshytten. Hunters considered it to be one of the best huts on

name: Bj°rnedal
description: Valley on SE Traill ╪ between Mountnorris Fjord and Kong Oscar Fjord. So named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Ove Simonsen because while surveying here two bears were shot. The valley appears to be a bear migration route (Fig. 33) between the

name: Bj°rnedal
description: Valley in the southern Giesecke Bjerge, corresponding to the present Randb°ldalen. So named on the NSIU (1932a) map, and given for the polar bear (Fig. 33). Franklindalen has been used for the same feature (Bang 1944).

name: Bj°rnegletscher
description: Glacier on the west side of outer Ingolf Fjord, draining the Prinsesse Elisabeth Alper. Named by the 1938-39 Drastrup/Kristoffersen expedition, possibly for the incident recorded by Kristoffersen (1969) of a bear that had followed their ski tracks up to

name: Bj°rneheimen
description: Norwegian hunting hut on the west side of Antarctic Sund at the mouth of Nanortalikdal, AndrΘe Land, built in September 1934 by Arktisk Nµringsdrift. This hut is often referred to as Nanortalik or Nanortalikhytten. Bj°rneheimen (= home of the bear) has a

name: Bj°rnehytten
description: Norwegian hunting hut built for Arktisk Nµringsdrift in September 1950 at Kap Broer Ruys, the SE point of Hold with Hope. So named because a bear had disturbed the depot of materials intended for the hut, and dragged a complete wall out to sea. The wall

name: Bj°rnepas
description: Pass between ╞beltoft Vig and Begtrup Vig, eastern Traill ╪, a migration route for bears. Named during Lauge Koch's 1936-38 expeditions by Hans Peter Schaub.

name: Bj°rneskµrene
description: Line of skerries NE of Gamma ╪. So named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen because they encountered many bears here, of which two were shot. (Bj÷rneskµrene, Bear Skerries, Bj°rne Skµrene, Bj°rneskµr).

name: Bj°rnes°
description: Small lake on the east side of Mesters Vig. Named by prospecting teams associated with Lauge Koch's 1948-49 expeditions, for an incident involving a bear (Fig. 33).

name: Bj°rnes°
description: Lake SE of Lauge Koch's scientific station on northern Ella ╪. The name is said to have originated in the 1930s with Aage de Lemos, Lauge Koch's telegraphist at the station, and was given for an incident involving a bear. (Bear Lake).

name: Bj°rnes°
description: Lake in Pσskedalen, Ad. S. Jensen Land. The name first appeared on the map of the 1932 Gefion expedition (Jennov 1935), and was so named because on his first visit to the lake J.G. Jennov had seen bear tracks.

name: Bj°rnes°
description: Lake near Mesters Vig where samples were taken for radiocarbon age determinations (Cremer et al. 2008).

name: Bj°rnetoppen
description: Name used by the 1908-09 FLOREN expedition for a hill near their house at Kap Borlase Warren, SE Wollaston Forland, where they shot bears in October and December 1908. The name is used in the diary of the expedition published by Brandal (1930), although

name: Bj°rne°
description: Small island near the mouth of Geologfjord, so named by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst in as Bj÷rn÷n because a polar was shot here by Ivar Arwidsson, the expedition zoologist. (Bear Island, Bj°rn°n.)

name: Angelin Bjerg
description: Mountain 1900 m high on central Ymer ╪. The 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst named it after Nils Peter Angelin [1805-1876], a Swedish palaeontologist and stratigrapher noted especially for his work in Skσne, Sweden. Angelin ha

name: Anita ╪
description: Small island in Vega Sund. The Danish S°kortarkivet proposed the name in 1956-57 when surveying the channel through Vega Sund as an alternative approach for ships on their way to Nyhavn. It was named after the ANITA DAN, a 3225-ton ice-strengthened polar

name: Ankerbjerg
description: Mountain on the north side of Moskusoksefjord. It was named by Helge Backlund during Lauge Koch's 1929 expedition in the form Mt. Ankar for the anchorage on its south side. Farther east Moskusoksefjord becomes very shallow and unnavigable. (Kap Anker, An

name: Ankerbjergsdalen
description: Valley in southern Hudson Land, in which Ankerbjergselv flows, and which reaches the coast east of Ankerbjerg. The name was approved at the suggestion of Peter Friend following his 1968-70 expeditions, although it had also been used occasionally earlier

name: Ankerbjergselv
description: River draining into Moskusoksefjord east of Ankerbjerg, named by Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions in the form Anker River.

name: Ankerbukta
description: Bay SE of Ankerbjerg in Moskusoksefjord, an anchorage used by NSIU in 1929, and probably identical with Ankerplads. (Ankerhamna, Ankerplassen).

name: Ankerlien
description: Norwegian hunting hut built in September 1929 by Arktisk Nµringsdrift near Ankerbjerg, about 6 km from the head of Moskusoksefjord. It is also known as Braasted.

name: Ankerplads
description: Name used by Gelting (1934) during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen for the anchorage SE of Ankerbjerg in Moskusoksefjord. Probably identical with Ankerbukta.

name: Ankerpladsen
description: Anchorage on the north side of inner M°rkefjord, Daniel Bruun Land, named by Eigil Knuth's 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition which anchored the expedition motorboat here.

name: Ankervig
description: Small bay at the mouth of Hj°rnedal, on the north coast of Gσseland. So named by the 1963 Geodµtisk Institut expedition because it is possible to anchor small boats here.

name: Anna Bistrup Fjelde
description: Mountain on southern Hovgaard ╪, west of Kap Anna Bistrup. Named by John Haller during Lauge Koch's 1956-58 expeditions. See also Kap Anna Bistrup.

name: Anna Sten Gletscher
description: Name used for the present Tvegegletscher, west of Th. Thomsen Land. The name only appears on the 1932 1:1 million scale Geodµtisk Institut map prepared by Lauge Koch during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen (Fig. 15). It commemorates a Russian-American fil

name: Annekss°en
description: Elongate NW-SE-trending lake north of Sµls°en. It was discovered by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen and named as Annekss÷en or Annekss°. Like nearby Sµls°en it appears at one time to have been a fjord. (Anneks S°, Annexs°, Anneks-S°en.)

name: Annielva

name: Ansgar
description: One of the summits of Korsbjerg, 1011 m high, south of Mestersvig airfield. It was named by prospecting teams associated with Lauge Koch's 1948-49 expeditions, probably after Ansgar [801-865], archbishop of Hamburg. A missionary to Denmark, he built the

name: Aansketinde
description: Peak 2460 m high on the southern spiky ridge of Dansketinden. It was climbed and so named by the 1996 Scottish Mountaineering Club expedition.

name: Antarctic Dal
description: Name used by Bearth (1959) for the present Kolledalen, which drains eastwards to Antarctic Havn, northern Scoresby Land.

name: Bontekoe ╪
description: Large island in Foster Bugt. The name occurs on charts published in Paris by F.E. Foster in 1783 and 1788, and that published in 1818 to accompany Hidde Dirks Kats æDagboek eener Reize i de jaren 1777 en 1778'. The name was adopted by William Scoresby Jr

name: Devon Hills
