name: Devondal
description: Valley on south Wegener Halv°, draining into Nathorst Fjord. So named by Katharina Perch-Nielsen during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions because the southernmost outcrops of Devonian rocks in East Greenland are found here.

name: Devonpas
description: Pass in Ole R°mer Land leading eastwards to Vibeke Gletscher. Named by John Haller during Lauge Koch's 1956-58 expedition, after occurrences of Devonian rocks.

name: Diadem
description: Name used by Hans Gsellman's 1957 expedition for a three-peaked mountain about 2400 m high east of Granta Brµ, Stauning Alper, because of the manner in which the peaks caught the sun. According to Bennet (1972) the west peak was subsequently climbed in 1

name: Diamond Peak
description: Peak about 2150 m high on the south side of Roslin Gletscher, south Stauning Alper. Climbed by the 1982 Sheffield University expedition.

name: Diannsketinden
description: Peak about 2532 m high on the spiky ridge south of Dansketinden, Stauning Alper. So named by the 1996 Scottish Mountaineering Club expedition, although after their return they discovered it had been climbed two months earlier by the 1996 Norwegian Stauni

name: Dickens Bjerg
description: Prominent mountain in SW Dronning Louise Land. One of the names given by the British North Greenland expedition 1952-54 for novelists (Fig. 21), it commemorates Charles Dickens [1812-1870], generally regarded as the greatest English novelist. It was clim

name: Dickson Fjord
description: Fjord between Suess Land and Gletscherland (Fig. 52). Named by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst for Robert Dickson [1843-1923] who had made contributions to the expedition's finances. (Dicksons Fjord.)

name: Didrik Pining Bjerge
description: Mountain range up to 966 m high west of Fleming Fjord. The name was one of a group of names given by the Place Name Committee in 1939 to replace proposals by Hans Stauber. It was given for Didrik Pining, an admiral and administrator in Iceland whom Chris

name: Aucellabjerg
description: Mountain 985 m high in western Wollaston Forland, named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Hans Frebold for finds of species of Aucella, a fossil lamellibranch.

name: Aucellabjerget
description: Mountain on southern Store Koldewey. So named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen for the presence of conglomerate beds containing the fossil Aucella. It was occasionally called Muslingebjerget (J. L°ve, personal communication 2009). (Aucella Mt.)

name: Aucellaelv
description: River in SW Jameson Land. Named by the 1898-1900 Carlsbergfondets Expedition, the name appeared first in the form Aucella Elv in a report by Nordenskj÷ld (1907). It was given for the fossil finds. (Aucella River, Aucellariver.)

name: Aucellapasset
description: Pass between Palnatoke Bjerg and Aucellabjerg in Wollaston Forland, so named by Lauge Koch's 1926-27 expeditions for the common fossil Aucella. (Aucellapas.)

name: Aucellaskrσningerne
description: SW slope of Aucellabjerg. The name has been used as a reference locality by scientists at Zackenberg Forskningsstation.

name: Augsburger Spids
description: Mountain on the north side of uppermost Duart Gletscher, central Stauning Alper. First climbed by the 1966 Deutsche Gr÷nland-Expedition in die Staunings-Alpen led by Karl M. Herligkoffer on 17 August, and named after the Bavarian city of Augsburg. (Augsb

name: Augustadalshytten
description: Name often used for the Norwegian hunting hut built at the mouth of Dronning Augustadalen in July 1928 by the Hird expedition. It was originally known as Bj°rnebu, and has also been called Stordalen. (Augusta Dal Hytten, Dronning Augusta Dal Hytten.)

name: Devon Canyon
description: Name used by Poulsen (1937) for a narrow ravine 1 km south of Gunvor Bjerg, Strindberg Land. It was given for the rocks of Devonian age.

name: Auspiciedalen
description: Small valley on south Clavering ╪, east of Eskimonµs. The name originated from the wintering party at Eskimonµs during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, and refers to an area thought to be promising (auspicious) for mineral prospecting. O. Eklund and Davi

name: Bj°rne°er
description: Group of islands off NE Milne Land. So named by the 1891-92 Den ╪stgr°nlandske expedition led by Carl Ryder as the Bj°rne ╪er, because a bear was shot during exploration of the islands on 4 September 1891. The main islands are sometimes numbered I to XI

name: Bj°rnnesstua
description: Norwegian hut SE of the Giesecke Bjerge built in July 1932 by the W. Holmboe salmon fishing expedition. It has also been known as Holmboehytten and Giskehuset.

name: Bj°rnselv
description: Minor stream on eastern Clavering ╪, between Storstr°mmen and Gr°nnedal, so called by Danish hunters. The name first appeared on a sketch map in Gustav Thostrup's 1921 logbook (M°ller 1939). The name has apparently also been used for the present Hennings

name: East Icecap
description: Name used in a report of the 1969 Watkins Bjerge expedition for the present Geikie Plateau, an ice-covered plateau south of Scoresby Sund.

name: East Pond
description: Name used by the 1974 Joint biological expedition for a small lake near Langdyssen, east of Mestersvig airfield.

name: Easter Glacier
description: Name used in reports of the 1962 Oxford University expedition for the present ╪stre Gletscher in the north Werner Bjerge. The name appears to have arisen from a mis-translation of æ°stre' as æEaster' (°stre = eastern).

description: Name used by Gunnar SΣve-S÷derbergh during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, together with Western Circus Valley, for two small cirque-shaped valleys on the north slopes of Celsius Bjerg, Ymer ╪ (SΣve-S÷derbergh 1932).

name: Ebbe Gletscher
description: Glacier in south Dronning Louise Land flowing NE into Budolfi Isstr°m (Fig. 21). Named by the 1952-54 British North Greenland expedition after the Danish journalist and diplomat Ebbe Munck [1905-74]. Munck began his close association with Greenland as a

name: Ebensbjerge

name: Eckhorn
description: Mountain about 2230 m high in the northern Stauning Alper. Named and first climbed by Hans Gsellman's 1957 expedition (eck = corner). Fantin (1969) and Bennet (1972) give different locations for this peak. Fantin locates it close to Diadem and Bavariaspi

name: Eckturm

name: Edam Kulle
description: Highland area in east Germania Land. The Land van Edam was reported as discovered at about this latitude by a Dutch whaler in 1655, and the name is found on several early Dutch charts (e.g. Joannes van Keulen's atlas printed in 1785). The name was adopte

name: Edderfugldal
description: Valley north of Fleming Fjord, about 4 km west of Kap Biot. Named during Lauge Koch's 1958 expedition by K. Grasmⁿck and Rudolf Trⁿmpy, for the large numbers of eider ducks observed here.

name: Edinbrae
description: Name used by Bennet (1972) for a glacier draining from the east flank of the Stauning Alper northwards into Skeldal.

name: Edinburgh
description: Mountain 2010 m high north of Jupiter Gletscher, south Stauning Alper. First climbed by James Clarkson's 1961 expedition, and named after Edinburgh Castle, Scotland.

name: Edla Skµr
description: Two skerries, one of them 8 m high, about 1400 m due east of the SE point of Jackson ╪. They are said to have been found by L.M. Coulet-Svendsen, first mate on the GUSTAV HOLM in 1930. Girl's name. The name is used in Den Gr°nlandske Lods (1968).

name: Edvard Bay Dal
description: Major NE-SW-trending valley between Martin Karlsen Bugt and Eielson Gletscher. Named during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions after Edvard Bay, the geologist of the 1891-92 Den ╪stgr°nlandske expedition led by Carl Ryder. See also Bay Fjelde. (Ed

name: Edward Bailey Gletscher
description: Glacier more than 40 km long in eastern Renland. Named during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions by Brian Chadwick, after Sir Edward Bailey [1881-1965], a British geologist noted especially for his work on the Caledonian rocks of Scotland. The roc

name: Bopladsdalen

name: Bordbjerget
description: Mountain on NE Traill ╪, a flat-topped summit in the Rold Bjerge. So named by Desmond Donovan during Lauge Koch's 1949-50 expeditions (bord = table).

name: Bordet
description: Ice-covered area at the margin of the Inland Ice NW of Hobbs Land. This name was given by the Place Name Committee replacing a suggestion by Hans R. Katz. The area is flat and notable for a lack of crevasses (bordet = the table).

name: Boreal Zenith
description: Impressive summit with fine views on the south side of Grejsdalen, AndrΘe Land. Climbed by the 2007 Army Boreal Zenith expedition.

name: Borestok
description: Ridge in northern Scoresby Land between Jµgerdal and Segldal. So named by Hans Kapp during Lauge Koch's 1957-58 expeditions because of the three stake-like humps on the ridge eroded in basalt (bore = drill, stok = stick, stake).

name: Bores°
description: Lake in the Zackenberg area named in 1998 by Kisten S. Christoffersen because Bent Fredskild took cores for paleolimnological studies here. Information from Lars Holst Hansen, 2011. Samples were also used for radiocarbon age determinations (Cremer et al.

name: Borg
description: Wintering station of the 1912-13 Den danske Ekspedition til Dronning Louises Land in the centre of Bredebrµ, to which it had been transported by pony and boat from Danmarkshavn. The retreat of Bredebrµ means the original location is now in the fjord east

name: Borganes
description: Primitive Norwegian hunting hut at Kap Borlase Warren, Wollaston Forland, originally built in 1908 by the 1908-09 FLOREN expedition on the ruins of an Inuit house. The old hut and the cape have been known by a variety of names: Bj°rn-heimen, Gammen, Sver

name: Borgbjerg Gletscher
description: Major glacier on the north side of central Nordvestfjord. One of the names used on the 1932 edition of the Geodetic Institute 1:1 million scale map, it derives from Lauge Koch's aerial observations during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen. Frederik Borgbje

name: Borgbjergkamm
description: Ridge up to 2400 m high leading northwards to Borgbjergtinde, in the NE part of the Borgbjerg Gletscher region, southern Stauning Alper. Probably named by the 1977 SchwΣbische Stauning Alper expedition.

name: Borgbjergtinde
description: Peak 2546 m high in the NE part of the Borgbjerg Gletscher region, southern Stauning Alper. Probably first climbed and named by the 1977 SchwΣbische Stauning Alper expedition.

name: Borgen
description: Mountain on Volquaart Boon Kyst flanked by ╪stre Borggletscher and Vestre Borggletscher. Named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Laurits Bruhn for its castle-like appearance.

name: Borgen
description: Feature in NW Hold with Hope, named by Eigil Nielsen during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen. The position is said to be uncertain because it is not found on his map, but from the description in the text (Nielsen 1935 p. 49), it is most probably the ridge

name: Borgfjorden
description: Fjord between Daniel Bruun Land and Lindhard ╪, so named by the 1912-13 Den danske Ekspedition til Dronning Louises Land because it lay east of the wintering station Borg. (Borg Fjorden, Borg-Fjord, Castle Fjord, Borgarfjor≡ur.)

name: Borggletscher
description: Glacier in Suess Land between ╪stre Vikingeborg and Vestre Vikingeborg. Named by John Haller during Lauge Koch's 1952-53 expeditions.

name: Borgj°kelen
description: Glacier in central Dronning Louise Land, so named by the 1912-13 Den danske Ekspedition til Dronning Louises Land as Borgj°klen or Borgj÷klen, because it was situated west of the wintering station Borg. The definitive æen' ending was part of the approved

name: Borgvig
description: Bay at the front of Vestre Borggletscher, west of Borgen, Volquaart Boon Kyst. Named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Laurits Bruhn.

name: Borg°en
description: Largest island in the western part of the Broch ╪er group, east of Ymer ╪. The name seems to appear first on an NSIU map (NSIU 1932a) in the form Borg÷ya, and was presumably named for a castle-like appearance.

name: Borlase Warren Hytten
description: Danish hut built by Sirius in the summer of 1956 at Kap Borlase Warren, Wollaston Forland (P.S. Mikkelsen 1994).

name: Eros
description: Mountain about 2018 m high at the head of Mercurius Gletscher and Oxford Gletscher, south Stauning Alper. It was first climbed by the 1975-76 Scottish Scoresby Land expeditions, and named after the minor planet Eros which has a highly eliptical orbit; th

name: Avalanche Valley
description: Name used by the 1932-34 Helge Ingstad expedition for a valley visible from Antarctic Havn, eastern Scoresby Land (Ingstad 1937). Exact location uncertain.

name: Avantpost
description: Mountain ridge on eastern Clavering ╪. The name is found on Lacmann's (1937) maps.

name: Aztekerborgen
description: Mountain in the northern Stauning Alper, south of the front of Skjoldungebrµ. Named by John Haller during Lauge Koch's 1954 expedition, for a resemblance to an Aztec pyramid. It was first climbed by a Norwegian party in 1951.

name: Aagenoesfjellet
description: Mountain on north Clavering ╪, so named on Lacmann's (1937) topographic maps.

name: Bacchus Gletscher
description: Glacier in the NE part of the Borgbjerg Gletscher region, southern Stauning Alper, north of Bacchustinde. Probably named by the 1977 SchwΣbische Stauning Alper expedition.

name: Bacchustinde
description: Peak 2397 m high in the NE part of the Borgbjerg Gletscher region, southern Stauning Alper. Probably first climbed and named by the 1977 SchwΣbische Stauning Alper expedition.

name: Bach Dal
description: Valley in central Dronning Louise Land draining SW from Ad Astra Iskappe to join Beethoven Dal (Fig. 21). One of the names given by the 1952-54 British North Greenland expedition for German composers, it commemorates Johan Sebastian Bach [1685-1750], not

name: Backlund Bjerg
description: Mountain c. 1600 m high on the north side of innermost Nordvestfjord. Named by Eduard Wenk after Helge G÷trik Backlund [1878-1958], a Swedish geologist especially noted for studies of rapakivi granites. He was professor of geology at Uppsala 1924-43. Bac

name: Backlund Ridge
description: Mountain ridge on northern Geographical Society ╪, east of Rudbeck Bjerg. The name was used by Gunnar SΣve-S÷derbergh (1933, Plate 3) during his work on the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, and commemorates Helge G. Backlund. See also Backlund Bjerg. (Backlu

name: Badger
description: Summit 2044 m high on the ice cap between Catalinadal and Edward Bailey Gletscher, Renland. Climbed and named by the 2007 West Lancashire Mountaineering Group Expedition.

name: Badlanddal
description: Broad N-S-trending valley between Loch Fyne and Mackenzie Bugt. So named by Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions in the form Badland Valley, because of the characteristic erosion forms developed in the glacial sediments on the valley floor. (Badland Tal.)

name: Baesdalen
description: Valley on SE Clavering ╪, between Rundetσrn and Brinkley Bjerg, in which Moskusokseelv flows. The name originated from the wintering party at Eskimonµs during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, and was first used in the form Basdalen (baes = bas = lead dog

name: Bagatellerne
description: Group of small islands off SE Hovgaard ╪. So named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen, which left a depot here in October 1907. Named for their small size (bagatel = trifle).

name: Broer Ruys Nord
description: Danish hunting hut at the mouth of Glommen, about 4 km NE of Kap Broer Ruys, built by Nanok in September 1945. It has often been known as Domkirken. It is close to, and slightly south of the Norwegian hut known as Skandalen or Bukta.

name: Broer Ruys Syd
description: Danish hunting hut on the south coast of Hold with Hope, SW of Kap Broer Ruys. It was built by Nanok in 1945.

name: Brogetdalen
description: Large valley in Strindberg Land draining east to Nordfjord. The name was first used by Teichert (1933) during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, and is a translation of his original Buntes Tal (= painted valley) given for the extravagant colours of the roc

name: Brorson Halv°
description: Northern peninsula of Wollaston Forland. The name appears to have been given by the Place Name Committee in 1939, possibly after Hans Adolf Brorson [1694-1764], a Danish bishop and noted hymn writer. Maync (1947) used the form Brorsons Halbinsel.

name: Brorson Pynt
description: South cape of Mσtten, an island south of Kap Bismarck. Named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen as Brorsons Pynt, perhaps for H.A. Brorson. See also Brorson Halv°.

name: Brown-Stua
description: Norwegian hunting hut built by the M°re expedition in Fleming Fjord in August 1931, about 5 km SW of Kap Brown. It is also known as Holstad. (Kap Brown Hytten, Brownhuset.)

name: Broxdalen
description: Valley on western Geographical Society ╪. So named on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937) after the Norwegian telegraphist Leif Brox [b. 1905], who was stationed at Myggbukta from 1928 to 1930.

name: Bruce Fjord
description: Fjord on the north side of Manby Halv°, northern Blosseville Kyst. Named by Malcolm Slesser's 1969 expedition for William Speirs Bruce [1867-1921], a polar explorer and oceanographer, who took part in expeditions to the Antarctic in 1902-04 and Spitsberg

name: Bruddal
description: Valley in south Liverpool Land, so named by Alfred Rosenkrantz during Lauge Koch's 1926-27 expeditions because the valley follows a fault zone (= brud). (Fault Valley.)

name: Edward Ensom Plateau
description: Small plateau on the west side of Hurry Inlet, north of Moskusoksekl°ft. Named by Hermann Aldinger during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen (Aldinger 1935).

name: Egede Land
description: Some atlases place this name in the region south of Scoresby Sund (e.g. Bartholomew 1920). Hans Egede [1686-1758], æGreenland's apostle', travelled to West Greenland in 1721 in search of the remnants of the lost Viking settlers, and founded a mission to

name: Ehrenberg Fjeld
description: Mountain 1239 m high in east Payer Land, west of Kap Ehrenberg. The name came into general use among Danish and Norwegian hunters in the 1930s, and appears to have first been used on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937) in the form Ehrenbergfjellet.

name: Eidechselspitze
description: Snow summit about 2500 m high west of Trekantgletscher, eastern Nathorst Land, climbed and so named by Wolfgang Weinzierl's 1970 expedition. The name translates as æLizard Peak'.

name: Eielson Gletscher
description: Glacier at the head of Rypefjord. This is one of the new names on the 1932 edition of the Geodµtisk Institut 1:1 million scale map, drawn on the basis of Lauge Koch's aerial observations during the first two summers of the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen. Th

name: Charcot Havn
description: Bay on the east coast of Milne Land. The name was first used in reports of the work of the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen in the form Charcots Harbour (Thorson 1934), and commemorates Jean-Baptiste Charcot, whose expeditions had carried out geological work

name: Charcot Land
description: Land area at the head of Nordvestfjord between Daugaard-Jensen Gletscher and F. Graae Gletscher. The name first appears on the 1932 1:1 million scale Geodµtisk Institut map prepared on the basis of aerial observations by Lauge Koch during the 1931-34 Tre

name: Charpentier Gletscher
description: Glacier in southern Goodenough Land draining into Agassiz Dal. Named during the 1937 Louise A. Boyd Arctic expedition as Charpentier Glacier after Johann von Charpentier [1786-1855], a Swiss naturalist whose work on glaciers in 1830-40 was closely relate

name: Chatham Elv
description: River draining the SE part of Stormlandet. Named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by David Malmquist for a friend, Gottfrid Nordland, usually known as æChatham', who subseqently became headmaster and dean in GΣllivaare, Sweden.

name: Chattonbugt
description: Bay on east Milne Land, the present Charcot Havn. The name was used in the report by Parat & Drach (1934), who visited the region during J.-B. Charcot's 1933 expedition. It was named after A. Chatton, captain of the expedition ship POURQUOI PAS? in 1932

name: Chattonkl°ft
description: Gulley SW of Charcot Havn on east Milne Land, equivalent to the small valley termed Kosmocerasdal by Callomon & Birkelund (1980). The name was used by Parat & Drach (1934). See also Chattonbugt.

name: Chokoladebjerg
description: Mountain 1010 m high on western Ymer ╪, north of Blomsterbugten (Fig. 74). The name was given by Arthur B. Cleaves and Ernest F. Fox in the course of geological work during John K. Howard's 1933 expedition, originally in the form Big Chocolate Mountain.

name: Chopin Dal
description: Valley trending E-W in central Dronning Louise Land between Himmerland Hede and Beethoven Dal (Fig. 21). One of the names given by the 1952-54 British North Greenland expedition after composers, it commemorates FrΘdΘrik Franτois Chopin [1810-49], a Polis

name: Christian IV Gletscher
description: Major glacier draining from Geikie Plateau southwards to the Blosseville Kyst. The glacier is said to have been partly mapped by Gino Watkins, but its extent was first realised during flights by Lauge Koch in 1933 during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen.

name: Christians Skµr
description: Skerry east of Bµlgen, Nanok ╪, in Dove Bugt. Discovered and so named during the 1932 Gefion expedition after one of the Danish hunters, Christian Jensen, who prevented the ship from running into it (Jennov 1935). The name is used in Den Gr°nlandske Lods

name: Christianshavn
description: Danish hunting station built in 1921 at Kap Mary, eastern Clavering ╪, by 1919-24 A/S ╪stgr°nlandske Fangstkompagni, beside a Norwegian hunting hut originally built in 1909 (see Maryhuset). The station may have been named after Christian Thielst [1877-19

name: Christinabjerg
description: Peak about 2350 m high on the north side of Kirkebrae, NE of Sefstr÷m Gletscher, Stauning Alper. Climbed and named by the 1968 Scottish expedition.

name: Erratic Bloc Bay
description: Name used by Bⁿtler (1954) for a small bay at Kap Franklin, Gauss Halv°, where erratic boulders were found. This name is only used on Bⁿtler's maps, and in the text of his report is replaced by Findlingsbucht.

name: Erzberg
description: Name commonly found in Swedish and German publications (erz = ore) describing the molybdenum deposit at Malmbjerg, Werner Bjerge (e.g. Sj÷gren 1962). See also Malmbjerg.

name: Escher von der Linth Gletscher
description: Name occasionally used for the present Cirkusgletscher which drains from the eastern Werner Bjerge to Blomsterdal. The name is found in the description by Brooks et al. (1982) of samples collected by Peter Bearth in 1953-54. See also Arnold Escher Land.

name: Eskdal
description: Valley on SW Traill ╪ draining south into Karupelv. Named by Geoffrey Halliday following his botanical work during the 1961-1962 Leicester University East Greenland expeditions and the 1971 Northern Universities East Greenland expedition, probably after

name: Eskimo Land
description: Name used by Dahl (1925) for the peninsula west of Germaniahavn, Sabine ╪, where the observatory of the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt was built in 1869-70. It was given for the presence of Inuit (Eskimo) ruins.

name: Eskimobugt
description: Bay on the north side of inner Nordvestfjord, southern Nathorst Land, on the shore of which are well-preserved Inuit ruins. The site has been known since the 1930s when visited by Eduard Wenk, but was named by the 1963 Geodµtisk Institut (Geodetic Instit

name: Eskimohamna
description: Name used on the NSIU (1932a) map for ╪sthavn in south Clavering ╪, beside Eskimonµs scientific station.

name: Eskimonµs
description: Prominent peninsula on south Clavering ╪, named during 1929-30 Lauge Koch's geological expeditions as Eskimonµsset, for the Inuit (Eskimo) settlement of four houses here, of which two were excavated (Glob 1946). The same name is now officially used for t

name: Eskimonµs
description: Peninsula on the NE coast of Holm Land. So named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen as Eskimonµsset, because ruins of a large Inuit settlement were found here in March 1907. The same name is used for the Sirius hut at the cape slightly farther north. (

name: Eskimovig
description: Small bay on the south side of Clavering ╪, named by the 1926 Cambridge East Greenland expedition as Eskimo Bay because of the many Inuit (Eskimo) ruins. A settlement of 25 winter houses occurs here, of which 18 have been excavated (Glob 1946). On Norweg

name: Essemmceebrae
description: Minor glacier on the south side of Sefstr÷m Gletscher, Stauning Alper. Explored by the 1998 Scottish Mountaineering Club (SMC) Greenland expedition, and so named after the club (SMC).

name: Etagefjµldet
description: This name has been used by Danish hunters of 1919-24 A/S ╪stgr°nlandske Fangstkompagni for a mountain in south Wollaston Forland, probably the present Herschell Bjerg. It probably derives from the stratified appearance of the basalt rock formations (etag

name: Etzelbreen
description: Glacier draining NW in north Clavering ╪. So named on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937) after Etzel (Attila), King of the Huns, the second husband of Kriemhild in the German epic poem from c. 1200, the Nibelungenlied.

name: Eugen-Heinz Tinde
description: Peak 2415 m high in the NE part of the Borgbjerg Gletscher region, southern Stauning Alper. Probably first climbed and named by the 1977 SchwΣbische Stauning Alper expedition.

name: Eva ╪
description: Small island off NE Lambert Land. The name was used by the 1996 Mylius-Erichsen's Mindeekspedition.

name: Evald Gletscher
description: Glacier in NE S°ndermarken, on the south side of C.F. Mourier Fjord. So named by David Malmquist during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen after Evald Hellman, an old friend and class-mate, later chemist and assistant at the Chemical Institute in Uppsala, S

name: Evans Bjerg
description: Mountain on the SW coast of Gauss Halv°. Named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Gunnar SΣve-S÷derbergh as Mt. Evans, after John William Evans [1857-1930], a widely travelled British geologist, who was an authority on the Devonian deposits of Gre

name: Eventyrfjelde
description: Nunatak with summits reaching 2000 m south of A.B. Drachman Gletscher (Fig. 21), south Dronning Louise Land. The name was given by the 1952-54 British North Greenland expedition, and arose apparently because this outlying area was hardly investigated by

name: D'Aunay Bugt
description: Deep bay or fjord south of Kap Ryder on the Blosseville Kyst. The name was adopted by the 1898-1900 Carlsbergfondets Expedition from a map made by Jules de Blosseville in 1833, where it appears as Baie d'Aunay. Raoul d'Aunay was second in command of the

name: Brudelv
description: River in south Liverpool Land draining Bruddal. Named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Laurits Bruhn.

name: Brumse Gletscher
description: Glacier on SE Traill ╪, south of Mountnorris Fjord. Named during Lauge Koch's 1936-38 expeditions by Hans Peter Schaub for the lead dog in his sledge team. (Brumsegletscher, Brumses Gletscher.)

name: Brun Bjerg
description: Mountain in central Hudson Land, north of Ritoms°. Named by Heinrich Bⁿtler during Lauge Koch's 1936-38 expeditions for Albert Brun, a naturalist who visited Spitsbergen in the early 1900s. (Brunberg, Bruns Bjerg.)

name: Brune Nunatakker
description: Nunatak group west of Graben Land. So named by Peter Homewood during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions because of their characteristic brown (= brune) colour.

name: Brunedal
description: Valley on the west side of R°defjord. Named during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions by Kai S°rensen, for the dominant brown-weathering colour of the rocks.

name: Brⁿnhildbreen
description: Small glacier on north Clavering ╪. Used on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937), the name commemorates Brunhild (Brunhilde), the Queen of outstanding strength and beauty who married Gunther in the the German epic poem from c. 1200, the Nibelungenlied. Brunhi

name: Brⁿnhorn
description: Peak 2066 m high on the south side of Grejsdalen, AndrΘe Land. Climbed by the 2007 Army Boreal Zenith expedition.

name: Brunkn°s
description: Mountain in C.H. Ostenfeld Land. The name originated from the wintering party at Kulhus during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, and was given for the abundant occurrence of rusty brown rocks.

name: Brygger Elven
description: Name used by Danish hunters in the 1930s for a minor river west of Nanok hunting station, Hochstetter Forland (Nyholm-Poulsen 1985).

name: Bryozoen-Ryg
description: Ridge in NE Giesecke Bjerge where Bendaelv begins. The name was used by Maync (1942), and was given for finds of fossil bryozoa.

name: Brystet
description: Conical hill 412 m high at the SE end of Sµls°en, so named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen because of its shape. (The Breast.)

name: Brystvµrnene
description: Mountain ridge about 2000 m high in northern Goodenough Land, east of Nordenski÷ld Gletscher. It was named by J.M. Wordie's 1929 Cambridge expedition as Battlements for its appearance.

name: Brµdal
description: Valley in SW Dronning Margrethe II Land draining into Bredefjord. The name originated from the wintering party at Kulhus during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, and was given for the many glaciers which drain into the valley (brµ = glacier).

name: Brµdalhytten
description: Norwegian hunting hut east of the mouth of Brµdal, on the north side of Bredefjord, built in August 1933 by John Giµver's expedition. It was also known as Bredruphytten and Solstrand, but had completely disappeared by 1988.

name: Brµfjorden
description: Fjord on the north side of Rechnitzer Land. The name was reported as used by Nanok hunters, and appears first on a map in Jennov (1939). It was named for the two picturesque glaciers on the south side of the fjord. (Brµfjord.)

name: Brµfjordhytten
description: Danish hunting hut on the north side of the mouth of Brµfjorden, built by Nanok in May 1934. Now a ruin. It has occasionally been referred to as Jarnershytte.

name: Firmannsdalen
description: Name given in 1934 to Fladedal, central Ymer ╪, to record a successful hunting trip in the valley by four Norwegian hunters (firmann = four men). The name has also been used for the Norwegian hut built in 1934 at the mouth of the valley (see Namdalsstua)

name: Firndalen
description: N-S-trending valley crossing Holm Land. So named by Eigil Nielsen during the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition because of the large glaciers (= firn) on both sides.

name: First Point of Aries
description: Peak 1944 m high on the south side of Mercurius Gletscher, south Stauning Alper. First climbed and so named by James Clarkson's 1961 expedition. The æFirst Point of Aries' is the intersection of the celestial equator and the apparent annual pathway of th

name: Fiskeelv
description: Small river on SE Clavering ╪, named by Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions in the form Fish River because of finds of fossil fish.

name: Fiskeplateau
description: Minor plateau between River 7 and River 8, on the north slope of Frebold Bjerg, Home Forland. So named by Eigil Nielsen during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen for finds of fossil fish. (Fiskeplateauet.)

name: Fiskergrav
description: Locality in SW Jameson Land between Schuchert Flod and Gurreholm Dal where Stemmerik et al. (2001) located the Permian-Triassic boundary on the basis of palynological data.

name: Fiskerhytten
description: Norwegian hut built for fishing by Hermann Andresen's expedition about 500 m west of Zackenberg hunting station. It is also known as Laksehytten.

name: Fiskerhytten
description: Danish hunting hut at the head of Syttendemajfjorden, Ad. S. Jensen Land, built by Nanok in August 1951.

name: Fjellborg-hytten
description: Norwegian hut built in October 1950 by Arktisk Nµringsdrift on the SW side of Langelv, 18 km from the east coast of Hochstetter Forland. It replaced Langelv-hytten.

name: Fjerma
description: River on Ymer ╪ draining north into DusΘn Fjord. So named on an NSIU map (1932a).

name: Fjordblick Schulter
description: Snow dome with a view of Nordvestfjord in the NE part of the Borgbjerg Gletscher region, southern Stauning Alper. Probably first climbed and named by the 1977 SchwΣbische Stauning Alper expedition.

name: Churchill Pas
description: Pass between the head of Storgletscher and Kirkbrae, a side glacier to Sefstr÷m Gletscher. Named by the 1963 Cambridge University expedition after Churchill College, Cambridge, founded in 1960 and named after Sir Winston Churchill. See also Winston Bjerg

name: Cicero
description: Mountain 2400 m high on the east side of Cavendish Gletscher, northern Stauning Alper. Climbed on 26 July 1984 by Sandro Pucci's expedition, and named after the Roman orator and statesman Marcus Tullius Cicero [106-43 BC].

name: Cima Blonde
description: Peak on the NE side of Vertebrµ, on the north side of Gully Gletscher, Stauning Alper. Climbed on 29 July 1984 by Sandro Pucci's climbing expedition, and probably named for the light colour of the rocks.

name: Cima Caesar
description: Peak WNW of Dansketinden, north Stauning Alper. Climbed on 6 August 1984 by Sandro Pucci's climbing expedition, and named after the Roman general and statesman Gaius Julius Caesar [100-44 BC].

name: Cima di Granito
description: Name used by Guido Monzino's 1963 expedition for Glamis Borg, a 2200 m granite peak on the SW side of Bersµrkerbrµ. The expedition made the second ascent by a new route.

name: Cima Est
description: Peak about 2500 m high on the south side of Vikingebrµ, north Stauning Alper. First climbed by Guido Monzino's 1964 expedition, and probably named after the mountain of the same name in the Dolomites, one of the Tre Cime.

name: Cima Marco Aurelio
description: Peak on the north side of Gully Gletscher, north Stauning Alper. Climbed on 2 August 1984 by Sandro Pucci's climbing expedition, and named after the Roman emperor Marcus Aurelius [121-180 AD]. (M. Aurelio).

name: Agnete S°
description: Lake in NW Hochstetter Forland. The lake was visited by Norwegian hunters and Danish scientists in l933, and the name subsequently appeared as a reference locality in botanical reports of the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen. Girl's name. A Norwegian hut at t

name: Agnetehytten
description: Norwegian hunting hut built by John Giµver's expedition in the spring of 1933 at the south point of Agnete S°, NW Hochstetter Forland. (Agnete S° Hytten, Agnetes°en.)

name: Agnetenµs
description: Minor cape on the SE coast of Clavering ╪, just east of Basaltkap. The name appears on a sketch map in Gustav Thostrup's 1921 logbook (in M°ller 1939). Girl's name.

name: Agnetes°elven
description: River draining Agnete S°, northern Hochstetter Forland. Named by the Danish hunting company Nanok in 1939.

name: Agurkes°
description: Lake close to Danmarkshavn weather station. The name was reported by Hans Meltofte as in general use by the staff at the weather station in 1969-71, and derives from the shape of the lake (agurk = cucumber); it was later approved with other Meltoft sugge

name: Aiguille de Jardin
description: Mountain on the west side of Prinsessegletscher, south of Fures°. Named and first climbed by the 1968 ExpΘdition Franτaise au Groenland Nord-Est led by Claude Rey expedition. Origin of name uncertain.

name: Ailsa
description: Hill 196 m high in Hochstetter Forland. Named by Douglas Clavering in 1823 for its resemblance to the island Ailsa Craig in the Firth of Clyde. Scottish maps of the early 19th century used the short form æAilsa'. (Ailsa Bjerg, Mt. Ailsa, Ailsa Hill.)

name: Ailsa S°
description: Small lake west of Ailsa, Hochstetter Forland. The name was first used by the 1976 Swedish-Danish expedition which core-sampled the sediments in the lake (see also Bj÷rck et al. 1994).

name: Ailsahytten
description: Danish hunting hut on the east coast of Hochstetter Forland, east of Ailsa, built by Nanok in August 1933.

name: Aina Dal
description: Ravine on the SW coast of Gauss Halv°. So named by Gunnar SΣve-S÷derbergh during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, for Aina Stensi÷, wife of Erik A:son Stensi÷. See also Stensi÷ Bjerg.

name: Ainadalhytten
description: Name often used for the Norwegian hut built in October 1930 a few kilometres east of the mouth of Aina Dal, Gauss Halv°. It has also been known as Von Krogh or Krogh-hytta.

name: Ajorpoq
description: Mountain in eastern AndrΘe Land, NE of the mouth of Grejsdalen. So named by Erdhart FrΣnkl during Lauge Koch's 1948-50 expeditions because his Greenlandic assistant did not like it. The name translates as something æbad'. (Agiorpoq.)

name: Ajunngilaq
description: Nunatak 2284 m high in southern Hobbs Land. The name was used by the 1931 H°ygaard & Mehren expedition in the form Ajungilakfjellet, and was employed in a broader sense than the present to include the whole of the present Hobbs Land. The nunatak seemed i

name: Akileqitaa
description: Narrow cape or point in east Henry Land, on the northern Blosseville Kyst. The name was recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, and translates as æthat lying inbetween'. (AkileqitΓ, AqiliqitΓ.)

name: Daedalus
description: Mountain 2040 m high between Jupiter Gletscher and Mercurius Gletscher, southern Stauning Alper. Named and first climbed by James Clarkson's 1961 expedition. Daedalus was the mythical Greek architect said to have built the labyrinth for King Minos of Cre

name: Dagfinvika
description: Bay on south Geographical Society ╪, west of Kap McClintock. Used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937; Fig. 14), the name was given for the Norwegian painter and sculptor Dagfin Werenskiold [1892-1977] who participated in the 1931 NSIU expedition to the area

name: Dagmar Havn
description: Small bay on the NE coast of Store Koldewey, named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen as Dagmars Havn. Possibly named after the 640-ton corvette DAGMAR on which J.P. Koch, a member of the expedition, trained for entry into the navy in 1887. (Dagmar Har

name: Dagmar Havn Hytten

name: Dalheim

name: Damelv

name: Damesten

name: Antarctic Gletscher

name: Antarctic Havn
description: Large bay on the south side of Davy Sund, northern Scoresby Land, so named Antarctics Hamn by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst because the expedition ship ANTARCTIC anchored here on 20 August. See also Antarctic Bugt. Torn

name: Fjordhytten
description: Danish hunting hut on the south side of Lindeman Fjord, built by Nanok in August 1938. It is also known as Lindeman Fjord Hytten. It was burnt down in December 1978 (P.S. Mikkelsen 1994).

name: Flade Telt°
description: Island off SE Daniel Bruun Land near Port Arthur. So named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition because of the occurrence of 14 large Inuit tent rings (telt = tent).

name: Fladebugt

name: Fladebugt

name: Fladedal
description: Large, flat-bottomed valley in the central part of Ymer ╪, named by Silvio Eha during Lauge Koch's 1947-49 expeditions.

name: Fladegletscher
description: Glacier on eastern Traill ╪ on the north flank of Ellemandsbjerge. So named by Hans P. Schaub during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition led by Lauge Koch, because it is fairly flat.

name: Fladepynt
description: Low-lying point on the north side of Vestfjord. Named by the 1891-92 Den ╪stgr°nlandske expedition led by Carl Ryder as Flade Pynt, and traversed on the expedition's second sledge trip in May 1892.

name: Fladstrand

name: Flakkerhuk
description: Flat-lying coastal region in south Jameson Land, characterised by a moraine ridge system 1-2 km wide and 50-80 m high. Hermann Aldinger's original name for this feature was The Highway, and it was changed to Flakkerhuk by the Place Name Committee in 1935

name: Flata
description: Norwegian hunting hut in Badlanddal, NW of Myggbukta, built by Arktisk Nµringsdrift in 1931 (NSIU 1932c). It was named for the flat terrain. It has also been known as Giesecke.

name: Flatbreen
description: Name used by the 1931 H°ygaard & Mehren expedition for the present Hamberg Gletscher. They described it as a large, flat glacier about 10 km wide with a very low gradient.

name: Diener Bjerg
description: Mountain 800 m high in northern Hold with Hope, named by Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions in the form Mt. Diener. It commemorates Carl Diener [1862-1928], an Austrian stratigrapher and vertebrate palaeontologist noted for his studies of Triassic strata.

name: Diener River
description: Name used by Eigil Nielsen during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen for a river draining Diener Bjerg, northern Hold with Hope (Nielsen 1935).

name: Dijmphna Sund
description: Sound north of Hovgaard ╪ and south of Holm Land and Lynn ╪ (Fig. 24). Named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen for the steamer DIJMPHNA, which captained by Andreas Peter Hovgaard became trapped in the Kara Sea in 1882-83 during an attempt to assist tw

name: Dinosaur
description: Highest summit, about 1900 m high, of an impressive row of rock peaks SW of Ursus Minor Gletscher, south Stauning Alper. First climbed by James Clarkson's 1961 expedition, and named for the profile of the ridge that resembled a dinosaur's back.

name: Dinosaurus Elv
description: River on the west side of Hurry Inlet, near the mouth of which an alleged dinosaur footprint was found by Nikolaj Hartz in July 1900 during the 1898-1900 Carlsbergfondets Expedition. The name was used by Rosenkrantz (1934) who expressed doubt as to the i

name: Dinosaurus Kl÷ft
description: Name used by Rosenkrantz (1934) for the ravine west of Hurry Inlet in which Dinosaurus Elv flows, the present Quppaalakajik.

name: Fjord-Eidet
description: Name used for a Norwegian hunting hut said to have been built by the M°re expedition in 1931 in Nathorst Fjord. However, P.S. Mikkelsen (1994) records that the first hut built on this site was Siste-Huset, erected in 1932. (Fjordeidet.)

name: Akinnarteqitaa
description: Peninsula west of Steward ╪, northern Blosseville Kyst. One of the names recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, it derives from its position between two fjords, translating as æthat lying inbetween'. (AkφnartequtΓ.)

name: Akselborg
description: Mountain in the northern Stauning Alper, SW of Syltoppene. Named by Erdhart FrΣnkl during Lauge Koch's 1950-51 expeditions, originally in the form Gammel Axels Tinde (FrΣnkl 1953), after Axel Jensen, skipper of the POLYPEN in 1950-51. The name was altere

name: Akuliaruseq Janet Watson
description: Peninsula at the head of Brµfjorden, west of Dove Bugt. The name was proposed by Brian Chadwick, following his geological mapping in the region with the 1988-90 GGU northern East Greenland project. It commemorates Janet V. Watson [1924-85], an eminent Br

name: Alabama
description: Hut in NE Shannon built from the timbers of the ALABAMA (Fig. 26), a 50-ton sloop purchased and strengthened for the 1909-12 Alabama-ekspeditionen. The hut was used by 1919-24 A/S ╪stgr°nlandske Fangstkompagni, and from 1929 was taken over by Nanok. The

name: Alabama Havn

name: Alabama Nunatak
description: Nunatak west of Hertugen af OrlΘans Land, so named by the 1909-12 Alabama expedition for the expedition ship. See also Alabama.

name: Black Hills
description: Area of low hills between Noa S° and innermost DusΘn Fjord, Ymer ╪. The name was given for the colour of the rocks by Cleaves & Fox (1935) during geological work on the 1933 John K. Howard expedition.

name: Black Mountain
description: Mountain 1635 m high south of Korridoren, Milne Land, carved into black basaltic lava flows. Climbed by the 2004 West Lancashire Scouts expedition, after an approach by ski.

name: Blackwall
description: Mountain 1850 m high between Dunottar Gletscher and Harlech Gletscher, northern Stauning Alper. First climbed by the 1963 Imperial College expedition and named, like many of their other ascents, after a London locality. Blackwall is a district of Poplar

name: Blair
description: Mountain about 2200 m high on the SW side of Orion Gletscher, southern Stauning Alper. First climbed by James Clarkson's 1961 expedition, and named after Blair Castle, a Scottish mansion built by the Duke of Atholl in 1269, and rebuilt in 1869.

name: Blanke Bugt
description: Small bay on SW Milne Land, SW of Mudderbugt. Named during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions by Svend Funder for the calm water.

name: Blaskbjerg
description: Mountain in Gunnar Andersson Land, northern Ymer ╪. The name was used by Gunnar SΣve-S÷derbergh during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen in the form Mt. Blask, because he had expected to find fossils here, and when he didn't it was a æblask' (blask = splas

name: Blattspitze
description: Mountain 2000 m high in the Trekantgletscher area, west of Alpefjord. Climbed and so named by Wolfgang Weinzierl's 1970 expedition. Exact location a little uncertain. (Leaf Peak.)

name: Blika
description: River flowing into the south end of Loch Fyne. So named on the NSIU (1932a) map, and apparently derived from a Norwegian dialect word for a white stripe on a hillside.

name: Blindeskµr
description: Submerged rock 1.5 km off Kap Tyrrell, the NW point of Canning Land, which the ANTARCTIC sailed over on 24 August 1900. Named by the 1898-1900 Carlsbergfondets Expedition.

name: Blindtarmen
description: Short fjord in east Liverpool Land NW of Kap Jones. So named by Laurits Bruhn during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen (blindtarm = appendix).

name: Blindtarmen
description: Name sometimes used by Norwegian hunters for the narrow NW-SE-trending inner part of Tyrolerfjord, between Payer Land and A.P. Olsen Land.

name: Blindtarmen
description: Deep bay on the east side of inner Dijmphna Sund. The name is attributed to David Malmquist, and arose during Lauge Koch's geological expeditions. It was approved in 1958.

name: Bloch Nunatakker
description: Nunatak group on the north side of Lambert Land, named by the 1909-12 Alabama-ekspeditionen after Commander Bloch of the HEKLA, who had assisted the expedition. The Place Name Committee position for this group of nunataks, adjacent to the north point of

name: Blockfjellet
description: Mountain on central Clavering ╪, named on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937) after Walter Block [b. 1902], who assisted in the photogrammetric construction of the NSIU maps of East Greenland.

name: Antarctic Spids
description: Mountain 1483 m high in the Werner Bjerge, Scoresby Land, north of Antarctic Pas. It was named during Lauge Koch's 1953-54 expeditions by Peter Bearth and Eduard Wenk, and climbed by Bearth in 1953.

name: Antarctic Sund
description: Sound connecting central Kejser Franz Joseph Fjord with Kong Oscar Fjord. It was named by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst for the ship ANTARCTIC. See also Antarctic Bugt. (Antarctics Sund, Antarctic Strait, Antarcticsundet

name: Antezedenzpingo

name: Anthons ╪
description: Island east of Daniel Bruun Land, the present Midterholmen. So named on maps of the l932 Gefion expedition (Jennov 1935), after Anthon Jensen, ship's boy on the GEFION.

name: Antiklinalbugt
description: Bay on SW Ella ╪, dominated by an imposing anticlinal structure in the rocks of the cliff behind the bay (Fig. 28). Named by John Cowie during Lauge Koch's 1949-54 expeditions.

name: Antoinette
description: Name used by Wolf Maync during Lauge Koch's 1936-38 expeditions for a mountain 992 m high in Wollaston Forland, north of Hammeren (Maync 1949). Girl's name.

name: Anton Jensensundet
description: Sound between Nordenski÷ld ╪ and Kap Palander in Vega Sund. Used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937), and named after Anton Jensen [b. 1890]. As captain of the TERNINGEN, Jensen sailed a Norwegian hunting expedition to East Greenland in 1928.

name: Antonsens Hytte
description: Norwegian hunting hut in Store S°dal, A.P. Olsen Land, built by Gerhard Antonsen for Arktisk Nµringsdrift in the summer of 1937.

name: Apostlene

name: Appaliarseqarteq

name: Appenzeller Nunatak
description: Nunatak west of Gletscherland in the upper reaches of Hisinger Gletscher. So named by EugΦne Wegmann during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, for the inhabitants of the Swiss canton of Appenzeller, noted for their conservatism (behind the mountains and be

name: Apuseeq
description: Ice cap NE of Scoresbysund [Illoqqortormiut], south Liverpool Land. Recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, the name translates as æthe big snow-patch'. (ApusΩq.)

name: Apusiaajiip Nuaa
description: Cape NE of Kap Swainson, south Liverpool Land. Recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, the name means æApusiaajik's cape'. (ApusiΓjεp n√a, Apusiaajiip nuua.)

name: Apusiaajik

name: Apusiikajik

name: Apusinikajik

name: Aqartersiorpik

name: Disa Gletscher
description: Minor glacier on the north side of Nordenski÷ld Gletscher, named by J.M. Wordie's 1929 Cambridge expedition as Disa Glacier and traversed on the approach to Petermann Bjerg. The name was approved in 1951 at the suggestion of John Haller. (Disas Gletscher

name: Diskordansdal
description: Valley on Wegener Halv°. Named by Katharina Perch-Nielsen during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions for a well-exposed discordance between two geological formations.

name: Dislokationsdal
description: Valley on east Clavering ╪ marked by a tectonic dislocation or fault. The name was used by Maync (1949).

name: Diver Loch
description: Name used by the 1974 Joint biological expedition for a very small lake in the hills west of Nyhavn, near Mestersvig airfield, and named after the red-throated diver. In some descriptions, two lakes are distinguished, Diver North Loch and Diver South Loc

name: Djµvleborg
description: Mountain about 1800 m high in central AndrΘe Land, on the south side of Grejsdal. So named during Lauge Koch's 1949-51 expeditions by John Haller, because the mountain can be likened to a castle (= borg), and is sited at the entrance to Djµvlekl°ft.

name: Djµvlekl°ften

name: Djµvlekl°fthytten

name: Djµvlespalterne
description: Area of extensively crevassed glaciers along the margin of the Inland Ice, west of Frµnkel Land. Hans R. Katz encountered large numbers of wide crevasses here during his journey with motor-sledges in 1951 (djµvlespalterne = the devil's crevasses).

name: Djµvle°en
description: Island in west Dove Bugt. So named by the 1932 Gefion expedition because of its association with Teufelcap (= devil's cape) and Hestefoden (= horse's hoof) on the same island.

name: Dobbeltskµret
description: Skerry off the east coast of Germania Land, south of Syttenkilometernµsset. The name is found in Thostrup's (2007) account of the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen (J. L°ve, personal communication 2009).

name: Dobbelttop
description: Mountain 1090 m high on NE Kuhn ╪, named by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt as Doppelgipfel for its two summits.

name: Dobbelttoppen
description: Mountain 1040 m high south of Storefjord in Liverpool Land. Named by William Scoresby Jr. in 1822 as Double Mount for its two summits. It is similar to but slightly lower than Kirken on the north side of Storefjord. (Doppelberg.)

name: Bagfjorden
description: Name given by the 1912-13 Den danske Ekspedition til Dronning Louises Land to a small fjord unexpectedly found west of Lindhard ╪ and Kap Jarner (bag = behind), partially blocked by an ice tongue from Storstr°mmen. (Bagfjord, Bakfj÷r≡ur.)

name: Baie Brongniart
description: Bay on the northern Blosseville Kyst, probably identical with Barclay Bugt. The name is found on a map by Jules de Blosseville from 1833 (Fig. 4).

name: Baie Watkins
description: Name used for a small bay on the west side of Lillefjord, southern Liverpool Land, on a very inaccurate map prepared by Maurice Parat during J.B. Charcot's 1933 expedition (Parat & Drach 1934). An adjacent glacier was referred to as Glacier Watkins. The

name: Baie d'Orleans
