description: Minor valley in NW Hold with Hope on the north slope of Stensi÷ Plateau, draining into Blσelv. So named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Eigil Nielsen, probably because of the numerous fossiliferous boulders.

name: Blokelv
description: River in south Liverpool Land west of Scoresbysund [Illoqqortoormiit]. So named by Alfred Rosenkrantz during Lauge Koch's 1926-27 expeditions as Blok Elv or Block River, because in 1926 he found here two large boulders containing a particular suite of fo

name: Blokelv
description: River in Jameson Land flowing SW to enter the sea close to Vandreblokken. So named by Laurits Bruhn during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, after Vandreblokken.

name: Blokelv
description: Minor river in Blokdal, on the north slope of Stensi÷ Plateau, draining into Blσelv, NW Hold with Hope. Named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Eigil Nielsen.

name: Blokken
description: Mountain in eastern Strindberg Land. The name was first used by Teichert (1933) during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen (blokken = the block).

name: Blokken
description: Name occasionally used by Eigil Nielsen for Knolden, a minor feature north of Frebold Bjerg, Hold with Hope.

name: Blomsterbjerg
description: Mountain in southern AndrΘe Land between Luciagletscher and Blσbµrgletscher, named by Erdhart FrΣnkl during Lauge Koch's 1948-50 expeditions for the abundant flowering plants (= blomster).

name: Blomsterbugten
description: Bay on the west coast of Ymer ╪ (Fig. 35). So named by Gunnar Seidenfaden and Arne Noe-Nygaard during Lauge Koch's 1929 expedition because abundant botanical collections were made here. Vargbukta has also been used. (Blomster Bay, Blomsterbukta, Bay of F

name: Blomsterbugthytten
description: Norwegian hunting hut built for Arktisk Nµringsdrift in March 1930 at Blomsterbugten, west Ymer ╪. It was originally known as Varghytta. (Blomsterbugt.)

name: Blomsterdal
description: Valley in northern Scoresby Land draining via Kolledalen into Antarctic Havn. The name was given by the Place Name Committee about 1956 as a replacement for a suggestion by Peter Bearth. (Blomsterdalen.)

name: Eiger
description: Cliff about 800 m high on the north side of Clavering ╪, so named by Julius Payer during the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt for its resemblance to the mountain of the same name in the Bernese Oberland, Switzerland. (Eigerfjellet.)

name: Eiger Fjeld
description: Mountain about 2000 m high in central AndrΘe Land, on the north side of Gneisdal. Named by John Haller during Lauge Koch's 1949-51 expeditions, after the mountain of the same name in the Bernese Oberland, Switzerland.

name: Eigerhytta
description: Norwegian hunting hut in the corner of Lerbugt, north Clavering ╪, east of the mountain Eiger. It was built in August 1939 as a base hut for glaciological studies by Hans W:son Ahlmann and Kσre Rodahl, and is also known as Leirvσgen.

name: Eigil Elv
description: Large river on west Clavering ╪, draining west into the delta Tangen. Named during Lauge Koch's 1930 expedition in the form Eigil River, possibly after Eigil Riis-Carstensen [1892-1953], a naval officer who was commander of the GODTHAAB during the 1930 e

name: Eigil S°
description: Lake in west Dronning Louise Land, east of Revaltoppe (Fig. 21). Named by the 1952-54 British North Greenland expedition after Eigil Knuth [1903-96], sculptor and archaeologist, noted for his numerous expeditions to Greenland between 1932 and 1994 and th

name: Eigtvedsund
description: Sound south of Trums ╪ in the mouth of Bessel Fjord. Named by Henning Bistrup during the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen as Eigtved Sund, after his future wife Ellen Marie Birgitte Eigtved. Her father was Carl Anton Eigtved [1841-1916], a lieutenant in the

name: Eilan Donan
description: Rock peak about 1500 m high on the east side of Dammen, north Stauning Alper. First climbed by the 1958 Scottish East Greenland expedition led by Malcolm Slesser, and named after Eilan Donan Castle, Scotland, a stronghold of Clan MacRae, now a memorial.

name: Einarfjellet
description: Mountain about 1200 m high on the south side of Gauss Halv°, corresponding to part of Smith Woodward Bjerg. The name is found on an NSIU map (1932a), and was giver for Einar, one of the original Norse settlers of Greenland.

name: Eirik Raudes Tinde
description: Name occasionally used for Norsketinden, a 2870 m high peak in the north Stauning Alper. The name occurs in accounts of the first ascent on 7 August 1954 by the Dansk-Norsk Gr°nlandsekspedition. See also Eirik Raudes Land and Norsketinden. (Erik R°des Ti

name: Blokadedal
description: Valley in Hudson Land west of Stordal. So named by Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions in the form Blocade Valley, because the mouth of the ice-filled valley is partially blocked by moraine. (Blockade Tal).

name: Bosigran
description: Pinnacle about 2700 m high on the NE ridge of Hj°rnespids, north Stauning Alper. Climbed by the 1968 Queen Mary College expedition on 13 August, and named after a climbing locality in Cornwall.

name: Botanikerbugt
description: Bay on the south coast of Ymer ╪. The name was used as a botanical reference locality in reports of the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen. Thorvald S°rensen carried out detailed botanical studies here. (Botaniker Bugt).

name: Bothriolepis Cleft
description: Ravine on the south side of Gauss Halv°, west of Paralleldal. The name was used by Gunnar SΣve-S÷derbergh during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, because of finds of fossil Bothriolepis (SΣve-S÷derbergh 1934).

name: Bothriolepis Mtn
description: Name used by Stensi÷ (1936) for a mountain on the north side of Ymer ╪ where Devonian fossils (Bothriolepis) were collected in 1934. Location uncertain, but it may be the 826 m high mountain east of the mouth of Zoologdal.

name: Botnhuset
description: Norwegian hunting hut at the south end (botn = bottom) of Loch Fyne, built by the Foldvik expedition in August 1926. It was also known as ╪iens hus and Bunnhuset.

name: Bottom Terrace
description: Name used by Gunnar SΣve-S÷derbergh during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen for a terrace at the foot of Stensi÷ Bjerg, southern Gauss Halv° (SΣve-S÷derbergh 1933). (Bottenterrassen.)

name: Boulder
description: Prominent small nunatak 3 km from the head of Oxford Gletscher, southern Stauning Alper. Named by the 1970 University of Dundee expedition which had a base camp on its top. The 1975 Scottish expedition made use of the same site.

name: Boulder Glacier
description: Name occasionally used by the 1970 University of Dundee expedition for Oxford Gletscher, south Stauning Alper; they established their base camp on a locality named Boulder. Uranus Glacier has also been used.

name: Boulder Ridge
description: Ridge on the south side of Djµvlekl°ften, east Clavering ╪, where large boulders of Permian and crystalline rocks were found in a Cretaceous sequence. The name was used by Maync (1949).

name: Boulderbjerg
description: Prominent peak about 2200 m high on the west side of upper Oxford Gletscher, south Stauning Alper. So named by the 1970 University of Dundee expedition, which made the first ascent, because of its proximity to their base camp on Boulder. (Boulder Peak.)

name: Bourbon ╪
description: Island in the Franske ╪er. Named after Kap Bourbon by John Haller during Lauge Koch's 1956-58 expeditions.

name: Bow
description: Mountain 1700 m high at the head of Harlech Gletscher, north Stauning Alper. First climbed by the 1963 Imperial College expedition, and named after the London locality of Bow, which originally had a bow-shaped bridge over the River Lea.

name: Bowen Bjerg
description: Mountain in east Canning Land. Named by Arne Noe-Nygaard during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen as Mt. Bowen after Norman Levi Bowen [1887-1956]. A leading Canadian petrologist and geochemist, he was noted particularly for his studies of assimilation in

name: Box°erne
description: Small islands in the southern part of J°kelbugten. So named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen, probably because a depot of 37 boxes of dog-pemmican was made here during a snowstorm in February 1907. (Box÷erne, Box Islands.)

name: Boyd Bastion
description: Mountain forming the SW point of Louise Boyd Land. Named by John Haller during Lauge Koch's 1951 expedition.

name: Boykowdalen
description: Valley on NE Geographical Society ╪, equivalent to the present Hundeklemmen. Used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937), it was named after Johann Maria Boykow [1879-1935], an Austrian who gave instruction in photogrammetry, navigation and ballistic principle

name: Brachiopoddal
description: Valley in western Wollaston Forland. So named by Hans Frebold during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, for finds of fossil brachiopods. (Brachiopodendal.)

name: Bragebreen
description: Glacier on central Clavering ╪, a tributary to Skillegletscher. Used on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937), and named after Brage, the poet-god of old Nordic mythology noted for his wisdom.

name: Bramgσses°
description: Small lake on Winge Kyst in southern Germania Land. Named Bramgaases° by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen after the barnacle geese (= bramgσs), which are common breeding birds in the region.

name: Bramgσss°
description: Small lake on SW Milne Land near R°defjord. Named during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions by Svend Funder for the numerous young barnacle geese seen here.

name: Bramsen Bjerg
description: Mountain ridge with three summits about 1270 m high on west Clavering ╪. Named by Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions in the form Mt. Bramsen. The name has been applied to two different summits of the same mountain, but now covers the entire mountain. It is

name: Brandaelv
description: River on the south coast of Hold with Hope, named on an NSIU map (NSIU 1932a; Fig. 13) as Branda. There are many similar Norwegian place names.

name: Brandal
description: Valley on SE Geographical Society ╪, equivalent to the present Adam af Bremen Dal. So named on NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937), for the locality of the same name in Sunnm°re, Norway, home port of many sealers.

name: Bakkehaug
description: Norwegian hunting hut on the NW side of Clavering ╪, west of Louise Elv, built by the Foldvik expedition in August 1927. It has also been called Louise Elv Hytten. (Bakkehytten, Bakkehuset.)

name: Bakkehytta
description: Norwegian hunting hut built in September 1930 for Arktisk Nµringsdrift on the NW point of Geographical Society ╪. The name derives from it being placed on an awkward slope (= bakke). The hut has also been known under the names Svedenborg, Joplassen, R°vb

name: Balderbreen
description: Glacier on central Clavering ╪, a minor tributary to Skillegletscher. So named on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937) after Balder, son of Odin in old Nordic mythology, noted for his gentleness.

name: Balders Hage
description: Name reported used by the wintering party at Kulhus in 1935 for Mσgenµs, the peninsula on the north side of central Grandjean Fjord. See also Balderbreen.

name: Baldwin-Huset
description: Name sometimes used for the eight-sided depot hut built at Kap Philip Broke in south Shannon for the 1901 Baldwin-Ziegler expedition. It has also been known as Ziegla-Husa. See also Kap Philip Broke.

name: Balmunggletscher
description: Small glacier on northern Clavering ╪, named on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937) in the form Balmungbreen. The name is derived from old Nordic mythology.

name: Balnes
description: Small cape on the east coast of Payer Land, south of Revet. Named after the area near Troms, Norway, from which many Norwegian hunters originated. Lacmann's (1937) maps use the spelling Balsnes.

name: Baltos Bre
description: Name given to a northern branch of Roslin Gletscher by the 1996 Norwegian Stauning Alper expedition. It was named after Samuel Johannes Balto [1861-1921], who accompanied Fridtjof Nansen on his crossing of the Inland Ice in 1888.

name: Balσs flyveplass
description: Natural landing field on Vestersletten, west of Mackenzie Bugt. Named during the 1932 NSIU expedition, which had two aircraft used mainly for aerial photography based there. (Balσs Flyvplass.)

name: Bamsegletscher
description: Glacier on SE Traill ╪, south of Mountnorris Fjord. Named during Lauge Koch's 1936-38 expeditions by Hans Peter Schaub for the polar bear (bamse = teddy bear).

name: Banangletscher
description: Glacier on SE Traill ╪. Named by Hans-Peter Heres during Lauge Koch's 1956-58 expeditions for the banana-like shape of the glacier.

name: Barclay Bugt
description: Name given by Amdrup's 1898-1900 expedition to the bay on the northern Blosseville Kyst south of Kap Barclay. It may be identical with Jules de Blosseville's 1833 Baie Brongniart. (Barclay-Bugt, Barclay Bight, Barchlay Bugt.)

name: BΣrenkamm
description: Mountain in southern AndrΘe Land. The name is found on a panorama sketch drawn by John Haller in 1949 published in Schwarzenbach (1993).

name: Barenzahne
description: Mountain between Sefstr÷m Gletscher and Gully Gletscher, Stauning Alper. Climbed and so named by the 1964 Zurich expedition.

name: Barnabas Dal
description: Valley on southern Ymer ╪, draining SE to Sofia Sund. Named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Ove Simonsen after J°rgen Barnabas, a Greenlander who assisted the expedition from 1932 to 34 and sometimes hunted here. It has also been called Raudale

name: Barnabasdal Hytten
description: Norwegian hunting hut built in October 1930 on the east side of Barnabas Dal, Ymer ╪. It is also known as Raudalshytta and Stor-Dalen.

name: Barnacle Cliffs
description: Cliff west of Klµgbugt, Nordmarken, where barnacle geese nest. Named by the 1987 Irish expedition to northern East Greenland.

name: Barriere Gletscher
description: Minor glacier in western Svejstrup Dal, the valley between Th. Thomsen Land and A.P. Olsen Land, so named by the 1948 Leeds University expedition because it formed a difficult obstacle. (Barrier Glacier).

name: Barrieren
description: Elongate N-S mountain ridge on northern Ymer ╪, named by Silvio Eha during Lauge Koch's 1947-49 expeditions (barrieren = the barrier).

name: Barrieren
description: High peak in Dronning Louise Land, which to the 1952-54 British North Greenland expedition appeared to form a barrier across Budolfi Isstr°m when sledging down that glacier from the west.

name: Barrikadegletscher
description: Glacier on SE Traill ╪, NE of Steenstrup Bjerg. So named during Lauge Koch's 1936-38 expeditions by Hans Peter Schaub because it formed a barrier across Bj°rnedal in 1937; the glacier has retreated significantly since then.

name: Barrikadental
description: Name used by Stauber (1938) for the present Bj°rnedal, a valley on the south side of Mountnorris Fjord on SE Traill ╪ partially blocked by Barrikadegletscher.

name: Brµhytten
description: Norwegian hut east of the mouth of Knµkdalen, south Frµnkel Land, built in April 1950. The inner part of the fjord is often blocked by ice calved from Nordenski÷ld Gletscher (brµ = glacier). The hut has also been known as Gregorydalhytten and Knµkelvhytt

name: Brµndestablen
description: Small skerry just off the south point of R°de° in R°defjord, so named by the 1891-92 Den ╪stgr°nlandske expedition led by Carl Ryder. A prominent dolerite dyke here is divided by joints into horizontal prismatic blocks which resemble a pile of firewood (

name: Brµ°erne
description: Three islands off the front of Bredebrµ at the west end of Borgfjorden. So named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen. The southernmost island has been referred to as Southern Brµ ╪. (Brµ÷erne, Glacier Islands, Brµ-Inseln, Brµ÷erne, J÷kuleyjar.)

name: Ejnar Gletscher
description: Short glacier in south Dronning Louise Land flowing west into Vedel S° (Fig. 21). Named by the 1952-54 British North Greenland expedition after the Danish explorer Ejnar Mikkelsen [1880-1971]. See also Ejnar Mikkelsen Gletscher.

name: Ejnar Mikkelsen Gletscher
description: Large N-S-trending glacier draining south into the head of Smallefjord and east into the head of Bredefjord (Fig. 81). The name first appeared on the 1932 edition of the Geodµtisk Institut 1:1 million scale map, and derives from Lauge Koch's aerial obser

name: Ekkodal
description: Valley on SE Traill ╪, so named during Lauge Koch's 1956-58 expeditions by Hans-Peter Heres, for an echo.

name: Ekspeditionshuset
description: House built on the west side of Mesters Vig by prospecting teams associated with Lauge Koch's 1948-49 expeditions. In early 1973 it was swept away by an avalanche, and a new house, Nyt Ekspeditionshus, was built in 1974 about 200 m to the south. (Expedit

name: Ekstra Bladets Varde
description: Cairn on the north side of Dickson Fjord, Suess Land, built on 6 August 1932 by C. EugΦne Wegmann and Aage Poulsen. Its name records the support given to the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Ekstra Bladets ╪stgr°nlands Fond. The cairn record was recovered

name: Ekstraelv
description: River in Home Forland, SW of Kap Stosch, so named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Eigil Nielsen. The name was originally given to the first large river south of River 1. However, in 1952 the published Geodµtisk Institut map sheet attached the n

name: Elefantbjerg
description: Ridge 490 m high in northern Scoresby Land, on the north side of Kolledalen. The name was used by Hans Kapp during Lauge Koch's 1957-58 expeditions, and given for the massive, rounded ridges, supposedly elephant-like in proportions.

name: Cima Ouest
description: Peak about 2400 m high on the south side of Vikingebrµ, north Stauning Alper. First climbed by Guido Monzino's 1964 expedition, and probably named after the mountain of the same name in the Dolomites, one of the Tre Cime.

name: Cima Virgilio
description: Pinnacle on Satans Galleri, the ridge running NNE from Korsspids, north Stauning Alper. Climbed on 6 August 1984 by Sandro Pucci's climbing expedition, and named after the Roman poet Virgil [70-19 BC]. (Virgilio).

name: Cirkusbjerg
description: Mountain on Gauss Halv° between Karin Dal and Paralleldal, named by Helge G. Backlund during Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions in the form Mt. Karboncircus. The original name was found to be geologically misleading and was changed to Circus Mountain (subs

name: Cirkusdal
description: Upper part of Djµvlekl°ften, NE Clavering ╪. So named by Arne Noe-Nygaard and Gunnar SΣve-S÷derbergh during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen for the bowl-shape of the valley.

name: Cirkuselv
description: River in east Hudson Land draining NE into Loch Fyne. The name was used by Gunnar SΣve-S÷derbergh during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, originally as Cirkus River, because it drains a cirque or bowl-shaped valley.

name: Cirkusgletscher
description: Glacier on the east side of the Werner Bjerge, at the head of Blomsterdal. Named during Lauge Koch's 1953-54 expeditions by Peter Bearth and Eduard Wenk for the arena-like shape. It has occasionally been called Escher von der Linth Gletscher.

name: Cirkuskl°ft
description: Ravine east of Farvefjµldet on the north side of Sµls°en. Named by Eigil Knuth's 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition, probably for its shape.

name: Cirque d'Acropole
description: Name used by the 1968 ExpΘdition Franτaise au Groenland Nord-Est led by Claude Rey expedition for a traverse of the snow domes around their Glacier des Oubliettes on the west side of Prinsessegletscher, eastern Nathorst Land. The peaks include L'Acropole

name: Citadel
description: Mountain about 2000 m high on the north side of Mercurius Gletscher, south Stauning Alper. First climbed by James Clarkson's 1961 expedition, and so named because when first seen it towered above all the neighbouring peaks.

name: Cittα di Roma
description: Peak about 2410 m high in the Vikingebrµ area of the north Stauning Alper, climbed by G. Dionisi's 1982 expedition. Exact location uncertain. It was named after the Italian city of Rome.

name: City Hytta
description: Norwegian hunting hut at Kap Negri on the west side of Fligely Fjord, built by the 1932-34 Sigurd Toll°fsen expedition in August 1932. It was named after Gerhard æCity' Antonsen [1900-1945], a legend among Norwegian hunters who spent seven years without

name: Claraiadal
description: Valley in the SW part of Wegener Halv°. Named by Katherina Perch-Nielsen during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions for the fossil mussel æClaraia', commonly found in the valley.

name: Clare Fjeld
description: Snow peak 2220 m high on the south side of Gully Gletscher, Stauning Alper. Climbed on 19 August 1963 by the Cambridge University expedition. It was named after Clare College, Cambridge, founded in 1326 as University Hall, and refounded in 1338 by Lady E

name: Brandalhytten
description: Norwegian hunting hut in AndreΘ Land on the west side of Geologfjord, built in September 1933 for Arktisk Nµringsdrift; it has now disappeared. The hut was named after Knut O. Brandal, who helped build the hut, but died two weeks later of an acute illnes

name: Brandalvatnet
description: Lake in Adam af Bremen Dal (= Brandal), Geographical Society ╪. Used on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937).

name: Evers Gletscher
description: Glacier between Hvidbj°rn Nunatakker and Knud Ringnes Nunatak. The area was first explored by the 1931 H°ygaard & Mehren expedition, and in 1932 overflown by Lauge Koch during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen. The name first appears on the 1932 Geodµtiske

name: Ewaldfjellet
description: Mountain 1500 m high in north Clavering ╪. So named on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937), after Erich Ewald [b. 1884], a German minister who encouraged the NSIU work on maps of East Greenland which were drawn in Berlin. (Ewald-Fjellet.)

name: Eyvind Fjeld Gletscher
description: Tributary glacier on the north side of Adolf Hoel Gletscher. Named by the 1931 H°ygaard & Mehren expedition after their fellow student Eyvind Fjeld, the initiator of their expedition who had been unable to join them on their crossing of the Inland Ice.

name: F. Graae Gletscher
description: Glacier at the head of Nordvestfjord, on the NE side of Charcot Land. The name first appeared on the 1932 1:1 million scale Geodµtisk Institut map prepared by Lauge Koch during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen. It was named after Frederik Graae [1875-1948

name: F. Toula Plateau
description: Plateau in Germania Land, SE of Fladebugt. Named during Lauge Koch's 1956-58 expeditions by John Haller after the Austrian geologist Franz Toula [1845-1920], who had worked up collections made in this area by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahr

name: Fakirgryde
description: Glacier-filled, basin-shaped valley north of the head of Segldal, northern Scoresby Land. Named by Hans Kapp during Lauge Koch's 1957-58 expeditions.

name: Falkberget
description: Norwegian hunting hut SE of Falkebjerg, on the north side of Falskebugt, Wollaston Forland, built by the HIRD expedition in August 1928. The name of both hut and mountain derive from the gyrfalcon, formerly common in the region. The hut has also been kno

name: Falkebjerg
description: Mountain 307 m high in NE Wollaston Forland, north of Falskebugt. See also Falkberget.

name: Falkeelv
description: River draining into Ugleelv on the west side of the head of Hurry Inlet. Named by Alfred Rosenkrantz during Lauge Koch's 1926-27 expeditions as Falkon River. Roberts (1935) placed the name in error on a south-flowing river west of Nathorst Fjeld. (Falke

name: Falkepynt
description: Peninsula in NE Gσseland. Named by the 1891-92 Den ╪stgr°nlandske expedition as Falke Pt. Gyrfalcons (Falco rusticolus) were seen by the expedition on several occasions.

name: Falkeryg
description: Minor ridge between River 9 and River 10, on the north flank of Frebold Bjerg, Home Forland. So named by Eigil Nielsen during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, after the gyrfalcon.

name: Falketind
description: Eastern peak of Celsius Bjerg, about 880 m high, NW of Kap Humboldt on Ymer ╪. So named on an NSIU map (1932a).

name: Falkonerklippe
description: Nunatak in SW Dronning Louise Land, west of Helgoland. So named during the 1912-13 Den danske Ekspedition til Dronning Louises Land because two gyrfalcons were seen here on 5 May 1913. (Falkonerklippen, Falkoner Klippen, FalkonΦrklippen.)

name: False Col
description: Col between the heads of Bersµrkerbrµ and Skjoldungebrµ, between Bosigran and Kensington, Stauning Alper. Named by the Queen Mary College expedition which climbed the col from the Bersµrkerbrµ side on 15-16 July 1968.

name: Falske Bugt Hytten
description: Norwegian hunting hut built in August 1928 on the peninsula north of Falskebugt, Wollaston Forland, by the HIRD expedition. It was originally known as Falkberget, and has also been known as Taymors Fjell. See also Falskebugt.

name: Falskebugt
description: Bay in NE Wollaston Forland. So named by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt as Falsche Bai, because the bay appears from the sea to be much larger than it is, due to the low ground at its head (falske = false). (Falschen Bai, Falschen Bay, Fa

name: Falskenµs
description: Prominent peninsula NW of Vesthavn, near Eskimonµs, on the south coast of Clavering ╪, similar to and sometimes mistaken for the peninsula Eskimonµs. Named by the wintering party at the station during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen. (Falske Nµs.)

name: Falsterselv
description: River in Jameson Land flowing west into Hall Bredning. Named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Laurits Bruhn after the island of Falster, Denmark.

name: Br°ggerhytta
description: Norwegian hunting hut on the north side of DusΘn Fjord, Gunnar Andersson Land, east of Zoologdalen. Built by Arktisk Nµringsdrift in September 1929, the name commemorates a lawyer named Br°gger (P.S. Mikkelsen 1994). (Br°dger, Br°gger-hytta, Br£gger-Hytt

name: Br°nlunds Grav
description: Point on the east coast of Lambert Land, so named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen because J°rgen Br°nlund died here about November-December 1907, one of the three expedition members to die on their return from their northern explorations. J°rgen Br°

name: Braastad
description: Norwegian hunting hut on the north side of Moskusoksefjord, east of Ankerbjerg. Built in September 1929 by Arktisk Nµringsdrift, the hut was named after Johan Braastad [b. 1888], geologist and secretary of NSIU 1924-35. It is also known as Ankerlien. (Br

name: Buache ┼s
description: Ridge in eastern Scoresby Land north of Fleming Fjord. It was named by William Scoresby Jr. in 1822 as Cape Buache in compliment to a French philosopher, probably Jean Nicholas Buache [1741-1825].

name: Buch Bjerg
description: Mountain 770 m high on the west side of Carlsberg Fjord. Named by William Scoresby Jr. in 1822 as Cape Buch after the celebrated geological traveller Baron Christian Leopold von Buch [1774-1853]. Buch was considered to be the most illustrious geologist t

name: Buddha
description: Mountain 1880 m high NE of Graben Land. So named by Johan D. Friderichsen during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions because from the SW it resembles a buddha.

name: Buddingbjerg
description: Mountain between Benjamin Dal and Junctiondal, southern AndrΘe Land. Named during the 1948-50 Lauge Koch expeditions by Erdhart FrΣnkl for its rounded shape and layered appearance, resembling a pudding (= budding).

name: Budolfi Isstr°m
description: Large glacier in Carlsbergfondet Land, southern Dronning Louise Land, flowing eastwards to join L. Bistrup Brµ (Fig. 21). Named by the 1912-13 Den danske Ekspedition til Dronning Louises Land, perhaps for Saint Budolfi, patron of a church in ┼lborg, Denm

name: Buegletscher
description: Glacier on SE Traill ╪, south of Mountnorris Fjord. Named during Lauge Koch's 1936-38 expeditions by Hans Peter Schaub for its curved shape (bue = bow, curve).

name: Bukta
description: Norwegian hunting hut in a bay (= bukta) on the east coast of Hold with Hope, NW of Kap Broer Ruys, built by the Foldvik expedition in August 1927. It was also known as Skandalen and Moskusoksehytten.

name: Bulbjerg
description: Mountain on Volquaart Boon Kyst. So named by Laurits Bruhn during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, after the prominent cliff of the same name in NW Jylland, Denmark. It was climbed by the 1934 Bonzi expedition and named Punta Roma.

name: Bⁿltrop Fjelde
description: Mountains on the south side of V. Clausen Fjord, inner Skµrfjorden. So named by David Malmquist during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, after the husband of his wife's sister, the mathematician Einar Bⁿltrop Lunell. He was professor at the University of

name: Bundermannfjellet
description: Mountain 1369 m high on west Clavering ╪, corresponding to Koralbjerg. So named on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937) for Max Bundermann [b. 1904], who took part in photogrammetric work on NSIU aerial photographs of East Greenland.

name: Bundfjeldet
description: Innermost mountain on the north side of Vigfus Dal, Daniel Bruun Land. Named by Eigil Knuth's 1938-39 expedition for its position at the end of the fjord (bund = bottom, also the inner part of a fjord or bay).

name: Bundhuset
description: Norwegian hunting hut built by the 1932-34 Helge Ingstad expedition in August 1932 about 3 km from the inner end of Fleming Fjord. It has also been known as Heimen and Ingstadheimen.

name: Bundhytten
description: Danish hunting hut on the north (inner) side of Peters Bugt, north of the mouth of Ardencaple Fjord, built for Nanok in August 1930. It is officially known as Petersbugthytten, and has also been called Nummer 1 Hytten.

name: Flatdalshytta
description: Norwegian hunting hut on the south side of Ymer ╪ at the mouth of Fladedal, built in August 1934 by Arktisk Nµringsdrift. It has also been known as Firmannsdalen and Namsdalsstua. (Flatdalen, Fladedalhytten.)

name: Flatstranda
description: Norwegian hunting hut built in August 1931 by the M°re expedition on the NW side of Fleming Fjord, and named for the flat terrain around the hut. It was destroyed by high seas in 1953 (P.S. Mikkelsen 1994, 2008). (Stranda-huset.)

name: Flat°yra
description: Delta on the north side of Geographical Society ╪. So named on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937) for its flat nature.

name: Clark Bjerg
description: Mountain about 400 m high in eastern Wollaston Forland. It was observed at a distance by William Scoresby Jr. in 1822, and named Cape Clark in compliment to John Clark, who had married Scoresby's sister Mary. The cape was identified as a mountain south o

name: Claudius Clavus Bjerge
description: Mountain range 900-1100 m high north of ╪rsted Dal, Scoresby Land. The name was one of a group of names given by the Place Name Committee in 1939, and commemorates the Danish cartographer Claudius Clavus, who prepared some of the earliest maps of Greenla

name: Claverhouse
description: Mountain about 2300 m high between Storgletscher and Gannochy Gletscher, central Stauning Alper. Named by the 1968 University of Dundee expedition which made the first ascent, probably for John Graham of Claverhouse [1649-89], 1st Viscount of Dundee.

name: Clavering Bukta
description: Name used by Norwegian hunters in the 1920s and 1930s for the present Kirchenpauer Bugt, NE Clavering ╪ (see e.g. White 1927).

name: Clavering Fjorden
description: Name used by Norwegian hunters, and on NSIU maps from about 1929, for the sound on the south side of Clavering ╪ now known as Godthσb Gulf. The 1908-09 FLOREN expedition appears to have been the first to have used the name, although they may have intende

name: Clavering ╪
description: Large island west of Wollaston Forland (Fig. 15). Named by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt as Clavering Insel after Douglas Charles Clavering [1794-1827], commander of the GRIPER on the 1823 voyage to this region (Sabine 1825; Clavering 18

name: Alabamablick
description: Feature in the vicinity of the base camp of the 1943-44 German meteorological station at Kap Sussi, Shannon. The name is recorded by Olsen (1965). It apparently had a view to the south of the hut Alabama.

name: Albert

name: Albert Heim Bjerge
description: Mountain range on the north side of Promenadedal, south of Wordie Gletscher. So named during Lauge Koch's 1936-38 expeditions by Heinrich Bⁿtler for one of the most noted of Swiss geologists, Albert Heim [1849-1937]. He was a structural geologist and pro

name: Albrecht Bugt
description: Large bay on the north coast of Wollaston Forland (Fig. 15). Named by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt as Albrecht Bai (Fig. 6) for George Alexander Albrecht [1834-98], treasurer of the æBremisches ComitΘ fⁿr die zweite Deutsche Nordpolarfa

name: Albrechts-slette

name: Albrechtbugthytten
description: Sirius hut built in August 1960 about 2 km NW of the head of Albrecht Bugt, northern Wollaston Forland, adjacent to the old Norwegian hut (Sletta) built in August 1928 by the Hird expedition and known as Albrechtsbugthytten.

name: Albuen
description: Cape on the west side of Hurry Inlet, so named by Alfred Rosenkrantz during Lauge Koch's 1926-27 expeditions for its shape (albuen = the elbow).

name: Aldebaran Gletscher
description: Glacier in the SW Werner Bjerge flowing west to join Schuchert Gletscher. The name first appeared on the maps of Styger (1951), in his report on a climbing excursion during Lauge Koch's 1950 expedition. It was named after the red giant star Aldebaran (=

name: Aldinger Elv
description: Major south-flowing river on SE Milne Land. The name appears on the maps of Callomon & Birkelund (1980) and Larsen et al. (2003), and commemorates Hermann Aldinger, a geologist who made pioneer studies in the region in 1933. Attempts to obtain approval o

name: Aletschhorn
description: Mountain in eastern Louise Boyd Land, west of Gerard de Geer Gletscher. It was named by John Haller during Lauge Koch's 1949-51 expeditions, after the mountain of the same name in central Switzerland.

name: Clare Lloyd River
description: Name used by the 1974 Joint biological expedition for the river in Lunedal draining into Holm Bugt, SW Traill ╪. It was named after one of the expedition participants.

name: Fame ╪er
description: Group of two large and three small islands at the head of Hurry Inlet. Named by William Scoresby Jr. during his 1822 expedition as the Fame Islands, after his father's ship the FAME of Hull, the first to explore Hurry Inlet. The FAME was a teak-built shi

name: Fangergletscher

name: Fangersund

name: Daneborg
description: This name was originally given to the Nord°stgr°nlands Slµdepatrulje base at Sandodden, built in 1944 with assistance of USA forces (daneborg = the Danes castle), and is the name now used for the present Sirius headquarters. At the end of the war the bas

name: Danevirke
description: Ridge SE of Noret, north Scoresby Land. Named by prospecting teams associated with Lauge Koch's 1948-49 expeditions, after the complex of earthworks in Sydslesvig between Trene and Slien, the oldest dating from c. 750 A.D.

name: Daniel Bruun Land
description: Land area between Sµls°en and Borgfjorden, named by the 1912-13 Den danske Ekspedition til Dronning Louises Land as Daniel Bruuns Land. Daniel Bruun [1856-1931], a captain in the Danish Navy and author of several books on the Arctic, had assisted Ludvig

name: Daniel Schmidtfjellet
description: Mountain 1400 m high on north Clavering ╪. Named after Daniel Schmidt [b. 1902], who undertook photogrammetric work on the detailed NSIU maps of Clavering ╪ and Geographical Society ╪ (Lacmann 1937).

name: Danmark Havn
description: Sheltered harbour in south Germania Land, so named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen after the expedition ship DANMARK, which wintered here. The DANMARK, a 377-ton barque built in Sunderland in 1855, had previously sailed under the names SIR COLIN CAM

name: Danmark ╪
description: Island in the inner part of Scoresby Sund, named Danmarks ╪ by the 1891-92 Den ╪stgr°nlandske expedition led by Carl Ryder for the kingdom of Denmark (Fig. 7). The expedition wintered in Hekla Havn on Danmark ╪. Ragnvald Knudsen occasionally used Heklala

name: Danmarks Monumentet
description: Impressive mountain buttress between inner M°rkefjord and Pustervig, Daniel Bruun Land, so named during the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen. According to Charles Poulsen (1991), and Thostrup (2007) it received its name from the pattern of light and dark ro

name: Danmarks Pynt
description: Name used by Gull°v (1991) for the east peninsula of Hekla Havn where the over-wintering station was erected (J. L°ve, personal communication 2010).

description: Weather station at Danmark Havn, the site of the original base of the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen. The modern ICAO weather and radio station around ╪sterelv was established in 1948 and is still in use. Fischer (1983) reported it as manned by 11 men and

name: Danmarkshavnhuset
description: Name often used for the base of the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen at Danmark Havn, which was originally known as Villaen. It was briefly used by the 1909-12 Alabama-ekspeditionen, and repaired and taken over in 1919 as a hunting station by 1919-24 A/S ╪s

name: Fleineset
description: Small peninsula in extreme SE Geographical Society ╪. So named on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937) after the locality of the same name in Vesterσlen, Norway.

name: Fleming Dal
description: Name sometimes used by Norwegian hunters for the present Pingel Dal, which drains into Fleming Fjord (Ingstad 1935, 1937). The name has occasionally been used in ornithology reports (e.g. Marris & Ogilvie 1962).

name: Fleming Dal Hytten
description: Norwegian hunting hut in Pingel Dal (sometimes called Fleming Dal), built by the 1932-34 Helge Ingstad expedition about 8 km south of the head of Fleming Fjord. It has also been known as Pingel Dal Hytten and Landhuset.

name: Fleming Fjord
description: Fjord NW of Wegener Halv°. Named by William Scoresby Jr. in 1822 as Fleming Inlet after John Fleming [1785-1857], noted for his æPhilosophy of Zoology' published in 1822. He subsequently became professor at Aberdeen and Edinburgh. Scoresby thought that h

name: Fleming Fjord Hytten
description: Norwegian hunting hut on the north side of Fleming Fjord, 10 km SW of Kap Biot, built for Hermann Andresen's expedition in September 1954. It has also been known by the names Lapstun-Hytten, Fladestrand, Sur°je and S°ndre Biot. (Flemmingfjordhytten, Flem

name: Fleming Fjord Nord
description: Norwegian hut erected in the summer of 1955 for Hermann Andresen's expedition beside Lapstun Hytten on the north side of Fleming Fjord, 10 km SW of Kap Biot. The hut was moved by Otto Lapstun from Nathorst Fjord, where it was known as Kaares-bu. Lapstun

name: Flemingfjordhuset
description: Small wintering station on the east side of Fleming Fjord at the mouth of the valley Vimmelskaftet. It was built in 1934 during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, and is also known as Vimmelskaftet and Kap Brown Huset. (Flemmingfjordhuset, Fleming Fjord Hu

name: Fleskesvoren

name: Flett Plateau
description: Plateau about 1500 m high on western Gauss Halv°. So named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Gunnar SΣve-S÷derbergh after Sir John Smith Flett [1869-1947], a British petrologist who was director of the British Geological Survey from 1920 to 1935.

description: N-S-trending sound bounding the west side of Kuhn ╪ (Fig. 15). Named by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt after August von Fligely [1810-79], an Austrian field marshal and cartographer. Fligely was noted for his map making, especially of Hun

name: Flyverbjerg
description: Mountain in south Kronprins Christian Land, south of Centrums° (Fig. 24). Named during Lauge Koch's 1952-53 expeditions by Erdhart FrΣnkl, for the pilots of the Catalina aircraft which transported the expedition. This was the only mountain which the Cata

name: Dolerite Point Ponds

name: Dolezalfjellet
description: Mountain on central Geographical Society ╪, corresponding to the present T°rvestakken. Used on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937), the name was given for Eduard Dole₧al [1862-1955], an Austrian, and one of the leading developers of photogrammetric technique

name: Alfred Wegener Bjerg
description: Peak in the southern Stauning Alper, in the inner NE part of Borgbjerg Gletscher. Probably first climbed and named by the 1977 SchwΣbische Stauning Alper expedition.

name: Aliertinde
description: Rock peak on the SW ridge of Dansketinden about 2580 m high. It was climbed and so named by the 1996 Scottish Mountaineering Club expedition.

name: Allday Dal
description: Valley draining north into ╪rsted Dal, Scoresby Land. The name was one of a group given by the Place Name Committee in 1939 to replace proposals by Hans Stauber. Allday Dal commemorates Jacob Allday, sent out by Frederik II of Denmark in 1759 to rediscov

name: Alpebjerg

name: Alpedal
description: Valley in SE AndrΘe Land draining into Eleonore Bugt, named by Erdhart FrΣnkl during Lauge Koch's 1948-50 expeditions.

name: Alpedal
description: Valley in the central part of northern Strindberg Land. Named during Lauge Koch's 1948-49 expeditions by Hans R. Katz for its alpine character.

name: Alpefjord
description: N-S-trending fjord between Nathorst Land and the northern Stauning Alper (Fig. 27). Named Alpfjorden by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst for the spectacular high mountains of the Stauning Alper on the east side of the fjord

name: Blomsternunatak

description: Lake at the NW end of Snedrivegletscher, SW of Tµrskeldal, Nathorst Land. Named during Lauge Koch's 1954-55 expeditions by Hans Zweifel, for the many flowers along its shores.

name: Blosseville Bjerg
description: Mountain 1283 m high west of Clavering ╪. The 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt had given the name Cap Blosseville in commemoration of Jules Baron de Blosseville [1802-33], a lieutenant in the French navy who disappeared without trace off the ea

name: Danske Villa

name: Danske ╪er

name: Archer ╪er

description: Fjord between Dronning Margrethe II Land and C.H. Ostenfeld Land, which divides westwards into two branches known as Bredefjord and Smallefjord (Fig. 59). It was named by Douglas Clavering in 1823 as Ardencaple Inlet for Ardencaple Castle, Dumbarton, the

name: Ardvreck Bjerg
description: Mountain 1866 m high in eastern Nathorst Land between Sandgletscher and Sydvestgletscher. It was first climbed by the 1958 Scottish East Greenland expedition led by Malcolm Slesser, and named Ardvreck for Ardvreck Castle, a MacLeod stronghold on the shor

name: Arenaen

name: Arentzhytta
description: Norwegian hunting hut on the north side of Sofia Sund, west of the mouth of Barnabas Dal and about 7 km east of R°debjerg. It was built in October 1929, and named after Gustav A. Arentz, a director of Arktisk Nµringsdrift. It has also been known as Snehy

description: Glacier in northern Lyell Land, draining north to Kempe Fjord. The name was used by EugΦne Wegmann during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen in the form Argand glacier, and commemorates ╔mile Argand [1879-1940], a structural geologist especially known for h

description: Valley on NE Clavering ╪. The name was used by Arne Noe-Nygaard and Gunnar SΣve-S÷derbergh during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, because of the occurrence of dolomite. (Dolomittal.)

name: Dolomitpynt

name: Dombjerg
description: Snow-capped mountain about 1200 m high south of Lindeman Fjord and north of Store S°dal. Named Domberg by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt, possibly for the Alpine mountain of similar name. (Mt Domberg).

name: Dombravadal

name: Dome

description: Ice cap about 680 m high in south Liverpool Land, equivalent to the present Hvidefjeld [Apuseeq]. The French International Polar Year expedition 1932-33 had determined the thickness of the ice at 50-70 m, and the name is used on maps in several of their

name: D⌠me du Trappeur

name: Domkirken

name: Barth-hytta

description: Valley in southern AndrΘe Land. Named during Lauge Koch's 1948-50 expeditions by Erdhart FrΣnkl for its berries. (Blaabµrdal, Blaabµr Dal.)

name: Blσbµrdalen
description: Valley in east Th. Thomsen Land, draining into Fligely Fjord. Named probably by Nanok, which built a hut at the mouth of the valley in 1931. Berries are plentiful here in the summer. The original form was Blaabµrdal. (Blaabµr Dal.)

name: Eleonore Bugt
description: Broad bay on the east coast of AndrΘe Land between Teufelsschloss and Grejsdalen. Named by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt as Eleonoren-Bai. This is the only girl's name given by the expedition, and was apparently given by Karl Koldewey hi

name: Eleonore S°
description: Lake in Arnold Escher Land. So named during Lauge Koch's 1951 expedition by Hans R. Katz because the rocks appeared to be of the same type as those found at Eleonore Bugt. (Eleonore-See, Eleonores S°.)

name: Eleonorebukta
description: Norwegian hunting hut in the NE part of Eleonore Bugt at the mouth of Grejsdalen. Built by Arktisk Nµringsdrift in March 1937, it was originally known as Ragnildshytta.

name: Eleonorebuktdal
description: Name occasionally used by Norwegian hunters for Grejsdalen, the large valley in AndrΘe Land draining into the sea on the north side of Eleonore Bugt. Bretz (1935) used the English variation Eleonore Bay Valley.

name: Elephant
description: Mountain 1830 m high at the head of Tσrnfjeld Gletscher, north Stauning Alper. First climbed by the 1963 Imperial College expedition, and named after the London locality, Elephant and Castle, originally a smithy converted to a tavern in 1760.

name: Eli Knudsen ╪er
description: Two small islands off Lambert Land. The name was approved in 1958, and is attributed to the work of David Malmquist during Lauge Koch's expeditions. It commemorates Eli Knudsen, Danish hunter and member of Nord°stgr°nlands Slµdepatrulje, who was shot by

name: Eli Knudsens Hytte
description: Hut built in 1934 at the head of a small bay on the west side of Maria ╪. It was repaired in September 1941 by Eli Knudsen and Hans Siewers.

name: Eli Knudsens Varde
description: Prominent cairn on the north cape of Kap Hedlund (Fig. 39), built by Eli Knudsen on 1 August 1942 when he was stationed on Ella ╪.

name: Eli Knudsens Vig
description: This name was reported by Olsen (1965) as used for the small bay on western Maria ╪ where Eli Knudsens Hytte was built in 1934.

name: Blyryggen
description: Ridge west of the bay Mesters Vig, north Scoresby Land, rising to 1051 m. Named by prospecting teams associated with Lauge Koch's 1948-49 expeditions for finds of lead ore.

name: Elis Bjerg
description: Mountain 540 m high NW of the head of Hurry Inlet. Named by Alfred Rosenkrantz during Lauge Koch's 1926-27 expeditions after his Greenlandic assistant, Eli Napartok, and used in the form Eli Fjµld and Mount Eli Fjµld. A.G. Nathorst's Ammonitbjerg had bee

name: Arion Bjerg
description: Mountain 1010 m high in western Gσseland, on the south side of Snes°, so named during Lauge Koch's 1958 expedition by Eduard Wenk's Greek assistant (J. Papageorgakis), who was the only man to climb it. It was named after the Greek singer Arion, the semi-

name: Arken
description: Nunatak in the glacier north of Paul Stern Land. Named by the 1963 Geodµtisk Institut expedition for its supposed likeness to a ship in a sea of ice (arken = the ark).

name: Arkoseelv
description: River in eastern Hudson Land draining NE to Loch Fyne. The name was used by Gunnar SΣve-S÷derbergh during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen in the form Arkose River, and records the presence of arkosic sandstones.

name: Arkosepas
description: Pass between ╪vre Arkosedal and ╪demarksdal, on the west side of Schuchert Flod. Named by Enrico Kempter during Lauge Koch's 1956-58 expeditions.

name: Army Iskappe
description: Ice cap in central Dronning Louise Land (Fig. 21). Named by the 1952-54 British North Greenland expedition to commemorate the help given by the British Army, which provided several of the expedition members, as well as tracked vehicles and clothing.

name: Arnljotstua
description: Norwegian hunting hut built in September 1932 for the 1932-34 Sigurd Toll°fsen expedition on the south side of Kap Buch, easternmost C.H. Ostenfeld Land. It was named after Arnljot Toll°fsen, who died during a hunting trip in May 1933.

name: Brandegga
description: Mountain 726 m high on the north side of Adam af Bremen Dal (= Brandal), on SE Geographical Society ╪, equivalent to the present Leitch Bjerg. Used on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937).

name: Bratskµret
description: Island in western Dove Bugt, perhaps rather large for a skerry. Named by the Eigil Knuth's 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition, for its appearance (brat = steep; skµr = skerry). Tutlas ╪ has also been used.

name: Brattegga
description: Mountain 1260 m high on northern Geographical Society ╪, south of Rudbeck Bjerg. So named on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937), for the steep (= bratt) sides of the mountain.

name: Bratthuken
description: The name is used in Den Gr°nlandske Lods (1968), for the present Takkerne, the NE point of Ellemandsbjerge, eastern Traill ╪. It was named for the steep coastal cliffs. (Kap Bratthuken.)

name: Breccie Elv
description: Stream in Brachiopoddal, western Wollaston Forland. The name was used in the geological report of Rosenkrantz (1932) following work during Lauge Koch's 1929 expedition, and was given for the brecciated nature of the rocks. (Breccia River.)

name: Brede Spµrregletscher
description: Glacier on the south side of Ingolf Fjord, which extends across the fjord and partly blocks the sledge route to the interior. Named by Eigil Nielsen during Eigil Knuth's 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition as Spµrregletscher (brede = broad, spµrre = block, obs

name: Bredebrµ
description: Broad glacier at the head of Borgfjorden, formed by the confluence of Storstr°mmen and L. Bistrup Brµ; it produces many large icebergs. Named as Brede Brµ by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen. (Broad Glacier, Brede Glacier, Breidij÷kull.)

name: Bredefirn
description: Glacier in the Werner Bjerge flowing west to join Arcturus Gletscher. Named during Lauge Koch's 1953-54 expeditions by Peter Bearth and Eduard Wenk.

name: Bredefjord
description: The broader of the two inner branches of Ardencaple Fjord (Fig. 51), named Brede Fjord by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen. The narrower branch was named Smallefjord. (Brede Fiord, Breifjorden.)

name: Bredegletscher
description: Wide glacier on the south side of Scoresby Sund flowing north into Vikingebugt. So named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Laurits Bruhn.

name: Bredehorn
description: Mountain 1900 m high in the southern Werner Bjerge at the head of Breithorn Gletscher. It was originally named Breithorn by Peter Bearth and Eduard Wenk during Lauge Koch's 1953-54 expeditions (Bearth 1959), after the Swiss mountain of the same name. The

name: Bredetop
description: Broad flat-topped mountain in NW Strindberg Land, west of Granitelv. Named during Lauge Koch's 1948-49 expeditions by Hans R. Katz for its broad summit. (Breitstock.)

name: Bredgletscher
description: Glacier on SE Traill ╪, south of Mountnorris Fjord. So named during Lauge Koch's 1936-38 expeditions by Hans Peter Schaub, because it is broad compared to nearby glaciers.

name: Bredningskµrene
description: Group of skerries and islands on the east side of Inderbredningen, east of Rechnitzer Land. So named by Eigil Knuth's 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition because of their position in the expansion of a sound (= bredning).

name: Bregnepynt
description: Peninsula on the NE coast of Milne Land, so named Bregne Pynt by the 1891-92 Den ╪stgr°nlandske expedition led by Carl Ryder because Nikolaj Hartz found numerous ferns (= bregne) here.

name: Brehytta
description: Norwegian hunting hut in Nordfjord, on the east side of Waltershausen Gletscher (bre = gletscher = glacier). It has also been known as Solstrand, Nordfjord and R°dtophytten.

name: Barth Bjerge
description: Name used for the Norwegian hunting hut built in 1949 by Arktisk Nµringsdrift in a valley on the north side of the Barth Bjerge, southern Dronning Margrethe II Land. It was reported to have been destroyed by strong winds in 1949 or 1950 (P.S. Mikkelsen 1

name: Bartholin Borg
description: Mountain c. 1600 m high in east Bartholin Land. Named by John Haller during Lauge Koch's 1956-58 expeditions. Thomas Bartholin [1616-80] was a Danish mineralogist noted for studies of amber in Denmark (borg = castle).

name: Bartholin Brµ
description: Glacier west of Henry Land, on the northern Blosseville Kyst. Named by the 1898-1900 Carlsbergfondets Expedition as Bartholins Brµ for Thomas Bartholin. See also Bartholin Borg. B÷ggild (1905) used Henry Glacier for the same feature. (Bartholin Glacier.)

name: Bartholin Land
description: Land area on the north side of Waltershausen Gletscher. So named by Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expedition, and better defined in 1932 as a result of aerial reconnaissance (Fig. 15). Its boundaries are now Vibeke Gletscher, Indelukket, and to the west longitude

name: Bartholin Nunatak
description: Nunatak south of Korsgletscher, in southern Bartholin Land. Named during Lauge Koch's 1956-58 expeditions by John Haller. See also Bartholin Borg.

name: Bartletts Skµr
description: Submerged skerry west of Kap Stosch where Robert Bartlett ran aground in the EFFIE M. MORRISSEY in 1931. He was dragged off with the assistance of the POLARBJ╪RN, and was somewhat offended to receive later a bill from the owners (see Bartlett 1934). The

name: Basalt Havn
description: Reference locality used by Dunbar (1955) for the harbour (= havn) on the NW coast of Clavering ╪, west of Basalt ╪. Dunbar mis-spells the name as Basalt Haven. (Diabase Haven.)

name: Basalt Table Mountain
description: Locality in southern Jameson Land, referred to by Spath (1935) as a place where H. Bⁿtler collected fossil ammonites. Basalt sills form small plateaus at several locations in this area (see Aldinger 1935, plate 2).

name: Basaltdal
description: Valley on SE Traill ╪, so named during Lauge Koch's 1956-58 expeditions by Hans-Peter Heres for the presence of thick basalt sills.

name: Basaltelv
description: River in SE Jameson Land, originally named by Aldinger (1935) as Basalt River for the dolerite sills. The name was officially approved in 1972, following new work in the area by GGU.

name: Basaltkap
description: Minor cape on the SE coast of Clavering ╪. The name arose during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, and was first used in a report by Backlund & Malmquist (1932). The cape is formed by a basalt intrusion.

name: Basaltkl°ft
description: Minor valley or ravine in northern Scoresby Land, west of the Pictet Bjerge. So named by Hans Kapp during Lauge Koch's 1957-58 expeditions because of the presence of a basalt sill.

name: Basaltnµs
description: Peninsula east of Kap Hope, southern Liverpool Land, made of basaltic rocks. So named by Alfred Rosenkrantz during Lauge Koch's 1926-27 expedition.

name: Basaltpynt
description: Cape on eastern Traill ╪, NW of the mouth of ╞beltoft Vig. Named during Lauge Koch's 1936-38 expeditions by Hans Peter Schaub for the basaltic rocks.

name: Basaltpynten
description: Peninsula on eastern Clavering ╪, west of Basalt°. The name is used on Lacmann's (1937) maps.

name: Basaltspids
description: Peak of basalt in northern Arnold Escher Land, named by Hans R. Katz during his traverse through the nunatak region on Lauge Koch's 1951 expedition.

name: Basalts°
description: Lake on southern Geographical Society ╪. The name came into use in the 1950s during Lauge Koch's geological expeditions, and records the occurrence of basaltic rocks. Hofgaardvatna has also been used.

name: Basalt°
description: Island in Young Sund off eastern Clavering ╪, so named during Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions in the form Basalt Island because it is composed of basaltic rocks. Klippe° has also been used.

name: Baselbjerget
description: Mountain 750 m high on western Kuhn ╪, so named during Lauge Koch's 1936-38 expeditions by Wolf Maync and Andreas Vischer for the Swiss city of Basel (Baselbjµrget..

name: Baselfjeld
description: Nunatak 2600 m high in western Frµnkel Land. Named by John Haller and Eduard Wenk during Lauge Koch's 1951 expedition, for the town and university of Basel in Switzerland where both were based.

name: Basen
description: Name used for the house and depot hut built in 1947 at Zackenberg Bugt, east of Zackenberg, for Eigil Knuth's 1947-50 Danish Peary Land expeditions; it was subsequently used by the 1952-54 British North Greenland expedition. It is also known as Zackenber

name: Basisdalen
description: Common name for S°ndre Basisdal and Nordre Basisdal in SE Canning Land. The name appears to have first been used by SΣve-S÷derbergh (1937) in the form Basis Valley, and derives from work during Lauge Koch's 1936-38 expeditions.

name: Bundhytten i Besselfjorden
description: Norwegian hunting hut built by John Giµver's expedition in innermost Bessel Fjord in August 1932. It was a ruin in 1989. (Botten, Bundhytten.)

name: Elisabeth Bjerg
description: Mountain 588 m high on the west side of Geologfjord, AndrΘe Land, named by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst as Elisabeths Berg, probably after Nathorst's daughter Elisabeth. See also Kap Elisabeth.

name: Elisabethsminde
description: Mountain 2260 m high in the northern Stauning Alper, climbed by Peter Braun and Fritz Schwarzenbach in August 1951 during Lauge Koch's 1951 expedition. The original name was Elisabethstinde (Braun 1953), and was given for Elisabeth FrΣnkl-Fischer, wife o

name: Elizabeth Sharon S°
description: Name used on 1952 WAC maps for the present Gunner Andersen S° in eastern Ad. S. Jensen Land.

name: Ella ╪
description: Large island at the mouth of Kempe Fjord, inner Kong Oscar Fjord (Figs 8, 29). Named by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst as Ellas ╓, after his wife Amy Rafaela (Ella) Windahl [1858-1936]. (Ella Island, Ella-÷ya, Ellainsel.)

name: Ella ╪ Station
description: Name often used for Lauge Koch's scientific station built in August 1931 at the head of Solitµrbugt (Fig. 40), an excellent harbour in northern Ella ╪. The main house, often referred to as ╪rnereden, was continuously manned from 1931 to 1943 and 1947 to

name: Ellemandsbjerge
description: Mountain range on the north side of Mountnorris Fjord, eastern Traill ╪. Named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Ove Simonsen after the Danish locality of the same name at Helgenµs, Jylland.

name: Elsa Dal
description: Ravine on the SW coast of Gauss Halv°. So named by Gunnar SΣve-S÷derbergh during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, after Elsa Warburg, an assistant professor at the University of Uppsala, Sweden.

name: Elsinore Fjeld
description: Mountain 1829 m high north of Bersµrkerbrµ, north Stauning Alper. First climbed by John Hunt's 1960 expedition, and named Elsinore after the castle in the Danish town of Helsing°r, made famous by Shakespeare's æHamlet'. The second ascent of the peak was

name: Elvdal
description: Valley adjacent to the settlement of Scoresbysund, south Liverpool Land (elv = river, dal = valley). It was so named during the 1924 colonisation expedition (Pedersen 1926).

name: Elvdalen
description: NW-SE-trending valley north of Hekla Havn on Danmark ╪, which carries the only significant stream on the island. So named by the 1891-92 Den ╪stgr°nlandske expedition led by Carl Ryder.

name: Claveringstrµdet
description: Strait between Sabine ╪ and Wollaston Forland. Named by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt as Clavering Strasse, for Douglas Charles Clavering (see Clavering ╪). It corresponds approximately to William Scoresby Jr.'s Kater Bay. (Clavering Str

name: Cleft Island
description: Small island off Kap Young, eastern Traill ╪, so named by J.M. Wordie's 1926 Cambridge expedition (Fig. 12); officially it has the name æRock'. The island has a split appearance.

name: Cliff Lake
description: Lake south of Klµgbugt, Nordmarken. Named by the 1987 Irish expedition to northern East Greenland.

name: Cloos Klippe
description: Cliff on the south side of Borg Gletscher, central Dronning Louise Land. Named by the 1952-54 British North Greenland expedition (Fig. 21) after the German structural geologist Hans Cloos [1885-1951], professor at the University of Breslau 1919-26 and su

name: Col de Furesoe
description: Pass between the heads of Prinsessegletscher and Borgbjerg Gletscher, eastern Nathorst Land. Named by the 1968 ExpΘdition Franτaise au Groenland Nord-Est led by Claude Rey expedition after nearby Fures°.

name: Col de Scoresby
description: Pass between the heads of Prinsessegletscher and Borgbjerg Gletscher, eastern Nathorst Land. Named by the 1968 ExpΘdition Franτaise au Groenland Nord-Est led by Claude Rey expedition after William Scoresby Jr. See also Scoresby Land.

name: Col de la Tourmente
description: Pass between two tributary glaciers in the upper part of Prinsessegletscher, eastern Nathorst Land. Named and first climbed by the 1968 ExpΘdition Franτaise au Groenland Nord-Est led by Claude Rey.

name: Col des Jaspes
description: Col in the mountain range south of Charcot Gletscher, east Milne Land, explored by a group from J.B. Charcot's 1933 expedition (Parat & Drach 1934). Probably named for the presence of the mineral jasper in the basalts.

name: Col des Pulkas
description: High col (2130 m) between Kirkebrµ and Storgletscher, discovered in May 1985 during a W-E crossing of the northern Stauning Alper.

name: Cold Shoulder
description: Peak 2450 m high on the east side of upper Gullygletscher, northern Stauning Alper. Climbed and named by the 2007 SMC East Greenland expedition.

name: Colinedal
description: Valley on SW Ymer ╪ draining southwards, where Colin Hallenstein located a tungsten-antimony mineralisation while prospecting for Nordisk Mineselskab (Harp°th et al. 1986).

name: Breidhausen
description: Mountain north of Foldaelv in the Giesecke Bjerge, corresponding to the present Bonney Plateau. So named on an NSIU map (1932a), it derives from the Norwegian for broad (= breid, brei). It was climbed in 1933 by Noel Odell and Walter Wood.

name: Breidifj≥rdr
description: Broad fjord, interpreted as possibly equivalent to the present Dove Bugt by Torn°e (1944). The name is recorded in the Icelandic sagas (Bj°rn J≤nssons Gr°nlands Annaler), and has been variously placed by early authorities. Torn°e (1944) suggested this lo

name: Breithorn Gletscher
description: Glacier in the southern Werner Bjerge, draining into the NW end of Pingo Dal. The name was given by Peter Bearth and Eduard Wenk during Lauge Koch's 1953-54 expeditions, and named after the mountain at the head of the glacier (Breithorn, now Bredehorn).

name: Breivik
description: Norwegian hunting hut on the south side of Clavering ╪, east of Eskimovig. Originally built on west Clavering ╪ by the Foldvik expedition in 1927, it was moved to this site in the summer of 1929. It was named after the bay which the Norwegians called Bre

name: Breivika
description: Bay on south Clavering ╪, equivalent to the present Eskimovig. So named in this form on 1932 NSIU maps, and as Breidvika on the later maps of Lacmann (1937). Named for the form of the bay (breid = broad, wide).

name: Fangsthytten
description: Official name for the Danish hunting hut on the south side of Ardencaple Fjord at the mouth of Femdalen, built by Nanok in September 1930. Now a ruin (1988). This hut was usually known as Femdalhytten.

name: Fangsthyttegletscher
description: Glacier in the NW Stauning Alper draining into Alpefjord. Named by John Haller during Lauge Koch's 1954 expedition, for the hunting hut west of the front of the glacier.

name: Faraway How
description: Nunatak about 1500 m high in the upper part of Wordie Gletscher, named by J.M. Wordie's 1926 Cambridge expedition. It is a whimsical name for a very distant object.

name: Farimagdalen
description: Valley south of Borgj°kel in central Dronning Louise Land containing Farigmags°. Named by the 1912-13 Den danske Ekspedition til Dronning Louises Land as Farimagsdalen or Farimag-Tal because it was easy sledging (far i mag = travel at leisure).

name: Farimags°
description: Lake in Farimagdalen, on the south side of Borgj°kel, Dronning Louise Land. Named by the 1912-13 Den danske Ekspedition til Dronning Louises Land as Farimagsvandet or Farimags°en, because it was covered by snow-free smooth ice. (Farimagsee.)

name: Farsund
description: Sound between Winge Kyst and N°rre Orienterings°, off the south coast of Germania Land. So named by Christian B. Thostrup during the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen because they always travelled this way during their journeys in Dove Bugt; however, in his

name: Farvefjeldet
description: Mountain on the north side of western Sµls°en. Named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition, for the contrasting colours of the rocks (farve = colour). (Farvefjµldet.)

name: Farvel Nunatak
description: This ænunatak' was originally two small nunataks close together, the most westerly nunataks of Dronning Louise Land (Fig. 21). Since 1954 the melting of the ice has revealed a group of six closely spaced nunataks. So named by the 1952-54 British North Gr

name: Fata Morgana Landet
description: Elusive land area or island supposedly lying between NE Greenland and Spitsbergen. Eigil Knuth (1940) reported it was first seen by Johan Peter Koch and Aage Bertelsen in 1907, and subsequently noted by Lauge Koch from the air in 1933, and by Peter Freuc

name: Fault Valley
description: Name used by Gunnar SΣve-S÷derbergh during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen for a deep and narrow valley on the NW side of Celsius Bjerg, Ymer ╪. In SΣve-S÷derbergh (1933) Northern Fault Valley is used for this feature and together with Southern Fault Val

name: Fausts°en
description: Long lake in innermost Eremitdal, central AndrΘe Land. Named by John Haller during Lauge Koch's 1949-51 expeditions, for the magical, grave and mysterious scenery surrounding the lake. Faust, or Dr. Faustus, was the hero of the legend of a German astrolo

name: Colle Colosseum
description: Col 1950 m high between Colosseum Gletscher and Vertebrµ, north Stauning Alper. Climbed on 27 July 1984 by Sandro Pucci's climbing expedition, and named after the Colosseum in Rome, one of the most impressive of Roman remains.

name: Colle Genova
description: Broad col on Torvgletscher, Volquaart Boon Kyst. Named by Leonardo Bonzi's 1934 expedition, after the Italian city. The expedition also used the name Ghiacciao Genova for the present Torvgletscher.

name: Colle Milano
description: Col at the head of Milano Gletscher, between Punta Gilberti and Punta Balestrieri, Volquaart Boon Kyst. Named by Leonardo Bonzi's 1934 expedition. Milan was the point of departure of the expedition.

name: Collet Bjerg
description: Mountain about 1550 m high in central Hudson Land, NE of Ritoms°. Named by Heinrich Bⁿtler during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition led by Lauge Koch, after LΘon William Collet [1880-1957], a noted Swiss geologist and geomorphologist. (Collets Bjerg, Colle

name: Coloradodal
description: Valley in north Jameson Land draining NW into ╪rsted Dal. So named by Hans Stauber during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition led by Lauge Koch because the valley is incised into coloured layered rocks reminiscent of the Grand Canyon, Colorado.

name: Coloradodal Hytten
description: Hut in northern Jameson Land built in July 1983 for Gr°nlands Milj°unders°gelse where the rivers draining Coloradodal and Major Paars Dal meet at Qilerneq. It was used by a group studying and marking muskox.

name: Colosseum Gletscher
description: Glacier on the north side of Gully Gletscher, Stauning Alper. Named by the 1984 climbing expedition after the Colosseum in Rome. See also Colle Colosseum.

name: Coltart
description: Summit 2395 m high in the upper reaches of Sefstr÷m Gletscher. Climbed by the 1998 Scottish Mountaineering Club expedition, and so named for a shape like a lobster claw.

name: Combe d'Argent
description: Tributary glacier on the west side of Prinsessegletscher, eastern Nathorst Land. Named by the 1968 ExpΘdition Franτaise au Groenland Nord-Est led by Claude Rey expedition, perhaps for the colour (combe d'argent = silver comb).

name: Commandment Peak
description: High point, 2127 m high, on the ice cap south of Edward Bailey Gletscher and east of Catalinadal, Renland. Climbed and named by the 2007 West Lancashire Mountaineering Group expedition.

name: Concordia
description: Confluence of several glaciers in central Bj°rnbo Gletscher, Stauning Alper, forming a broad level area. So named by John Hunt's 1960 expedition after similar glacier confluences in the Swiss Alps.

name: Concordia Fjeld
description: Nunatak in Arnold Escher Land north of a confluence of glaciers. Named during Lauge Koch's 1951 expedition by Hans R. Katz.

name: Concordia Plads
description: Confluence of glaciers north of Cecilia Nunatak. So named by EugΦne Wegmann during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen after the similarly named glacier confluences in the Swiss Alps. (Konkordiaplatz).

name: C⌠ne des Eboulis
description: Mountain about 1600 m high west of the front of Prinsessegletscher. Named and first climbed by the 1968 ExpΘdition Franτaise au Groenland Nord-Est led by Claude Rey.

name: Consolation Point
description: Summit 1914 m high south of Edward Bailey Gletscher, Renland. Climbed and named by the 2007 West Lancashire Mountaineering Group Expedition.

name: Alpefjordhytten
description: Norwegian hunting hut on the east side of Alpefjord. It was built by the 1932-34 Helge Ingstad expedition. (Alpehuset.)

name: Alvinh÷gda
description: Hill 365 m high in southern Hold with Hope, east of Myggbukta. The name is found on an NSIU map (1932a), and is apparently derived from a personal name.

name: Alwin Pedersens Hus
description: Hut built in August 1938 at Hvalrosodden, adjacent to Hvalrosodden Station, and used by the zoologist Alwin Pedersen during the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition. It was in good condition in 1990.

name: Amaroqarteq
description: Inuit ruin on the north coast of Nordvestfjord, opposite the mouth of Flyverfjord. Recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, the name translates as æwhere there are wolves'.

name: Ambolten
description: Island in J°kelbugten, named by Eigil Knuth's 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition together with Stigb°jlen and Hammeren, for an apparent resemblance in shape to bones in the ear (ambolt = anvil).

name: Amdrup Havn
description: Small sheltered bay east of the settlement of Scoresbysund [Illoqqortoormiut], southern Liverpool Land. First visited by Otto Nordenskj÷ld in 1900, the bay was named subsequently by the 1924-25 colonisation expedition after Georg Carl Amdrup [1866-1947],

name: Amdrup Hytte
description: Hut built by the 1898-1900 Carlsbergfondets Expedition in a small bay on the north side of Kap Dalton, northern Blosseville Kyst. It was intended as an emergency wintering hut for the planned 1900 coast exploration, and features on expedition maps as Amd

name: Favre Bjerg
description: Mountain about 1900 m high in central Hudson Land. Named by Heinrich Bⁿtler during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition led by Lauge Koch, after Jean Alphonse Favre [1815-1890], a Swiss structural geologist and pioneer of alpine geology, who became director o

name: Faxa S°
description: Large lake in western Gσseland, draining via Hj°rnedal to F°nfjord. It was reported by Eduard Wenk to have been so called throughout the 1958 summer by Lauge Koch, expedition members, and the crew of the FlugfΘlag Islands Catalina which landed Wenk and h

name: Fegin Elv
description: River in Jameson Land draining SW to Hall Bredning. One of a group of names given by the Place Name Committee in 1939, it was given for Finn Fegin, son of Olav den Hellige, who was lost with his ship in Greenland in about 1028. See also Lodin Elv.

name: Fellenberg Gletscher
description: Glacier in Hudson Land. Named by Wolf Maync and Andreas Vischer during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition led by Lauge Koch after one of the pioneers of Swiss geology, E. von Fellenberg. Lacmann's (1937) maps use H÷ygaardbreen.

name: Felspingo
description: Name used by Mⁿller (1959) for the remains of a pingo in Pingo Dal, north Jameson Land, which consists of a barrier of rock debris 29 m high across the valley (fels = rock).

name: Femdalen
description: Valley on the SW side of Ardencaple Fjord, named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen in the form Fem-Dalene because it branches into five valleys. (Femdalene.)

name: Darien
description: Small snow peak about 2400 m high on the divide between the heads of Bj°rnbo Gletscher and Spµrregletscher, Stauning Alper, first climbed by James Clarkson's 1961 expedition. Darien was the name formerly applied to the entire district of Panama, where, f

name: Darien Pass
description: Pass between the upper part of Bj°rnbo Gletscher, and the head of Spµrregletscher, Stauning Alper. The name is used by Bennet (1972), and derives from nearby Darien.

name: Daudmanns°yra
description: Coastal stretch of D°demandsbugten in south Clavering ╪, where numerous Inuit houses and graves occur (daudmann = dead man). The name was reported in 1930 as used by Norwegian hunters, and subsequently incorporated in NSIU charts (Lacmann 1937). Danish h

name: Daugaard-Jensen Gletscher
description: Large glacier between Hinks Land and Charcot Land, and one of the most productive in East Greenland. The name first appears on the 1932 1:1 million scale Geodµtisk Institut map prepared on the basis of aerial observations by Lauge Koch during the 1931-34

name: Davy Sund
description: Wide inlet connecting to the NW with Kong Oscar Fjord. William Scoresby Jr. named Davyæs Sound in 1822 for Sir Humphry Davy [1778-1829]. Davy was a noted chemist, president of the Royal Society 1820-27, and most remembered for his invention of the miners

name: Davy Sund Hytten
description: Norwegian hut on the south side of Davy Sund, NW of Kap Biot, built in August 1930. It has also been known as Biot-Stua and Villa. (David Sund Hytten).

name: Dead Lake
description: Large lake SW of Klµgbugt, Nordmarken. Named by the 1987 Irish expedition to northern East Greenland.

name: Deichmann Fjord
description: Fjord SW of Manby Halv° on the northern Blosseville Kyst. Named by the 1898-1900 Carlsbergfondets Expedition after Henrik Deichmann [1871-1939], entomologist, physician and ornithologist on the expedition. He had also taken part in Carl H. Ryder's 1891-9

name: Delta ╪en
description: Name occasionally used on maps in the 1950s for the large area between two branches of Tunnelelv, that before Mestersvig airfield was built appeared as an island during the melt when rivers were high.

name: Deltadal
description: Wide, flat-bottomed valley draining into Mesters Vig, marked by a meandering network of streams and deposits of sand and mud. The name was adopted by the Place Name Committee from a suggestion by Peter Bearth and Eduard Wenk during Lauge Koch's 1953-54 e

name: Demos Glacier
description: Minor glacier on the SW side of Bj°rnbo Gletscher, Stauning Alper. The name appears on some of the maps of James Clarkson's 1961 expedition and in Bennet (1972). Possibly named after Deimos, a small moon of Mars.

name: Den Ny Hytte
description: Hut built by Danmarkshavn weather station personnel in 1966 on an island in Dove Bugt, NE of Licht ╪. The name means æthe new hut'.

name: Favoritdal
description: Valley on the SE slope of Zackenberg. The name is used as a reference locality by scientists visiting Zackenberg Forskingsstation (e.g. Meltofte & Thing 1996). (Favorite valley.)

name: Immikkeertikajiit Martik
description: Two islands off the coast of north Liverpool Land. Recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, the name translates as æthe two islands'. (IngmφkΩrtikajεt martik.)

name: Immikkeertikajik
description: Island off the east coast of south Liverpool Land. Recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, the name means æthe little island'. (IngmφkΩrtikajik.)

name: Immikkeertikajik
description: Island on the north Blosseville Kyst. One of the names recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, it translates as æthe little island'. (IngmφkΩrtikajik.)

name: Immikkeertikajik
description: Island east of Sydkap, at the mouth of Nordvestfjord. The name was recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, and means æthe little island'. (IngmφkΩrtikajik.)

name: Immikkeertikajik Kiattikajik
description: Island in east Liverpool Land between Campbell Sund and Tvµrsund. One of the names recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration.

name: Immikkeertikajik Uunertertalik
description: Island off the east coast of Liverpool Land. Recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, the name means æthe little island which has something that burns', a reference to hot springs on the SW side of the island. (IngmφkΩrtikajik √narterta

name: Immikkeertivaqqat
description: Two islands and a skerry east of Sydkap. One of the names recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, it translates as æthe small islands'. (IngmφkΩrtivarqat.)

name: Immikkoortilaq
description: Prominent high and narrow peninsula of northern Hinks Land projecting eastwards into Nordvestfjord. It is connected to Hinks Land by a relatively low neck of land. Recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, the name can be translated as æ

name: Imperial College Peak
description: Minor peak on the north ridge of Merchiston Tinde, at the head of Bersµrkerbrµ, Stauning Alper. The name was used by the 1968 Queen Mary College expedition during their climb of Bersµrker Tinde via this ridge. A cairn from the 1963 Imperial College exped

name: Indelukket
description: Hidden valley in Bartholin Land, closed off at both east and west ends by glaciers. The name is said to have originated from the wintering party at Eskimonµs during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen (indelukket = shut in).

name: Inderbredningen
description: Broad bay at the front of Soranerbreen east of Rechnitzer Land. Named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition, possibly by Paul Gelting during his journey in April 1939 (inderbredning = inner bay).

name: Inderdal
description: Valley on east Traill ╪ draining the Mols Bjerge. Named by Hans P. Schaub during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition led by Lauge Koch, for its position within the mountains. It appears as Binnental on Stauber's (1938) map. (Indlandsdal.)

name: Inderdalen
description: Valley on south Gauss Halv°, draining east into Margrethedal. Named by Wolf Maync and Andreas Vischer during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition led by Lauge Koch.

name: Inderfjord
description: Fjord in east Liverpool Land, SW of Kap Vidar. So named by Laurits Bruhn during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen because of its situation in the interior of a fjord and island complex.

name: Inderhytten
description: Norwegian hunting hut built in September 1931 about 10 km from the inner end of Forsblad Fjord by the M°re expedition. It was destroyed by an avalanche in the spring of 1976. It had also been known as Bj°rktun.

name: Immikkeerterajivit Qeqqartiit
description: Middle island of the Fame ╪er group in Hurry Inlet. The name was recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, and means æthe middle island'. (IngmφkΩrterajivit qeqartεt, Immikkoortukajik.)

name: Inderhytten
description: Norwegian hunting hut built in September 1938 by the Fransk-Norsk Polarekspedition on a small peninsula in the NE corner of Berg Fjord. It is also known as Bergfjordhytten.

name: Inderhytten
