description: Danish hunting hut on the north coast of inner Sµls°en, said to have been built by Nanok in 1938. Officially known as Inderhytten, it has also been known as Bundhytten, although in fact the hut was never built (P.S. Mikkelsen 1994, 2008). The innermost h

name: Ingerborgvatnet
description: Lake in extreme SE Geographical Society ╪. So named on NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937), after Ingeborg Leuch Elieson [b. 1884], wife of Werner Werenskiold. See also Werenskioldflya.

name: Ingers Vig
description: Name used for a bay on the north side of Bessel Fjord by Poulsen (1991, p. 191). It may have been named after Inger Martie Thostrup [b. 1884], sister of Christian Thostrup (J. L°ve, personal communication 2009).

name: Kronen
description: Prominent mountain 674 m high NW of Kap Leslie, east Milne Land. Named by Alfred Rosenkrantz during Lauge Koch's 1926-27 expeditions as Mt Kronen, for the shape of its summit (kronen = the crown). (Kronenberg.)

name: Kronprins Christian Land
description: Extensive land area between Danmark Fjord to the west and the Greenland Sea (Gr°nlandshavet) to the east, with a southern boundary at Nioghalvfjerdsfjorden. So named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen after the then Crown Prince of Denmark, later King

name: Kronprins Frederik Land
description: Land area at the NE margin of the Inland Ice including a large part of North Greenland west of Kronprins Christian Land. It commemorates the journey made by Kronprins Frederik of Denmark in 2000 as a member of the Sirius Sledge Patrol. Kronprins (Crown P

name: Krosseyjar
description: According to Torn°e (1944) the group of islands in the SW part of Dove Bugt may have been the æKrosseyjar' of the Icelandic sagas, but the identification is highly speculative. The description in Bj°rrn J≤nssons Gr°nlands Annaler is of four large islands

name: Krumme Langs°
description: Long lake in west Hudson Land, with a pronounced right-angled bend (krumme = bend). Named by Th. Johansen during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen. Gaassj° has also been used. (Krumme Langsee.)

name: Krummedal
description: Valley with a pronounced hook-like shape, draining via Rencontre Dal to Flyverfjord. Named by Peter Vogt during Lauge Koch's 1957 expedition (krumme = bend).

name: Krypt Gletscher
description: Minor glacier in a deep, crypt-like valley in the Syltopperne, north Stauning Alper. Named by the 1963 University of Cambridge expedition who ascended the glacier on their route to Menander Spir. (Crypt Glacier.)

name: Kuhn ╪
description: Large island NW of Wollaston Forland (Fig. 15). Named by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt as Kuhn Insel, after the Austrian war minister, Baron Franz Kuhn [1817-1896], who supplied generous quantities of rifles and ammunition to the expedit

name: Kuhnpashytten
description: Danish hunting hut west of Kuhnpasset, Wollaston Forland, about 6 km from the coast. Built by Nanok in July 1951. (Kuhn Pas-hytten.)

name: Kuhnpasset
description: Pass in Wollaston Forland between Cardiocerasbjerg and Aucellabjerg. Named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Hans Frebold as Kuhnpas, perhaps because it was used as a route to Kuhn ╪.

name: Kuldal
description: Small valley NE of the settlement at Kap Brewster, so named for a sequence of Tertiary sediments containing three coal beds. Greenlanders collected coal here. The name was used by Hassan (1953) in his description of material collected during Lauge Koch's

name: Kuldedal
description: Valley west of southern Schuchert Flod draining into ╪demarksdal, eroded in barren, sterile sandstone. Named by Enrico Kempter during Lauge Koch's 1956-58 expeditions.

name: Kulfjeldet
description: Coastal cliffs adjacent to Kulhus, where Danish hunters have mined substantial supplies of coal (Hansen 1939; Nyholm-Poulsen 1985). The official name of this locality is Jarners Kulmine. (Kulfjµld.)

name: Kulhus
description: Danish scientific station on the SW coast of Hochstetter Forland, built in 1932 during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen. It was named for the nearby outcrops of coal - see also Kulfjeldet and Jarners Kulmine. The station was rarely used after the 1930s, a

name: Margerie Dal
description: Valley on SW Ymer ╪, named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by EugΦne Wegmann as Margerie Valley after Emmanuel de Margerie [1862-1953], a noted French geologist and geographer. He was an honorary professor at the University of Strasbourg, libraria

name: Margretabjerg
description: Mountain 2430 m high on the west side of upper Storgletscher with an M-shape as seen from the SW, central Stauning Alper. Climbed and named by the 2007 SMC East Greenland Expedition; the name was given for Margaret N. Litterick [1927ù2005].

name: Margrethedal
description: Valley on south Gauss Halv°, named during Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions in the form Margrethe Valley, after the wife of Richard B°gvad. B°gvad and Arne Noe-Nygaard worked here in August 1930. Norwegian maps use the name Smedal or Smedal Valley.

name: Maria ╪
description: Island north of Ella ╪ at the mouth of Kempe Fjord. Named by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst after Nathorst's daughter Ella Maria Charlotte [b.1881], in the form Marias ╓ (Fig. 8). See also Ruth ╪ and Ella ╪. (Maria Island

name: Lepidurus Loch
description: Name used by the 1968-74 University of Dundee expeditions for a very small lake in the hills west of Nyhavn, because of the occurrence of æLepidurus arcticus', a common freshwater entomostracean (daphnia).

name: Lepidurus Pond
description: Two small ponds SW of Sommerfugls°, north of Zackenberg Forskningsstation, were given the names Lepidurus Pond 1 and Lepidurus Pond 2 by Kirsten S. Christoffersen in 1998. The names record the abundant tadpole shrimps of the genus Lepidurus (daphnia). In

name: Lerbugt
description: Bay on the north coast of Clavering ╪, named on NSIU 1937 maps in the form Leirevag, for the clay deposits. (Ler Bugt, Ler Bay, Leirevaagen, Leirvσgen.)

name: Lerelv
description: Large river draining into the west side of R°defjord. So named by the 1891-92 Den ╪stgr°nlandske expedition because of the large banks of clay and silt formed at its mouth.

name: Lerelv
description: Clayey river draining into the south side of C.F. Mourier Fjord, west of Kap Li. The name was first used by David Malmquist, following his surveying in the region with the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen.

name: Lers°en
description: Name used by Danish hunters for a lake behind the hunting station Nanok in southern Hochstetter Forland (Hansen 1939).

name: Lervig
description: Small bay on the SE coast of Clavering ╪. The name was first used by Gelting (1934) as a botanical reference locality during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, and records the clayey nature of the bay.

name: Ler°
description: Small island in ╪sterelven, north of Danmark Havn, largely made up of clay (= ler). So named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen, and first used in the description of the vegetation by Lundager (1912). (Ler÷.)

name: Les Cinq Doigts
description: Line of five nunataks on the south side of Charcot Gletscher, SE Milne Land. So named by Parat & Drach (1934) in their report on J.B. Charcot's 1933 expedition. There were five in 1933, but three have merged, and there are now two with a long thin strip

name: Les Diablarets
description: Name used in a climbing report by Buess (1953) for the ridge on the north side of Knµkdalen, opposite Portgletscher. It was climbed by a party during explorations on Lauge Koch's 1951 expedition, and apparently resembles the 3246 m peak above the Swiss w

name: Leutkircher Tinde
description: Mountain on the SW side of Roslin Gletscher. Climbed by the 1966 Deutsche Gr÷nland-Expedition in die Staunings-Alpen led by Karl M. Herligkoffer on 21 August, and named after the Bavarian town of Leutkirch. (Leutkirchnertinde.)

name: Levynitfjeld
description: Mountain ridge 1826 m high between Magga Dan Gletscher and Kista Dan Gletscher. Named by W. Stuart Watt during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions for an occurrence of the zeolite mineral levynit.

name: Liaselv
description: River on the west side of Carlsberg Fjord north of Liasryggen. So named by Hans Stauber during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition because it cuts through rocks of Liassic age.

name: Liasryggen
description: Mountain ridge 840 m high in eastern Jameson Land, west of inner Carlsberg Fjord. Named in geological reports on work during the Lauge Koch expeditions by John H. Callomon, for the age of the rocks.

name: Moskusdalen
description: Name given by the 1930-32 M°re expedition to the first side valley to Blomsterdal, south of their hunting station at Antarctic Havn. It is possibly the present Flexurdal (Rogne 1981). Named for the numerous muskoxen. Steinr°isdal has been used for the sa

name: Moskusdalen
description: Name used by Sigurd Skaun and Harald Welde in 1932 for the present Johan Davidsen Dal, the boundary between Ole R°mer Land and west Hudson Land. It was named for the numerous muskox (Fig. 60).

name: Moskusfjorden
description: Name used during the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen for the locality where A.L.V. Manniche had shot muskoxen in 1906 (Poulsen 1991), probably the bay east of Snenµs.

name: Moskusheimen
description: Norwegian hunting station on the west side of the sound Revet, west of Clavering ╪. Built by Henry Rudi during the Devold expedition in 1928, and so named because while building it a flock of muskox came down from the hills and milled around the hut as i

name: Moskusokseelv
description: River in Moskusoksekl°ft on the west side of Hurry Inlet. The name was first used in the report by Harris (1931) on his work during Lauge Koch's 1926-27 expeditions as Musk Ox River. The same name was used in error by Roberts (1935) for the present Gσsee

name: Moskusokseelv
description: River on SE Clavering ╪, named during Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions in the form Muskox River or Musk-Ox River, after the numerous muskox. It has also been called Mausa and Giskovselv. (Muskusoksenelv.)

name: Moskusoksefjeld
description: Mountain about 1100 m high in south Strindberg Land, named by Hans R. Katz during Lauge Koch's 1948-49 expeditions after the muskox. (Moskusoksefjµld.)

name: Moskusoksefjeldene
description: Range of hills in Germania Land east of Hvalrosodden, named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen. Traces of muskox were seen nearly everywhere by the expedition, and some were shot here. (Moskusfjµldene, Musk-ox-mountains, Moskusoksefjelde, Muskox Mts.)

name: Kap Elisabeth
description: NE cape of Ella ╪. Named by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst, probably after Nathorst's daughter Elisabeth Jane [b. 1885]. The Norwegian hunting station 3 km south of the cape is known as Maristua. (Kap Elizabeth.)

name: Kap Ellen
description: Cape between Helge G. Backlund Fjord and V. Clausen Fjord, west of Skµrfjorden, so named during the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen. It may have been named by Henning Bistrup after his wife, Ellen Marie Birgitte Eigtved.

name: Kap Eva
description: Cape on the north side of Jordanhill opposite Kap Adam. Named as Kapp Eva on the 1932a NSIU map. The two capes were evidently named after Adam and Eve.

name: Kap Ewart
description: Cape on the north Blosseville Kyst. Named by William Scoresby Jr. in 1822 as Cape Ewart, probably after Peter Ewart [1767-1842], an engineer, and owner of a cotton mill in Manchester.

name: Kap Fennia
description: Cape in east Liverpool Land west of Trekanten. So named by Helge G. Backlund during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, after his homeland Finland.

name: Kap Fletcher
description: Cape on the east coast of Canning Land, named Cape Fletcher by William Scoresby Jr. in 1822 after an Edinburgh friend, possibly John Fletcher [1792-1836]. Scoresby's original cape was probably 3-4 km further south, the position used on Koch's (1902) map.

name: Kap Franklin
description: Cape on the east point of Gauss Halv°. It was named by William Scoresby Jr. in 1822 as Cape Franklin after John Franklin [1786-1847], a noted Arctic explorer, whose last expedition to discover the NW Passage was lost with all hands. This calamity led to

name: Kap Freuchen
description: Cape-like peninsula in Dronning Louise Land between Budolfi Isstr°m and L. Bistrup Brµ, named by the 1912-13 Den danske Ekspedition til Dronning Louises Land after Peter Freuchen, their companion during the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen. Peter Freuchen [

name: Kap Georg Cohn
description: Cape in southern Mylius-Erichsen Land, facing the Inland Ice, eastern North Greenland. It was named in 1933 during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen when a Heinkel seaplane made a reconnaissance flight from the Norske ╪er that extended over parts of Kronp

name: Kap Givagt
description: Cape on the west side of Kuhn ╪. The name is seen in reports by Helge G. Backlund on his work during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen (in: Koch 1955), and warns of the numerous, dangerous sandbanks around the cape (giv agt = beware).

name: Kap Gladstone
description: Bold headland forming the northern termination of Liverpool Land. Named Cape Gladstone by William Scoresby Jr. in 1822 (Fig. 3) as a compliment to John Gladstone [1764-1851], an enterprising Liverpool merchant and member of parliament.

name: Kap Godfred Hansen
description: Peninsula on the east coast of north Liverpool Land (Fig. 72). The name was originally used by Henning Bistrup on his coast profiles drawn in 1923 during the drift of the TEDDY, but was not approved until 1939. See also Godfred Hansen ╪.

name: Kap Graham
description: Cape SW of Kap Brewster between Kap Russel and Kap Pillans. It was named by William Scoresby Jr. in 1822, although the name does not occur on his chart. From his table of latitudes and longitudes it is clear that Scoresby's Cape Graham was intended for a

name: Kap Greg
description: Headland, almost an island, on the east coast of Liverpool Land. Named Cape Greg by William Scoresby Jr. in 1822 out of respect and regard to Samuel Greg [1758-1834] of Quarry Bank. A hunting hut was built on the low col west of the cape by Scoresbysund

name: Kap Greville
description: Cape in north Liverpool Land. William Scoresby Jr. named Cape Greville in 1822, with several other promontories after different friends chiefly resident in Edinburgh. Robert Kaye Greville [1794-1866], was a noted botanist, and like Scoresby a member of t

name: Kap Graah
description: East cape of Gunnar Andersson Land, the northern part of Ymer ╪. Named Cap Graah by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt for Wilhelm August Graah [1793-1863], a Danish naval officer, especially noted for his expedition to SE Greenland in 1828-3

name: Pasterze
description: Glacier west of the head of Tyrolerfjord. So named during the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt by Julius Payer because of its azure blue colour and purity (Payer 1876), and after the glacier of the same name in Austria. See also Grossglockner.

name: Paul Stern Land
description: Large nunatak area west of Vestfjord Gletscher. Named by Eduard Wenk after Paul Stern, a Swiss geologist who worked in East Greenland during the 1955-1958 Lauge Koch expeditions, and was the first to reach this nunatak. He died on 20 July 1959 in an acci

name: Payer Dal
description: Major valley on south Kuhn ╪. Named by Wolf Maync and Andreas Vischer during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition (Maync 1947). See also Payer Tinde.

name: Payer Gletscher
description: Glacier in north Suess Land, west of Payer Tinde. Named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Ove Simonsen. The glacier used by Payer during his ascent in 1870 was Solklargletscher. See also Payer Tinde. (Payers Gletscher.)

name: Payer Land
description: Area between Wordie Gletscher and Tyrolerfjord (Fig. 15), largely covered by an ice cap reaching an altitude of 1700 m. Named by Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions to commemorate the observations by Julius Payer in this region in 1869. See also Payer Tinde

name: Payer Tinde
description: Mountain 2320 m high in north Suess Land, named by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt as Payerspitze or Payer Spitze for Julius Johannes Ludovicus Payer [1842-1915], an Austrian army officer and polar explorer who was co-leader of the expedit

name: Pebermyntefjeld
description: Mountain 1680 m high between Rolige Brµ and Vestfjord. So named by Laurent Jemelin during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions because it is built up of red and white layers reminiscent of a peppermint.

name: Peder Andresenvika
description: Open bay on the north coast of Geographical Society ╪, south of Tveholmen. Used on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937), and named after Peder Andresen [b. 1891], a Norwegian who was captain of the S╞LBARDEN on its 1934 voyage to East Greenland.

name: Pederpynt
description: Minor cape on NE Ella ╪. Named by John W. Cowie during work carried out from 1949 to 54 on Lauge Koch's geological expeditions, after Peter J. Adams, the British geologist who worked with him.

name: Pegasus Gletscher
description: Glacier in the south Stauning Alper, a minor branch of Bj°rnbo Gletscher. Named by John Hunt's 1960 expedition as Pegasus Glacier after the constellation.

name: Pelion
description: Mountain 1200 m high in northern Jameson Land. Named by Katherina Perch-Nielsen during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions after PΘlion or ╙ros Pφlion, a mountain chain in Thessaly, Greece. In Greek mythology it was the home of centaurs. The name i

name: Pembroke Kuppel
description: Snow dome about 2710 m high on the east side of Spµrregletscher, Stauning Alper. Climbed by the 1963 Cambridge University expedition on 8 August, and named after Pembroke College, Cambridge, founded in 1347 by the Countess of Pembroke.

name: Pemmikanelv
description: River in south Germania Land draining into Slambugten east of Hvalrosodden. So named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition because depots of pemmican were made here.

name: Pemmikankl°ft
description: Depression between ╪stre Skanse and Vestre Skanse occupied by Pemmikanelv, south Germania Land. Named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition.

name: Pendelbua
description: Hunting hut on the south side of Lille Pendulum, built in the summer of 1921 for ╪stgr°nlandske Fangstkompagni when it was known as Kap Desbrowe Hus. It was repaired by the Hird expedition in 1928, who subsequently described it as a Norwegian hut under t

name: Pendulum ╪er
description: Island group off NE Wollaston Forland, made up of Sabine ╪, Lille Pendulum, Bass Rock and Hvalros ╪. So named during Douglas Clavering's 1823 expedition as the Pendulum Islands, because Edward Sabine swung the pendulum on the largest of the islands (Sabi

name: Pendulumstrµdet
description: Strait between Sabine ╪ and Lille Pendulum, named by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt as Pendulum Strasse. This may correspond to Scoresby's 1822 placing of Gael Hamke Bugt. (Pendulumstrasse, Pendulumsundet, Pendulum Straits.)

name: Naasut
description: Minor ravine in NW Hold with Hope, draining River 10. Named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Eigil Nielsen as Nasutdal, after the grass. (Naussut.)

name: Puderne
description: Snow domes on Milne Land, supposedly resembling white pillows or cushions (= puderne). Named by the Geodµtisk Institute in 1963.

name: Pukkelen
description: Nunatak on the west side of Vindue Gletscher. Named by Peter Homewood during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions for its humped shape (pukkel = hump).

name: Pukkitsivakajiip Akinnarteqitaa
description: Penisula between Manby Halv° and Turner ╪, on the northern Blosseville Kyst. One of the names recorded by the Geodµtisk Institute 1955 survey, the name derives from its location relative to Pukkitsivakajik [Manby Halv°]. (P·kitsivakajεp ak∞narteqitΓ.)

name: Pukkitsivakajiip Kiammut Kangertiva
description: Fjord on the northern Blosseville Kyst. The name was recorded by the Geodµtisk Institute 1955 survey, and translates as æthe fjord with Pukkitsiakajik to its north'. (P·kitsivakajεp kißmut kangertiva).

name: Pukkitsivakajiip Oqqummut Kangertiva
description: Fjord SW of Pukkitsivakajik [Manby Halv°]. One of the names recorded by the Geodµtisk Institute 1955 survey, the name translates as æthe fjord in the lea of Pukkitsivakajik'. (P·kitsivakajεp orqungmut kangertiva).

name: Pukkitsivakajik
description: Peninsula on the north Blosseville Kyst, SW of Kap Brewster. The name was recorded by the Geodµtisk Institute 1955 survey, and translates roughly as æthe little low', a reference to its relative prominence. (P·kitsivakajik, Pukkitsukajik).

name: Pukukkiarpik
description: Hillside NE of Ittaajimmit [Kap Hope], SW Liverpool Land. Recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, the name means æwhere one picks berries to take home'. (Pukugkiarpik.)

name: Pulfrichfjellet
description: Mountain ridge on north Clavering ╪. Used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937), and named after Carl Pulfrich [1858-1927], a German scientist who was one of the founders of the photogrammetric developments of Carl Zeiss, Jena.

name: Punktum
description: Small nunatak 2175 m high in SW Dronning Louise Land (Fig. 21), so named by the 1912-13 Den danske Ekspedition til Dronning Louises Land because it was the last nunatak passed before crossing the Inland Ice (punktum = full stop).

name: Punta Celso Gilberti
description: Mountain 1262 m high west of Milano Gletscher on Volquaart Boon Kyst. It was climbed by Leonardo Bonzi's 1934 expedition, and named after an Italian climber killed in a mountaineering accident in 1933. (Gilberti Peak.)

name: Punta Club Alpino Italiano
description: Mountain on the Volquaart Boon Kyst, the present Sfinxen. It was climbed by Leonardo Bonzi's 1934 expedition. (P. CAI, Club Alpino Italiano Peak.)

name: Punta Karfen
description: Peak in the Vikingbrµ region, climbed by G. Dionisi's 1982 expedition.

name: North Gletscher
description: Name used on 1951 USAF aeronautical charts for the present F. Graae Gletscher at the innermost end of Nordvestfjord. North-West Gletscher has also been used.

name: North Lochan
description: Name used by University of Dundee expeditions between 1968 and 1974 for a small pool near Langdyssen at the NE end of Mestersvig airfield.

name: North River
description: Name used by University of Dundee expeditions between 1968 and 1974 for a minor stream west of Karupelv draining into Holm Bugt, SW Traill ╪.

name: North-West Gletscher
description: Name used on 1957 AMS maps for the present F. Graae Gletscher at the head of Nordvestfjord. North Gletscher has also been used.

name: Notting Hill
description: Mountain 2400 m high on the south side of Dunottar Gletscher, north Stauning Alper. First climbed by the 1963 Imperial College expedition, and named after the London district of north Kensington, now best known for its Caribbean carnival. There has been

name: Nuaa
description: Cape in south Liverpool Land. The name was recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, and means æthe cape'. (N√a.)

name: Nuclei
description: Name used by Mittelholzer (1941) for the three peaks Monacleus, Binucleus and Trinucleus on Clavering ╪, in his report on work during Lauge Koch's 1938-39 expeditions.

name: Nucleisee
description: Small lake in Gr°nnedal, east Clavering ╪, east of the mountain group which Mittelholzer (1941) called Nuclei.

name: Nukkaatsoq
description: Hill in south Liverpool Land west of Scoresbysund. Recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, the name translates as æthat which is believed to have great strength'. (N·kaitsoq.)

name: Nuldal
description: Valley SW of Ekspeditionshuset draining into Mesters Vig. Named by prospecting teams associated with Lauge Koch's 1948-49 expeditions. On the 1:15 000 maps of the Mesters Vig region it is situated between two groups of rivers referred to informally as 1╪

name: Mariager Fjord
description: Fjord on the east coast of Liverpool Land. Named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Laurits Bruhn after the fjord of the same name on the east coast of Jylland, Denmark.

name: Marianne Nunatakker
description: Group of nunataks in Wordie Gletscher, named by Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions as the Marianne Nunataks. They were visited by a geological party in 1932. Girl's name.

name: Mariannes See
description: Lake east of Marianne Nunatakker on the NE side of Wordie Gletscher. The name was used by Mittelholzer (1941), and also appears on AMS maps.

name: Marie-Theresia Bjerg
description: Mountain on SE Traill ╪, so named during Lauge Koch's 1956-58 expeditions by H.P. Heres after Marie-ThΘrese of Austria [1638-83], consort of Louis XIV of France.

name: Maristua
description: Norwegian hunting hut on NE Ella ╪, 3 km south of Kap Elisabeth, built by Arktisk Nµringsdrift in 1930. The hut has also been known as Camp Lindquist.

name: Markusdal
description: Minor valley draining into Gurreholm Dal, west of Schuchert Dal. Named by Enrico Kempter during Lauge Koch's 1956-58 expeditions, after his co-worker Markus Aellen.

name: Marmorbjerg
description: Mountain in west Gletscherland, traversed by several thick marble bands. Named by John Haller following explorations during Lauge Koch's 1952-53 expeditions (marmor = marble).

name: Marmorknold
description: North point of an 890 m high nunatak on the SE side of Vestfjord Gletscher. So named by W.E.A. Phillips during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions because it was formed of yellow-white marble.

name: Marmorvigen
description: Bay on the west side of Hekla Sund, Kronprins Christian Land (Fig. 24). So named by Elmar Drastrup's 1938-39 expedition because yellow marble (= marmor) crops out at the head of the bay.

name: Maroussia
description: Small island east of Lille Koldewey where the 1905 ExpΘdition Arctique du Duc d'OrlΘans landed on 26 July 1905. The Duc named it after his yacht, the MAROUSSIA, used previously on voyages to Svalbard in 1896 and 1904. (╬lot Maroussia, Maroussia ╪, Marous

name: Marrakajik
description: Extensive muddy delta area at the head of Nordostbugt, the lower part of the Schuchert Flod braided river system. Recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, the name translates as æthe small clay'. This Greenlandic name has also been used

name: Mars Glacier
description: Glacier on the north side of Edward Bailey Gletscher, Renland. Named by the 2007 West Lancashire Mountaineering Group Expedition.

name: Mars Gletscher
description: Glacier on the north side of Bj°rnbo Gletscher, south Stauning Alper. Named Mars Glacier by John Hunt's 1960 expedition, after Mars, the fourth major planet from the sun.

name: Mars Tooth
description: Tooth-like summit about 1500 m high on northern Milne Land. It was climbed by the 1989 Greenland Milne Land Expedition.

name: Marstranderfjellet
description: Mountain 1162 m high on SW Clavering ╪, the present Vestmar Bjerg. The name is used on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937), and was given for Fredrick Marstrander [b. 1915], who took part in the 1932 NSIU expedition to East Greenland.

name: Martaajik
description: Name used by Tuborg & Sandell (1999) for an Inuit ruin site on the coast of southern Jameson Land, at the western mouth of the river draining Flakkerhuk.

name: Martin Karlsen Bugt
description: Prominent bay on the south side of central Nordvestfjord. Named during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions after the expedition ship used in 1968, the MARTIN KARLSEN, formerly the KISTA DAN. The MARTIN KARLSEN was named after the noted Norwegian sh

name: Martin Karlsen Dal
description: Valley in Th. S°rensen Land, draining into Martin Karlsen Bugt. Named during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions. See also Martin Karlsen Bugt.

name: Plinganser Col
description: Col between the upper part of Duart Gletscher and the upper basin of Spµrregletscher. Climbed and so named by the 1966 Deutsche Gr÷nland-Expedition in die Staunings-Alpen led by Karl M. Herligkoffer.

name: Plovjernet
description: Mountain on the east side of Vikingebugt. So named by Laurits Bruhn during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen for its appearance (plovjern = plough share).

name: Pluto Nunatak
description: Nunatak on the west side of Nordenski÷ld Gletscher, where the Danish Air Force Catalina 853 æPluto' dropped provisions on 23 July 1953 for the use of a geological exploration party. Named by John Haller, who reached the summit with other members of the p

name: Kap H.N. Andersen
description: NE cape of Hovgaard ╪. So named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen after Hans Niels Andersen [1852-1937], one of the founders and a director of the ╪stasiatiske Kompagni, then Denmark's largest shipping company. The company had contributed 10 000 Danis

name: Gammel Hellerup Gletscher
description: Glacier between N°rreland and N°rre Mellemland, Hertugen af OrlΘans Land. Named during the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition by Svend S°lver, after Gammel Hellerup Gymnasium, his old school.

name: Gamssteig
description: Feature in the vicinity of the base camp of the 1943-44 Operation Bassgeiger at Kap Sussi, Shannon. The name is recorded by Olsen (1965).

name: Gamvik
description: Norwegian hunting hut on the east coast of Hold with Hope, NW of Holland ╪. Built by Nils Foldvik's expedition in August 1927, the hut name appears in the Orvin (1930) list of hunting huts. It may have been named after Gamvik in the Troms° region of Norw

name: Gannochy Gletscher
description: Glacier in the Stauning Alper, between Storgletscher and Roslin Gletscher. Named and explored by the 1968 University of Dundee expedition.

name: Garagebugt
description: Bay on the north side of Flyverfjord, the present Lancaster Bugt, where numerous icebergs are stranded, as if parked in a garage. So named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Helge G. Backlund (in: Koch 1955).

name: Garbh Bheinn
description: Name appearing in an early report of the 1958 Scottish East Greenland expedition led by Malcolm Slesser for the present Dunvegan Toppene (Bennet 1959), in the north Stauning Alper. It was named for its resemblance to a Scottish mountain of the same name.

name: Garde Nunatakker
description: Nunatak group west of Hertugen af OrlΦans Land, including Gr°nne Nunatak and Tuborgfondet Land. Named by the 1909-12 Alabama-ekspeditionen after Captain Thomas Vilhelm Garde [1859-1926], director of the Naval Department and from 1918 admiral, who had sho

name: Garmischer Spids
description: Mountain 2209 m high on the SW side of Roslin Gletscher, Stauning Alper. Climbed by the 1966 Deutsche Gr÷nland-Expedition in die Staunings-Alpen led by Karl M. Herligkoffer, and named after the Bavarian mountain resort of Garmish-Partenkirchen.

name: Gasserfjellet
description: Mountain about 1000 m high on central Geographical Society ╪. Used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937), the name was given for Max Gasser [1872-1954], one of the pioneers in the development of practical mapping techniques from aerial photographs.

name: Gastisdal
description: Valley on Gauss Halv° draining north into Moskusoksefjord. Named by Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions in the form Gastis Valley, it commemorates the then famous Uppsala restaurant æGΣstis'.

name: Gauche Peak
description: Mountain at the head of Schuchert Gletscher, SE of Trumpington Pas, Stauning Alper. First climbed by the 1961 University of Bangor expedition.

name: Gauli Dal
description: Valley in southern AndrΘe Land, draining west from Gauli Gletscher. Named by John Haller following explorations during Lauge Koch's 1949-51 expeditions. See also Gauli Gletscher.

name: Gauli Gletscher
description: Glacier in southern AndrΘe Land. Named by John Haller following explorations during Lauge Koch's 1949-51 expeditions after the glacier of this name in the Bernese Oberland, Switzerland, where an American war plane had made an emergency landing. Gauli Gle

name: Gausa
description: River in west Hold with Hope flowing into the head of Loch Fyne. So named on an NSIU map (1932a), possibly after the river Gausa in the Oppland district of Norway.

name: Gauss Halv°
description: Peninsula between Muskusoksefjord and Kejser Franz Joseph Fjord. The 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt originally gave the name Cap Gauss to a point on the south side of this peninsula, probably the present Sydvestpynt, but the 1899 Swedish East

name: Gavlen
description: Mountain 1150 m high on Volquaart Boon Kyst, so named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Laurits Bruhn because in shape it resembled the gable of a house.

name: Gedderyggen
description: Mountain ridge 1050 m high on west Clavering ╪. The name originated from the wintering party at Eskimonµs during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen and was given for the spikey appearance, like the fin of a fish (gedde = pike).

name: Gefion Havn
description: Harbour on the south coast of Godfred Hansen ╪, SW Dove Bugt. So named after the three-masted Danish schooner GEFION, the ship of the 1932 Gefion expedition which anchored here and unloaded building material in the harbour. The Nanok hunting station ┼lbo

name: Gefion Havn Hytten
description: Danish hunting hut built for Nanok in May 1934 at Gefion Havn, on the south side of Godfred Hansen ╪, SW Dove Bugt. It was replaced in 1938 by ┼lborghus hunting station.

name: Nadel Klipper
description: Name used on a map in Wegener (1932) for the present Neill Klinter, a cliff on the west side of Hurry Inlet. It probably arises from a mis-reading of æNeill'.

name: Nail Glacier
description: Tributary glacier to Pasterze on its south side. The name was used by Battle (1952).

name: Nakkaakajik
description: Small glacier on Volquaart Boon Kyst. Recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, the name means æthat which falls down', a reference to active calving of the front. (NßkΓkajik.)

name: Nakkehoved
description: Peninsula on the east coast of Liverpool Land, north of the mouth of Horsens Fjord. So named by Laurits Bruhn during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen after the headland of the same name in north Sjµlland, Denmark.

name: Namsdalsstua
description: Norwegian hunting hut built for Arktisk Nµringsdrift in August 1934 at the mouth of Fladedal, south Ymer ╪, by Ole Klokset and Magne Rσum. The latter was from the Namsdalen district of Norway. The hut has also been known as Flatdalshytta, Karl Jakobsens

name: Nannabreen
description: Glacier on central Clavering ╪. Used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937), and named after Nanna, wife of Balder in old Nordic mythology.

name: Nannut Qeqertaat
description: Island group north of Milne Land. Recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, the name is a translation of the existing Danish name, meaning æbear islands'. (Nßnut qeqertait.)

name: Nanok
description: Danish hunting station on the south coast of Hochstetter Forland, built in 1929. The name commemorates the hunting company Nanok (nanok = polar bear). A radio station was added in 1931. The station was manned from 1929 to 1941, and intermittently in the

name: Nanok ╪
description: Island in SW Dove Bugt. The name was given by the Place Name Committee in 1940, to commemorate the activities of ╪stgr°nlandsk Fangstkompagni Nanok. It was a replacement of the name Tuxens°, suggested by Nanok, but rejected by the committee. (Nanoks ╓.)

name: Nanortalik
description: Locality at the mouth of Nanortalikdal in NE Suess Land, so named by Lauge Koch because he killed an unusually large bear here on 15 November 1926, and the next day met three more bears. The Greenlandic name translates as æthe place where there are many

name: Nanortalik pass
description: Name occasionally used by Eha (1953) for Dalf°ret, the pass at the crest of Nanortalikdal in Suess Land.

name: Nanortalikdal
description: Valley in Suess Land extending from north of Lumskebugten to Nanortalik at the coast of Antarctic Sund. The name was used by EugΘne Wegmann during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, and first appeared on maps as Nanortalik Valley.

name: Nanortalikhytten
description: Norwegian hunting hut at Nanortalik, Suess Land, built in 1934 for Arktisk Nµringsdrift. It was originally known as Bj°rneheim.

name: Napassorssuaq
description: Mountain 497 m high on Lille Pendulum with a spire-like summit. The name is essentially a translation of the Danish name, meaning æthe upright-standing'.

name: Naportoqs Elv
description: River at the head of Hurry Inlet, NE of Eli Bjerg. Named by Alfred Rosenkrantz during Lauge Koch's 1926-27 expeditions as Naportok River, after his Greenlandic assistant, Eli Napartok.

name: Nappangulikajiip kangersiva
description: Name recorded by the Scoresbysund local newspaper in 1984 for Hartz Vig, also known as Kangertivatsiaakajik, the bay between Kap Tobin and Kap Swainson.

name: Nappangulikajik
description: Name recorded by the Scoresbysund local newspaper in 1984 for the Kap Swainson area, and apparently also for the point known as Napparutikajik.

name: Napparsimmaviip Nuaa
description: Cape on the east side of Scoresbysund town. Recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, the name translates as æhospital cape'. It is due south of the old hospital building, which was originally the French expedition house of 1932-33. (Nßp

name: Napparutikajik
description: Point on the coast a little west of Kap Swainson, south Liverpool Land. Recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, the name means æthe little upstanding', and refers to a cairn. Nappangulikajik was reported by the Scoresbysund local newsp

name: Narhvalgletscher
description: Large glacier on the Lyell Land side of Narhvalsund, named by the 1937 Louise A. Boyd Arctic expedition as Narhval Glacier. Detailed studies were made here by Richard Foster Flint.

name: Narhvalsund
description: Sound between Ella ╪ and Lyell Land. Named by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst as Narhvalssundet because they were surprised to see a flock of narwhales here (Fig. 8). Today they are a not uncommon sight in many East Greenl

name: Nulog
description: Name used by Eha (1953) for the isolated hill on the south side of inner DusΘn Fjord known as Rumpen. This was apparently Eha's original suggestion and has the same meaning in Greenlandic (nulog = rumpen = the rump).

name: Nummer 1 Hytten
description: Danish hunting hut built in August 1930 by Nanok on the north side of Peters Bugt, and officially known as Petersbugthytten. It has also been known as Bundhytten.

name: Numsen
description: Small peninsula on east Clavering ╪ between Kap Mary and Dahls Skµr. The name appears on a sketch map in Gustav Thostrup's 1921 logbook, and was given for the shape of the peninsula (numsen = backside, bottom).

name: Nuna Land
description: Name used by Henning Bistrup in October 1907, and other members of the Danmark Ekspedition, for the present day Dronning Louise Land, that comprises numerous large and small nunataks. (Jan L°ve, personal communication, May 2012.) (Nunalandet.)

name: Nunataami Elv
description: River draining Romer S°, which flows through Vandredalen to the north inner arm of Ingolf Fjord. Named by Elmar Drastrup's 1938-39 expedition as NunatΓme Elv. Drastrup (1945) observed that the name was derived from an Inuit dialect word from the Kap York

name: 1982 Nunatak
description: Reference name for a nunatak in the Prinsen af Wales Bjerge, northern Kong Christian IX Land (Nielsen et al. 2001). Geological work was carried out here in 1982.

name: Lamprenen Dal
description: Valley west of Fleming Fjord draining NW into ╪rsted Dal. The name was one of a group of names given by the Place Name Committee in 1939 to replace proposals by Hans Stauber. It was given for one of the ships used by Jens Munk on his voyage in search of

name: Lancaster
description: Peak about 2510 m high in the south Stauning Alper between Borgbjerg Gletscher and Orion Gletscher. Climbed by the 1971 University of Lancaster expedition. See also Lancaster Bugt.

name: Lancaster Bugt
description: Deep bay on the north side of Flyverfjord. Named by Geoffrey Halliday during the 1971 Northern Universities expedition after the University of Lancaster, to which he was affiliated. The town of Lancaster grew up on the site of a Roman fortification, whil

name: Landhuset
description: Norwegian hunting hut built by the 1932-34 Helge Ingstad expedition in Pingel Dal, about 12 km south of the head of Fleming Dal. It is also known as Fleming Dal Hytten and Pingel Dal Hytten.

name: Landingsdalen
description: Valley in east Wollaston Forland, south of Kap Wynn. So named by NSIU in 1929 when the VESLEKARI was unable to reach the huts at Kap Wynn due to ice conditions, and landed all their supplies at the mouth of this valley.

name: Landtungen
description: Name used by Kempter (1961) for the tongue of land between Nordostbugt and Schuchert Flod. Langtungen was used by the 1962 Oxford University expedion for the same feature (Sugden & John 1965).

name: Lang Peak 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6
description: Series of six summits ranging from 1940 m to 2100 m in altitude on the ridge NE of Storgletscher, central Stauning Alper. Storgletscher was for a period known as Langgletscher. The 1961 Bangor Mountaineering Club expedition named the peaks, and climbed n

name: Langbjerg
description: Elongate mountain ridge up to 522 m high on Geographical Society ╪, so named during Lauge Koch's 1949-50 expedition by Desmond T. Donovan.

name: Langbjerg
description: Elongate N-S ridge on Gauss Halv°, named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Gunnar SΣve-S÷derbergh as Long Mountain.

name: Langdyssen
description: Small ridge west of Noret, north Scoresby Land, resembling an elongate burial mound (langdyssen = long barrow). Named by prospecting teams associated with Lauge Koch's 1948-49 expeditions.

name: Pluto S°
description: Lake in SW Renland, NE of Rypefjord, at the margin of Eielson Gletscher. The approved name given by J.D. Friderichsen during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions is Tappes° because the lake drains (= tappe) through Tappedal. However, the name Pluto

name: Podiet
description: Cliff in SE Paul Stern Land overlooking Vestfjord Gletscher. So named by W.E.A. Phillips during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions because it rembles a podium.

name: Point Ambler
description: Summit on the north side of Polkorridoren, Milne Land. Climbed by the 2004 West Lancashire Scouts expedition.

name: Point Hope
description: Cape in south Liverpool Land a few kilometres east of Kap Hope, corresponding to the present Basaltnµs. It is marked on maps in E. Mikkelsen (1927), and appears in some accounts as falska Kap Hope. Timber was left here in 1924 during the colonisation exp

name: Point Jilly
description: Prominent pinnacle on the north ridge of the mountain Lambeth, Stauning Alper. It was climbed by the 1996 Scottish Mountaineering Club expedition.

name: Point Neurose
description: Mountain at the head of Schuchert Gletscher, Stauning Alper. The position is somewhat uncertain, but is described in Bennet (1972) as a short distance SW of Royal Peak. It was climbed by the 1961 Bangor expedition

name: Pointe C. Jacquemard
description: Mountain on the west side of Prinsessegletscher. Named and first climbed by Claude Rey's 1968 expedition. Exact position uncertain.

name: Pointe Humbert
description: Mountain about 2100 m high on the west side of Prinsessegletscher, north of Gl. des Violettes. Named and first climbed by the 1968 ExpΘdition Franτaise au Groenland Nord-Est led by Claude Rey.

name: Pointe Michel Gravost
description: Peak on the north side of Vikingebrµ, north Stauning Alper, climbed by Claude Rey's 1970 expedition. It was reported by Bennet (1972) to be probably identical with one of the Dreispitz.

name: Pointe d'Argent
description: Rock pillar about 2480 m high on the west side of Prinsessegletscher, south of Combe d'Argent. Named and first climbed by the 1968 ExpΘdition Franτaise au Groenland Nord-Est led by Claude Rey.

name: Polarheimen
description: Norwegian hunting hut on the NE coast of Suess Land, built by Arktisk Nµringsdrift in July 1947. It has also been known as R°iskattlia and Grσkollen.

name: Polhem Dal
description: Major N-S-trending valley in east Lyell Land. Named by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst, probably after the steamer POLHEM used on the 1872-73 expedition to Spitsbergen. (Polhem Valley, Polhems Dal, Polhemdalen.)

name: Polhemsdalhytten
description: Norwegian hunting hut in Forsblad Fjord, 2 km west of Polhem Dal, built in September 1931 by the M°re expedition. It was originally known as Bµrtun. (Polheim, Polhem Dal Hytten.)

name: Pollen
description: Bay SW of Trums ╪, south of the mouth of Bessel Fjord. The name originated from the wintering party at Kulhus during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, and is a Norwegian word for a small bay. The hut in the bay, originally known as Perka Hytta, is sometim

name: Pollux
description: Peak on the SW side of the upper basin of Spµrregletscher, very close to the summit Castor. Named by the 1966 Deutsche Gr÷nland-Expedition in die Staunings-Alpen led by Karl M. Herligkoffer, although not climbed. See also Pollux Elv.

name: Pollux Elv
description: One of a pair of similar rivers in south Liverpool Land draining west into Hurry Inlet, the other being Castor Elv. Named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Laurits Bruhn after the stars Castor and Pollux, which derive their names from the twins o

name: Pollux Glacier
description: One of two minor tributaries to Spµrregletscher on its west side, named by James Clarkson's 1961 expedition. See also Pollux Elv. German mountaineering accounts use Kleine Sydney Gletscher for the same glacier.

name: Polluxbjerg
description: Mountain about 2300 m high on the south side of the west end of Fures°, opposite Castorbjerg on the north side of the lake. The two mountains were named by Hans Zweifel during Lauge Koch's 1954-55 expeditions after two mountains with similar names in Wal

name: Niviarsiat
description: Mountain on the south side of Antarctic Sund, named during Lauge Koch's 1926-27 expeditions (Koch 1929a). The mountain is formed by strongly folded exposures of the Eleonore Bay Group, and the name derives from the vivid colours, some of which are remini

name: Gefiontinder
description: Group of summits in SW Dronning Louise Land, named by the 1912-13 Den danske Ekspedition til Dronning Louises Land as Gefions Tinder. Gefion was the virgin sister of Danish gods said to have ploughed out the island of Sjµlland from Sweden in a single nig

name: Geheimrat Finsterwalders Fjell
description: N-S-trending mountain ridge in Geographical Society ╪. Used on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937), the name was given for Sebastian Finsterwalder [1862-1951], a German pioneer of theoretical developments in aerial photogrammetry.

name: Hareknoldene
description: Small hills on the east side of ╪stelv, east of Eskimonµs station, Clavering ╪. The name originated from the wintering party at Eskimonµs during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, and was named after the Arctic hares.

name: Haremarken
description: Plain in eastern AndrΘe Land between Morµnedal and Grejsdalen, named by Erdhardt FrΣnkl during Lauge Koch's 1948-50 expedition. A total of 34 hares were shot here for food one summer when the expedition ship was delayed by ice and many parties were runni

name: Hareskindpynten
description: Point on the north side of the inner part of Ingolf Fjord, Kronprins Christian Land, named by the 1938-39 Danske Hundeslµde-Ekspedition. The expedition had a camp at this location, and presumably shot and skinned a hare.

name: Hareskσret

description: Snow-capped mountain in Lambert Land. The name is one of a group of five given by the Place Name Committee for dogs used on the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen. They replaced names suggested by John Haller. æMisanthropen' was an old and rather miserable do

name: Missing Ring
description: High point (2110 m) on the ice cap north of Edward Bailey Gletscher, Renland. Climbed and named by the 2007 West Lancashire Mountaineering Group Expedition.

name: Misteltengletscher
description: Glacier on north Clavering ╪. Originally named on 1937 NSIU maps in the form Mistelteinbreen, after an enchanted sword of old Nordic mythology, Mistelten (made of mistletoe), with which H°der killed Balder. The name was first approved for general usage i

name: Mittenwalder Tinde
description: Peak about 2500 m high on the south side of the upper basin of Spµrregletscher, climbed by the 1966 Deutsche Gr÷nland-Expedition in die Staunings-Alpen led by Karl M. Herligkoffer on 18 August. Two of the climbers, Michl Anderl and Gebhard Plangger, were

name: Mitternachtspitze
description: Mountain SE of Trekant at the head of Trekantgletscher. It was climbed and so named by Wolfgang Weinzierl's 1970 expedition. This peak is probably identical with Damslottet. (Midnight Peak.)

name: Punta Roma
description: Mountain 1267 m high west of Roma Gletscher on Volquaart Boon Kyst, the present Bulbjerg. It was climbed by Leonardo Bonzi's 1934 expedition. (Rome Hill, Rome Peak.)

name: Punta Umberto Balestreri
description: Mountain 1636 m high on Volquaart Boon Kyst, the present Isjomfruen. It was climbed by Leonardo Bonzi's 1934 expedition, and dedicated to the president of the Club Alpino Accademico who had died in a mountaineering accident in 1933. (P. Balestrieri, Bale

name: Punta degli Italiani
description: Mountain 1701 m high on Volquaart Boon Kyst, the present Pyramiden. This was the highest peak climbed by Leonardo Bonzi's 1934 expedition. (P. Italiani, Peak of the Italians.)

name: Purpurfjeld
description: Mountain on south Traill ╪, SE of Dr°mmerbugt. The name came into use during Lauge Koch's geological expeditions in the 1930s, and is attributed to Helge Backlund. It derives from the colour of the rocks.

name: Purtscheller Tinde
description: Mountain between Spµrregletscher and Prinsessegletscher. First climbed by the 1967 Berchtesgaden expedition, and named probably after L. Purtscheller who made notable climbs in the Alps and on Kilimanjaro in the 1870s and 1880s.

name: Puslingen
description: Small island in Vega Sund, west of Nordenski÷ld ╪. Used on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937), and named for the shape (pusling = goblin, tiny tot).

name: Pusterdal
description: Valley at the head of Pustervig. The name was first used as a reference locality in the meteorological reports of the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen. (Pustertal, Pustervigdalen.)

name: Kumaat
description: Fossil locality at the coast on the west side of Rosenvinge Bugt, south Liverpool Land. The name was first recorded by Alfred Rosenkrantz in 1926, and reported to be that used by the settlers at Kap Hope [Ittaajimmiit]. Greenlandic Inuit are said to refe

name: Kumaat
description: Mountain on the NW side of Nathorst Fjord, named by Lauge Koch's 1926-27 expeditions as Komait, after the Inuit word for lice. Numerous fossils were collected here. The original locality was at the south foot of the mountain which now bears the name. (Ku

name: Kumaqarteq
description: Coastal stretch on the NW side of Nathorst Fjord. Recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, the name means æit has lice' (= fossils) - see also Kumaat.

name: Kuplen
description: Ice-capped mountain 1750 m high north of Rolige Brµ. Named by Laurent Jemelin during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions for the dome-like appearance.

name: Kuplen
description: Mountain 506 m high in west Wollaston Forland, named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Hans Frebold (kuplen = the dome).

name: Kuppelpashytten
description: Danish hunting hut near Kuppelpasset, near the head of Isdal. Built by Nanok in May 1946.

name: Kulh°j
description: Hill at the NW end of Annexss°en, so named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen for the occurrence of abundant loose blocks of low-grade coal. The coal blocks are found over a wide area, and the exact location of the original finds is uncertain. (Kulh÷j.

name: Kullabjerg
description: Nunatak in the upper part of Nordenski÷ld Gletscher, SW of Shackleton Bjerg. The name derives from Kullaberg (or Kullen) in southern Sweden, which features in the childrens story by Selma Lagerl÷f (see also Nils Holgersen Nunatakker).

name: Kuppelpasset
description: Pass at the head of Isdal, west Wollaston Forland, north of the mountain Kuplen. So named probably by Nanok. The name appears on a map in Jennov (1939) and also scientific reports from the same year. Hunters used the pass as a route across Wollaston Forl

name: Kursbrµ
description: Glacier in south Dronning Louise Land draining east into Farimagdal. So named by the 1912-13 Den danske Ekspedition til Dronning Louises Land because by following its direction the expedition regained their planned route (kurs = bearing). (Kursbrµen.)

name: Kuuk
description: River flowing in Elvdal, southern Liverpool Land, entering the sea at Ittoqqortoormiit [Scoresbysund]. Recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, the name means æthe river'. (K√k.)

name: Kuuk iserdoq
description: Name reported by the Scoresbysund local newspaper in 1984 as in use by the inhabitants of the town for Mσgeelv. It translates as æmuddy river'.

name: Kuukajik
description: River in south Liverpool Land, flowing into Amdrup Havn. One of the names recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, the name means æthe little river'. (K√kajik.)

name: Kuukajik
description: Small stream NE of Sydkap. The name was recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, and translates as æthe little river'. (K√kajik.)

name: Kuukajik
description: River in ╪rkendal, SE Suess Land. The name was recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, and translates as æthe little river'. (K√kajik.)

name: Kuukajik Kittikajik
description: River on the west side of Rosenvinge Bugt, southern Liverpool Land. Recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, the name translates as æthe western little river'. (K√kajik kφtikajik.)

name: Kvaksnes
description: SW peninsula of Magga ╪ in Vega Sund. So named on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937), because it resembles in shape the body of a wasp (kvaks = hveps = wasp).

name: Kvalen
description: Island in the western part of the Broch ╪er group. So named on the 1932a NSIU map, possibly from its appearance. The name may derive from the Norwegian dialect word for a whale.

name: Kvalpen
description: Small island in Vega Sund, east of the Scott Keltie ╪er. Used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937; Fig. 14), the name was given for its diminutive size (kvalp/hvalp = whelp, young dog).

name: Kvarven
description: Mountain on central Geographical Society ╪, SW of Rudbeck Bjerg. So named on the NSIU (1932a) map, and in Lacmann (1937), after a mountain of the same name in the Nordland district of Norway.

name: Kvelnadalen
description: Valley on east Clavering ╪ draining south into Lervig. So named on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937) after the Norwegian river Kvelna.

name: Kvina
description: River on the east coast of Loch Fyne, south of Midtstua. So named on an NSIU map (1932a), possibly after a river of the same name in the Vest-Agda area of south Norway.

name: Kvisladalen
description: Valley on SW Clavering ╪, the present Vildbµkdalen. The name is used on the NSIU (1932a) map, and by Lacmann (1937), and derives from the Norwegian dialect word to describe the turbulent noise of a swift-flowing river.

name: Kvitegga
description: Minor snow summit about 2400 m high on the south side of Darien Pass, just south of the snow peak Darien, on the divide between the heads of Bj°rnbo Gletscher (Main Glacier) and Spµrregletscher, Stauning Alper. It was climbed and so named by the 1996 Nor

name: Kvitfjell
description: Mountain about 2350 m high on the ridge between the heads of Gullygletscher and Schuchert Gletscher. Climbed and so named by the 1996 Norwegian Stauning Alper expedition (kvit = white).

name: Irene ╪
description: Small island 10 m high and 100 m across off the coast of Hold with Hope, about 6 km SE of Knudshoved. The name is used in Den Gr°nlandske Lods (1968), and is said to have been given by L.M. Coulet-Svendsen, the first mate on the GUSTAV HOLM in 1930. Girl

name: Irisgletscher

name: Isar-Passet
description: High pass on the SW side of Roslin Gletscher in the Stauning Alper, connecting with a branch of Mars Gletscher. So named by the 1966 Deutsche Gr÷nland-Expedition in die Staunings-Alpen led by Karl M. Herligkoffer after the Bavarian river Isar.

name: Isboksen
description: Norwegian hunting hut built in October 1929 by Arktisk Nµringsdrift on the north side of DusΘn Fjord (isboksen = icebox, freezer). It was originally known as Devoldhytta.

name: Isbrosund
description: Sound between Janus ╪ and the east coast of Liverpool Land. The name was given by Helge G. Backlund because the sound was bridged by winter ice during his explorations in 1933 (isbro = ice bridge).

name: Kap Hamburg
description: South cape of Kuhn ╪. Named Cap Hamburg by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt, probably for the German city of Hamburg, the base for one of the expedition's supporting committees, the æHamburger ComitΘ fur die Nordfahrt v. 1869'. The senate o

name: Kap Harry
description: SE cape of Ella ╪. Named by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst's, probably after Nathorst's son Harry Johan Hjalmar Nathorst [1882-1938], who became a mining engineer. Many features in the vicinity were named by Nathorst afte

name: Kap Hartlaub
description: Cape in NE Lille Pendulum. Named Cap Hartlaub by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt after Carl Johan Gustav Hartlaub [1814-1900], an ornithologist noted for his studies of African birds. Hartlaub together with Moritz Lindeman edited Koldewey'

name: Kap Hedlund
description: Prominent cape in NW Lyell Land at the mouth of Rhedin Fjord (Fig. 52). Named by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst, possibly after both Sven Adolf Hedlund [1821-1900] and Henrik Hedlund [1851-1932]. Both were publishers, and

name: Kap Hedlund Hytten
description: Hut built by Sirius in 1964 in the bay on the east side of Kap Hedlund. It replaced the Norwegian hut on the same site known as Kapp Hedlund hytta or Rimhytten.

name: Kap Helgoland
description: Northern cape of Store Koldewey. Named Cap Helgoland by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt after the island off the NW coast of Germany.

name: Kap Helgoland Hytten
description: Hut built by Danmarkshavn weather station personnel in 1965 in a small bay near Kap Helgoland. It is also known as Aldersro.

name: Kap Hendil
description: SE cape of Louise Boyd Land. This is one of the names found on the 1932 edition of the Geodµtisk Institut 1:1 million scale map, drawn from Lauge Koch's aerial observations during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen. It was named after Leif Hendil [1898-1961

name: Kap Hewitt
description: Cape on the east coast of Liverpool Land, named by William Scoresby Jr. in 1822. It was one of several names in the north part of Liverpool Land which Scoresby gave for different unspecified friends chiefly resident in Manchester. Scoresby probably inten

name: Kap Hilding
description: Cape on the west side of Trekanten, east Liverpool Land. So named by Helge G. Backlund during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen after his youngest son. Officially it is stated to be in the sense of æhilding' (= giant or warrior).

name: Kap Hodgson
description: Prominent cape in SE Liverpool Land. Named Cape Hodgson by William Scoresby Jr. in 1822 after his friend Adam Hodgson.

name: Kap Hooker
description: The south point of Jameson Land was named Cape Hooker by William Scoresby Jr. in 1822 after William Jackson Hooker [1765-1865], professor of botany at the University of Glasgow from 1821, and from 1841 director of Kew Gardens. Hooker contributed the list

name: Kap Hope
description: Greenlandic village east of Kap Hope (see below) in south Liverpool Land. The 1924-25 expedition that founded Scoresbysund built two houses here in 1924-25, and it has been continuously occupied until the late 1980s. The population in 1987 was reported a

name: L÷gtoppene
description: N-S-trending ridge between Grµnsedalen and Blµsedalen in south Wollaston Forland. The name was used by Wolf Maync and Andreas Vischer during their work on the 1936-38 Two-year expedition, and is found on Vischer's (1943) maps. The mountain summits may be

name: L°vebastionen
description: Prominent crag 2500 m high on the south side of Nordenski÷ld Gletscher (Fig. 69), named by J.M. Wordie's 1929 Cambridge expedition as Lion Bastion for its appearance (l°ve = lion). (L÷vebastionen.)

name: L°vehovedet
description: Mountain 902 m high in west Strindberg Land, on the NE side of Geologfjord. So named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Th. Johansen because of a resemblance to the L°vehovederne in north Bornholm (l°vehovedet = the lion's head).

name: Penthievre Fjord
description: NE branch of Skµrfjorden, south of Stormlandet. Named by the 1905 ExpΘdition Arctique du Duc d'OrlΘans as Fiord PenthiΦvre after a branch of the Duc's family. His great-great-grandmother was Louise-Marie AdΘlaide de Bourbon-PenthiΦvre. (PenthiΦvres Fjord

name: Perisphinctes Ravine
description: Ravine in SE Kuhn ╪, named by Maync (1947) for the finds of fossils during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition.

name: Perka Hytta
description: Norwegian hunting hut built by John Giµver's expedition in August 1932 in the small bay known as Pollen, south of the mouth of Bessel Fjord. It is also known as Pollenhytta.

name: Perlehuset

name: Permdal
description: Valley at the head of Nathorst Fjord. So named by Hans Stauber during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition, presumably because the valley is formed in Permian rocks.

name: Permdal
description: Valley in west Wollaston Forland, so named by H. Frebold during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen after the Permian rocks. It has also been called Zechsteindal.

name: Permklippen
description: Cliff about 100 m above sea level on the west side of the mouth of Mesters Vig. It was originally named Bⁿtlers Klippe. Named by prospecting teams associated with Lauge Koch's 1948-49 expeditions. The rocks are of Permian age.

name: Permpasset
description: Pass at the north end of Blµsedalen, central Wollaston Forland. So named during Lauge Koch's 1936-38 expeditions by Wolf Maync and Andreas Vischer for the outcrops of Permian dolomites (Maync 1947).

name: Pernaryggen
description: Ridge east of Kronen and NW of Kap Leslie, east Milne Land, named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by H. Aldinger as Pernarⁿcken or Perna Rⁿcken, for the fossil æPerna'.

name: Peschel Island
description: Name used in the English edition of the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt narrative (Koldewey 1874), for the landmass between Bessel Fjord and Roon Bugt which he believed to be insular, and of which Kap Peschel is the NE cape. It corresponds to

name: Peter Elv

name: Petermann Bjerg
description: Mountain 2970 m high in west Frµnkel Land (Figs 65, 69), named by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt as Petermanns Spitze. It was first seen from the ice cap NE of Payer Tinde in August 1870, and described as an ice pyramid about 3300 m high,

name: Peters Bugt
description: Bay on the SW side of Hochstetter Forland. Named by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt as Peters Bai, after Wilhelm Karl Hartvig Peters [1815-1883], who wrote one of the zoological sections for Koldewey's expedition narrative. Peters was a ph

name: Peters Bugt S°
description: Small lake on the east side of Peters Bugt. The name was first used by the 1976 Swedish-Danish East Greenland expedition that had core-sampled the lake bottom sediments (see also Bj÷rck et al. 1994).

name: Petersbugthytten
description: Danish hunting hut on the north side of Peters Bugt, Hochstetter Forland, built by Nanok in August 1930. It has also been called Bundhytten and Nummer 1 Hytten. (Peters Bugt Hytten.)

name: Pusterelv
description: Name very occasionally used for the river draining into Pustervig. It appears on a map by Charles S. Poulsen, youngest member of the the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen, which was reproduced by Lundbye (1984).

name: Pusters°
description: Name used on a sketch map by Charles S. Poulsen reproduced by Lundbye (1984), for a lake in Pusterdal. See also Pusterelv.

name: Pustervig
description: Deep small bay on the south side of M°rkefjord, south of Danmarks Monumentet. Named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen. It was originally known as Lysevig.

name: Pustervig
description: Hut used as a meteorological station by Peter Freuchen from September 1907 to April 1908, erected on the west side of Pustervig by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen. Only the stone walls reinforcing the hut remain; the wood was removed for use as firewoo

name: Pututaajik
description: Small bay on the north side of the Heywood Bjerge, south Liverpool Land. Recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, the name means æit has a hole', and refers to a natural hole or cave in the cliff. (PututΓjik.)

name: Pyramid Peak
description: Prominent rock peak 2293 m high south of Dammen, central Stauning Alper. So named and first climbed by the 1964 AAC Zⁿrich expedition. Published Geodetic Institute maps apply the name Queens Tinde to this peak.

name: Pyramide
description: This 2250 m high mountain is described as the dominant peak at the head of the Trekantgletscher basin. Climbed and so named by Wolfgang Weinzierl's 1970 expedition. Location a little uncertain.

name: Pyramidedalen
description: Valley west of Fuglenµbsfjeldet on the north side of M°rkefjord. Named by Eigil Knuth's 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition for the cones of moraine in the valley.

name: Pyramideelv
description: River draining NE from Keglen into the head of Ingolf Fjord. Probably named by John Haller following explorations during Lauge Koch's 1956-58 expeditions.

name: Pyramidefjeld
description: Mountain between the head of Vikingebrµ and Bersµrkerbrµ, north of Hj°rnespids. The name is found first in the form Pyramide in a report by Braun (1953), who made an unsuccessful attempt from the north side while assisting Erdhardt FrΣnkl during Lauge Ko

name: Pyramiden
description: Prominent pyramid-shaped peak 1701 m high on Volquaart Boon Kyst, so named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Laurits Bruhn for its shape. It has also been called Punta degli Italiani.

name: Pyramiden
description: Feature on the north slope of Frebold Bjerg, NW Hold with Hope, between River 8 and River 9. Named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Eigil Nielsen for its shape.

name: Pytelv
description: Small river in south Liverpool Land draining west into Hurry Inlet, so named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Laurits Bruhn because of its small size (pyt = puddle).

name: Pythagoras Bjerg
description: Mountain south of Holger Danske Briller on the north side of Nordvestfjord. The name originated during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen and was adopted at the suggestion of R. SpΣrck. In shape the mountain approximates to a right-angled triangle. The name

name: Pytten
description: Westernmost lake in Vigfus Dal, west of M°rkefjord. The name was given by the Place Name Committee in 1940 to replace a suggestion by Eigil Knuth's 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition (pyt = puddle).

name: Pµlen
description: Hill in east Milne Land between Charcot Havn and Kap Leslie, named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Hermann Aldinger as Pfahl (pµl = pole, stake).

name: P°llen
description: Peninsula in east Liverpool Land, north of Trekanten. The name was proposed by the Place Name Committee in 1938, and was named for its shape (p°llen = the cushion). It was originally thought to be an island.

name: P°lseneset
description: Narrow peninsula on east Geographical Society ╪, NW of Kap Mackenzie. So named on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937) for the sausage-like shape. (P÷lseneset.)

name: P°lsevika
description: Small bay on east Geographical Society ╪, NW of Kap Mackenzie near P°lseneset. Used on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937). (P÷lsevika).

name: Nunatak Godfrey
description: Peak 2585 m high in the Lindbergh Fjelde, west of Christian IV Gletscher, northern Christian IX Land. Climbed by the 2001 Lanchester Greenland expedition and named after Dan Godfrey, surveyor on Martin Lindsay's 1934 expedition. A surveying spike on the

name: Nunatakgletscher
description: Glacier at the head of Geologfjord. Discovered by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst, and named Nunatak glacieren because of the several mountain tops or nunataks which appeared to project from it. (Nunatak Glacier.)

name: Nunatakken
description: Rocky prominence forming the east point of Kap Sussi, which was used as a lookout post by the 1943-44 Operation Bassgeiger. The name is reported by Olsen (1965). It has a small stone wall enclosure on the summit, and is still (1988) connected by a teleph

name: Kyber
description: Surveying station in central Dronning Louise Land. The name was used in the report on the 1952-54 British North Greenland expedition by Hamilton et al. (1956), and was presumably named after the Kyber Pass.

name: Martin Knudsen Nunatakker
description: Nunatak area west of Victor Madsen Gletscher. Mapped by Lauge Koch during flights in 1932 on the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, and named after Martin Knudsen [1871-1949]. Knudsen was professor at the University of Copenhagen from 1912 to 1941, leader of D

name: Maryhuset
description: Norwegian hunting station at Kap Mary on SE Clavering ╪, built in August 1909 by Vebj°rn Landmark, and subsequently used by the 1927-29 HIRD expedition and Arktisk Nµringsdrift. Dangerous ice conditions that caused the death of three hunters led to a dec

name: Masclet Bay
description: Fjord in Liverpool Land, now known as Storefjord. The name Masclet Bay was given by William Scoresby Jr. in 1822 to what appeared to be a small bay or inlet, and was named after the late French consul at Liverpool, Chevalier Masclet. The name is not give

name: Matterhorn
description: Mountain 1624 m high in the southern Barth Bjerge, north of Ardencaple Fjord (Fig. 59). Named by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt after the mountain of the same name in Switzerland. Several names in the region were derived from Swiss or Aus

name: Matterhorn æS' Peak
description: Mountain on the south side of Jµttegletscher, the present Lille Cervin, so named informally by the 1931 Louise A. Boyd Arctic expedition. It appears on some of Boyd's maps marked æSæ.

name: Mattmarks°
description: Lake in central Hudson Land. Named during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition by Heinrich Bⁿtler after the Mattmarksee in Vispertal, Switzerland.

name: Maud S°
description: Lake in west AndrΘe Land. Named by John Haller following explorations during Lauge Koch's 1949-51 expeditions, after Queen Maud [1869-1939], a daughter of Edward VII of Great Britain who married Haakon VII of Norway. (Maud-See.)

name: Mauritius Tinde
description: Mountain in north AndrΘe Land, south of Eremitdal, named by Erdhardt FrΣnkl during Lauge Koch's 1948-50 expeditions. (Mauritiustinde.)

name: Mauritz Diesens Sj÷
description: Lowest and largest lake in Brogetdalen in Strindberg Land, the present Lakses°. The name is only used by Munsterhjelm (1937), and was named after Mauritz Diesen, a Norwegian lawyer who fished here with Munsterhjelm in 1936.

name: Maursundet
description: Sound between Robertson ╪ and north Geographical Society ╪. Used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937), the name is a Norwegian expression for a sound with a strong current.

name: Mausa
description: River on SE Clavering ╪, the present Moskusokseelv. So named on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937) after the Mauseeidvσg in the M°re and Romsdal district of Norway, home of the Norwegian hunter Peder R°bek (see also R°bekfjellet).

name: Mausdalen
description: Valley on SE Clavering ╪ containing the river Mausa, equivalent to the present Baesdalen. The name is used on an NSIU map (1932a).

name: Mears Fjeld
description: Peak 2100 m high in the upper reaches of Sefstr÷m Gletscher, Stauning Alper. Climbed by the 2001 Scottish Mountaineering Club expedition.

name: Medalselva

name: Medusagryde
description: Bowl-shaped valley with a small glacier on the east side of Majdal, north Scoresby Land. Named by Hans Kapp during Lauge Koch's 1957-58 expeditions, for the shape, somewhat reminiscent of a jelly fish (= medusa).

name: Mehrendalen
description: Valley in north Hudson Land draining north to Wordie Gletscher, equivalent to the present Slugtdalen. So named on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937) after Martin Mehren [b. 1905], a Norwegian who, with Arne H°ygaard, made a crossing of Greenland from west t

name: Melander River
description: Name used by 1968-74 Dundee University expeditions for the river in Eskdal, SW Traill ╪, which drains into Karupelv.

name: Melch Dal
description: Valley on the north side of Dickson Fjord from which a conspicuous, white, foaming waterfall drains south into the fjord. It was named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by EugΦne Wegmann, after Melchtal north of Lausanne, Switzerland.

name: Mellemdal
description: Valley joining Tyrolerdal and Svejstrup Dal. The name was adapted from the Verbindungstal (= connecting valley) of Mittelholzer (1941), at the suggestion of W.R.B. Battle in 1948 (mellemdal = between valley).

name: Mellemfjeld

name: Kap Hope
description: SW point of Liverpool Land, named Cape Hope by William Scoresby Jr. in 1822 out of respect to Samuel Hope of Everton. The settlement east of the cape is known as Kap Hope [Ittaajimmiit] (see also above).

name: Kap Hovgaard
description: Cape on southern Geographical Society ╪, west of Nordenski÷ld ╪ (Fig. 14). The name was given by J.M. Wordie's 1926 Cambridge expedition, originally as Cape Hovgaard, to commemorate the Danish member of the VEGA expedition through the NE Passage. Andreas

name: Kap Humboldt
description: Eastern cape of Ymer ╪. William Scoresby Jr. named Cape Humboldt in 1822 in compliment to the celebrated traveller Friedrich Heinrich Alexander, Freiherr von Humboldt [1769-1859]. Humboldt was noted for his travels in Central and South America betwen 179
