name: Koralkl°ft
description: Small ravine west of Margrethedal on SE Gauss Halv°. Originally the river was named by Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions in the form Coral Creek or Coral River, because of the abundance of fossil corals. SΣve-S÷derbergh's (1934) maps suggest the official

name: Korpvatnet
description: Small lake SW of Freycinet Bjerg on SW Geographical Society ╪. So named on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937) (korp = raven).

name: Korridoren
description: Deep valley occupied by a major glacier extending from central ╪fjord eastwards across Milne Land (Fig. 56). So named during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions by Niels Henriksen, because the valley provided a route, or corridor, across Milne Land

name: Korridoren
description: Broad sound between Kap Bornholm, the north point of Lille Koldewey and Bσdskµret, Danmarkshavn, marked by a strong current. The name was reported by Hans Meltofte as in general use by weather station staff in 1969-71.

name: Korsbjerg
description: Mountain in southern Liverpool Land, so named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Laurits Bruhn, probably for the four summit ridges in the shape of a cross. A cairn at the 1400 m high summit was discovered by the 1989 Snow Dance expedition, and co

name: Korsbjerg
description: Mountain in north Scoresby Land west of Mesters Vig, with the highest summit at 1060 m. So named by prospecting teams associated with Lauge Koch's 1948-49 expeditions, because it is formed by several intersecting high ridges.

name: Korseneset
description: Name used by the 1908-09 FLOREN expedition for a peninsula in the vicinity of Kap Borlase Warren (Brandal 1930). Exact position uncertain.

name: Langgletscher
description: Name occasionally used, and also briefly officially approved, for the long glacier in the Stauning Alper flowing east to Schuchert Dal, now known as Storgletscher. Bj°rn Jorsalfarers Gletscher has also been used, and was the approved name between 1939 an

name: Langkl°ftgletscher
description: Glacier north of Fures°, north of Castorbjerg. So named during Lauge Koch's 1954-55 expeditions by Hans Zweifel, because the glacier occupies a long, narrow ravine.

name: Langryggen
description: N-S-trending ridge up to 1800 m high on the west side of Vestre Borggletscher, south of Scoresby Sund. So named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Laurits Bruhn.

name: Langsiden
description: N-S-trending ridge in Home Forland. Named originally in the form Langsuen on the NSIU (1932a) map.

name: Langs°
description: Elongate lake on NW Ella ╪, so named by the 1931-32 wintering party on Ella ╪. (Langes°, Long Lake, Langsee.)

name: Langs°
description: Long lake in Dronning Margrethe II Land, that first appears with this name on the 1932 Geodµtisk Institut 1:1 million scale map compiled by Lauge Koch.

name: Langs°dalen
description: Very long E-W-trending valley in Hochstetter Forland that contains the lake Langs°. Although commonly used, this name was not officially approved until 1981.

name: Langs°hytten
description: Danish hunting hut built by Nanok in August 1933 on the north side of Langelv. It was rescued from falling into the sea by J.G. Jennov in 1948, who moved it nine metres inland. It functioned as a provisions shed after M°nstedhus was built on the same sit

name: Lang°en
description: Island west of R°de° and immediately north of Edvard ╪ in western Dove Dugt. The name was used on a sketchmap recording Henning Bistrup's observations during a sledge journey in October 1907. (Jan L°ve, personal communication May 2012).

name: Langσren
description: Elongate island in the western part of the Broch ╪er group, first named on the 1932a NSIU map in the form Langσra. (Langaaren.)

name: Laplace Bjerg
description: Mountain 1190 m high on Geographical Society ╪ (Fig. 12). William Scoresby Jr. in 1822 gave the name Cape Laplace out of respect to Pierre Simon, Marquis de Laplace [1749-1827], a mathematician and astronomer. Both spellings of his name (Laplace and La P

name: Laplace Huset
description: Name sometimes used for the Norwegian hunting station built in 1938 at the foot of Laplace Bjerg, Geographical Society ╪, by Ole Klokset's expedition. It was manned as a wintering station only in 1938-39, and is now in poor condition. (Laplace, Kap Lapla

name: Laplace ╪er
description: Low islands NE of Geographical Society ╪. The name is used in Den Gr°nlandske Lods (1968), and they are probably the small islands off Laplaceneset.

name: Laplaceneset
description: Cape on the north coast of Geographical Society ╪, due north of Laplace Bjerg. The name is used on Lacmann's (1937) maps, and also in Den Gr°nlandske Lods (1968).

name: Lapstun Hytten
description: Norwegian hunting hut erected in September 1954 by Otto Lapstun for Herman Andresen's expedition on the NW side of Fleming Fjord. It replaced the nearby hut Flatstranda, which was swept away by a storm in 1953. The new hut has also sometimes been known a

name: Lars Christensenfonna
description: Ice cap on central Clavering ╪, the present Snemarken. So named on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937) after Consul Lars Christensen [1884-1965], a Norwegian whaling magnate, ship owner and philanthropist. He made major contributions to Antarctic exploration

name: Lars Jakobsen Pynt
description: Peninsula on the south side of Heimland Havn, west Sabine ╪. Named by J.M. Wordie's 1926 Cambridge expedition as Lars Jakobsen Point after the captain of the HEIMLAND, the expedition ship.

name: Larsens Skµr
description: Skerry 5 km NE of Teufelkap in Dove Bugt. Discovered during the 1932 Gefion expedition (Jennov 1935), and named after a business acquaintance named Larsen. The name is used in Den Gr°nlandske Lods (1968).

name: Larsfjeldene
description: Mountains in east Nordmarken between Agsutsund and V. Clausen Fjord, on both sides of H.G. Backlund Fjord, so named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by David Malmquist. The name has been changed in recent official name lists to Larsfjeld.

name: Laub Nunatakker
description: Nunatak group west of Hertugen af OrlΘans Land. Named by the 1909-12 Alabama-ekspeditionen after Vilhelm Laub, second in command of the expedition, who led a party to the west side of Dronning Louise Land. Vilhelm Laub [1887-1945] later became a director

name: Mitterspids
description: Mountain on the north side of Sefstr÷m Gletscher, Stauning Alper, where Kirkbrae and a smaller unnamed glacier meet. Named and first climbed by Hans Gsellman's 1957 expedition. (Mitterspitze.)

name: PourhelΦne
description: Mountain 1909 m high in Renland. Climbed and named by the 2007 West Lancashire Mountaineering Group expedition.

name: Nordenski÷ld Bugt
description: Bay on the east coast of Shannon. Named by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt as Nordenskj÷ld Bucht, probably after Nils Adolf Erik Nordenski÷ld [1832-1901], the noted Swedish Arctic explorer (Fig. 64). See also Nordenski÷ld Gletscher. The al

name: Nordenski÷ld Gletscher
description: Major glacier at the head of Kejser Franz Joseph Fjord (Fig 65), named by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst after Niels Adolf Erik Nordenski÷ld [1832-1901]. Nordenski÷ld (Fig. 64) had encouraged Nathorst to take up his perha

name: Nordenski÷ld ╪
description: Island at the mouth of Vega Sund (Fig. 14), named by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst as Kap Nordenski÷ld. White (1927) interpreted Nathorst's cape as an island which he renamed Nordenskiold Island, although it is possible

name: Nordfjord
description: N-S-trending fjord 13 km wide between Strindberg Land and Gauss Halv°. Named Nordfjorden by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst for its direction. A hut on the east side of the fjord is sometimes known as Nordfjord (see Brehyt

name: Nordfjordhuset
description: Scientific station built in 1931 on the east coast of Strindberg Land during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen. It is sited immediately south of Strindberghytten.

name: Nordhoek Bjerg
description: Mountain 1502 m high on the west side of Loch Fyne, named by H.G. Backlund during Lauge Koch's 1929 expedition in the form Mt. Nordhoek after the captain of the expedition ship GODTHAAB, Hannes Gysbert Nordhoek [1894-1953]. Nordhoek was first mate on the

name: Nordkap
description: Northern cape of Schnauder ╪ in J°kelbugten. Named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition.

name: Nordkjosen
description: Bay on SE Geographical Society ╪, south of Cambridge Bugt. Used on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937), the name derives from a place of the same name in the Troms district of Norway.

name: Nordlige Jµgersundhytte
description: Norwegian hunting hut built on the island Tvillingerne, SW Dove Bugt, in August 1933. Jµgersund is the channel between Tvillingerne and Nanok ╪. The hut has also been called Kroken, Vestre Tvillingen and Tvillinghytten.

name: Nordmarken
description: Extensive land area between Kofoed-Hansen Brµ and Skµrfjorden, north of S°ndermarken. Named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition, who considered it the northern segment of an expanded Germania Land.

name: Nordneset
description: Name used by the 1930-32 M°re expedition for a peninsula near the hunting station at Antarctic Havn, possibly the present Kap Syenit (Rogne 1981).

name: Nordostbugt
description: Shallow bay east of Sydkap, usually filled by stranded icebergs. Named by the 1891-92 Den ╪stgr°nlandske expedition led byCarl Ryder as Nord÷st Bugt because of the general trend. (Nord°st Fjord, Nordostbugten, Nord÷stbugten, North-east Bay, North-East Fj

name: Nordprofil
description: Geological reference locality on SE Kuhn ╪, used by Maync (1947) in his description of work during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition.

name: Nordre Basisdal
description: Valley in SE Canning Land draining north to ┼lborg Fjord. The name appears to have first been used by SΣve-S÷derbergh (1937) in the form N. Basis Valley, and derives from surveying work during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition.

name: Nordre Funddal
description: Valley in north Scoresby Land, a north branch of Nedre Funddal. Named by prospecting teams associated with Lauge Koch's 1948-49 expeditions for minor finds of lead ore in quartz veins.

name: Nordre Gneisnµs
description: Northern of two gneiss ridges bounding areas of sediments on the east side of Store Koldewey. Used by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen in the form Northern Gneiss Naze. (Northern Gneissnµs, Nordliche Gneisnaes.)

name: M°rkefinger
description: Mountain 2354 m high on the west side of inner Agassiz Dal. The name was used by EugΘne Wegmann during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, and was given for its appearance (= dark finger). (Markefinger.)

name: M°rkefjord
description: Narrow fjord incised into Daniel Bruun Land. Named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen as M°rke Fjord, because of an unpleasant voyage along the long and narrow fjord in 1906. Vigfusdalfjord has been used for the same feature. (M÷rkefjord, Dark Fjord, S

name: M°rkefjord Station
description: Danish scientific station built in 1938 north of the mouth of M°rkefjord, west of Hvalrosodden. So named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition. It was manned from 1938 to 1941, the last two years because the Danish Meteorogical Institute had requested a c

name: M°rkefjordsbugten
description: Bay at the entrance to M°rkefjord and Pustervig. The name was first used by the 1932 Gefion expedition.

name: M°rkefjordselv
description: River running into the head of M°rkefjord, so named by the 1912-13 Den danske Ekspedition til Dronning Louises Land. (M°rkefjords-elven, M°rkefjord-Bach.)

name: M°rkefjordshytten
description: Danish hunting hut on the north side of M°rkefjord; it was sailed to this location from Hvalrosodden by Nanok in August 1933. Now a ruin. (M°rkefjordhytten.)

name: M°rkefjordsplateau
description: High plateau area between M°rkefjord and Sµls°en. Named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition. (Dimmafjar≡arhßlµndi.)

name: M°rkeklint
description: Cliff in northern Th. Thomsen Land. The name originated from the wintering party at Kulhus during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, and was given for its dark colour.

name: M°rkholmen
description: Small island off the coast of SE Geographical Society ╪. Used on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937), the name commemorates Rolf M°rk [b. 1907], a Norwegian artist who took part in the 1933 NSIU expedition to East Greenland.

name: M°ya
description: Mountain about 2350 m high on the SW side of Orion Gletscher. Climbed by the 1996 Norwegian Stauning Alper expedition, and named after a resemblance to a mountain of the same name in northern Norway.

name: Revaltoppe
description: Nunataks in SW Dronning Louise Land, west of Dannebrogsfjeldene, named by the 1912-13 Den danske Ekspedition til Dronning Louises Land as Reval-Toppene or Revaltoppene. Reval, an old Nordic name for the capital of Estonia, was the site of a battle betwee

name: Revdal
description: Valley in Karstryggen draining east to Schuchert Flod. Named by Enrico Kempter during Lauge Koch's 1956-58 expeditions for the massive reef-building carbonates (rev = reef).

name: Revet
description: Narrow passage between west Clavering ╪ and the east coast of Payer Land. The name was used by Norwegian hunters from about 1927 because it is so shallow that it can be waded at low tide (revet = shallow water place). The hunting station on the west side

name: Revet
description: Official Danish name for the Norwegian hunting station on the west side of the passage Revet, west of Clavering ╪. The original hut on this site, Tyrolerheimen, was supplemented in 1928 by a larger station known to Norwegians as Moskusheimen.

name: Revlerne
description: Mountain ridge up to 1210 m high adjacent to Roma Gletscher on Volquaart Boon Kyst, so named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Laurits Bruhn for its barred appearance (revle = bank, bar).

name: Reynolds ╪
description: Island off the north coast of Liverpool Land (Fig. 72). Named Reynolds Island by William Scoresby Jr. in 1822 in compliment to descendants of the late Richard Reynolds of Bristol. Richard Reynolds [1735-1816], a Quaker philantropist, who retired from bus

name: Rhedin Fjord
description: N-S-trending fjord between Gletscherland and Lyell Land (Fig. 52). Named by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst after a Swedish businessman, Martin Werner Rhedin [1865-1930] of Ellesbo, who contributed 5000 Swedish kronor to t

name: Rhodesia Peak
description: Peak 1440 m high on the south side of Korridoren, Milneland, climbed by the 2004 West Lancashire Scouts expedition.

name: Rhµtelv
description: River west of the head of Fleming Fjord. So named by Hans Stauber during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition because the river drains through a valley formed in Rhaetic rocks. Rhaetelv Valley is occasionally used for the valley in English publications (e.g.

name: Richardpynt
description: Minor cape on NE Ella ╪. Named by John Cowie during Lauge Koch's 1950 expedition for his assistant, Richard Nielsen of Copenhagen.

name: Richmond
description: Rock peak 1650 m high on the east side of Kishmul Gletscher, Stauning Alper. First climbed by the 1963 Imperial College expedition and named after the London borough, now Richmond-upon-Thames.

name: Korsgletscher
description: Glacier in Bartholin Land dividing into three branches in a cross-shaped pattern. Named by John Haller following explorations during Lauge Koch's 1956-58 expeditions.

name: Korsspids
description: Massive mountain about 2780 m high east of the head of Cavendish Gletscher, Stauning Alper (Fig. 27). Climbed by the 1963 University of Cambridge expedition. Hans Gsellman's 1957 expedition may also have climbed the peak, and called it Weisswand, but no

name: Kortedal
description: Valley south of Roslin Gletscher draining east into Schuchert Dal. Named by the Place Name Committee in 1959 as a replacement for a suggestion by Enrico Kempter.

name: Kosmoceras Bjerg
description: Name found only in Surlyk et al. (1973), where it was used for a mountain in Jameson Land west of Olympen. It derives from finds of fossil kosmoceras ammonites.

name: Kosmocerasdal
description: Minor valley on SE Milne Land draining NE into Charcot Bugt. The name appears on maps of Callomon & Birkelund (1980), and derives from finds of kosmoceras ammonites. It has also been called Chattonkl°ft.

name: Kostenbaderbjerg
description: Minor peak 460 m high NW of Kap Leslie, east Milne Land. Named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen as Kostenbader Berg or Kostenbaderberg by Hermann Aldinger. Origin uncertain, but possibly given for a German geologist.

name: Kote 800
description: Prospectors name for the 800 m high isolated hill west of Bay Fjelde, east Milne Land, where Nordisk Mineselskab investigated a placer deposit. Shallow drilling has proved 5 million tons of ore with 1-3.8% Zr and 0.5-1.9% rare-earth elements (Harp°th et

name: L°yningdalen
description: Valley on west Geographical Society ╪ draining south into Vega Sund. Used on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937), and named after Paul L°yning [1895-1960], a Norwegian zoologist who became curator at the Zoological Museum in Oslo in 1926, and took part in NS

name: Lσghumpen
description: Hill 315 m high in south Hold with Hope. The name appears on an NSIU map (1932a; Fig. 13, and was probably given for its relatively low, humpy nature.

name: Mackenzie Bugt
description: Bay south of Hold with Hope. William Scoresby Jr. had seen an opening of the land at a great distance in 1822, and named it Mackenzie's Inlet in compliment to Sir George Steuart Mackenzie [1780-1848]. A mineralogist, noted for his proof of the identity o

name: McKenzie Glacier
description: Minor branch of Essemmceebrae on the south side of Sefstr÷m Gletscher, Stauning Alper. So named by the 1998 Scottish Mountaineering Club expedition.

name: Mackenzie River
description: River draining through Badlanddal into Mackenzie Bugt. The name was used by Goodhart & Wright (1958).

name: Mackenzie Valley
description: Valley north of Mackenzie Bugt, the present Badlanddal. The name was used in reports of the 1933 Louise A. Boyd Arctic expedition (Boyd 1935).

name: Macknight Bjerg
description: Mountain 540 m high on the west side of Carlsberg Fjord. Named by William Scoresby Jr. in 1822 as Cape Macknight, probably after Thomas Macknight [1763-1836], minister of the Old Church Edinburgh from 1810. Like many of Scoresby's capes it was later show

name: Maclear
description: Mountain about 1900 m high on the north side of Mercurius Gletscher, south Stauning Alper. First climbed by James Clarkson's 1961 expedition.

name: Madum S°
description: Lake in west AndrΘe Land at the north margin of Gerard de Geer Gletscher. So named by Ove Simonsen during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen because, like the Danish lake of the same name in NE Jylland, it has no apparent exit.

name: Magdalenas°
description: Lake at an altitude of 585 m in west Strindberg Land, named by Hans R. Katz during Lauge Koch's 1948-49 expeditions.

name: Magdalene Spids
description: Highest peak west of Vertebrae, on the north side of Gully Gletscher, Stauning Alper. Climbed by the 1963 Cambridge University expedition on 18 August, and named after Magdalene College, Cambridge, founded in 1542. (Magdalene.)

name: Magga Dan Gletscher
description: Larger of two major glaciers which flow northwards into Gσsefjord (Fig. 22). Named by W. Stuart Watt during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions after the expedition ship MAGGA DAN used in 1969. The MAGGA DAN, built in 1956 for the J. Lauritzen ship

name: Magga ╪
description: Small island adjacent to Kista ╪ in Vega Sund. The name was proposed by S°kortarkivet in 1956-57 following surveying of the channel through Vega Sund as an alternative approach for ships en route to Mestersvig, and given for the MAGGA DAN. See also Magga

name: Magnetikerbjerg
description: Mountain on east Clavering ╪, named by Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions in the form Mt. Magnetiker. Probably named after Max Grotewahl, a member of the 1930 expedition who carried out geomagnetic observations in the region.

name: Mittlandet
description: Name used by Anrick (1932) for the landmass between Gerard de Geer Gletscher and Jµttegletscher, the present Louise Boyd Land.

name: Mittleres Profil
description: Geological reference locality on SE Kuhn ╪, used by Maync (1947) in his description of work during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition.

name: Mobu Dal
description: Valley on west Gauss Halv°, running NE to Moskusoksefjord. The name was used by Swedish geologists during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, and is said to be an abbreviated name of a geological society.

name: Modiolaelv
description: Minor river in SE Jameson Land running into Lakseelv NW of Kap Stewart. Named by Alfred Rosenkrantz during Lauge Koch's 1926-27 expeditions as Modiola Elv after the fossil lamellibranchs.

name: Moena Tinde
description: Peak 1940 m high on the south side of Gully Gletscher, north Stauning Alper. Climbed on 2 August by Sandro Pucci's 1984 expedition. Origin of name unknown.

name: Molehill
description: Small peak about 2300 m high at the head of Dalmore Glacier, central Stauning Alper. So named by the 1968 Dundee University expedition, which made the first ascent. (The Molehill.)

name: Molen
description: Mountain NW of the head of Hurry Inlet, named by Tom Harris and Alfred Rosenkrantz during Lauge Koch's 1926-27 expeditions in the form Mole Mountain.

name: Mollytinde
description: Low mountain close to camp on the west side of Storgletscher, only 1670 m high, central Stauning Alper. Climbed and named after a living person by the 2007 SMC East Greenland Expedition.

name: Mols Bjerge
description: Mountain range north of Mountnorris Fjord, east Traill ╪. Named by Ove Simonsen during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen after the Danish locality of the same name in Jylland.

name: Moltke Bjerg
description: Mountain 1388 m high on north Clavering ╪. Named by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt as Berg Moltke, after Count Helmuth Karl Bernhard von Moltke [1800-91], field marshal in the German army, and one of those present when the expedition sail

name: Moltke Nunatak
description: Nunatak group west of Hertugen af OrlΘans Land. On official lists appears as ænunatak', but most often seen used in the plural form ænunatakker'. Named by the 1909-12 Alabama-ekspeditionen as Moltke's Nunatakker after Count Carl Poul Oscar Moltke [1869-

name: Moltvika
description: Bay on the NE side of Traill ╪, west of Kap Palander. Used on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937), the name was given for Walter Molt [b. 1901], a Norwegian hunter who wintered in East Greenland in 1932-33 and 1934-35.

name: Mona Bjerg
description: Mountain c. 2300 m high NE of Nordenski÷ld Gletscher, named by Noel Ewart Odell after his wife (Odell 1937a; Fig. 65). Gwladys Mona Odell [1891-1977] accompanied her husband on many of his expeditions between 1919 and 1961. In 1933 they had climbed Mona

name: Monacleus
description: Mountain on SE Clavering ╪ with one summit 1403 m high. Named during Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions by H.G. Backlund in the form Mt. Monacleus. See also Binucleus and Trinucleus. (Monaclius Bjerg.)

name: Mont Bertram
description: Mountain 1300 m high on SE Milne Land on the south side of Charcot Gletscher. So named in the report by Parat & Drach (1934) on their work with J.-B. Charcot's 1933 expedition, after one of the members of the 1933 Cambridge expedition which was transport

name: Mont Blanc de Furesoe

name: Mont du Pollux
description: Mountain 1510 m high on SE Milne Land, NW of Bay Fjelde. The name was used during J.-B. Charcot's 1933 expedition (Parat & Drach 1934), and was named after the French icebreaker POLLUX that accompanied the POURQUOI PAS? on the 1932 and 1933 expeditions.

name: Mont Freudo
description: Mountain about 2480 m high on the east side of Prinsessegletscher, south of Fures°. Named and first climbed by the 1968 ExpΘdition Franτaise au Groenland Nord-Est led by Claude Rey.

name: Mont Lack
description: Mountain 1720 m high on the north side of Charcot Gletscher, east Milne Land. So named in the report on J.-B. Charcot's 1933 expedition by Parat & Drach (1934). Named after David Lambert Lack [1910-73], a member of the 1933 Cambridge expedition transport

name: Nordre Koldewey ╪

name: Nordre Muschelbjerg
description: Slightly more northern part of Muschelbjerg, situated ENE of S°ndre Muschelbjerg, Hochstetter Forland. So named by Hans Frebold during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen. An unapproved danicised version of the name, Nordre Muslingebjerg, was used by Surlyk

name: Kystfjµld
description: Name used by Danish hunters for part of S°ndre Muschelbjerg in Hochstetter Forland, close to the coast (Nyholm-Poulsen 1985).

name: Kystkµrene
description: Boggy area along the coast of Zackenberg Bugt, south of Zackenberg Forskningsstation. The name is used as a reference locality in reports by visiting scientists.

name: Kaares-bu
description: Norwegian hunting hut in Nathorst Fjord, 6-7 km south of Kap Brown. Built in August 1932 by the 1932-34 Helge Ingstad expedition, and named after Ingstad's brother, Kaare [b. 1901], a diplomat who was Norway's ambassador in Tel Aviv from 1966 to 1971. Th

name: Kµmpebµnken
description: Nunatak west of Hamberg Gletscher. Named by the 1931 H°ygaard & Mehren expedition as Kjempebenken, and described as a strange box-like nunatak 800 m long, 400 m wide and 75 m high, resembling a giant bench. (KΣmperbΣnken.)

name: Kµmpeh°jen

name: Kystens Perle

name: Kµrdal

name: Kµrelv
description: Minor river east of Zackenberg Forskningsstation draining south into Young Sund. The name is used as a reference locality by visiting scientists (Meltofte & Thing 1996). (Fen river.)

name: KΣthispids

name: L. Bistrup Brµ
description: Large glacier flowing northwards between Dronning Louise Land and Rechnitzer Land (Fig. 21). Named by Henning Bistrup as L. Bistrupsbrµ during the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen, after his father Lauritz Hans Christian Bistrup [1850-1914], who was a colon

name: Knorten

name: Knuthsminde

name: Knot Hill

name: Knotten

name: Magog
description: Mountain with twin summits at the head of the easternmost branch of Canta Brµ. It was reported as shaped like the head and beak of a bird. The 1963 Cambridge University expedition climbed the east spire on 8 August, and in some of their reports refer to

name: Majskµr

name: Qarrtsilunisletta

description: Peninsula on the east side of Rosenvinge Bugt, south of Scoresbysund, south Liverpool Land. One of the names recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, it translates as æthe place where one puts out nets'. The Scoresbysund local newspaper

name: Lady ╪er

name: Messterfjellet
description: Mountain 1308 m high on central Clavering ╪. The name is used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937), and was given for Eduard O. Messter [b. 1893], a director of Zeiss Aerotopograph Gesellschaft Jena.

name: Knud Ringnes Nunatak
description: Nunatak north of Evers Gletscher. Named by the 1931 H°ygaard & Mehren expedition after Knud Ringnes, a Norwegian businessman and director. The Ringnes brewery was at one time the largest in Norway, and was noted for its support for Norwegian Arctic explo

name: Knudedal
description: Steep valley draining south from Knolden, SE Gauss Halv°. Named during Lauge Koch's 1950 expedition by P. Graeter. (Knuden Dal.)

name: LinnΘ Gletscher
description: Large glacier in the northern Stauning Alper, named by Erdhardt FrΣnkl during Lauge Koch's 1950-51 expeditions after Carl von LinnΘ [1707-1778]. LinnΘ (or Carol Linnaeus) was a noted Swedish botanist and explorer, who framed the principles for defining g

name: Lisbet ╪

name: Listerudodden

name: Listhaug°ya

name: Pic Flotard

name: N°kkefossen

description: Area of pronounced alpine topography in north Hudson Land (Fig. 15). Named by Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions in the form N°rlund Alps after N.E. N°rlund [1885-1980]. N°rlund was professor at the University of Copenhagen from 1922 to 1956, and director

description: Land area between Ardencaple Fjord and Bredefjord in the south, and Bessel Fjord to the north. This was one of the new names on the 1932 edition of the Geodµtisk Institut 1:1 million scale map, given by Lauge Koch following aerial observations during the

name: N°rreland

name: N°rresund

description: Mountain on the SW coast of Gauss Halv°. The name was used by Gunnar SΣve-S÷derbergh during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, and commemorates the prominent Russian zoologist and vertebrate palaeontologist, Dmitri Obruchev [1900-1970], an authority on Dev

description: Deep bay or small fjord on the SW side of Kong Oscar Fjord. Named by the 1899 Swedish East Greenland expedition led by A.G. Nathorst as MΣsters Vik. The assumption that it was given for the master of the ANTARCTIC, the expedition ship (see Forsblad Fjor

description: Mountain 1011 m high on SE Milne Land (Fig. 71). The earliest appearance of the name occurs in a report by Parat & Drach (1934) in the form Pic de Pourquoi Pas?, and was originally applied to a 1643 m high mountain 7 km west (70░41'N 26░03'W) of that whi

description: Mountain on the west side of Duart Gletscher. Climbed by the 1966 Deutsche Gr÷nland-Expedition in die Staunings-Alpen led by Karl M. Herligkoffer on 17 August,. See also Priener Kalotte. (Prienerspids.)

name: Primula Pond

description: Pronounced small bay on the west coast of Strindberg Land. The name first appears as a botanical reference locality in a report of the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen (Gelting 1934). Gunnar Seidenfaden had collected specimens of æPrimula stricta' here in 192

name: Primulaelv
description: River on the west side of Hurry Inlet entering the fjord at Constable Pynt. Named during Lauge Koch's 1926-27 expeditions by Alfred Rosenkrantz, appearing first as Primula River in the report by Harris (1931), although without precise location. The name

name: Primulakl÷ft
description: Name used by Rosenkrantz (1934) for the ravine in which Primulaelv flows.

name: Prins Axel Nunatak
description: Large nunatak in north Dronning Louise Land, named by the 1909-12 Alabama-ekspeditionen as Prins Axel's Nunatak for Prince Axel Christian Georg of Denmark [1888-1964], an uncle of Frederik IX. He was a Danish naval officer, who reached the rank of Captai

name: Prinsen af Wales Bjerge
description: Group of nunataks north of Kangerlussuaq (68░35'N), named after the British crown prince [1894-1972], briefly Edward VIII in 1936, who was patron of the 1934 British Trans-Greenland expedition (Lindsay 1935). (Prince of Wales Mtns.)

name: Prinsesse Caroline-Mathilde Alper
description: Mountain range in east Kronprins Christian Land, south of Ingolf Fjord. Named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition after the wife of the Danish Prince Knud, patron of the expedition, for her always friendly interest. Princess Caroline-Mathilde [1912-1995

name: Prinsessegletscher
description: Major glacier on the south side of Fures°. Named by John Haller following explorations during Lauge Koch's geological expedition in 1954, probably for one of the three Danish princesses, daughters of Frederick IX. Glacier du Furesoe has also been used.

name: Lindsay Nunatak
description: Nunatak NW of the Prinsen af Wales Bjerge, northern Kong Christian IX Land, originally named by L.R. Wager's 1935-36 expedition in the form Lindsay Nunataks to cover a group of three. On the northernmost nunatak L.R. Wager had found a broken ice axe left

name: Lingularyggen
description: Minor ridge NW of Kap Leslie, east Milne Land, between Glaukonitbjerg ansd Slottet. It was named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Hermann Aldinger as Lingularⁿcken or Lingula Rⁿcken after the fossil brachiopod Lingula.

name: Lloyds Point
description: A prominence in Hurry Inlet, it was named by William Scoresby Jr. in 1822 after the captain of the TRAFALGAR, who had made useful investigations in the area. It was probably a point on the west side of Hurry Inlet, but was not depicted on Scoresby's (182

name: Loch Fyne
description: N-S-trending fjord between Hold with Hope and Hudson Land. It was explored by Douglas Clavering in 1823 and named Loch Fine after the fjord of the same name in Scotland. Maps of Scotland used the form æLoch Fine' until at least the middle of the 19th cen

name: Loch Fyne Station
description: Danish hunting station built by Nanok in 1945 on the west side of inner Loch Fyne. It was manned from 1945 to 1951, and subsequently maintained by Sirius. It is considered to be one of the best stations on the coast, which has given rise to the alternati

name: Loddevig
description: Small bay south of Danmark Havn, so named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen because detailed soundings were made here (J. L°ve, personal communication 2009; lod = a sounding weight).

name: Lodin Elv
description: River in Jameson Land draining SW to Hall Bredning. The name was one of a group of names given by the Place Name Committee in 1939 to replace names proposed by Hans Stauber. It was given for Lodin, who brought home the body of Finn Fegin from Greenland a

name: Lodlineklippe
description: Near vertical cliff on the south side of Budolfi Isstr°m, south Dronning Louise Land. Named by the 1952-54 British North Greenland expedition as Lodlinieklippe (Fig. 21) because it was so nearly vertical that a plumb line (= lodline) could be dropped fro

name: Lollandselv
description: River in Jameson Land flowing west to Hall Bredning. So named by Laurits Bruhn during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen after the island of Lolland, Denmark.

name: Lommens° Hytten
description: Hut built by Nordisk Mineselskab not far from the Loms°en airstrip, where Pingo Dal meets Schuchert Dal. It is also known as Pingo Dal Hytten. The hut was removed in 1990 by a Nordisk Mineselskab clear-up team.

name: Paradisdal
description: Valley on the east side of Kjerulf Fjord near its junction with inner Kejser Franz Joseph Fjord. So named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Ove Simonsen because of the rich vegetation and pleasant grassy slopes, which are in great contrast to the

name: Paradisdalen
description: Name often used for the Norwegian hunting hut at Paradisdal, NW Suess Land. It was originally known as Rendalshytta.

name: Paradisklippe
description: Long cliff on the north side of Borgj÷kel, below Himmerland Hede (Fig. 21), Dronning Louise Land. Named by the 1952-54 British North Greenland expedition.

name: Paradisterrasse
description: Plateau area between D°de Brµ and Rolige Brµ with an imposing view. Named by Laurent Jemelin during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions for the biblical association with nearby Arken and Arrarat.

name: Paralleldal
description: Valley crossing central Gauss Halv°, trending approximately E-W and nearly following latitude 72░30'N. Named by Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions in the form Parallel Valley (parallel = line of latitude). It has sometimes been used in the forms Western Pa

name: Parat Kl°ft
description: Ravine south of Charcot Havn, east Milne Land, named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Hermann Aldinger in the form Parat-Schlucht, for Maurice Parat of the University of Paris. He was a member of J.B. Charcot's 1933 expedition which visited the

name: Nesvatnet
description: Lake behind the peninsula Dragneset on SE Geographical Society ╪. So named on Lacman's (1937) maps.

name: Neuhausendal
description: Valley on the north side of ╪rsted Dal, apparently the present Horsedal. So named during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition by Hans Stauber (1940), after the Swiss town of Neuhausen near Schaffhausen, the home of his assistant Hans Hⁿbscher.

name: Nevis
description: Mountain about 2150 m high at the head of Jupiter Gletscher, south Stauning Alper. It was first climbed by James Clarkson's 1961 expedition, and probably named after Ben Nevis, the highest mountain in Scotland.

name: New Mountains
description: Name used by Gino Watkins for the present Watkins Bjerge, situated almost entirely south of latitude 69░N. The mountain range was observed during a flight along the coast in 1930. See also Watkins Bjerge.

name: New Valley

name: Newnham Pas
description: Pass about 2350 m high between the head of Cantabrµ and Newnham Glacier, Stauning Alper. Named by the 1963 Cambridge expedition after Newnham College, Cambridge, established in 1875 as the second women's college. (Newnham Col.)

name: Newnham Glacier
description: Glacier in the central Stauning Alper, south of Newnham Tump, so named by the 1963 Cambridge East Greenland expedition. It was later named Ravnas Bre by a Norwegian expedition.

name: Newnham Tump

name: Newton Klippe
description: Prominent cliff on the north side of Admiralty Gletscher, NW Dronning Louise Land (Fig. 21). One of the names given by the 1952-54 British North Greenland expedition for notable scientists, it commemorates the British physicist and mathematician Sir Isaa

name: Nid-Bjerge
description: Name used by Styger (1951) for a ridge in the Werner Bjerge, north of Vestre Gletscher, in his report on a climbing excursion during Lauge Koch's 1950 expedition.

name: Nidelv
description: Minor river in the Werner Bjerge draining east into Deltadal, which rises on the north side of the ridge named Nid-Bjerge by Styger (1951). The name was used during Lauge Koch's 1948-50 expeditions by Peter Bearth and Eduard Wenk.

name: Nidsdal
description: Name used by Pessl (1962) for the valley in which Nidelv flows.

name: Krabbegletscher
description: Glacier draining into Dammen at the head of Alpefjord (Fig. 38), notable for the two partly submerged moraine ridges resembling the claws of a crab. Named during Lauge Koch's 1954 expedition by John Haller.

name: Kranges Fjeld
description: Mountain on the south side of Ardencaple Fjord between Femdalen and Kildedal, corresponding to the present Vesterport. The name was used by Nanok hunters (Hvidberg 1932), and was said to have been given for a Copenhagen lawyer of that name.

name: Kratersee

name: Krabbedalen
description: Small valley at the head of Bopladsdalen, Kap Brewster, where well-preserved fossil crabs were collected by D. Mackney and F.W. Sherrell during Lauge Kochs 1951 geological expedition. The name was used by Hassan (1953).

name: Kraterseepingo

name: Kratlien

name: Krebs Bjerg
description: Mountain in Dronning Louise Land, so named by the 1909-12 Alabama-ekspeditionen. Probably named after Holger Klingberg Krebs [1872-1953], a Danish marine officer promoted to captain in 1909 (J. L°ve, personal communication 2009). It was climbed by member

name: Krebsedal

name: Observatoriehalv°
description: Peninsula on south Sabine ╪, on the SW side of Germania Havn. Named Sternwartenhalbinsel by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt because it was the site of Edward Sabine's 1823 observatory where he conducted his pendulum experiments. Karl Kolde

name: Odd Arnesenfjellet

name: Odin Dal

name: Odinsborg
description: Mountain in NE S°ndermarken on the south side of C.F. Mourier Fjord. So named by David Malmquist during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen. See also Odin Dal.

name: Odinshanes°

name: Lauge Koch Bjerg
description: Mountain 2436 m high in Goodenough Land. J.M. Wordie gave it the name Mount Lauge Koch during his 1929 Cambridge expedition, as a mark of his respect for Koch's work. Lauge Koch [1892-1964], a Danish geologist and Greenland explorer, took part in the 191

name: Lauge Koch Vig
description: Bay on the SW coast of Hochstetter Forland. The name appears to have first been used on a sketch map made by T. Johansen in 1932 during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, and was subsequently used by Koch (1940). See also Lauge Koch Bjerg. (Lauge Koch's Vi

name: Laupdalen
description: Valley on north Clavering ╪. Used on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937), the name is derived from a Norwegian dialect word (laupa = shine, glisten).

name: Laussedatfjellet
description: Mountain 1525 m high on north Clavering ╪. Used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937), the name was given for AimΘ Laussedat [1819-1907], a French officer and scientist credited with the invention of photogrammetry. He became professor of geodesy at the ╔cole

name: Lavenesset

name: Le Nez Blanc

description: Bay on the north side of Flyverfjord. Named by Geoffrey Halliday during the 1971 Northern Universities expedition after the University of Leeds, to which the senior geologist David Rex was affiliated. Leeds in west Yorkshire originated as an Anglo-Saxon

description: Nunatak at the margin of the Inland south of Mylius-Erichsen Land, eastern North Greenland. It was named by the 1909-12 Alabama-ekspeditionen for Ernest de K. Leffingwell [1875-1971], a Canadian scientist who accompanied Ejnar Mikkelsen on an expedition

description: Bay on the north side of inner Nordvestfjord, east of Backlund Bjerg. Named by Geoffrey Halliday during the 1961-1962 Leicester University East Greenland expeditions, which reached this point during botanical journeys. The university in Leicester was fou

description: Spectacular ice-covered mountain in NW Dronning Louise Land (Fig. 21). Named by the 1951 British North Greenland reconnaissance expedition after the patron of the expedition, then Princess Elizabeth, now Queen Elizabeth II, Queen of the United Kingdom an

name: Prinsessen Col

name: Nordredepot ╪

name: Nord°stelv

name: Nord°stre Havnenµs

name: Norma Hytta

name: Norma-°ien
description: Name used by the 1932-34 Helge Ingstad expedition for a small hill rising from a flat valley floor, possibly in ╪rsted Dal or Pingel Dal. It was named after the daughter of his companion Normann Andersen (Ingstad 1935). (Norma Island.)

name: Norsemandal
