name: Pariser°erne
description: Island group on the east side of J°kelbugten. Named by the 1905 ExpΘdition Arctique du Duc d'OrlΘans as Ile de Paris, after the capital city of France, and possibly also after the Duc's father Philippe D'OrlΘans who was Compte de Paris. The 1906-08 Danma

name: Parker ╪er
description: Two small islands off the coast of south Liverpool Land. Named by William Scoresby Jr. in 1822 as Parker Island after a friend, Charles Parker.

name: Parkers Piece
description: Ice plateau between Pembroke Kuppel and Snetoppen, Stauning Alper. Named by the 1963 Cambridge University expedition after Parker's Piece, an open space south of Emmanuel College in Cambridge commemorating Edward Parker, to whom it was leased in 1587. On

name: Parkinson Bjerg
description: Mountain in east Hudson Land, named by Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions as Mt. Parkinson after one of the geologists of J.M. Wordie's 1929 Cambridge expedition, Mark Mervyn Leofric Parkinson. (Parkinsonfjellet, Parkinsonberg, Parkinson-Berge.)

name: Parnas
description: Mountain in north Jameson Land 1249 m high, adjacent to and higher than Olympen. Named during Lauge Koch's 1958 expedition by John H. Callomon after Mount Parnassus or ╙ros Parnassos in central Greece. Within sight of Delphi and sacred to the Dorians, it

name: Pasdalen
description: Name used by Andreas Vischer (Vischer 1943) in a report on 1937 field work, for the valley issuing from a pass in the centre of eastern Wollaston Forland.

name: Pasdalshuset
description: Norwegian hunting hut built by the 1932-34 Helge Ingstad expedition at the mouth of Solfaldsdal, Fleming Fjord. Now disappeared. It has also been known as Syveren, Mellemhuset and Funkis.

name: Paselv
description: River in northern Klitdal draining into Carlsberg Fjord. So named during Lauge Koch's 1926-27 expeditions by Alfred Rosenkrantz and Tom Harris as R. Pass Elv, because its course runs close to the pass in the valley between Carlsberg Fjord and Hurry Inlet

name: Pasfjord
description: Short fjord west of Kap Vidar, east Liverpool Land. So named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Laurits Bruhn because a pass in the valley at the head of the fjord leads over to Carlsberg Fjord.

name: Pashuset
description: Danish hunting hut at the mouth of Permdal, Wollaston Forland, a valley which leads to Kuppelpasset. It was built by Nanok in August 1933.

name: Pashytten
description: Danish hunting hut on the east side of Store Koldewey, where a low pass leads over to Berg Fjord, built by Nanok in August 1933. It is officially known as Bergfjordhytten, and has also been known as Yderhytten.

name: Pashytten
description: Danish hunting hut NE of Sµls°en, built by Nanok in the spring of 1938. Named for its position on the route to Passet in central Slµdelandet. It has also been known under the names Trekronerhytten, Schultzhytten, Hvalsletten and Slettehytten.

name: Passagegletscher
description: Glacier in south Goodenough Land on the west side of Agassiz Dal, used by John Haller as a route westwards into the nunataks during Lauge Koch's 1953 expedition.

name: Passageh°je
description: Mountain range rising to about 900 m west of Loch Fyne, named during Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions by Helmar G. Backlund as Passage Hills or Passage Berge. They had originally been called Devon Hills. (Passageh÷hen.)

name: Passagen
description: Valley west of Carlsberg Fjord providing an easy connection to Pingel Dal. The name was one of a group of names given by the Place Name Committee in 1939 to replace proposals by Hans Stauber.

name: M°ysalen
description: Twin-peaked mountain with summits 2450-2500 m high on the SW side of Orion Gletscher. Climbed by the 1996 Norwegian Stauning Alper expedition, and named after a resemblance to a mountain of the same name in northern Norway.

name: Mσgebjerg
description: Mountain in the Werner Bjerge. Named during Lauge Koch's 1953-54 expeditions by Peter Bearth and Eduard Wenk, and initially published in the forms M÷wenburg and Maagebjerg (Bearth 1954, 1959), the name was given for the gulls (= maage, mσge). The mountai

name: Mσgeelv
description: River in south Liverpool Land west of Mσgefjeld draining south into Hvalrosbugt. Named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Laurits Bruhn. (Maageelv.)

name: Mσgefjeld
description: Hill north of Scoresbysund town in south Liverpool Land. It was named during the 1924-25 colonisation expedition after the numerous gulls (Pedersen 1926). (Maagefjeld, Gullfjeld.)

name: Mσgefjeldet
description: Coastal cliff in Daniel Bruun Land south of Port Arthur. The name was recorded by Pedersen (1942) who observed here 40 pairs of glaucous gulls in 1938. There was still a glaucous gull colony here in 1989.

name: Mσgefjeldet
description: Mountain in NE Holm Land. Named by Eigil Nielsen during the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition as Maagefjeldet, because it is a breeding-place for gulls, and as a counterpoint to Mallemukfjeldet in SE Holm Land. (Maagefjµld.)

name: Mσgefjeldet
description: Name used by Helge Vedel in his diary of the 1891-92 Den ╪stgr°nlandske expedition, for a hill with a gull colony on Danmark ╪ (Gull°v 1991).

name: Kriemhildbreen
description: Glacier on north Clavering ╪. So named on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937), after Krimhild, wife of Siegfried, Burgundian princess of Worms who killed the defenceless Hagen in the German epic poem from c. 1200, the Nibelungenlied.

name: Kristiern Nielsen Dal
description: Valley draining east into ╪rsted Dal, the present Pingo Dal. The name was one of a group of names given by the Place Name Committee in 1939, which replaced proposals by Hans Stauber. The name was officially approved from 1939 to 1957, although only rarel

name: Krogen
description: Peninsula on the south coast of Gσsefjord. Named during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions by Georg Sawatzki for the hook-like shape (krogen = the hook).

name: Krogh-Hytta
description: Norwegian hunting hut on the south side of Gauss Halv° east of the river in Aina Dal, built by Arktisk Nµringsdrift in October 1930. John Giµver and Otto Johnsen, who built the hut, had got to know Rolf von Krogh during the summer, when he had undertaken

name: Krogh-Johansens Isbanke
description: Shallow part of Dove Bugt between Kap Bjarne Nielsen, the NE point of Edvard ╪, and Bratskµret, where hundreds of icebergs derived from Bredebrµ lie stranded. So named during the 1932 Gefion expedition, after V. Krogh-Johansen, a member of the committee

name: Kroghsundet
description: Sound between Jackson ╪ and Home Forland. The name was used on the 1932a NSIU map for the present Gulmann Sund, and commemorates Rolf von Krogh. See also Krogh-Hytta.

name: Krognesfjellet
description: Name sometimes used by Norwegian hunters for the mountain behind the hunting station Krogness, equivalent to the present Frebold Bjerg.

name: Krogness
description: Norwegian hunting station about 2 km SW of Kap Stosch, built by the Foldvik expedition in 1926, and also commonly called Kapp Krogness. The station was manned from 1926 to 1930 and 1935 to 1937. It was named after Ole Andreas Krogness [1886-1934], Norweg

name: Krognessfjellet
description: Mountain ridge on central Geographical Society ╪. The name was used on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937), and commemorates O.A. Krogness. See Krogness.

name: Krogs°
description: Small lake at the corner where Ptarmigan Gletscher meets Nordenski÷ld Gletscher, named by J.M. Wordie's 1929 Cambridge expedition as Corner Lake (krog = corner).

name: Krokdalen
description: Valley on west Geographical Society ╪ draining north into Sofia Sund. Used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937), and named for the shape (krok = hook).

name: Malia Havn
description: Small harbour on south Geographical Society ╪, adjacent to Kap Hovgaard. The name was proposed by S°kortarkivet in 1956-57 following surveying of the channel through Vega Sund as an alternative approach for ships en route to Mestersvig. Jomfrupollen was

name: Mallemukfjeld
description: Cliff in SE Holm Land, named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen as Mallemukfjeldet because of the large colony of fulmars observed here in April 1907. Eigil Nielsen (1941) noted that the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen were inconsistent in their usage, s

name: Mallemukgletscher
description: Glacier on the north side of Mallemukfjeldet in SE Holm Land. Named during the 1909-12 Alabama-ekspeditionen after nearby Mallemukfjeld.

name: Mallemukken
description: Sirius hut on the south shore of Centrums°, built by Slµdepatruljen Daneborg on 8 August 1952. It was in regular use until May 1979, when it was replaced by the modern Sirius hut at the west end of Centrums°. (Mallemukhytten.)

name: Malmbjerg
description: Mountain between Schuchert Gletscher and Arcturus Gletscher, named by Peter Bearth and Eduard Wenk during Lauge Koch's 1953-54 expeditions. The name is usually applied to the conspicuous rust-red, black and yellow colours on the SW flank of the mountain

name: Leirasund
description: Sound between Stille ╪ and the delta at the mouth of Gulelv. So named on the 1932a NSIU map because of the muddy water.

name: Leirdalen
description: Valley on north Geographical Society ╪, draining north into Sofia Sund, west of Robertson ╪. So named on NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937) for the clay deposits.

name: Leirneset
description: Clayey delta on the north side of Geographical Society ╪, at the mouth of Leirdalen. So named on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937) for the clay.

name: Leirvσgen
description: Norwegian hunting hut built in August 1939 on the west side of Lerbugt, originally for glacial investigations by Hans W:son Ahlmann. It was also known as Eigerhytta. Norwegians also used the name Leirvσgen for the bay. (Lerbugt, Ler Bay, Leirevaagen, Ler

name: Leitch Bjerg
description: Mountain 726 m high on Geographical Society ╪. William Scoresby Jr. in 1822 gave the name as Cape Leitch, but his cape was recognised as a mountain by White (1927) and renamed Mount Leitch (Fig. 12). NSIU maps placed their Leitchfjellet a few kilometres

name: Lejrelv
description: River in east Jameson Land, draining into Klitdal. Named during Lauge Koch's 1926-27 expeditions by Alfred Rosenkrantz and Tom Harris, and used in various forms, Lejr River, Camp River or Lejr Elv, because they had a camp here.

name: Lejrgletscher
description: Glacier on the north side of Knµkdalen, named by the 1933 Louise A. Boyd Arctic expedition as Camp 2 Glacier. Louise Boyd's Arctic expedition had their second camp in the valley close to the glacier front. (Camp 2 Gletscher.)

name: Mont R÷hling
description: Mountain c. 1434 m high on south Clavering ╪. Named by Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions after Frederik Holger R°hling, a superintendent in the Technical Department of the Geodetic Institute, who was an expert in drawing and lithographic techniques. The n

name: Mont Saussure
description: Mountain 2580 m high on the north side of Duart Gletscher, Stauning Alper, now known as Duart Borg. It was first climbed by the 1964 AAC Zⁿrich expedition, which named it after H.B. de Saussure, a Geneva scientist. See also Saussure Massiv. The second as

name: Mont Wegener
description: Mountain about 1400 m high in south Liverpool Land, probably the highest peak of Tvillingerne, or possibly Korsbjerg. The name is used in a report by RothΘ (1941) on the work at the French International Polar Year Station at Scoresbysund, and was given f

name: Montane
description: Point 2201 m high on the ice cap north of Edward Bailey Gletscher, Renland. Climbed and named by the 2007 West Lancashire Mountaineering Group Expedition.

name: Monte Bello
description: Mountain in AndrΘe Land. Named during Lauge Koch's 1948-50 expeditions by Erdhardt FrΣnkl, it translates as beautiful mountain, and is a common place name (e.g. the castle in Bellinzona, southern Switzerland is known as Montebello).

name: Monte Carmela
description: Mountain in the north Stauning Alper, SW of Kap PetersΘns. Location uncertain, but probably the 1589 m high peak Blσhorn. Named during the 1930 NSIU expedition by Vittorio Beonio-Brocchieri, who climbed the mountain in August 1930, and named it after his

name: Monte Somma
description: Mountain 1885 m high in the south Werner Bjerge. Named during Lauge Koch's 1953-54 expeditions by Peter Bearth and Eduard Wenk, and climbed by Wenk in 1953. It apparently resembles Monte Somma on Vesuvias.

name: Monts Aldinger
description: Range of mountains on SE Milne Land, north of Vinkeldal, up to 1620 m high. So named in the report by Parat & Drach (1934) describing work during J.-B. Charcot's 1933 expedition, to commemorate Herman Aldinger, a geologist who worked in this region in 19

name: Monumentet
description: Prominent mountain south of Pony Gletscher in Dronning Louise Land. Named by the British North Greenland Expedition 1952-54 (monumentet = the monument).

name: Moorsom Dal
description: Valley on SE Traill ╪. Named by H.P. Heres during Lauge Koch's 1956-58 expeditions for its proximity to Kap Moorsom.

name: Moro Bjerg
description: Mountain in south AndrΘe Land. Named by John Haller following explorations during Lauge Koch's 1949-51 expeditions, for a resemblance to Monte Moro on the Swiss-Italian border south of Saas Fee.

name: Morris Bjerg
description: Mountain 942 m high on SE Traill ╪, west of Steenstrup Bjerg. Named by Desmond T. Donovan during Lauge Koch's 1949-50 expedition after John Morris, a 19th century palaeontologist who worked on fossils of the same age as the rocks which make up the mounta

name: Morten S°
description: Small lake at the south end of Klitdal. Named by Svend Funder who made borings in the lake during a GGU expedition in the 1970s. æMorten' is a Danish name sometimes used for æMartin', a nickname commonly used for the goose, the traditional dish eaten on

name: Morµnebakkerne
description: Moraine deposits at the east end of Store S°dal, near Zackenberg. The name is used as a reference locality by scientists at Zackenberg Forskningsstation (Meltofte & Thing 1996).

name: Norske ╪er
description: One large and several small islands east of the front of Zachariae Isstr°m, so named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen. J.P. Koch (1916) records that the name is to be considered a compliment to the two Norwegian members of the expedition, H.L. Hageru

name: Norskepashytten
description: Norwegian hunting hut built by the Foldvik expedition in 1927 on the NE side of Zackenberg Bugt, Wollaston Forland. It was originally known as Gisvold. It was given this name to distinguish it from the nearby Danish hut known as Pashuset.

name: Norskeryggen
description: Ridge in Jameson Land east of Olympen, of which the highest point is Pelion. The name was suggested by Russel Marris, following his journeys in 1968, as he thought it was a former Norwegian hunting area.

name: Norsketinden
description: Mountain peak 2870 m high in the north Stauning Alper between Vikingebrµ and Gullygletscher, the second highest peak in the region (Figs 27, 67). It was climbed by the Danish-Norwegian expedition on 7 August 1954, and originally referred to as Erik R°des

name: North Bay
description: Name occasionally used by Ejnar Mikkelsen for Sengstacke Bugt, a bay on the north side of Shannon, in his report on the 1909-12 Alabama-ekspeditionen (E. Mikkelsen 1922).

name: North Cirque Glacier
description: Name used in a report by Odell (1937a) for the north tributary of Louise Gletscher in Louise A. Boyd Land, studied during the 1933 Louise A. Boyd Arctic expedition.

name: Lagerholmen
description: Name used by the 1908-09 FLOREN expedition, probably for the small island off Kap Wynn which they also called Maageholmen (Brandal 1930). During the expedition they had deposited stocks of coal and salt here (lager = depot).

name: Lagernunatak
description: Name used by Katz (1952) for a nunatak west of Orienteringsnunatak where he camped on 5 August 1951 (lager = depot).

name: Lagertoppen
description: Peak in the NE part of the Borgbjerg Gletscher region, southern Stauning Alper. Probably named by the 1977 SchwΣbische Stauning Alper expedition.

name: Lagfjeld
description: Cliff up to 1821 m high on western Gauss Halv°, named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Th. Johansen for the striped appearance (lag = layer). The more common usage of the name is Lagfjeldet.

name: Lagunen
description: Small lagoon that builds up behind the beach ridge of ╪sthavn, adjacent to Eskimonµs station. The name originated from the wintering party at Eskimonµs during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen.

name: Lagunenµs
description: Minor cape between M°rkefjord Station and Hvalrosodden. Named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition (lagune = lagoon).

name: Lagunenµsdal
description: Valley on Wegener Halv° reaching Fleming Fjord at Lagunenµset. The name was adopted by Katherina Perch-Nielsen during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions after the Lagunenµsset valley of Grasmⁿck & Trⁿmpy (1969) and the Lagunenµsset Dal of Trⁿmpy (

name: Lagerberghytte
description: Norwegian hunting hut at Kap Lagerberg, SE Lyell Land, built by the M°re expedition in August 1930. It was originally known as Beinhaugen. (Kap Lagerberg Hytten.)

name: Lagunenµsset
description: Peninsula on the NW side of Wegener Halv°, so named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Arne Noe-Nygaard for a coastal lagoon. (Lagunenµs.)

name: Lake B1
description: Lake on Geographical Society ╪ where samples were collected for radiocarbon age determinations (Cremer et al. 2008).

name: Lake N1
description: Lake on Ymer ╪ where samples were collected for radiocarbon age determinations (Cremer et al. 2008).

name: Lakse S°
description: Name sometimes used in reports of the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen for Sµls°en, from which Lakseelven drains. The Arctic char found in rivers and lakes in East Greenland is commonly referred to as salmon (= laks).

name: Lakseelv
description: River in SE Jameson Land west of Kap Stewart. Named by Alfred Rosenkrantz during Lauge Koch's 1926-27 expeditions as Lakse Elv after the Arctic char (Fig. 57; laks = salmon).

name: Lakseelv
description: River draining Lakses° in Brogetdal, east Strindberg Land. Salmon (= Arctic char) were regularly fished here by Norwegian hunters. (Salmon River.) See also Giµver-hytta.

name: Lakseelva
description: Norwegian hunters name for a river in Tyrolerfjord where they fished in the summer, probably that east of Giesecke Bjerg. See also Giskehuset.

name: Lakseelven
description: River draining Blσbµrdalen, east Th. Thomsen Land, draining into Fligely Fjord. The name is said to have been given by Danish hunters in 1929, and first appeared in print on the 1932 edition of the Geodµtisk Institut 1:1 million scale map prepared during

name: Lakseelven
description: Name occasionally used by Danish hunters for the river draining Kildedal on the south side of Ardencaple Fjord, which they also called Kildeelven (Nyholm-Poulsen 1985).

name: Lakseelven
description: River draining Sµls°en. So named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen because of the many salmon (Arctic char), of which 200 kg were caught here in August 1907. (Salmon River, Laxß.)

name: Mσgegletscher
description: Glacier in NE Holm Land, west of Mσgefjeldet. Named by Eigil Nielsen during the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition in the form Maagegletscher.

name: Maageholmen
description: Name used by the 1908-09 FLOREN expedition for a small island off Kap Wynn, so named after the many gulls. It was also called Lagerholmen.

name: Mσgenµs
description: Peninsula on the north side of central Grandjean Fjord. The area was first visited by Gunnar Seidenfaden in August 1932 during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, and was named after the colony of gulls (= mσge), the only one then known in the region. The n

name: Mσgenµshytten
description: Danish hunting hut at the head of the bay at Mσgenµs, central Grandjean Fjord. Built by Nanok in August 1948.

name: Mσges°er
description: These are two small lakes on Winge Kyst, southern Germania Land, which were named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen after the Icelandic Gull and Glaucous Gull (mσge = gull), both common in the region. (Maages°.)

name: Mσgetuen
description: Small island on the north side of central Nordvestfjord. So named by the 1963 Geodµtisk Institut expedition because it resembled one of the grass-covered mounds (= tuer) which gulls like to perch on. Gulls (= mσge) also nest on the island.

name: Mσgeungen
description: Small island in Carlshavn, east Hold with Hope, so named because of the numerous gulls. The name appears on the NSIU (1932a) map in the form Skσrungen.

name: Mσl Glacier
description: Name used by the 2007 SMC East Greenland Expedition for a major western branch of Storgletscher, on their maps marked as æMσl Glacier'.

name: Mσlebjerg
description: Mountain 1873 m high in western AndrΘe Land. So named by Ove Simonsen during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen because it was the surveying station location from which the largest number of points were measured. (Maalebjerg.)

name: Maanedalpingos
description: Informal name used by Mⁿller during Lauge Koch's 1954-55 expeditions, for six pingos he studied in Mσnedal (Mⁿller 1959).

name: Mσnedal
description: Valley on north Traill ╪, south of Rold Bjerge. So named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Ove Simonsen because of the occurrence of pingos resembling small moon craters. (Maanedalen, Moon Valley.)

name: Mσnegletscher
description: Glacier east of Soltemplet on Volquaart Boon Kyst, so named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Laurits Bruhn for its association with the nearby names Soltemplet and Solgletscher (mσne = moon, sol = sun).

name: Mσnegletscher
description: Small glacier on SE Traill ╪, so named during Lauge Koch's 1956-58 expeditions by H.P. Heres for its nearly circular shape.

name: Mσnesletten
description: High plain in south AndrΘe Land east of Junktiondal, so named by Erdhardt FrΣnkl during Lauge Koch's 1948-50 expeditions for its desolate character, like the surface of the moon. (Maanesletten.)

name: Mσnevig
description: Inner E-W-trending part of Ingolf Fjord, Kronprins Christian Land. Named during Operation Groundhog 1960 together with Solvig (vig = bay, mσne = moon, sol = sun).

name: Mσsungane
description: Skerry on the south side of Carlshavn, so named on an NSIU map (1932a) after the numerous gulls.

name: Mσtten
description: Small island south of Danmark Havn, south of Kap Bismarck. Named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen as Maaten. (Maaten ╪, The Mat.)

name: N. Polar Bear Nunatak
description: Reference name for a nunatak in the Prinsen af Wales Bjerge, northern Kong Christian IX Land (Nielsen et al. 2001). It records an incident when a geologist's camp was visited by a polar bear.

name: N1, N2, N3, N4, N5, N6, N7
description: Designations used on 1:15 000 maps of the Mesters Vig region printed in 1951, for seven rivers west of Calamites Elv flowing northwards into Noret.

name: Naajat
description: Cliff SE of Svingnµs on the west side of southern Sµls°en, noted for its gulls and geese. Named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition from the Greenlandic word for gulls, originally in the form Naujat.

name: Kobberpynt
description: Peninsula on the north coast of Vestfjord. Named in this form by the Carl Ryder 1891-92 expedition because the deep, red-brown weathering, ultrabasic intrusions appeared to contain copper ore - there are small amounts of titanomagnetite and pyrrhotite. T

name: Koch Stones
description: This designation is used in some of the the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen reports for the cairn at Kap Bismarck used as a surveying station. The Greenlanders on the expedition used the term to distinguish cairns built by members of the expedition (e.g. J

name: Malmquist Plateau
description: Small plateau on SE Clavering ╪, west of Moskusokseelv. Named by Lauge Koch after David Malmquist [b. 1904] who undertook prospecting in the region during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen. (Malmquists Plateau.)

name: Malmros Klint
description: Cliff on the NW side of Fleming Fjord. Named by Katherina Perch-Nielsen during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions after Lone Malmros [d. 1969], a geologist who worked in the area in 1969, and died in a car-accident in Denmark shortly after returni

name: Manby Halv°
description: Peninsula on the northern part of the Blosseville Kyst. William Scoresby Jr. named Manby Island in 1822 after George William Manby [1765-1854], in gratitude of his exertions and success in the rescue of ship-wrecked mariners. Manby had developed an early

name: Manley Bjerg
description: Mountain 960 m high south of Grantafjord. Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions originally gave the name Manley Land to the area west of Copeland Fjord (Fig. 15) corresponding to the present Blosseville Bjerg, Courtauld Bjerg and Manley Bjerg, because the are

name: Manley Land
description: Name used on Lacmann's (1937) maps for the present Blosseville Bjerg west of Clavering ╪. See also Manley Bjerg.

name: Manniche S°
description: Lake in northern Ad. S. Jensen Land. Named during Lauge Koch's 1956-58 expeditions by John Haller, after a member of the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen. Arne Ludvig Valdemar Manniche [1867-1957] was ornithologist on the expedition, and subsequently wrote

name: Marabugt
description: Bay on east Ella ╪. Named by John W. Cowie during work carried out from 1949 to 1954 on Lauge Koch's geological expeditions, possibly after the wife of Peter Adams.

name: Marcia Bjerg
description: Mountain c. 1460 m high in SW AndrΘe Land, between Rendal and Jomsborg Dal. Named by John Haller following explorations during Lauge Koch's 1949-51 expeditions, after the mountain æLa Marcia' in Switzerland, which has a similar shape and similar rocks, a

name: Margaret Lambert S°
description: Name used for the eastern of the two lakes of Holger Danske Briller on 1952 WAC maps.

name: Margaretas°
description: Lake in Rendal, SW AndrΘe Land. So named by John Haller following explorations during Lauge Koch's 1949-51 expeditions, because the reflection of Margaretatop could be seen in it. Both features were named after Margareta Hediger.

name: Margaretatop
description: Mountain about 2360 m high in southern AndrΘe Land. Named by John Haller following explorations during Lauge Koch's 1949-51 expeditions, after Margareta Hediger. (Margarita Spids.)

name: Margarinecentralen
description: Hunting hut at Kap Steensby on the east coast of Germania Land, built in August 1938 by the Norsk-Franske Polarekspedisjon. The expedition had been given a large quantity of margerine, mainly used as dog food, and the hut was built with the empty boxes.

name: Ping Elv
description: River on the south side of Nedre Funddal, north Scoresby Land, which joins with Peter Elv to form Storm P. Elv. Named by prospecting teams associated with Lauge Koch's 1948-49 expeditions. æPeter & Ping' was the name of a cartoon series created by the Da

name: Pingel Dal
description: Eastern of two large valleys which drain to the head of Fleming Fjord. Named by the 1898-1900 Carlsbergfondets Expedition led by G.C. Amdrup as Pingels Dal, probably after the Danish geologist Chr. Pingel and his son J.V. Pingel. Norwegian hunters used t

name: Pingo Dal
description: Valley south of the Werner Bjerge where a number of pingos are found. Pingos are characteristic volcano-like mounds (Fig. 70), here up to 30 m high. Fritz Mⁿller who had studied them during Lauge Koch's geological expeditions, argued strongly for the nam

name: Pingoelv
description: Informal name used by Fritz Mⁿller during Lauge Koch's 1954-55 expeditions for the river in Pingo Dal, north Jameson Land (Mⁿller 1959).

name: Pingo Pass
description: Name occasionally used for the pass at the head of Pingo Dal leading over to Schuchert Dal (e.g. Schwarzenbach 1996).

name: Pinkfoot Lake
description: Lake in Nordmarken, north of Klµgbugt, where pink-foot geese congregate. Named by the 1987 Irish expedition to northern East Greenland.

name: Pinkfoot Pond
description: Name used in an ornithology report of the 1963 British East Greenland expedition (Hall & Waddingham 1966) for a lake on the north side of ╪rsted Dal. Nests of the pink-footed goose were found here.

name: Pinnacle
description: Mountain on the ridge between Storgletscher and Dalmore Glacier, central Stauning Alper. Named by the University of Dundee expedition which made the first ascent on 15 August 1968. (Pinnacle Peak, The Pinnacle.)

name: Morµnedal
description: Valley in NE AndrΘe Land, draining into Geologfjord. So named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Th. Johansen, because it is a typical glacial valley with moraine ramparts.

name: Morµnedalshytten
description: Norwegian hunting hut built in 1938 for Arktisk Nµringsdrift on the north side of Morµnedal. It is also known as Hastvµrkshytten. Now a ruin.

name: Morµnelandskab
description: Area of spectacular moraines on the east side of Kofoed-Hansen Brµ. Used in this form by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen, but probably intended as a descriptive rather than a formal name. A photograph appears in Koch (1912). (MorΣnenlandschaft.)

name: Morµnepynt
description: Small peninsula on the south coast of Milne Land. So named by Carl Ryder's 1891-92 expedition because of the gravel deposits (moraine) and fossil-bearing clays found here. The name Hvalpynten is used in Helge Vedel's diaries of the 1891-92 Den ╪stgr°nlan

name: Morµnevolden
description: Moraine ridge north of S°sters°er, encountered by Vilhelm Laub in northern Dronning Louise Land during the 1909-12 Alabama-ekspeditionen. It was probably intended as a descriptive rather than a formal name.

name: Morµne°
description: Small island at the entrance to Brµfjorden, at the foot of a glacier descending from Rechnitzer Land. So named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition because it consists of gravel deposited by the glacier (= moraine).

name: Mosaikskµrene
description: Skerries near Spydodden, off eastern Daniel Bruun Land. So named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition because of the red and white mosaic-like patterns in the rocks.

name: Moschusochsenalm
description: Plain rising northwards from the base camp of the 1943-44 Operation Bassgeiger at Kap Sussi, where six muskox were seen in mid-February 1944, of which one was shot. The name is reported by Olsen (1965).

name: Mosen
description: Name used in the ornithology reports of the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen for a part of Winge Kyst near Stormkap, south Germania Land, where there are numerous small lakes.

name: Quellpingo
description: Name used by Fritz Mⁿller during Lauge Koch's 1954-55 expeditions after a pingo beside Karupelv, Traill ╪. It is the smallest of a group of three pingos, 9 m high, and contains a spring (= quell) flowing at the rate of 1.4 litres a second (Mⁿller 1959).

name: Quensel Bjerg
description: Mountain on Wegener Halv°. Named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Arne Noe-Nygaard as Mt. Quensel, after Percy Dudgeon Quensel [1881-1966]. A Swedish igneous petrologist he was professor at the University of Stockholm, and noted for his work on

name: Quppaalakajik
description: River and ravine in south Liverpool Land draining into Hurry Inlet. Recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, the name translates as æthe little ravine'. (Q·paulakajik.)

name: Quppaalakajik
description: Ravine in Neill Klinter on the west side of Hurry Inlet. The name was recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, and means æthe little ravine'. Dinosaurus Kl÷ft has also been used. (Q·paulakajik.)

name: Quppaalakajik Kangitteq
description: River and ravine north of Quppaalakajik [Rendeelv], draining into Hurry Inlet. One of the names recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, it translates as æthe outer little ravine'. (Q·paulakajik kangigteq.)

name: Quppaalartivakajik
description: Ravine in SE Liverpool Land near Kap Lister. Recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, the name translates as æthe big ravine'. The Scoresbysund newspaper recorded in 1984 the local spelling Qappaalardivakajik. (Q·paulartivakajik.)

name: Raatiuup Nuaa
description: Cape at the mouth of Elvdal in Scoresbysund. The name was recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, and translates as æradio cape', referring to the former radio station on top of the low hill behind the cape. (RΓti√p n√a.)

name: Rabbit Ears Island
description: Large island in the Danske ╪er group, named by Jane A. Gilotti for its shape. The name is used as a geological reference locality in reports of studies on ultrahigh pressure eclogites (Lang & Gilotti 2007).

name: Rabsontinde
description: Minor outlying peak of Kapelle, about 1640 m high, on the north side of Sefstr÷m Gletscher. Climbed by the 1998 Scottish Mountaineering Club expedition. (Robson.)

name: Raceway
description: Locality in Jameson Land where Farish A. Jenkins during the 1988-89 Harvard University palaeontological expeditions discovered spectacular fossil dinosaur tracks. A network of 52 different tracks are preserved.

name: Radiobµk
description: Stream between M°rkefjord Station, which was also a radio station, and Termografengen. So named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition.

name: Raffles ╪
description: Island off the coast of south Liverpool Land. Named by William Scoresby Jr. in 1822 as Raffles Island out of respect to the Revd Thomas Raffles [1788-1863], a prominent independant minister, who held the living at Great George Street, Liverpool from 1812

name: Laksehytta
description: Norwegian summer station at the mouth of Brogetdal, Strindberg Land. It was built by Arktisk Nµringsdrift in June 1935 for fishing, and attempts at packing the æsalmon' (Arctic char) in tins were made here in 1938. It is also known as Strindberghuset.

name: Laksehytta
description: Hut at the head of DusΘn Fjord, Ymer ╪, built in August 1932 by the crew of the ISBJ╪RN to support fishing. It is also known as Noahytten, Bunnhuset and Holmboe-hytta.

name: Laksehytten
description: Norwegian hut built for salmon fishing in the summer of 1949 west of Zackenberg hunting station for Herman Andresen's expeditions. It is also known as Fiskerhytten.

name: Laksehytten
description: Danish hunting hut on the NE shore of Lakses°, Ad. S. Jensen Land, said to have been built by Nanok in 1939. Although this name is officially approved, the hut was never built (P.S. Mikkelsen 1994). It may have been confused with the Danish hut Fiskerhyt

name: Lakses°
description: Small lake on the east side of Mesters Vig. Named by prospecting teams associated with Lauge Koch's 1948-49 expedition.

name: Lakses°
description: Largest of the lakes in Brogetdal, Strindberg Land. Named during Lauge Koch's 1948-49 expeditions by Hans R. Katz, after the abundant Arctic char.

name: Lakses°
description: Lake in Ad. S. Jensen Land at the head of Syttendemajfjorden. The name was proposed by Nanok, and appears on a map in Jennov (1939).

name: Lambert Land
description: Land area almost surrounded by the glaciers of Nioghalvfjerdsfjorden and Zachariae Isstr°m. Adapted by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen from an old Dutch chart from 1718, which reported t'Land van Lambert to have been discovered at this latitude by a wh

name: Lambeth
description: Mountain 2450 m high between Gully Gletscher and the head of Bersµrkerbrµ, north Stauning Alper. First climbed by the 1963 Imperial College expedition, and named after the south London borough.

name: Lamorna
description: Pinnacle about 2700 m high on the NE ridge of Hj°rnespids, north Stauning Alper. Named and climbed by the Queen Mary College expedition on 13 August 1968.

name: Mestersvig
description: Airfield north of Mesters Vig, west of Noret, constructed in 1952 as part of the government agreement with Nordisk Mineselskab concerning the exploitation of lead at Blyklippen (P.S. Mikkelsen 2005). The gravel runway is 1800 m long. Additional buildings

name: Metacarpal
description: Mountain on the SW side of Sefstr÷m Gletscher, very close to Inverarnan. Named by the 1963 Cambridge University expedition.

name: Metaforgletscher
description: Small glacier in SW Dronning Louise Land, flowing SW to join Ebbe Gletscher (Fig. 21). The name was given by the British North Greenland Expedition 1952-54, and was derived from the Greenlandic custom of using picture language (metaphor) in giving names.

name: Meydenbauerfjellet
description: Mountain on central Geographical Society ╪, the present Knolden. So named on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937) after A. Meydenbauer [1834-1922], a German architect and archaeologist.

name: Meyer-Hus
description: Norwegian hunting hut on the north side of Tyrolerfjord, south of Zackenberg. Built by the Foldvik expedition in September 1927, and named after Meyer Olsen, a Norwegian hunter who helped build it. It has also been known as Trangfjordhuset and Zackenberg

name: Meyerstein Bjerg
description: Mountain 305 m high on NE Shannon. Named by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt as Meyerstein Berg, probably after Moritz Meyerstein [1808-1882], an instrument maker in G÷ttingen, who supplied meteorological and surveying instruments to the ex

name: Micardbu
description: Norwegian scientific and hunting station 5 km north of Fyrretyvekilometernµsset on the east coast of Germania Land, of which only the foundations now remain. The remains of the house were taken down in 1960 and used to build a smaller hut for Danmarkshav

name: Koch's Corridor
description: Term used by the 1952-54 British North Greenland expedition for the route across Storstr°mmen from near Annekss°en to Ymer Nunatak, a problem-free passage used by J.P. Koch during the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen. The British expedition failed to find i

name: Kocheler Spids
description: Mountain on the SW side of Roslin Gletscher. Climbed by the 1966 Deutsche Gr÷nland-Expedition in die Staunings-Alpen led by Karl M. Herligkoffer on 21 August, and named after Kochel, a small town on the banks of the Kochelsee in the Bavarian Alps.

name: Kochsvighytten
description: Danish hunting hut in Lauge Koch Vig on the SW coast of Hochstetter Forland, built by Nanok in September 1931. (Koch Vig Hytten.)

name: Kodak Ridge
description: Name given to a 1500 m high ridge in northern Milne Land by the 1989 Greenland Milne Land expedition.

name: Kofoed-Hansen Brµ
description: Large glacier flowing north between S°nderland and Nordmarken. Named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen as Kofoed-Hansens Brµ, after Otto Joachim Moltke Kofoed-Hansen [1854-1918], a director of the Danish Admiralty who had shown great interest in the e

name: Knµks°
description: Lake in western N°rlund Land, draining the north branch of Ejnar Mikkelsen Gletscher. The name is a modification of an original suggestion by Lauge Koch, approved in 1957, and records the pronounced bend in the lake.

name: Kn°sen
description: Mountain on SE Gamma ╪ with a broad summit ice cap. Named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition after a Danish locality of the same name.

name: Kohleninsel
description: Temporary name given during the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt to the present Kuhn ╪, and so named because layers of coal up to 50 cm thick were found at Kap Hamburg.

name: Kokkens Lyst
description: Hut in the inner part of Nathorst Fjord erected in the summer of 1977 by Jan Juel-Brockdorff for Mestersvig airfield. It was intended as an emergency hut for aircraft personnel operating between Scoresbysund and Mestersvig. Brockdorff was cook (= kok) at

name: Kolddal
description: Small valley on SE Traill ╪ draining into Fossdal. Named by Geoffrey Halliday following botanical work during the 1961-1962 Leicester University East Greenland expeditions and the 1971 Northern Universities East Greenland expedition.

name: Koldewey ╪er
description: Island group including Store Koldewey and Lille Koldewey. Named by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt as Koldewey Inseln after Karl Koldewey [1837-1908] (Fig. 55), captain of the GERMANIA and leader of both the first and second German Polar

name: Kolding Fjord
description: Fjord on the east coast of south Liverpool Land, so named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Laurits Bruhn after the fjord of the same name in Jylland, Denmark.

name: Kolledalen
description: Valley west of Antarctic Havn in north Scoresby Land. Derived from the Kolldal of Norwegian hunting expeditions based at Karlsbak, Antarctic Havn. The name is found in the form Kolldalen on Norsk S°kort 511 (1937). Antarctic Dal was used by some members

name: Kollen
description: Mountain on the west side of the head of Hurry Inlet between Postkassen and Statuebjerg, and joined to Statuebjerg by a high col. Named by Alfred Rosenkrantz and Tom Harris during Lauge Koch's 1926-27 expeditions as Coll Mountain.

name: Kollen
description: Elongate hill on Canning Land, so named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Arne Noe-Nygaard, because of its shape (kolle = a rounded top).

name: Koloni
description: Name occasionally used on maps and in publications for the town of Illoqqortormiut / Scoresbysund (koloni = colony).

name: Kolossen
description: Mountain 1038 m high between Mellem Gletscher and ╪stre Gletscher, northern Werner Bjerge. Named during Lauge Koch's 1953-54 expeditions by Peter Bearth and Eduard Wenk, and climbed in 1953 by Wenk. It appeared on earlier maps of Styger (1951) as Central

name: Kolstad
description: Norwegian hunting station south of Haystack on the east coast of Hochstetter Forland. It was built by John Giµver's expedition in 1932, and has also been known as Ottostrand. The name Kolstad has also been used for another Norwegian station farther north

name: Loms°
description: Small lake on Winge Kyst. So named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen after the red-throated diver (= r°dstrubet lom), a common breeding bird in the region. (Loms°en.)

name: Loms°
description: Minor lake south of Zackenberg Forskningsstation, close to Young Sund. The name was introduced by Bent Fredskild in 1991 after nesting red-throated divers (= r°dstrubet lom). See e.g. Meltofte & Thing (1996). (Loon lake).

name: Pinnadal
description: Small valley on the east coast of Milne Land between Kap Leslie and Charcot Havn. Named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Hermann Aldinger as Pinnatal or Pinna-Tal, after the fossil lamellibranch æPinna'. (Pinna Valley.)

name: Pisa

name: Piz Coaz
description: Narrow ridge reaching 1950 m high between Spµrregletscher and Duart Gletscher, Stauning Alper. First climbed by the 1964 AAC Zⁿrich expedition which named it for Johanne Coaz, a pioneer Swiss climber who made the first ascent of Piz Bernina in 1850, the

name: Piz Dominant
description: Peak about 2370 m high on the west side of Spµrregletscher, Stauning Alper. First climbed and so named by the 1964 AAC Zⁿrich expedition. The second ascent was by the 1966 Deutsche Gr÷nland-Expedition in die Staunings-Alpen led by Karl M. Herligkoffer.

name: Piz Guarda Monti
description: Peak about 1840 m high on the west side of Spµrregletscher, Stauning Alper. Climbed and so named by the 1964 AAC Zⁿrich expedition.

name: Piz Spescha
description: Mountain 2210 m high east of Spµrregletscher. First climbed by the 1964 AAC Zⁿrich expedition, which named it after Father Plαcidus Spescha, a Benedictine monk who made a number of pioneer climbs in the Swiss Alps between 1788 and 1824. It is identical w

name: Piz Vadian
description: Mountain 1640 m high east of Spµrregletscher, Stauning Alper. So named and first climbed by the 1964 AAC Zⁿrich expedition.

name: Place Concordia
description: Broad, circular, flat area of Charcot Gletscher on east Milne Land. So named by Parat & Drach (1934), after the similarly named glacier confluences in the Swiss Alps.

name: Pladebjerg
description: Mountain in eastern Frµnkel Land so named during Lauge Koch's 1949-51 expeditions by John Haller, because the entire mountain is made up of rocks rich in plates (= plade) of mica.

name: Pladen
description: Mountain on SE Clavering ╪. The name originated from the wintering party at Eskimonµs during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen (plade = slab, plate). Herman Andresenfjellet has also been used.

name: Pladen
description: Small elongate island in the north part of Dove Bugt. Named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen (pladen = the slab).

name: Planck Klippe
description: Cliff on the south side of Admiralty Gletscher, east of Regnbue Klippe, Dronning Louise Land (Fig. 21). One of the names given by the 1952-54 British North Greenland expedition for notable scientists, it commemorates the German physicist Max [Karl Ludwig

name: Plant Hill
description: Mountain in east Hudson Land. It was named by Gunnar SΣve-S÷derbergh during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen for the finds of fossil plants, which showed the rocks to be younger than had been first supposed.

name: Pleinting Bjerg
description: Mountain on the south side of the head of Roslin Gletscher. Climbed by the 1966 Deutsche Gr÷nland-Expedition in die Staunings-Alpen led by Karl M. Herligkoffer on 15 August 1966, and named after the small Bavarian town of Pleinting. (Pleintingbjerg.)

name: Niels Hansen Nµs
description: Peninsula just west of Nanok hunting station. The name came into use in the 1930s by Danish hunters, and was given for Niels Hansen [1878-1963], known usually as æGamle Niels' or æNiels Ivigtut'. He was employed at Ivigtut for nine years, worked as a car

name: Nielsnµs
description: Cape on the coast of SE Clavering ╪, east of Basaltkap. The name occurs on a sketch map in Gustav Thostrup's 1921 logbook, and may have been given for the first mate on the DAGNY in 1921, Niels Larsen Sleth.

name: Niesen
description: Mountain in NW Wollaston Forland. So named during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition by Wolf Maync and Andreas Vischer because it resembled in shape and geology the mountain of the same name south of Spiez in the Berner Oberland, Switzerland. (Mt. Niesen.)

name: Niflheim
description: Mountain in northern C.H. Ostenfeld Land south of Smallefjord. The name originated from the wintering party at Kulhus during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, and was given because surveying here was greatly delayed by fog. Niflheim was a world of mists i

name: Niggli Dal
description: Valley in east Frµnkel Land south of Niggli Spids. So named by EugΘne Wegmann during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen because the valley was very dull in appearance, and Paul Niggli was said to be a dull lecturer (F. Schwarzenbach, personal communication

name: Raffles S°
description: Lake on Raffles ╪ where material was collected for radiocarbon age determinations (Cremer et al. 2008).

name: Ragekniven
description: Name used for a mountain on Nanok ╪, about 5 km SW of Teufelkap in Roon Bugt. According to Poulsen (1991) the name was given by Hσkon Jarner (ragekniv = razor).

name: Ragnhildshytta
description: Norwegian hunting hut at the east side of the mouth of Grejsdalen, east AndrΘe Land. Built in March 1937 for Arktisk Nµringsdrift by Magne Rσum, and named after Rσum's girlfriend, Ragnild Lien. The hut has also been known as Grejsdalshytten and Eleonoreb

name: Ragnas ╪
description: Name used by Henning Bistrup during the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen for the present Godfred Hansen ╪. It was probably given for one of Henning Bistrup's family (J. L°ve, personal communication 2009). Olgas ╪ has also been used.

name: Ramnfjellet
description: Mountain on the south side of Gauss Halv°, corresponding to the present Wiman Bjerg. So named on an NSIU map (1932a), and derived from the Norwegian dialect word for a raven. There are many similar place names in Norway.

name: Ramp
description: Upper part of Britannia Gletscher, Dronning Louise Land. The name was given by members of the 1952-54 British North Greenland expedition (Banks 1957) after the notable æRamp' which features in accounts of Scott's 1910-13 Antarctic expedition.

name: Rampe
description: Sand bank on the west side of Schuchert Flod river bed, at the front of Bj°rnbo Gletscher. Named by Enrico Kempter during Lauge Koch's 1956-58 expeditions.

name: Rampevµggen
description: Mountain wall north of Rolige Brµ forming a boundary to a ramp-like tongue of ice. Named by Laurent Jemelin during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions.

name: Ramsay Bjerg
description: Mountain on Gauss Halv°. Named during Lauge Koch's 1929 expedition in the form Mt. Ramsay by Helge G. Backlund after Wilhelm Ramsay [1865-1928], a Finnish mineralogist and petrologist and an authority on Fennoscandian structures. He was professor of geol

name: Oksebakkerne
description: Low hills NE of Zackenberg Forskningsstation, where muskoxen often graze. The name is used as a reference locality by visiting scientists.

name: Oksedal
description: Valley SE of Mestersvig. Named by prospecting teams associated with Lauge Koch's 1948-49 expeditions after the muskox.

name: Okseelv
description: River in Kuhnpasset, Wollaston Forland, draining SW to Zackenberg Bugt. The name is used as a reference locality by visiting scientists from Zackenberg Forskningsstation. (Okseelven.)

name: Oksefaldet
description: Steep cliff on the north coast of Sµls°en. So named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition, because Paul Gelting and Alwin Pedersen found two dead muskoxen at the foot of the cliff on 10 May 1939. They had fallen down the cliff since their previous visit t

name: Oksehorn
description: Mountain between the head of Oksedal and Kolledal. Named during Lauge Koch's 1953-54 expeditions by Peter Bearth and Eduard Wenk.

name: Okselandet
description: Triangular land area west of Annekss°en, bounded on the west by Storstr°mmen and to the south by Sµls°en. Named during the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition, probably by Paul Gelting who visited the area in June 1939 and considered it the best area in the re

name: Oksepas
description: Pass between the head of Oksedal and R°dedal, north Scoresby Land. So named by Hans Kapp during Lauge Koch's 1957-58 expeditions, because muskox cross the pass here.

name: Oksesletten
description: Area between Henningselv and Gr°nnedal on east Clavering ╪. The name appears on a sketch map in Gustav Thostrup's 1921 logbook, and was given for the muskox.

name: Oksestenen
description: Large stone on a cape east of M°rkefjord Station. So named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition, because muskox used it as a scratching stone.

name: Oksetrappen
description: Name used by Gelting (1934) for a locality about 3 km west of Carlshavn, Hold with Hope, where a series of marine terraces form a staircase-like feature where muskoxen graze.

name: Oktober°
description: Island NE of Gamma ╪, the northernmost point reached on depot-laying journeys by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition in October 1938.

name: Ole R°mer Land
description: Land area bounded by Promenadedal, Waltershausen Gletscher and Vibeke Gletscher. On some early maps this general area is part of Steno Land. The name first appears on the 1932 1:1 million scale Geodµtisk Institut map prepared on the basis of 1932 aerial

name: Oleryggen
description: Peak in the NE part of the Borgbjerg Gletscher region, southern Stauning Alper. Probably first climbed and named by the 1977 SchwΣbische Stauning Alper expedition.

name: Olestua
description: Norwegian hunting station on the east coast of Hochstetter Forland at Kap Carl Ritter, the most northerly station erected by John Giµver's expedition in 1932. Named after Ole Sivertsen, who helped build the station and manned it with John Johnsen from 19

name: Michelangelo Kl°ft
description: River gorge leading down from Slµdelandet to Fladebugt in Skµrfjorden. So named during the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition because of a 10-12 m high rock resembling the statue of a man, whose shape, posture and pathos was to Eigil Knuth reminiscent of a ro

name: Middelgrunden
description: Island in the mouth of Grandjean Fjord, the present Trums ╪. This name appears only on the sketch map by T. Johansen published in Koch (1940), a map drawn during the original exploration of the fjord in 1932. It is a common Danish name for an offshore sh

name: Middle Gneisnµs
description: Name used as a geological reference locality by Frebold (1935) and Maync (1949) for a point on the east coast of Store Koldewey between Nordre Gneisnµs and Sydlige Gneisnµs. (Mittlere Gneisnaes.)

name: Middle Peak
description: Peak in the north Stauning Alper, climbed by G. Dionisi's 1982 expedition during a traverse including Norsketinden.

name: Midnatspas
description: Pass across the west part of Gunnar Andersson Land, Ymer ╪. This name was given by A.B. Cleaves and E.F. Fox during John K. Howard's 1933 expedition, because their geological work began at midnight after they had made a traverse of the pass. The name was

name: Midnight Peak
description: Peak about 1700 m high on the south side of Mercurius Gletscher, south Stauning Alper. First climbed by James Clarkson's 1961 expedition, and so named because they reached the summit at exactly midnight.

name: Midnight Sun
description: Summit 930 m high in Liverpool Land, north of Bjerring Pedersen Gletscher. The name was recorded by the 2002 Loughborough Grammar School expedition that made the second ascent.

name: Midterfjeld
description: Mountain about 1200 m high in south Strindberg Land, named by Hans R. Katz during Lauge Koch's 1948-49 expeditions (midter = middle).

name: Midterfjellet
description: Mountain 752 m high in SE Hold with Hope, named for its position between two other peaks. An NSIU map (1932a) used the name MΘfjellet, while Gustav Thostrup used Kommafjeldet for the same feature.

name: Midterholmen
description: Island in the west part of Dove Bugt. So named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition because of its position centrally between Ring°en and R°de°. Anthons ╪ and Julles ╪ have also been used.

name: Profilbjerg
description: Mountain in north Scoresby Land, bounded to the south by Nordre Funddal and Nedre Funddal. Named by prospecting teams associated with Lauge Koch's 1948-49 expeditions. (Profilbjerget.)

name: Profildal
description: Valley in SE Renland, east of Rypefjord. So named by Johan D. Friderichsen during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions because of a well-exposed geological profile.

name: Profile Ravine
description: Ravine on the south side of Sederholm Bjerg, central Gauss Halv°. The name was used by Gunnar SΣve-S÷derbergh during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen, because geological profiles were measured here.

name: Profilfjeldet
description: Mountain on the north side of S°dalen. Named by Eigil Nielsen during the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition as Profilfjµldet, because geological sections were measured here.

name: Promenadedal
description: Prominent valley on the south side of Wordie Gletscher, named by Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions in the form Promenade Valley. It is a long and wide valley and is easy walking terrain (promenade = promenade, parade). (Promenade Tal, Promenadetal, Gangda

name: Prometheus
description: Mountain 2574 m high on the SW side of Orion Gletscher, south Stauning Alper. It was first climbed by James Clarkson's 1961 expedition, and named after the god of fire in Greek mythology.

name: Proppen
description: Nunatak at the head of Harefjord. So named by the 1963 Geodµtisk Institute expedition because it blocked the flow of ice like a cork (= prop) in a bottle.

name: Prospekt Dal
description: Small valley west of Ankerbjerg on the north side of Moskusoksefjord, named by Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions as Prospect Valley, because of a possible mineralisation prospect. Norwegian scientists used Vassdalen for the same feature. (Prospekttal, Pro

name: Prospektfjeld
description: Mountain on SE Traill ╪ on the south side of Mountnorris Fjord. So named by Desmond T. Donovan during Lauge Koch's 1949-50 expeditions.

name: Prµdikestolen
description: Mountain 1271 m high south of inner Harefjord. Named during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions by Heintz Rutishauser for its resemblance to the mountain æKanzel' in upper Lauterbrunnen Tal, Switzerland (prµdikestolen = kanzel = pulpit).

name: Prµstekraves°

name: Pr°vestenen
description: Nunatak in SW Dronning Louise Land, so named by the 1912-13 Den danske Ekspedition til Dronning Louises Land after one of the coastal sea forts off Copenhagen. (Pr÷vestenen.)

name: Puchan Glacier
description: Name used by the 2007 SMC East Greenland Expedition for the western upper branch of Gullygletscher.

name: Puchwhitstinde
description: Mountain 2339 m high on the east side of upper Storgletscher, central Stauning Alper. Climbed and named by the 2007 SMC East Greenland Expedition. The name derives from a combination of personal names.

name: Loms°en

name: Lonetoppen
description: Mountain 1131 m high in Claudius Clavius Bjerge, north of ╪rsted Dal. Named by Katharina Perch-Nielsen during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions after Lone Malmros who worked in the region in 1969 (see also Malmros Klint).

name: Loon Lake
description: Name used by Hall (1963, 1966) for a small lake at the east end of Holger Danske Briller where the red-throated diver (loon) was observed to nest by the 1962 Oxford University expedition.

name: Loon Lake
description: Lake on Geographical Society ╪ where samples were collected for radiocarbon age determinations (Cremer et al. 2008).

name: Loppa
description: Very small island in Vega Sund, west of Nordenski÷ld ╪. So named on the NSIU maps of Lacmann (1937), for its diminutive size (loppa = flea).

description: Snow-capped mountain on the west side of Polhemdal in south Lyell Land. So named by EugΦne Wegmann during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen in the form Mont Lugeon, after Maurice Lugeon [1870-1953], a French stratigrapher and structural geologist. For many

name: Lumskebugten
description: Name used by Helge G. Backlund (in: Koch 1955) for the iceberg-filled inner part of Nordvestfjord in front of Daugaard-Jensen Gletscher. Probably named for the near-fatal accident to Backlund's party caused when the front of nearby Daugaard-Jensen Gletsc

name: Lumskebugten
description: Bay on the SE coast of Suess Land at the mouth of Murgangsdal, named by J.M. Wordie's 1929 Cambridge expedition as Deceit Bugt for its misleading appearance. The flat valley at its head at first sight suggests the bay extends much farther north. Mineralb

name: Lumskebugten
description: Bay on the south coast of Germania Land. So named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen by Christian B. Thostrup after the bar or cafe just outside the gates of the Harbour authority in Copenhagen, now the noted restaurant at the same location. Thostrup (

name: Lumskebugthytten
description: Norwegian hut on the west side of the floodplain at the head of Lumskebugten. It was built between 1934 and 1938 by Arktisk Nµringsdrift, and was originally known as Sunnm°resheimen and later as Mineralbukta.

name: Passe Pσ
description: Summit 2013 m high on the corner between Edward Bailey Gletscher and Catalinadal, Renland. Climbed and named by the 2007 West Lancashire Mountaineering Group Expedition.

name: Passet
description: Col on the sledge route through Slµdelandet, NE of M°rkefjord Station. Named by the 1938-39 M°rkefjord expedition.

name: Niinngarpik

name: Niklausdal
description: Valley in Gletscherland on the NW side of Skrµntdal. Name used by EugΘne Wegmann during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen. See also Buri S°er.

name: Nils Hermans Hytta
description: Norwegian hunting hut on the north side of Vega Sund, SE of Svedenborg Bjerg. Built for Arktisk Nµringsdrift in August 1929 by Sverre S°rensen and Thor Halle, it was named after Halle's son Nils Herman. It has also been known as Lindqvist-Hytta and Nanse

description: Nunatak group west of Martin Knudsen Nunatakker. Named by John Haller following explorations on a Catalina flight during Lauge Koch's 1953 expedition. The name derives from a childrens' story by the noted Swedish writer Selma Lagerl÷f, translated into Da

name: Nioghalvfjerdsbrµ

description: Fjord between Lambert Land and Hovgaard ╪ entirely filled by floating glacier ice. So named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen because it lies at latitude 79░N. The name was originally regarded as temporary, but acquired a new significance in the diari

name: Nippoldt Gletscher
description: Small glacier in the N°rlund Alper draining north into Wordie Bugt, named by Lauge Koch's 1929-30 expeditions. Lacmann's (1937) maps use A. Schmidtbreen for this glacier. (Nippoldts Gletscher.)

name: Nissedal
description: Small valley draining into Jµttedal, south Liverpool Land. So named by Laurits Bruhn during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen for its relatively small size (nisse = pixie).

name: Nisseelv
description: River in Nissedal, south Liverpool Land, so named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Laurits Bruhn.

name: Niviarsiaq
description: Minor ravine in NW Hold with Hope, in which River 13 flows. Named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Eigil Nielsen, originally as Neviatiakdal. Probably named after the willow herb, the national flower of Greenland, which in Greenlandic is Niviars

name: Kroken
description: Norwegian hunting hut built in August 1933 for John Giµver's expedition on the west side of Tvillingerne, Dove Bugt. It has also been called Tvillinghytten and Nordre Jµgersund Hytten.

name: Krokfjellet

name: Kronborg Gletscher
description: Large glacier in East Greenland. From the coast at c. 68░25'N it extends northwards to just beyond latitude 69░N. It was named after the noted castle, Kronborg, in Helsing°r, Denmark.

name: Kronebjerg
description: Mountain 544 m high on west Sabine ╪, named by the 1869-70 Die zweite deutsche Nordpolarfahrt as Kronenberg for the crown-like shape of the summit carved out of a basalt sill. Sechsspitze and Sevenspits have also been used. (Kronenberge, Mt Kroneberg, La

name: Kronebjergpynten
description: Name used by Danish hunters for the locality beneath Kronebjerg, Sabine ╪, where Kroneberghytten was built in 1948.

name: Kronedal
description: Valley in the Bjergkronerne massive, draining south into ╪rsted Dal. Named by Katherina Perch-Nielsen during the 1967-72 GGU Scoresby Sund expeditions.

name: Kronen
description: Snow-capped mountain in south Liverpool Land, named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by Laurits Bruhn for its appearance (kronen = the crown).

name: Olgas ╪
description: Name used by C.S. Poulsen during the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen for the present Godfred Hansen ╪ in Dove Bugt (Lundbye 1984). The name has also been used for the present Tvillingerne in Dove Bugt, and is recorded by Henning Bistrup on an October 1907

name: ╥llumlengri
description: Fjord possibly identifiable with the present Scoresby Sund (Torn°e 1944). The name is mentioned in the Icelandic sagas, and means the æfjord longer than all other fjords'. While the description in the account of Ivar Bσrdsson admirably fits Scoresby Sund

name: Olrik Pynt
description: Minor cape on the east side of Lille Koldewey. Named by the 1906-08 Danmark-Ekspeditionen as Olriks Pynt, possibly after Ejnar Olrik of the Royal dockyard (J. L°ve, personal communication 2009). (Olrik Odde.)

name: Olsen Creek
description: Error for Foldvik Kl°ft, found in Koch (1929a p. 115) in a reference to the æOlsen Creek Formation' which should have been the Foldvik Creek Formation. Foldvik Kl°ft is about 6 km east of Kap Stosch. The Norwegian Olsen brothers were hunters based at the

name: Olsen Nunatakker
description: Two small nunataks in west Dronning Louise Land. Named by the 1909-12 Alabama-ekspeditionen as Olsen's Nunatakker after Hans P. Olsen, one of the members of the expedition who sledged to NW Dronning Louise Land with Wilhelm Laub in April 1910.

name: Oluf Kolsrudfjellet
description: Mountain ridge on central Geographical Society ╪. Used only on NSIU maps (Lacmann 1937), and named after Oluf Kolsrud [b. 1885], a Norwegian historian who was professor at Oslo University and had interests in developments in Greenland.

name: Olympelven
description: River in Jameson Land draining SE from Olympen. Named during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition by Hans Stauber.

name: Olympen
description: High mountain in Jameson Land, with a summit ice cap. So named during the 1936-38 Two-year expedition by Hans Stauber after the Olympus of the Greek gods. Stauber climbed the mountain in August 1938.

name: Oqaluppiup Ataa
description: Coastal stretch south of the church in Scoresbysund. One of the names recorded by the 1955 Geodµtisk Institut name registration, it means æthat lying below the church'. (Oqaluugpiup atΓ.)

name: Lejrryggen

name: Lembcke Bjerg
description: Nunatak in NW Dronning Louise Land (Fig. 21), named during the 1909-12 Alabama-ekspeditionen as Lembcke's Nunatak. Preben Lembcke [1886-1965] was a Danish naval officer and a contemporary of Wilhelm Laub who had explored this area.

name: Lemenkjeften
description: Small, enclosed bay on the west side of Mackenzie Bugt. Named in this form on an NSIU map (1932a), after the lemmings.

name: Lemming Bay
description: Name used by the 1968-74 Dundee University expeditions for the bay east of the mouth of Skeldal Elv.

name: Lemming Lake
description: Lake on Store Koldewey where sampling was undertaken for phytoplankton studies (Cremer et al. 2005).

name: Lemming Valley
description: Name used by the 1968-74 Dundee University expeditions for the broad valley west of Mestersvig airfield.

name: Lemmingbugt
description: Bay on eastern Ella ╪, named during the 1931-34 Treσrsekspeditionen by the Ella ╪ wintering party after the lemmings.

name: Lemmingdal
description: Valley on eastern Ella ╪, draining into Lemmingbugt. Named by John W. Cowie during work carried out during Lauge Koch's 1949-54 expeditions.

name: Lemmingelv
description: Name used for the river in Lemmingdal, eastern Ella ╪, by Christian Poulsen about 1950.

name: Lemminghoved
description: Mountain ridge 1527 m high in west AndrΘe Land, at the east border of Gerard de Geer Gletscher. So named by John Haller following explorations during Lauge Koch's 1950 expedition, because the rounded, long mountain ridge resembled in shape the head of a

name: Lenggrieser Ryggen
description: Mountain ridge about 2550 m high on the south side of the upper basin of Spµrregletscher. Climbed by the 1966 Deutsche Gr÷nland-Expedition in die Staunings-Alpen led by Karl M. Herligkoffer on 19 August.

name: Lennox Spids
description: Peak about 1800 m high on the SW side of Sefstr÷m Gletscher, north Stauning Alper. First climbed by the 1958 Scottish East Greenland expedition led by Malcolm Slesser, and named after the castle of Lennoxlove, East Lothian, Scotland. (Lennox.)

name: Leo Gletscher
description: Glacier on the south side of Bj°rnbo Gletscher, south Stauning Alper. So named by John Hunt's 1960 expedition after the constellation, the 5th sign of the zodiac. (Leo Glacier.)

name: Lepidoceraselv
description: River in eastern Jameson Land draining east into Carlsberg Fjord. Named during Lauge Koch's 1926-27 expeditions by Alfred Rosenkrantz and Tom Harris as R. Lepidoceras Elv, for the fossil flowering plants.
